<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040301.0008" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
BEIJING MIGHT USE BALLISTIC MISSILES TO ATTACK TAIWAN: MAGAZINE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 1 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mainland China has deployed three or four
ballistic missile brigades in its coastal provinces targeting Taiwan,
according to the latest quarterly on national defense policies issued
by the Taipei-based Society for Strategic Studies.
</P>
<P>
Among these missiles, modified M11A and M9A missiles have a
range of 600 kilometers and 800 kilometers, respectively and can
strike any area of Taiwan, according to the magazine.
</P>
<P>
The magazine, titled "Review of National Defense Policies, "
quoted a U.S. Defense Department report as saying that in 2002, the
mainland deployed 350 M-series ballistic missiles against the island,
with the annual increase estimated at about 50 units.
</P>
<P>
But the number had reached 450 units by 2003, far higher than the
estimate conducted by the U.S. Defense Department, the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that during the 1995-2003 period, the number of mainland
missiles targeting the island increased at least 11-fold, the
magazine indicates that Beijing is expected to have as many as 600
ballistic missiles deployed against Taiwan by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Most of the missiles have been deployed in the Nanjing military
region, encompassing Fujian, Jiangsi, Guangdong and Chejiang
provinces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040301.0009" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT URGED NOT TO IGNORE MAINLAND CHINA MARKET COMPETITION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 1 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Vice Minister of Economic Affairs Yiin
Chii-ming said Monday that the government should not play down the
importance of the vast mainland Chinese market while seeking to help
domestic manufacturers globalize their business operations.
</P>
<P>
Yiin, who has been serving in his current post for 10 years, made
the appeal during a press conference to introduce his new book,
titled "The Turning Point of Taiwan's Economy."
</P>
<P>
Saying that the government and domestic entrepreneurs should not
ignore the growing competition from the mainland, Yiin said that this
market must be included in Taiwan's business globalization project.
</P>
<P>
Yiin claimed that Taiwan is currently facing a host of economic
problems, such as a rising unemployment rate, an expanding gap in
incomes between rich and poor people, the lowering of public
investment, and the crisis of being marginalized from regional
economic integration.
</P>
<P>
In the face of so many challenges, the government must seek to
stage another wave of economic reforms in order to create an
environment favorable for domestic business and industrial
development and then forge a "business operation platform for East
Asian enterprises" by accelerating the country's economic
liberalization and globalization, Yiin added.
</P>
<P>
Yiin further said that "improving the economy" has recently
become a slogan in Taiwan, especially in the run-up to the March 20
presidential election, as political considerations have superseded
economic considerations.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that his new book is not aimed at any specific person,
Yiin said he is hopeful that the release of his book will prompt the
government, the industrial sector and the public in general to be
seriously concerned over the development of Taiwan's economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040301.0010" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
FERRY SERVICE BETWEEN KINMEN, MATSU AND MAINLAND CHINA EXPANDS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 1 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
New measures allowing more people to use
the ferry service between the two outlying islands of Kinmen and
Matsu and the mainland Chinese ports of Xiamen and Mawei in Fujian
Province took effect Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the new measures, Taiwanese who work on the mainland will
be allowed to return to Taiwan via Kinmen and Matsu.
</P>
<P>
Previously, this was only allowed for Taiwanese working in
Fujian, as it is an exception to the country's policy of no direct
transportation links with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
The Mainland Affairs Council (MAC) , which came up with the
measures to meet President Chen Shui-bian's promise Jan. 30 to a
group of Taiwanese businessmen working on the mainland, estimated
Monday that the new measures will increase the number of passengers
to and from the mainland via this route to 2,000 per day,
representing about 20 percent-25 precent of the number of passengers
who fly to and from the mainland through Hong Kong or Macau every
day.
</P>
<P>
MAC officials said the ferry service might be extended to include
Zhangzhou and Quanzhou, both in Fujian Province, as well as Xiamen
and Mawei -- as long as Beijing agrees.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan businessmen who do not work on the mainland can also opt
to go to the mainland through the two outlying islands but only for
business purposes and they must obtain prior approval, according to
the new measures.
</P>
<P>
A local air carrier has already launched a combined air-sea
service on the route with a round trip ticket priced at NT$5,200.
Passengers choosing this route will fly from Taiwan to Kinmen or
Matsu before being ferried to Xiamen or Mawei.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040301.0011" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
RICH SINGAPOREANS IN CLASS C HOSPITAL WARDS TO PAY MORE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Singapore,  March 1 (CNA)
(By Sherman Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hospital patients in Singapore who are
well-off can still opt to stay at Class C wards, but they will have
to pay more, Acting Health Minister Khaw Boon Wan said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This is because well-off patients will get less than the current
subsidy of 80 percent for Class C wards following the government's
proposal to link subsidies to how much a patient earns.
</P>
<P>
Khaw also said that to further help Singaporeans cope with rising
health care costs, the ministry is considering allowing the use of
Medisave to pay for insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
He said that his ministry is working with the insurance industry
to see how best this can be done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040301.0012" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL TASK FORCE TO BE FORMED TO REVIEW MILITARY SERVICE SYSTEM
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 1 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Cabinet has directed the Ministry of
National Defense (MND) and the Ministry of the Interior (MOI) to form
a joint task force to push for improvements to the nation's military
service system, Vice Defense Minister Chen Ti-tuan said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a ceremony to mark Conscription Day, Chen said the MND
will invite experts to join the task force to study feasible measures
for overhauling the military service system.
</P>
<P>
Basically, Chen said, the MND will carry out a troop-reduction
program first to cut the number of the nation's regular forces to
270,000 from the current 385,000 by 2012.
</P>
<P>
"After this goal is reached, we'll then implement an
enlistment-based military service system to replace the current
conscription system," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
According to the MND's plan, Chen said, the regular forces will
adopt an enlistment-based service system while the reserve forces
will continue to adopt a conscription-based system in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040301.0013" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN-U.S. TIES WILL NOT CHANGE AFTER PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION: OFFICIAL
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 1 (CNA)
(By Huang Kwang-chun)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Relations between Taiwan and the United
States will not change after the March 20 presidential election, a
government official predicted Monday.
</P>
<P>
Replying to questions raised by reporters after attending an
international symposium on Taiwan's national defense held in Taipei,
Lee Ming-hsien, Taiwan's deputy representative to the United States,
said that the United States will continue to support Taiwan in
accordance with the Taiwan Relations Act regardless of who wins the
election.
</P>
<P>
The United States has a neutral position on Taiwan's presidential
race, Lee noted, adding that Washington is more concerned about the
referendum, which it thinks might involve Taiwan's sovereignty and
its independence or unification with mainland China.
</P>
<P>
These concerns have been eased since President Chen Shui-bian
announced Jan. 16 the two questions to be put to the referendum,
which Lee said have nothing to do with a change in the cross-Taiwan
Strait status quo.
</P>
<P>
Washington now neither opposes nor endorses the referendum to be
held alongside the presidential election in which opposition
Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan will challenge Chen's re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
The two questions placed by Chen before the electorate are:
Should the government buy new anti-missile systems to counter
Beijing's growing missile build-up? And should the government open
talks with Beijing to establish a peace and stability framework for
cross-strait interaction?
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040301.0014" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN TO SEND ORANGUTAN TO BRITAIN FOR BREEDING
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Pingtung,  Taiwan,  March 1 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
National Pingtung University of
Science and Technology in southern Taiwan will send an orangutan to
Britain's Monkey World Wednesday for breeding, a spokesman for the
school said Monday.
</P>
<P>
It will be the fourth orangutan that the university has sent to
Monkey World for breeding, the spokesman said, adding that the first
three have formed two families with two local animals and have given
birth.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the orangutan to leave for Britain
Wednesday is about 12 years old and weighs more than 30 kilograms.
"He is healthy and good-tempered," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Monkey World has sent veterinarians and animal keepers to care
for the orangutan on his flight to the British city of Manchester,
the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
China Airlines, Taiwan's largest air carrier, will transport the
orangutan for free as part of its efforts to promote wildlife
conservation, the spokesman went on.
</P>
<P>
The university has maintained cooperative ties with Monkey World
since 1999. "We have been cooperating in breeding orangutans and
long-armed apes in Asia and Europe, " the spokesman said, adding that
the British government has attached great importance to the
cooperative project and has offered financial support.
</P>
</TEXT>
