<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040301.0016" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
NO ASYLUM REQUEST FROM OUSTED HAITIAN PRESIDENT: MOFA
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 1 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Republic of China has not received a
request for political asylum from ousted Haitian President
Jean-Bertrand Aristide, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MOFA) said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Neither our embassy in Haiti nor our embassy in the Dominican
Republic has received any asylum requests from Aristide, " said MOFA
spokesman Richard Shih. "We don't have any related information."
</P>
<P>
Shih was responding to a foreign wire service report that
Aristide had left Haiti under pressure of a rebellion at home and
that he might come to Taiwan for political asylum. Aristide is
Haiti's first freely elected president in the country's history.
</P>
<P>
Shih said the ROC government is pleased to see that the weeks of
tension and unrest in the Caribbean nation has gradually calmed down
with the resignation of Aristide and the inauguration of an interim
president.
</P>
<P>
"It is our hope that order can be restored in Haiti soon and that
the situation there will move toward stability and harmony, " Shih
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Shih said, the ROC government will continue all
bilateral cooperative projects with Haiti once the situation has
stabilized.
</P>
<P>
The ROC has provided agricultural and engineering assistance to
Haiti for many years. Members of the agricultural and engineering
missions in Haiti, who were evacuated to neighboring Dominican
Republic last week amid the upheaval, will return when it is safe to
do so, Shih said.
</P>
<P>
At present, Shih said, more than 10 ROC nationals, including five
embassy staff members and a few ordinary citizens, remain in Haiti.
"They are all safe," Shih said, adding that if any expatriates want
to leave Haiti, the ROC embassy will offer them all necessary
assistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040301.0017" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
FORMER NAVY CAPTAIN GIVES TESTIMONY IN EMBEZZLEMENT TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 1 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A former navy captain who was involved in
the death of the former chief of the navy's arms procurement
department, Captain Yin Ching-feng, appeared at a local court Monday
to give testimony in the trial of a former coworker accused of
stealing public funds while working at Navy General Headquarters in
1992.
</P>
<P>
Kuo Li-heng, who is a suspect in the death of Yin in 1993, is
already serving a life sentence for corruption in another case.
</P>
<P>
He was brought from jail to appear at the Taipei District Court
as a witness in the trial of former Commander Yuan You-fan, who is
accused of siphoning off the interest on funds earmarked for the
country's purchases of four minesweepers from Germany in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Yuan claimed that his confession used by prosecutors as evidence
against him in the case was dictated to him by Kuo during the navy's
own investigation in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Kuo, however rebutted Yuan's claims.
</P>
<P>
The navy commander-in-chief at the time, Adm. Ye
Chang-tong, was also indicted for trying to cover up Yuan's crime.
</P>
<P>
Instead of bringing Yuan to justice, Ye took advise from his
subordinates and forced him to retire in 1992, said the prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
Ye argued that Yuan's trial would have exposed the country's
secret purchase of the four minesweepers and might have ruined the
deal as two of the four minesweepers were still being built in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
Ye noted that Iraq invaded Kuwait at that time and that Germany
was criticized by the United States for selling a pesticide plant to
Iraq, which Washington claimed then used the plant to turn out poison
gas. Under international pressure, Germany then tightened the
restrictions on its arms exports in December 1990 and listed Taiwan
as one of the countries to which it would not sell any weapons.
</P>
<P>
In order to keep the deal secret, Ye said he decided to retire
Yuan rather than get him court-martialled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040301.0018" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
KAOHSIUNG CITY TO KICK OFF MECHANISM TO PREVENT DENGUE FEVER
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  1 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kaohsiung City will kick off a weekly
coordination meeting starting March 8 in an effort to ward off any
outbreak and spread of dengue fever, Kaohsiung Vice Mayor Lin
Yung-chien announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Lin made the announcement following a municipal meeting earlier
in the day in which officials from the health, environmental
protection, education and civil affairs took part to study possible
measures to prevent the mosquito-borne disease.
</P>
<P>
Lin said the city must move swiftly as the annual rainy season is
expected to begin in April and the temperature is gradually rising
every day. The vice mayor said the city has to pay great attention to
this task because of its special position as a busy seaport and
international air gateway.
</P>
<P>
The city decided to implement the mechanisms after the Center for
Disease Control (CDC) under the Cabinet-level Department of Health
informed the municipal authorities of the city's first-ever
foreign-acquired dengue fever case in the middle of last month.
</P>
<P>
According to the CDC, a Kaohsiung resident was confirmed to have
contracted the disease after developing diarrhea, headache and fever
following a trip to Thailand from Jan. 18 to Feb. 8. The patient has
now fully recovered after receiving treatment.
</P>
<P>
From the beginning of this year until Feb. 26, more than 14,000
dengue fever cases, including some fatalities, have been reported in
various countries in Southeast Asia, such as Indonesia, Singapore,
Hong Kong and Sri Lanka.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040301.0019" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
LABOR INSURANCE CONDUCIVE TO SOCIAL STABILITY: VICE PREMIER
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 1 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Vice Premier Lin Hsin-i said Monday that
the implementation of the labor insurance program has made great
contributions to the maintenance of laborers' livelihoods and to
social stability over the past five decades.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a ceremony to mark the 54th anniversary of the
implementation of the labor insurance program, Lin noted that some
laborers are suffering "labor pains" of unemployment caused by the
quick transformation of Taiwan's industrial structure and have to
rely on labor insurance relief.
</P>
<P>
For example, Lin said, the government paid unemployment subsidies
worth NT$10.2 billion (US$306 million) to local jobless workers in
2002 when the country saw a dramatically rising unemployment rate. He
added that unemployment subsidy payments dropped to NT$5.46 billion
in 2003 due to the improvement of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Lin further said that during the period, the government also
offered soft loans worth NT$21 billion to jobless workers to help
them support their families or create their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
According to Lin, over 8.1 million workers are covered by the
labor insurance program.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 54 years, the insurance regulations have been
revised several times in line with social evolution to satisfy
laborers' demands, Lin added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040301.0020" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE MINISTER VOWS ERADICATION OF ELECTION IRREGULARITIES
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 1 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Justice Minister Chen Ding-nan said Monday
that the police, investigation and prosecution agencies will continue
with a crackdown on all type of irregularities related to the March
20 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Chen made the remarks at a special meeting held in northern
Taiwan's Hsinchu City in which State Public Prosecutor General of the
Supreme Court Lu Ren-fa and Public Prosecutor General of the Taiwan
High Court Wu Kuo-i, as well as local investigation, police and
prosecution authorities, also took part to exchange views on measures
to fully carry out the mission.
</P>
<P>
Chen praised the hard work and performance of Hsinchu city and
county authorities in clamping down on voting buying prior to the
2000 election and said Monday's meeting in the Hsinchu area was meant
to underscore the importance of the anti-vote buying work.
</P>
<P>
Saying that the government will do everything it can to wipe out
all illegal activities that might affect the results of the election,
such as vote buying, violence and betting on the election outcome,
Chen said all relevant authorities will focus their investigation in
particular on domestic bookmakers teaming up with foreign bookies to
take bets on the election via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
With less than 20 days to go until the election, no hard evidence
has been collected to show attempts by either side to buy votes, the
minister said, pointing out that investigation and prosecution agents
nationwide have, however, targeted people who might be carrying out
illegal activities that could influence the election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
