<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040301.0022" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
FORMER DPP CHAIRMAN TO FAST TO PRESS FOR HALVING OF LEGISLATIVE SEATS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 1 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lin Yi-hsiung, a former chairman of the
ruling Democratic Progressive Party, and other members of an
anti-nuclear power group started a 10-day fast relay Monday in front
of the Legislative Yuan to press for the halving of the 225-seat
Legislative Yuan.
</P>
<P>
Following a recent statement on building the nation based on
honesty and credibility, Lin and Nuke-4 Referendum Initiative
Association (Nuke-4 RIA) members, began the 240-hour fasting relay
campaign.
</P>
<P>
Yeh Po-wen, executive director of the association, said that the
fast and sit-in will be carried out by each team in 24-hour shifts.
</P>
<P>
The anti-nuclear activists said, "We don't want promises...we
demand action and results."
</P>
<P>
Nuke-4 RIA noted in a statement that all political parties
promised to halve the number of legislative seats three years ago and
to do so, they also agreed to revise the Constitution to achieve that
end.
</P>
<P>
But the proposal, which should not be delayed for another minute,
the association said in a statement, was stalled in the legislature,
leaving no doubt that the foot-dragging legislature is good for
nothing but showboating and verbal sparring.
</P>
<P>
"The association simply cannot ignore the politicians for so
easily backing down from their promises," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The association demanded that all political parties ask all their
affiliated party members to toe the party line and promptly pass a
proposal to revise the Constitution to halve the legislative seats by
the March 20 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The public will then see the determination of all parties, the
statement said, adding that the political parties should not use any
procedural method to pass the buck or try other approaches such as
going into recess to stall the matter.
</P>
<P>
Yeh said that Lin and Lee Yuan-tseh, president of Academia Sinica
and a Nobel laureate, will hold a news conference this Saturday to
further elaborate their cause.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Chien Hsi-chieh, a former legislator and now
executive director of Peacetime Foundation of Taiwan, will join the
relay Friday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ruling and opposition parties had mixed reactions
to the latest appeal from Lin and his anti-nuclear supporters.
</P>
<P>
The DPP caucus in the Legislative Yuan presented Lin with
flowers, saying that they will give him full support.
</P>
<P>
Tsai Huang-lang, DPP party whip in the legislature, said that
when Lin and Lee Yuan-tseh recently asked all parties to honor their
promises to halve the number of legislative seats, the DPP said that
the party would "support it 100 percent, " and would ask other
political parties to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
But the Kuomintang (KMT) , the largest opposition party in the
legislature, and its ally, the People First Party (PFP), said that
Lin has a political ax to grind and that they "don't want to dance to
Lin's tune."
</P>
<P>
Liao Feng-teh, KMT party whip in the legislature, said that Lin's
move aims actually to campaign for President Chen.
</P>
<P>
Hsu Yen-kuo, PFP party whip in the legislature, said that though
the party has high respect for the high moral standard of Lin, it
believes that Lin "has no need to campaign for himself in this way."
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
