<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN  FIRST IN ASIA FOR  GENDER EQUALITY: VICE PRESIDENT LU
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 1 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Vice President Annette Lu said Monday that
Taiwan ranks first among Asian countries and 21st globally in gender
equality.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference held in downtown Taipei for the
opening of a series of activities marking March 8 Women's Day, Lu
voiced the hope that the country's gender equality ranking will be
upgraded to be in the top 10 globally.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan began to see the development of new feminism prior to the
lifting of martial law, Lu said, adding that she will try to put
together all information concerning the evolution of the movement.
</P>
<P>
The vice president further said that there are 11 women
presidents and prime ministers as well as five women vice presidents
in the world.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Commission for Women's Rights and Interests
Promotion under the Executive Yuan also touted various achievements
made by the commission over the past four years, including increasing
government spending on women-related affairs, the passage of a
platform of women's policies and the upgrading of women's
participation in political activities.
</P>
<P>
The eight-day event, sponsored by the Ministry of the Interior,
will include exhibitions of objet's d'art and forums on women's
issues. Lu and Premier Yu Shyi-kun have been invited to exchange
views on women's affairs-related issues during the forums scheduled
to be held March 6 and 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
