<HEADLINE>
ABOUT 10 PERCENT OF TOTAL POLICE FORCE TO GUARD AGAINST VOTE-BUYING
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  1 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More than 5,000 policemen have been
mobilized to assist in a national campaign to prevent vote-buying in
the run-up to the March 20 presidential election, a spokesman for the
National Police Administration (NPA) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
An additional 5,904 policemen have been organized into 1,476
units to join the current force of 154 people in 38 groups which are
normally in charge of probing fraud, according to the NPA official.
</P>
<P>
The more than 6,000 agents account for nearly 10 percent of the
nation's total police force of 70,000, the NPA official said.
</P>
<P>
The newly organized special task force will mainly focus their
evidence collecting and monitoring on those individuals who have been
proven to be or allegedly involved in irregularities related to
vote-buying or violence in past elections, the official said, adding
that the members of the force have been equipped with advanced
digital video cameras since Jan. 10 to record evidence.
</P>
<P>
Irregularities such as giving money or gifts, hosting free
parties or picnics and travel, as well as wagering on and violent
interference in the outcome of the election will be closely watched,
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040301.0026" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT CHEN OVERTAKES LIEN IN LATEST DPP POLL
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 1 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian now leads his sole
challenger, chairman of the opposition Kuomintang (KMT) Lien Chan, by
three percentage points, or the largest margin since November,
according to the latest survey conducted by the ruling Democratic
Progressive Party (DPP).
</P>
<P>
Wu Nai-jen, spokesman for the DPP ticket of President Chen and
Vice President Annette Lu, said that the party was greatly boosted by
the successful mobilization of over one million people to form a
mammoth human chain throughout Taiwan over the weekend to mark the
Feb. 28 Peace Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
The human chain activitity successfully gave momentum to the
Chen-Lu ticket, propelling their support rating to a new high, while
seeing the support rate for the rival team, the "pan-blue alliance"
of Lien and his running mate, James Soong, chairman of the People
First Party, hit a new low, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Wu said, DPP support from undecided voters increased
by between 3 percent and 5 percent, while support from those aged
20-29 widened to 8 percent. The DPP ticket also continues to lead in
the 50-59 age group, and only lags the "pan-blue alliance" slightly
in the 30-49 age group, he added.
</P>
<P>
In southern Taiwan, traditionally the bastion of the DPP's core
supporters, the DPP's lead has been more than 15 percent. The DPP has
a modest lead in central Taiwan, while in Taoyuan, Hsinchu and
Miaoli, it has narrowed the gap with the rival camp.
</P>
<P>
There is still no improvement for the DPP in Taipei City or
eastern Taiwan, Wu said, where the DPP ticket is behind by 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that the DPP has to make extra efforts to whip up the
support rate for Chen-Lu ticket in these areas.
</P>
<P>
But he said, "Overall, the DPP is cautiously optimistic about the
March 20 presidential election."
</P>
<P>
Chiou I-jen, secretary-general of the Chen-Lu ticket, also said
that the "hand-in-hand" human chain event helped break the stalled
presidential campaign and give the DPP a clear lead.
</P>
<P>
But with less than three weeks away from the March 20 election,
neither camp can let down their guard, Chiou said.
</P>
<P>
"Although the DPP is getting better day by day, " he said, "the
party will continue doing all it can to keep a solid lead until we
win the election."
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
