<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN TO JOIN ADVISORY CENTER ON WTO LAW
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Geneva, Feb. 29 (CNA)
(By Neil Lu and P.C. Tang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan will join the Advisory Center on WTO
Law (ACWL) under the name of "Taiwan, Penghu, Kinmen, Matsu Seperate
Customs Territories" next month, a well-placed source in Geneva said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The source said that in order to deal with relevant legal affairs
as well as challenges it might face in future trade dispute
settlement within the World Trade Organization, Taiwan has decided to
join the center. Taiwan became a member of the WTO at the start of
2002.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that the island has completed all the necessary
procedures for joining the ACWL, the source said that Yen
Ching-chang, Taiwan's permanent representative to the WTO, is
expected to sign an accession agreement with the center March 8 on
the government's behalf.
</P>
<P>
The ACWL, which is a public international organization
independent of the WTO, was established in 2001 to provide legal
advice on WTO law, support in WTO dispute settlement proceedings, and
training in WTO law to developing countries and customs territories,
countries with economies in transition and least developed countries.
</P>
<P>
As of Jan. 1, 2004, the ACWL had 20 developing country members
entitled to the services of the center and nine developed country
members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
