<HEADLINE>
MOE TO REDUCE CLASS SIZES IN FACE OF DWINDLING STUDENT NUMBERS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 1 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ministry of Education (MOE) hopes to
make elementary school class sizes smaller in view of the sharply
declining numbers of new students, an education official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Vice Education Minister Wu Ming-ching made the remarks while
giving a report at a Legislative Yuan budget committee meeting to
review the implementation of the central government's 2002 budget.
</P>
<P>
The ministry estimated last month that the number of Grade 1
students enrolling for the new school year which begins September
will be about 284,000, or the lowest figure in half a century.
</P>
<P>
Legislator Tang Chin-chuan from the ruling Democratic Progressive
Party (DPP) noted that the number of children born in Taiwan in 2003
was only about 220,000, down almost 100,000 from the figure for 1997.
</P>
<P>
He said this will surely affect the number of new student
enrollments which in turn will have a serious impact on the future
development of the nation's education system.
</P>
<P>
Wu responded by saying that a seminar was held on the issue last
week, with participants coming to an initial consensus on reducing
class sizes from the current level of about 30 to 40 students per
class.
</P>
<P>
"The ministry will take the opportunity to reduce class sizes,
but it will not move in the direction of cutting the number of
classes or teachers," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
