<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 1 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Monday, March 1, or the 11th day
of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according to the
lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that have
occurred on this date in the past:

1555: The "Book of Centuries," a book of prophecies telling the
500-year history of the future, is published in France by
Nostradamus, or Michel de Notredame, French physician and astrologer.

1562: Catholics massacre more than 1,000 Huguenot Protestants at
Vassy in France, starting the First War of Religion.

1803: Ohio becomes the 17th state of the United States.

1810: Frederic Chopin, Polish-born French composer and pianist of
the romantic era, is born.

1872: Yellowstone becomes the world's first national park.

1880: Pennsylvania becomes the first U.S. state to abolish
slavery.

1919: The March 1st Movement, or the Samil Independence Movement,
starts in Korea.

1934: Henry Pu Yi is enthroned as the "Emperor of Manchukuo" in
Changchun by Japanese militarists.

1941: The first session of the Second People's Political Council
is convened in Chungking.

1947: Hua Nan Commercial Bank, Ltd. is inaugurated in Taiwan.

1949: Boxer Joe Louis retires at the age of 35 after
having beaten 25 contenders competing for his title.

1950: After relocating from mainland China to Taiwan, Republic of
China President Chiang Kai-shek resumes office.

1950: Chiang Wei-kuo becomes brigade commander of the ROC
military's armored force tank division.

1954: The United States explodes the world's first full-scale
hydrogen bomb on the tiny Bikini Atoll in the South Pacific with what
is hailed as complete success.

1955: The Taiwan provincial government approves the renaming of
Taiwan Provincial Teachers College as National Taiwan Normal
University.

1958: Construction of the section of the East-West Cross-Island
Highway stretching from Taroko to Tienhsiang is completed.

1960: An earthquake and tsunami hit Morocco, killing more than
10,000 people and leaving more than 30,000 homeless.

1961: President John F. Kennedy of the United States sets up the
Peace Corps to work in Third World countries.

1966: The Soviet spacecraft Venus III lands on its namesake, the
second planet from the Sun.

1976: President Yen Chia-kan receives Acred F. Miossi, executive
vice president of U.S. firm Continental Bank.

1979: The U.S. embassy in Taipei formally closes, to be succeeded
by the American Institute in Taiwan.

1979: The Washington Office of the Coordination Council for North
American Affairs of the Republic of China opens.

1984: The ROC's first domestically developed jet trainer, the
AT-3, Rolls off the assembly line. The twin-seater, fitted with two
Garrett TFE 731-2-2L engines, each with a thrust of 1,590 kilograms,
was developed by the Aeronautical Institute of Science and
Technology.

1985: Legislator Tsai Cheng-chou is detained on charges of being
involved in bank fraud involving the Taipei 10th Credit Cooperative.

1990: The Executive Yuan approves direct trade between the
Republic of China and both the Soviet Union and Albania.

1995: The National Health Insurance program is formally
inaugurated.

1997: The cities of Taipei and Kaohsiung officially launch a
system that prohibits physicians from directly dispensing medicine.

2000: The ruling Kuomintang's Discipline Commission expels from
the party 16 of independent presidential candidate James Soong's
supporters.

2000: The Cabinet-level Overseas Chinese Affairs Commission
inaugurates a satellite television channel, called MSTV, to provide
TV programming free of charge to overseas Chinese around the world.

2001: Koo Chen-fu, chairman of Taiwan's Straits Exchange
Foundation, says that "one China, different interpretations" is the
only way to break the impasse between Beijing and Taipei over the
so-called "one China" issue.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "The general of an army may be
carried off, but a man of the common people cannot be robbed of his
free will."
</TEXT>
