WATCHDOG PASSES IMPEACHMENT AGAINST FORMER HOPING HOSPITAL STAFF
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  2 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Control Yuan Tuesday adopted an
impeachment resolution against two medical staff of the Taipei
Municipal Hoping Hospital because of their part in a mass
transmission of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) at the
facility early last year.
</P>
<P>
The impeachment proposal against Hoping Hospital Superintendent
Wu Kang-wen and Infection Division Chief Lin Jung-ti, co-authored by
Control Yuan members Chao Chang-ping, Chang Teh-ming, Lee Shen-yi and
Liao Chien-nan, was approved 8-1 during a session of the screening
committee of the country's supreme watchdog.
</P>
<P>
According to the resolution, Wu, who was in charge of the
hospital's administrative affairs and served concurrently as convener
of a task force on SARS infection control, failed to conduct tough
supervision, thorough planning and strict enforcement of various SARS
prevention measures inside the hospital.
</P>
<P>
Lin, for his part, did not inform his colleagues that patients
suspected of having been infected with the potentially fatal disease
were hospitalized in the municipal medical facility, thus leading to
a mass transmission inside the hospital, the resolution indicates.
</P>
<P>
The outbreak of SARS was first reported at the Hoping Hospital in
April 2003, from where the disease spread to other hospitals around
the island, creating a serious impact on the country's economic
development. The disease also claimed 37 lives in Taiwan.
</P>
