<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN WOMAN ASKS TAICHUNG MAYOR TO HELP SEARCH FOR MISSING SON
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taichung,  Taipei, March 2 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The mother of a U.S. citizen who
went missing in Taiwan last May paid a visit to Taichung Mayor Jason
Hu Tuesday to ask for his assistance in her search for her missing
son.
</P>
<P>
Barbara Klita, who has made several visits to Taiwan to search
for her son, Fryderyk Mieszko Frontier, told Hu that her son was
attracted by Taiwan's beautiful scenery and came to the island to
take up an English teaching job.
</P>
<P>
Hu encouraged Klita not to give up her hope and continue her
search for her son.
</P>
<P>
Hu, who once served as minister of foreign affairs and as
Taiwan's representative to the United States, wrote a letter in
Chinese to help Klita overcome language barriers when she travels to
other parts of the island to seek local police assistance in the
search of her missing son.
</P>
<P>
Hu also telephoned Hualien County Magistrate Hsieh Shen-shan in
eastern Taiwan to ask him whether he can offer more help to Klita.
</P>
<P>
Frontier arrived in Taiwan May 20, 2003 to take up an English
teaching job at a branch of the Hess Educational Organization in
Chungho, Taipei County, but did not show up for a pre-job training
program May 25 as originally scheduled.
</P>
<P>
According to a National Police Administration (NPA) probe,
Frontier stayed at Taipei hostel after his arrival in Taiwan. He told
a hostel information desk staffer that he was going to make a trip to
eastern Taiwan before reporting to Hess for work. Frontier left his
luggage at the Hess Chungho branch before departing for the eastern
county of Hualien.
</P>
<P>
NPA officials said Frontier stayed at the Catholic hostel in
Tienhsiang, in Taroko National Park, from May 21 through May 24. He
checked out of the hostel May 25 and has not been heard from since.
</P>
<P>
The NPA has said on many occasions that it has directed the
Hualien County Police Bureau and the Taroko National Park police to
step up the search for Frontier. Moreover, it urged local citizens to
come forward with any information they might have regarding his
whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
"Anyone who has information about the whereabouts of Frontier is
welcome to contact the NPA's foreign affairs office at (02) 2393-0989
or (02) 2394-0238, or the Hualien County Police Bureau at (03)
738-2000," an NPA official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Frontier stands 186 cm tall, weighs 96 kilograms and has curly
brown hair, according to NPA data. He was 28 years old when he came
to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued by the American Institute in
Taiwan in mid-July, Frontier called his former roommate in the United
States May 22, saying that he was going to visit a national park and
return to Taipei May 25. He also expressed an interest in going
hiking and visiting the southern city of Kaohsiung.
</P>
</TEXT>
