<HEADLINE>
TAIPEI PORT BECOMES AUXILIARY PORT TO KEELUNG HARBOR
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  2 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Transportation and Communications Vice
Minister Tsai Tui announced Tuesday the formal upgrading of Taipei
Port as an auxiliary port to the international Keelung Harbor in
northern Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Tsai made the announcement at a ceremony to mark the event, in
which Taipei County Vice Magistrate Lin Shi-yao and Pali township
chief Ker Ching-chang also took part.
</P>
<P>
With its existing three wharves, Taipei Port, in Taipei County's
Pali, will be expanded to a compound with 12 wharves by March 2008,
capable of berthing vessels of more than 80,000 tons, Tsai said,
adding that comprehensive port facilities will be available for lease
and private investment.
</P>
<P>
In line with the upgrading of Taipei Port from a gravel port to
an international container port, the Taipei county government has
also kicked off road construction to help better link the port with
nearby transport facilities, Tsai said.
</P>
<P>
The expanded port, including a special zone undergoing screening
by the central government, will become even more competitive and
productive if it forms an air-sea joint transportation network with
Chiang Kai-shek International Airport -- Taiwan's leading air travel
gateway in neighboring Taoyuan County.
</P>
<P>
In the short term, the port will see many distribution companies
set up shop in its compound, creating many job opportunities and
boosting Pali's economic development.
</P>
<P>
Ker hailed the port's expansion as a historic chance for Pali's
development.
</P>
<P>
China Motor General Manager Su Ching-yang said he hopes to sell
more than 150,000 sets of car accessories this year through a planned
automobile distribution center in the port, outperforming last year's
120,000 sets.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile that day, a distribution company that signed an
agreement with the port authorities to open a hub in July in the
compound has promised to offer 350 job opportunities for Pali
residents in the initial stage, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The company's chairman, Hung Chen-tung, said that Taipei Port
will provide a sound environment for the automobile industry because
of its low rates and distribution capacities, especially after a free
trade zone is approved to be set up in the port.
</P>
</TEXT>
