<HEADLINE>
CABINET TO BEGIN DISTRIBUTION OF REFERENDUM PUBLICITY BROCHURES
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 2 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Cabinet said Tuesday it has completed
printing what it described as a well-designed publicity pamphlet to
help local voters understand the rationale of Taiwan's first-ever
nationwide referendum to be held alongside the March 20 presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet spokesman Lin Chia-lung said grassroots administrative
offices will begin to distribute copies of the new pamphlet to local
households Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"A total of 8 million copies will be printed to guide the
electorate on how to vote in the upcoming referendum," Lin said.
</P>
<P>
The pamphlet's cover features a railway ticket from Yungkang to
Paoan in the southern Taiwan county of Tainan, dated March 20, 2004.
The two townships' Chinese names mean "ensuring peace and prosperity
permanently." The ticket also carries the nation's official title of
the Republic of China and the Chinese characters meaning "valid
forever."
</P>
<P>
"The cover design is aimed at reminding local voters that their
ballots in the referendum will help ensure Taiwan's permanent
well-being and sustainable development," Lin said.
</P>
<P>
The pamphlet covers five chapters, with each chapter expounding
on a single theme. The topics range from the meaning of referendum,
the significance of the March 20 "peace referendum," clarification of
various "misunderstandings" as to the possible impact of the
referendum and how to vote in the referendum.
</P>
<P>
The brochure also explains that each voter will receive a
presidential election gazette and a referendum gazette
simultaneously, as the two events will be held on the same day.
</P>
<P>
It also contains an illustration featuring the reverse U
shape-voting layout at polling stations. According to the pamphlet,
voters will receive white ballots for the presidential election
first. They must mark their choices and cast their ballots into a
white box before they can proceed to the other counter to receive two
referendum ballots -- one in light pink and the other in dark yellow.
After putting stamps on the two ballots, they have to cast their
ballots into two separate boxes of the same colors.
</P>
<P>
Voters will be asked whether Taiwan should install more
anti-missile batteries in the face of mainland China's intensified
military threat and whether Taiwan should negotiate a viable
mechanism with Beijing for peaceful interaction. The two questions
will be printed on two separate ballots.
</P>
<P>
Lin said overseas Taiwanese who do not have legal residence in
Taiwan but have registered with the nation's overseas offices to
return for the election do not have the right to cast ballots in the
referendum. "They can only vote in the presidential election, " he
explained.
</P>
<P>
Lin said the Government Information Office (GIO) has produced two
TV commercials urging voters to cast their ballots in the historic
referendum to show the world and Beijing's leaders the Taiwan
people's determination to safeguard their homeland through peace.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Lin said, the GIO will distribute 400 "beautifully
designed" publicity posters to attract voters' interest in the
referendum.
</P>
</TEXT>
