<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040302.0018" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
CREDIT DEPARTMENTS TAKEOVERS SUBJECT TO JUDICIAL INTERPRETATION: YU
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 2 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Premier Yu Shyi-kun said Tuesday that any
disputes over the takeover of 36 credit departments of local farmers'
and fishermen's associations by domestic commercial banks must be
resolved through a constitutional interpretation by the Council of
Grand Justices.
</P>
<P>
Yu made the remarks while fielding questions at a general
interpellation session of the Legislative Yuan, during which
Legislator Liu Cheng-hung, of the opposition Kuomintang, and
Legislator Cheng Mei-lan, of the People First Party, lashed out at
the Ministry of Finance for its policy of allowing commercial banks
to take over the 36 credit departments.
</P>
<P>
During their joint interpellation, the two lawmakers pointed out
that some of the credit departments' assets were under-appraised when
taken over by the government-designated banks, thus violating
people's property rights as set forth by the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
In response, Yu said that the takeover of credit departments is
not tantamount to the takeover of farmers' and fishermen's property.
If there are any different views on relevant laws and regulations,
such disputes should be settled through a constitutional
interpretation by the Council of Grand Justices.
</P>
<P>
The reason why the 36 credit departments were taken over was
because such institutions were poorly-managed and the net value of
their assets was negative, the premier claimed, adding that rights
and interests of local farmers and fishermen would have been
seriously affected if the government had not implemented the
management system.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Ministry of Finance issued a position paper,
clarifying that the takeover of the 36 poorly-managed credit
departments was conducted in conformity with the regulations
governing merging of financial institutions as well as the Statutes
for the Establishment and Management of Financial Restructuring Fund.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Progressive Party-led government launched a
financial reform program for local-level credit cooperatives in
August 2001, and it has so far taken over 36 debt-ridden credit
departments of farmers and fishermen's associations while planning to
liquidate those with serious overdue loan problems.
</P>
<P>
According to the program announced by the Ministry of Finance,
local-level credit cooperatives whose overdue loan ratios exceed 25
percent should stop offering new loans, should not raise capital from
their respective members, and must accept government assistance in
management.
</P>
<P>
In the same announcement, the ministry said those local-level
credit cooperatives whose overdue loan ratios stand at between 15
percent and 25 percent should not take any new deposits from
non-members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
