<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL LIAISON POLICE COULD HELP TAIWAN INVESTIGATIONS: CIB
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 2 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Police in Taiwan are considering sending
liaison officers overseas to deal with the growing trend of
international criminal activities, the Criminal Investigation Bureau
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made following recent cooperation among
Taiwan, the United States and Philippine police forces which led to
the discovery and seizure of an illegal drug production factory
operated by Taiwanese in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Criminal Investigation Bureau officers said they have established
closer ties with the international police organization Interpol, and
the next step is to post officers overseas to help with cross-border
investigations.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that in Europe, the United States and Japan, law
enforcement liaison officers are stationed in foreign embassies to
foster closer contact with the local police.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment of a liaison officer will enhance exchanges of
information, broaden investigations into multi-national crimes and
help in tracking down fugitives," they added.
</P>
<P>
Given Taiwan's relative political isolation, its inability to
sign binding extradition treaties or obtain judicial assistance from
foreign countries, law enforcers in Taiwan are often left with few
resources to pursue criminals who have fled the country.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of a liaison officer system would address this
issue, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
