<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040302.0022" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT CHEN VISITS LEGISLATIVE REFORM HUNGER STRIKERS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 2 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian threw his support
behind the proposal to halve the number of legislative seats when he
paid a visit to a group of demonstrators in front of the Legislative
Yuan Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators, lead by Lin Yi-hsiung, a former chairman of
the ruling Democratic Progressive Party, launched a 240-hour relay
hunger strike at the legislature courtyard Monday to push for the
passage of a constitutional amendment bill before the March 20
presidential election to pave the way for the much-anticipated
reduction of legislative seats.
</P>
<P>
The 10-day demonstration, organized by the Nuke-4 Referendum
Initiative Association (Nuke-4 RIA) , is being conducted in 24-hour
shifts. President Chen arrived at the demonstration site early in
the morning as the first 24-hour sit-in ended at 10 a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In addition to signing his name on a petition asking to halve the
225-seat legislature jointly initiated by Lin and Academia Sinica
President Lee Yuan-tseh, Chen shook hands with Lin and other
demonstrators to show his regard and support for them.
</P>
<P>
Chen said although the opposition-controlled legislature has
formed a special committee in charge of Constitution-amending
affairs, the committee has yet to call its first meeting.
</P>
<P>
During the 2001 legislative election campaign, Chen recalled that
candidates from across the political spectrum backed the legislative
downsizing proposal.
</P>
<P>
"More than two years have passed; the proposal remains on the
drawing board, " Chen said, adding that the opposition "pan-blue
alliance" of the Kuomintang (KMT) and the People First Party (PFP) ,
which controls a majority in the legislature, is responsible for the
delay of this important legislative reform program.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that both the DPP and its ally -- the Taiwan Solidarity
Union -- fully support the halving of legislative seats, Chen said
the "pan-blue alliance's" reluctance to cooperate has hindered
legislative reform.
</P>
<P>
As long as KMT Chairman Lien Chan and PFP Chairman James Soong
give the green light, Chen said he is convinced that the legislature
can easily pass a constitutional amendment bill to pave the way for
halving the number of legislative seats.
</P>
<P>
"I earnestly hope that lawmakers of different political stripes
can deliver on their campaign promise and pass a seat-reduction bill
before March 20 in response to Lin's appeal," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Braving cold wind and rain, Lin and other demonstrators, most of
whom are opponents of the nation's controversial Fourth Nuclear Power
Plant now under construction in Taipei County, staged the peaceful
hunger strike.
</P>
<P>
Lin said he would continue the sit-in fast after the first
24-hour session ended. He expressed gratitude for President Chen's
concern about his group's cause.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the Nuke-4 RIA's current campaign is aimed at
promoting the establishment of a refined political culture
characterized by honesty and credibility, Lin said he hopes all
domestic political figures can faithfully honor their campaign
promises.
</P>
<P>
"We are fed up with politicians making promises and breaking them
so easily. As legislative reforms and reduction of legislative seats
have become mainstream public opinions, top leaders of various
political parties should direct their lawmakers to take action to
realize the goal of halving the legislative seats as the first step
of legislative reforms," Lin urged.
</P>
<P>
Lin said he and Academia Sinica President Lee will unveil the
results of their signature campaign for the legislative reform
initiative at a joint news conference this Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on "pan-blue alliance" lawmakers' claim that the DPP
administration should call a referendum on the fate of the half-built
Fourth Nuclear Power Plant instead of the so-called "peace
referendum" against mainland China's missile threat, Lin said the
Referendum Act passed last November doesn't authorize the Cabinet to
hold a referendum on the nuclear power plant.
</P>
<P>
Under the current Referendum Act, Lin said, only civic groups can
initiate a nuclear power plant referendum with the endorsement of
700,000 individual citizens.
</P>
<P>
"It's a tall order for any civic group to secure such a large
number of endorsements," Lin said, adding that this seriously flawed
Referendum Act should be revised and improved in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
