<HEADLINE>
PASSENGER, CARGO TRAVEL GROWS RAPIDLY AT CKS TERMINAL
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 26 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The number of passengers and the volume of
cargo handled at the Chiang Kai-shek International Airport in
northern Taiwan has been growing every year since its operations
began 25 years ago, except for last year which saw outbreaks of
severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) , according to airport
statistics.
</P>
<P>
The tallies compiled by airport authorities show that a total of
a little more than four million passengers entered, left and
transferred in Taiwan via the airport in 1979 after it began
operations on Feb. 26 of that year.
</P>
<P>
The figure rose to top 10 million in 1990 and peaked at 19.22
million in 2002 -- the largest number of passengers ever seen by the
Taiwan's largest air travel gateway, which is located in Taoyuan
County.
</P>
<P>
In 2003, the number of passengers using the airport dropped to
15.51 million as a result of the outbreaks of the potentially deadly
SARS, a level similar to that recorded in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the volume of cargo dealt with by the airport
registered an all-time high of over 1.5 billion kilograms last year
-- 829 million kilograms of imports and 671 million kilograms of
exports, an astounding jump from its first-year level of 117 million
kilograms, the same statistic show.
</P>
</TEXT>
