<HEADLINE>
RIOTING HIGHLY UNLIKELY AFTER PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION: DEFENSE MINISTRY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 2 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rioting after the March 20 presidential
election and referendum vote is highly unlikely given that the people
of Taiwan have become very familiar with democratic elections over
the years, a Ministry of National Defense spokesman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Maj. Gen. Huang Suey-sheng made the remarks at a regular news
conference when he was asked about the possibility of unrest after
the election.
</P>
<P>
Pollsters say the race is currently too close to call. Incumbent
President Chen Shui-bian and Vice President Annette Lu are facing off
against opposition Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan and his running
mate, James Soong, chairman of the People First Party. Taiwan will
also be holding its first nationwide referendum on election day.
</P>
<P>
Huang said that the defense ministry has received no instructions
indicating that there could be trouble to the extent that a state of
emergency could be declared after the election.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the nation's armed forces are, as usual, always
refining their combat preparedness to ensure national security. The
defense ministry is also well aware of any military movements of the
mainland Chinese military, especially regarding those of its missiles
and submarine forces.
</P>
<P>
Huang said that mainland China's military is not doing anything
out of the ordinary currently. "If there are any unusual activities,
the ROC Army will act accordingly."
</P>
<P>
In addition, a 39-hour heightened alert will be in effect before,
during and after the March 20 election, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
He said that from 5 p.m. March 19 to 8 a.m. March 21, the armed
forces on duty in Taiwan proper or on the outlying islands will be on
round-the-clock heightened alert so that "the public will cast their
ballots in a safe and secure environment."
</P>
<P>
On possible rioting by supporters of different camps, Huang said,
"I believe this will not happen, judging from the experience the
people of Taiwan have had in numerous elections over the years."
</P>
<P>
The army is mainly concerned with foreign threats, Huang said,
and will leave possible rioting to the National Police
Administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
