<HEADLINE>
MAN SAYS SMUGGLED HEROIN ONLY TO RELIEVE HIS SUFFERING
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 2 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A man who was arrested Monday night for
smuggling heroin into Taiwan said that he was bringing in the drug to
ease his pain caused by cancer.
</P>
<P>
The cancer patient, who also admitted that he had become a drug
addict since being diagnosed with oral cancer, lympocancer, and
tuberculosis in 2002, was arrested at Kaohsiung International Airport
with heroin hidden in his shoes. He was returning from a trip to
mainland China, police said.
</P>
<P>
Police said Yen Kuo-hsien, 57, was stopped at the airport Monday
night because his shoes looked too big for his build and he was
acting suspiciously.
</P>
<P>
After a thorough check, they found heroin hidden in secret
compartments in his shoes, with 370.1 grams in his left shoe and
297.9 grams in the right one. The 668 grams of heroin has an
estimated street value of NT$10 million (US$301,200).
</P>
<P>
Yen told police that after being diagnosed with cancer he began
smoking more than 10 heroin-laced cigarettes a day to relieve his
suffering.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Yen went to Zhuhai for sightseeing, where he met a
woman in a park who was doing drugs. Yen asked her how he could get
heroin and how much it would cost.
</P>
<P>
He went to Zhuhai again Feb. 26 this year and through the woman
bought NT$650,000-worth of heroin from a man.
</P>
<P>
Yen was turned over to the Kaohsiung Prosecutors' Office for
violating the drug prevention law.
</P>
<P>
Police are now investigating whether Yen was part of a smuggling
ring that uses people with cancer or who are terminally ill as
couriers to bring in illegal substances.
</P>
</TEXT>
