<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040302.0036" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN TO JOIN WTO LEGAL ADVISORY CENTER
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  2 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs said
Tuesday that Taiwan will join the Advisory Center on WTO Law (ACWL)
soon to obtain a full understanding of the rights and obligations
under the World Trade Organization (WTO) system.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular news conference, Pu Kuo-ching, a section
chief with the foreign ministry's treaty and legal affairs division,
said the Republic of China will become a formal ACWL member next
month under the designation of the "Separate Customs Territory of
Taiwan, Penghu, Kinmen and Matsu."
</P>
<P>
According to ACWL rules, Taiwan has to pay an admission fee of
US$300,000. Pu said Taiwan has completed all membership application
procedures and that the ROC's representative to the WTO will sign an
entry protocol in Geneva March 8 on behalf of the government.
</P>
<P>
Besides Taiwan, Pu said, several other countries, including
Switzerland and El Salvador, are also seeking to join the ACWL to
acquire legal counseling about the WTO agreements, particularly its
disputes settlement mechanism.
</P>
<P>
Pu said the ACWL was established in July 2001 as a unique
inter-governmental organization, independent of the WTO, to provide
legal advice to developing and least-developed countries, customs
territories and economies. Its nine founding members -- Canada,
Denmark, Finland, Ireland, Italy, Holland, Norway, Sweden and Britain
-- have each donated US$1 million to help finance ACWL operations. So
far 23 developing countries have joined the organization.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the WTO has created a complex legal system with
elaborate procedures for the settlement of disputes, Pu said
effective access to those procedures is essential to ensure the
enforcement and maintenance of each WTO member's rights.
</P>
<P>
"After joining the ACWL, we'll obtain legal advice on WTO laws,
acquire support in WTO dispute settlement proceedings and receive
assistance in training of government officials in WTO laws through
seminars and other applicable means," Pu added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
