<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040302.0044" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
DILUTED SMALLPOX VACCINE DOSE EQUALLY EFFECTIVE: NTU RESEARCHERS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 2 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Diluted smallpox vaccine doses are equally
effective in producing antibodies in humans as doses that have not
been diluted, researchers at National Taiwan University (NTU)
announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Chang Shang-chun, director of NTU Hospital's Department of
Infectious Disease, said diluted doses are as effective in allowing
people to ward off smallpox in the event of a bioterrorism attack.
</P>
<P>
As Taiwan currently has roughly 2 million undiluted doses of
smallpox vaccine, the island has enough vaccine for the entire
population if the doses are diluted, Chang noted.
</P>
<P>
Clinical tests on more than 200 volunteers conducted at the NTU
Hospital over the past several months found that all three groups of
volunteers -- vaccinated with five-fold diluted, 10-fold diluted and
30-fold diluted smallpox vaccine doses, respectively -- showed
satisfactory results in terms of immunity to smallpox, Chang said.
</P>
<P>
Laboratory analysis found that 100 percent of the volunteers who
had previously received smallpox vaccination showed immune response
when administered with a 30-fold diluted dose of smallpox vaccine,
while 100 percent of those who had not previously received a smallpox
vaccination showed an immune response when given a 10-fold diluted
dose, Chang said.
</P>
<P>
He said that side effects of smallpox vaccination include fever,
headache, muscle aches, lymphatic swelling and skin rashes, adding
that one out of every 1 million people may develop encephalitis and
die.
</P>
<P>
He noted that children under the age of one and seniors aged over
65 are discouraged to receive any kind of smallpox vaccine as they
have weaker immune systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040302.0045" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 2 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Tuesday, March 2, or the 12th
day of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according to
the lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that have
occurred on this date in the past:

1791: John Wesley, British religious leader and founder of
Methodism, dies at the age of 88.

1793: Sam Houston, the American soldier who was responsible for
winning control of Texas from Mexico and who became the first
president of the Republic of Texas, is born.

1864: President Abraham Lincoln, who led the Union during the
American Civil War, rejects Gen. Robert E. Lee's call for peace
talks, demanding surrender.

1900: Legation ministers of various countries in Beijing demand
that China's Ching court take severe disciplinary measures against
the "Righteous Harmony Fist" Boxers, who laid siege to the foreign
legation, where a combined force of Japanese, French, British,
Russian and American troops held out for over a month.

1931: Mikhail Gorbachev, the last president of the Soviet Union,
who introduced liberalizing reforms popularly referred to as
"Glasnost" and "Perestroika," is born.

1943: Allied planes sink 12 Japanese ships carrying
reinforcements into battle in New Guinea, killing nearly 4,000.

1946: Ho Chi Minh is elected president of North Vietnam.

1949: Captain James Gallagher lands at Forth Worth in Texas after
completing the first round-the-world nonstop flight aboard a U.S. Air
Force B-50 bomber.

1955: Floods kill 200 people and leave 400,000 others homeless in
Australia.

1956: The Ministry of Education of the Republic of China approves
the upgrading of Tainan College of Technology to National Chengkung
University.

1956: France and Morocco issue a joint statement recognizing
Morocco's independence.

1961: Four divisions of Communist Chinese troops enter northern
Burma in an attempt to wipe out ROC anti-communist guerrillas
remaining there.

1962: General Ne Win overthrows Premier U Nu in a military coup
in Burma.

1969: Communist Chinese and Soviet troops engage in heavy
fighting around Chenpao (Damansky) Island along their shared border,
with each side accusing the other of intruding upon their national
territory.

1969: The French prototype 001 Concorde, the supersonic
Anglo-French airliner, makes a successful first test flight from
Toulouse, France.

1971: Gen. Kim Kye Won, new Korean ambassador to the ROC, arrives
in Taipei to assume office.

1971: The first Australian Industrial and Trade display in the
ROC opens in Taipei.

1982: South Korea releases 2,863 political prisoners and reduces
the prison term of Kim Young Sam from life to 20 years. Kim would
later become president of the country.

1986: Taiwan's first confirmed AIDS patient dies.

1986: Queen Elizabeth II signs the Australian Bill, severing
Britain's formal ties with its former colony almost two centuries
after British convicts were first shipped to Botany Bay in 1788.

1989: The first Vietnamese boat people to volunteer to return
home leave Hong Kong.

1991: Referendums are held in both Latvia and Estonia, with most
people in the Baltic Sea countries voting for independence.

1994: The ROC and Belize sign a joint communique pledging
bilateral cooperation.

1996: The Labor Party led by Paul Keating suffers a massive
defeat in Australian elections.

2000: The ROC Navy dispatches a frigate to rescue crew members on
board the Cambodian freighter Golden Dragon, which suffered
mechanical failure off the coast of Oluanpi, Pintung County.

2001: ROC Vice President Annette Lu presides over a ceremony
where US$570,000 in cash and US$270,000 worth of relief goods are
formally donated to India which was hit by a devastating earthquake
on Jan 26.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "When the cold of winter comes, it
is then you know that the pine tree and the cypress are the last to
lose their green."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040303.0001" type="story" >
