<HEADLINE>
TWO DEBATERS  CALL FOR BOYCOTT OF REFERENDUM
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 3 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two privates citizens, including former
Democratic Progressive Party Chairman Hsu Hsin-liang, called for the
public to boycott the March 20 referendum in the second round of
televised debate on the two questions in the referendum Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In Wednesday's first debate of the first question in the
referendum -- whether the country should strengthen its anti-missile
defense system -- Chan Chao-li, a poet and activist for the right of
farmers and fishermen, questioned the government's wisdom in setting
aside NT$700 billion (US$)(US$21.02 billion) to buy anti-missile
defense systems from the United State when the country is trying to
borrow money to finance its 10 major construction projects.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the country has already run into debt of NT$9.3
trillion (US$279.27 billion), or NT$400,000 (US$12,012) per capita,
the poet said that the government is not in its right mind if it
wants to buy more weapons to fill its arsenal against this
background.
</P>
<P>
Instead of guaranteeing the country's safety, Chang warned that
the anti-missile defense system will only trigger a arms race between
Taiwan and the mainland and sink the country deeper into debt.
</P>
<P>
He urged his countrymen to steer clear of the referendum,
claiming that they can highlight their wisdom and the country's
democracy by refraining from voting in the referendum.
</P>
<P>
The speaker for the affirmative side in the debate, Deputy
Secretary-General to the President Joseph Wu overlooked his opponent
by making a strong appeal to his audience, saying moves toward
democracy always have had detractors, just as is the case regarding
the referendum.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of national defense and the
government's attention to the well-being of farmers and fishermen,
citing the country's ever-increasing social welfare expenditure as
evidence.
</P>
<P>
In the second debate, Hsu Hsin-liang argued against Minister
without Portfolio Yeh Chun-jung over whether the government should
negotiate with Beijing for the establishment of a peace and stability
interaction framework.
</P>
<P>
Hsu claimed a yes vote on the question will be tantamount to
forcing the government to accept Beijing's "one-China" policy because
the referendum question doesn't ask the country's negotiator to
defend Taiwan's sovereignty while Beijing's precondition for any
political talks with Taiwan is its "one-China" policy.
</P>
<P>
The government which is obliged to follow the result of the
referendum can't help but accept Beijing's prerequisite to open
negotiation with mainland China, Hsu claimed.
</P>
<P>
Yeh dismissed Hsu's worries, claiming it is out of the question
that the Democratic Progressive Party's administration would accept
the "one-China" policy simply for talks with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"Accept the 'one-China' policy would be a change of the country's
status quo which needs the consent of the people as the DPP has
always said," Ye argued.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's debate is the second of five rounds before March 14.
The Central Election Commission which organizes the debates hopes to
deepen the public's understanding of the referendum through these
debates.
</P>
</TEXT>
