<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040303.0008" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PLAN TO DEMAND FINANCIAL GUARANTEE FOR MAINLAND SPOUSES DELAYED
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 3 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan's new measure requiring local
residents to produce NT$5 million (US$151,050) as a financial
guarantee if they have mainland Chinese spouses who want to settle in
Taiwan will not come into force until June 1 this year, an official
with the Ministry of the Interior (MOI) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the newly revised regulations concerning the
settlement or residency of mainland Chinese people in Taiwan, the new
measure took effect March 1, but the MOI decided to extend a
three-month grace period after receiving strong complaints from local
residents and women's groups.
</P>
<P>
Vice Minister of the Interior Chien Tai-lang said that starting
from June 1, all Taiwanese residents that apply for permanent
settlement on behalf of their spouses from mainland China will have
to abide by the new regulations.
</P>
<P>
The revised regulations, in line with the Nationality Law,
stipulate that mainland people wanting to settle or reside in Taiwan
must meet certain financial conditions, such as an average monthly
income over the past year of at least twice Taiwan's basic salary of
NT$15,840 (US$477).
</P>
<P>
Failing that, their Taiwanese spouses must present evidence that
they have assets worth over NT$5 million so that they can provide for
their mainland spouses in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
If put into force, the new measure is expected to affect many
less wealthy Taiwanese residents who are considering marrying
mainland brides.
</P>
<P>
Chien also explained that only those who apply to come to Taiwan for
settlement will be required to provide the NT$5 million financial
guarantee, while those who only come to Taiwan to be reunited with
their families will not be required to post such a guarantee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040303.0009" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL HEADLINE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Washington, March 3 (CNA)
(By Jay Chen)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Washington Post: Kerry Locks Up the
Nomination; Edwards to Withdraw After Being Overwhelmed on Super
Tuesday.

Sen. John F. Kerry locked up the Democratic presidential
nomination last night with a coast-to-coast string of Super Tuesday
victories that included landslides in California, New York, Ohio and
Maryland, eliminating Sen. John Edwards from the race and setting up
what promises to be a divisive confrontation with President Bush in
the general election.
