<HEADLINE>
JAPAN IN DANGER IF TAIWAN IS UNIFIED WITH  MAINLAND CHINA: OBSERVER
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Tokyo, March 3 (CNA)
(By Perry Hsieh and Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan has a relatively mature democracy and
a free society, and no matter who wins the March 20 presidential
election, its democratic system will not experience drastic changes,
a senior editorial writer of a Japanese nationwide daily said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But Seiji Yajima of Sankei Shimbun also said that if Taiwan is
united with mainland China, the interests and security of Japan will
be seriously compromised.
</P>
<P>
The former chief of the daily's Taipei bureau made the remarks
while he delivered a speech at a meeting in Tokyo on Taiwan's
presidential election and its prospects.
</P>
<P>
He noted that both the United States and Japan have expressed
serious concerns about Taiwan's plan to hold a referendum alongside
the presidential election and asked for discretion, saying that both
have their own reasons and considerations when making the unexpected
diplomatic move.
</P>
<P>
However, the United States has basically maintained its
longstanding stance on its strategy and foreign policy toward Taiwan,
as well as friendly attitude, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Yajima said that the "hand-in-hand" human
chain rally held in Taiwan over the weekend by supporters of
President Chen Shui-bian was very successful, although it will be
hard to say whether the rally has successfully inspired voters or
made an effect on the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
He observed that President Chen and his sole rival, Kuomintang
Chairman Lien Chan, are still running neck and neck.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that because of the undecided voters and close
surveys, the situation may only become more clear in the last two
weeks to the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Yajima, who was in Kaohsiung when more than one million people
stretched along 500 kilometers of the island and joined hands to
shout "yes to Taiwan" and "no to China" Saturday afternoon, also said
that he was impressed by the event.
</P>
<P>
He said that because of the passion of the people, the number of
participants at the event had been bigger than expected. The rally
was conducted in a rational and peaceful fashion without chaos or any
unfavorable incidents.
</P>
<P>
He especially lauded the manners of the Taiwan people, saying
that immediately after the end of the activity, people began picking
up litter along the path of the human chain.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a Japanese lawmaker spoke about his recently concluded
visit to Taiwan on the same occasion.
</P>
<P>
Hirostao Nakatsugawa of the Democratic Party said that he was
positive of and impressed by Taiwan's democratization and
internalization.
</P>
<P>
He also reaffirmed support for Taiwan's referendum to be held in
tandem with the presidential election and lashed out again at the
Japanese Foreign ministry for interfering Taiwan's internal affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
