<HEADLINE>
CHUNGHWA TELECOM LAUNCHES VIDEO-ON-DEMAND SERVICE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  3 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
State-run Chunghwa Telecom officially
launched its video-on-demand service Wednesday after months of
trials.
</P>
<P>
The service, known as MOD or multimedia-on-demand, is similar to
a neighborhood video rental store, but is provided on the Chunghwa
Telecom's metropolitan network.
</P>
<P>
In a ceremony marking the inauguration of the service, Ho
Chen-tan, chairman of Chunghwa Telecom said subscribers can choose
video from 13 channels offered by the company through an additional
set-top box for a fee no greater than the current charge of NT$600
(US$18) for most cable television services. Chunghwa currently has
20,000 subscribers.
</P>
<P>
The 13 new channels will run content on entertainment, public
interest, education, news and movies.
</P>
<P>
The company is first offering the service in Taipei County and
will expand to Taipei City and other parts of the island, said Ho.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, President Chen Shui-bian said the
company's MOD service has partially realized his administration's
dream of using the newest technology to improve people's daily life.
</P>
<P>
Hung Chong-juan, deputy director-general of the Government
Information Office lauded this as a milestone in the country's
television broadcast industry, because "people now can choose not
only the president but TV programs."
</P>
<P>
Taipei County Magistrate Su Tseng-chang said Chen's "new"
administration is devoted to the development of new technology and
thereby deserves part of the credit in bringing about the MOD
service.
</P>
