<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040303.0013" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
COA TO INVEST NT$600 MILLION TO PROMOTE TAIWAN-GROWN FARM PRODUCE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 3 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Council of Agriculture (COA) under the
Executive Yuan will invest NT$600 million in the coming three years
to help promote Taiwan-made farm products in the international
market, according to a COA official.
</P>
<P>
Wang Ming-lai, director-general of the COA's International
Cooperation Department, made the remarks during a roundtable forum
held at the Central News Agency on how to effectively promote
Taiwan-made agricultural products in the international market.
</P>
<P>
In line with a global promotion package aimed at stepping up
Taiwan's exports of agricultural products, a budget of NT$300 million
will be earmarked to set up special export zones for locally grown
products, such as bananas, soybeans and papayas, while the other
NT$300 million will be invested to boost exports of Taiwan's flagship
agricultural products, such as orchids and oolong tea, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The first special zone for soybeans is scheduled to be
inaugurated on a 1,500 hectare plot of land in the southern county of
Pingtung, Wang noted, adding that the COA is also planning to
establish a banana export zone on land belonging to the state-run
Taiwan Sugar Corp. in Pingtung County.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, the COA will enhance quarantine measures in
the planned export zones to facilitate exports of Taiwan-grown
produce to foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
All lawmakers, government officials and representatives from the
domestic business community who attended the symposium threw their
support behind the COA project to upgrade the competitiveness of
local farm produce in the international market.
</P>
<P>
Legislator Lin Kuo-hua of the ruling Democratic Progressive Party
said that Taiwan opened its market to foreign farm products following
its entry into the World Trade Organization, so the government should
help local farmers seek new outlets for their quality farm products.
</P>
<P>
Citing lettuce produced in his constituency of Yunlin County as
an example, Lin said that it is of excellent quality and is usually
used by foreign restaurants to make salads, so it is a sufficiently
high standard for export to overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
Lin also proposed that the government procure streamlined
quarantine and inspection equipment for the planned special marketing
zone for local farm produce.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the same occasion, Yeh Ming-shui, marketing director
of the quasi-official Taiwan External Trade Development Council
(TETRA) , claimed that agricultural production costs in Taiwan are
very high because of a micro-agricultural system.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, it is imperative for domestic farmers to create an
excellent image to facilitate the promotion of their products in the
international market, Yeh said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
