<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN PROMOTES CHICKEN EXPORTS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  3 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan is promoting chicken exports,
targeting 18 regions and countries, including Japan, Hong Kong, Saudi
Arabia and Indonesia, a Council of Agriculture (COA) official said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
COA Vice Chairman Hu Fu-hsiung made the remarks in a meeting to
discuss infectious diseases among animals, which was presided over by
COA Chairman Lee Chin-lung and Hu Sheng-cheng, a minister without
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
The COA vice chairman noted that Taiwan is not an affected area
with regard to the virulent H5N1 avian flu virus, although local fowl
have been found to have been infected with H5N2, a less virulent
strain of the disease that nevertheless prompted the culling of tens
of thousands of chickens in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The COA will try to persuade countries such as Japan and Hong
Kong, which have reported bird flu cases in their countries, to
resume importing chicken from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Hu reported that it is known that the Czech Republic has agreed
to resume the imports of Taiwan fowl.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan chicken and duck is exported mostly to Japan, accounting
for 80 percent of total exports, followed by exports to Hong Kong,
accounting for 10 percent. Exports to the Czech Republic account for
little.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, which used to import chicken from Thailand, needs
to find alternative suppliers, since fowl in Thailand and mainland
China have became infected with avian flu, Hu said.
</P>
<P>
"If necessary, the COA will send officials to Saudi Arabia to
sell the idea of importing Taiwan chickens," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040303.0019" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS OPTIMISTIC ABOUT TAIWAN STOCK MARKET
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 3 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Players in the domestic stock market are
very optimistic about the market prospects, with a confidence index
on the bourse jumping by more than 200 percent recently, according to
the results of a survey made public on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, carried out jointly by Shih Hsin University and Win
Win Weekly, using indices worked out by UBS Securities Investment
Advisory (Taiwan) Ltd., finds that the confidence level of local
investors toward the stock market rose from 32.85 points in December
to 106.82 points in February, an astounding rise of 224 percent.
</P>
<P>
Judging from a cross analysis, male players are more optimistic
than female players, while high-income people are more optimistic
than low-income workers, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the weighted index -- the key barometer of the
domestic bourse -- stood at 6932.17. points as of Wednesday, close to
a nearly four-year high of 7,000 points. Some 56 percent of the stock
market players polled think that now is a good time to buy shares.
</P>
<P>
According to Win Win Weekly Chairman Liang Yung-huang, the
political ideology could affect players' investment willingness,
despite the fact that more than half of the stock players hold a
positive view toward the bourse.
</P>
<P>
Some 68 stock players who support the ruling Democratic
Progressive Party notched up profits in the last three months, ahead
of only 55 percent of the opposition backers who said they made
money, the survey points out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040303.0020" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT PLANS TO DEMAND FINANCIAL GUARANTEE FOR MAINLAND SPOUSES
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 3 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The government is planning to ask Taiwan
residents to produce NT$5 million (US$151,050) as a financial
guarantee if they have a mainland Chinese spouse who wants to settle
in Taiwan, which is in line with the existing practice for foreign
spouses of Taiwan residents, a government spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Lin Chia-lung made the remarks after the Executive Yuan approved
revised regulations concerning the settlement or residency of
mainland Chinese people in Taiwan the previous day.
</P>
<P>
The revised regulations, in line with the Nationality Law, state
that mainland people wanting to settle or reside in Taiwan must meet
certain financial conditions, such as an average monthly income over
the past year of at least twice Taiwan's basic salary of NT$15,840
(US$477).
</P>
<P>
Failing that, the Taiwan spouses must provide evidence that they
have assets worth over NT$5 million so that they can provide for
their mainland spouses in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Lin said that the measures worked out by the Ministry of the
Interior are "in line with international standards" and "will reduce
the burden on society, as well as protect the mainland spouses."
</P>
<P>
He said the measures "should not be considered as being hard on
the public."
</P>
<P>
However, the measures, if implemented, are bound to affect many
less wealthy Taiwan people who are considering marrying mainland
brides.
</P>
<P>
According to Lin, foreign people who apply to become ROC citizens
have to meet the financial threshold according to the Nationality Law
and mainland spouses should be no exception.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, only those who apply to come to Taiwan for
settlement will be required to provide the NT$5 million financial
guarantee, while those who only come to Taiwan to be reunited with
their families will not be required to post such a guarantee.
</P>
<P>
Noting that mainland spouses who come to Taiwan to settle will
enjoy social resources, welfare and benefits, Lin said that the
government has to make the revision based on the overall development
of society.
</P>
<P>
"The measures will also help prevent mainland spouses from
suffering in the event that the finances of their Taiwanese
dependents worsen."
</P>
<P>
Lin said that the revisions are based on "equal treatment" for
all people and are not aimed at "making it hard on people's rights to
marry."
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
