<HEADLINE>
RIVAL PARTIES BOTH ENDORSE WHITE PAPER ON SENIOR WELFARE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 3 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The two rival presidential election tickets
endorsed a white paper on welfare for the elderly Wednesday, with the
aim of ensuring that the country's senior citizens will be better
taken care of in years to come.
</P>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian endorsed the white paper, which was
drafted by the non-profit League of Welfare Improvement for Older
People (LWIOP) and passed at the national Silver-Haired Summit last
year, at the opening of the league's general meeting.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony, Chen said that he feels sorry
for the country's elderly for not having benefited from a
long-planned pension scheme.
</P>
<P>
If it had not been boycotted by the opposition parties, the
scheme would have taken force long before, with the abundant profits
generated from the public lottery over the past two years, Chen
claimed.
</P>
<P>
After Chen left, Legislative Yuan President Wang Jin-pyng -- who
is also election campaign manager for Chen's rival, opposition
Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan and his running mate, People First
Party Chairman James Soong -- arrived and endorsed the white paper on
Lien's behalf.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that at present, each of the country's senior citizens
receives NT$3,000 per month as a subsidy. The figure, he said, could
be raised to around NT$8,900 if the "pan-blue alliance" ticket of
Lien and Soong is elected in the March 20 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The LWIOP, a nationwide private organization established some 10
years ago to push for better welfare for senior citizens, had invited
both presidential rival sides to jointly endorse the welfare for the
elderly policies.
</P>
<P>
League officials said that regardless of which party wins the
election, welfare for the elderly should be bolstered rather than
compromised.
</P>
<P>
The LWIOP white paper provides 45 suggestions for the next
administration to implement. The suggestions include efforts to
respect the elderly, help the elderly lead independent lives,
facilitate their right to vote, and beef up services for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
