<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040303.0025" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
ORANGUTAN SENT TO U.K. UNDER COOPERATION PROGRAM
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Chiang Kai-shek International Airport,  Taoyuan,  March 3 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A
female orangutan was sent to Britain early Wednesday morning under a
great ape reproduction cooperation program between Taiwan and the
United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The red-haired primate, aged 12 and weighing 30 kilograms, was
handed over by zoologists from National Pingtung Technology
University (NPTU) to staff from Monkey World - Ape Rescue Center, a
aBritish primate conservation center, at the CKS International
Airport. The Monkey World personnel had traveled to Taiwan
exclusively for the purpose of taking the orangutan to her new home
in Britain.
</P>
<P>
China Airlines offered free transportation of the orangutan from
Taiwan to the United Kingdom to show its support for wildlife
conservation efforts.
</P>
<P>
The NPTU shelter for abandoned wild animals, located in the
southern county of Pingtung, has plans in place dating back to 1999
to send a total of eight orangutans to Britain for reproduction and
related research. The plan is being carried out under the assistance
of the Council of Agriculture (COA) as part of a cooperative program
with Monkey World. As of the end of 2002, five orangutans and 11
gibbons have been sent to Britain.
</P>
<P>
The orangutan sent Wednesday was the sixth, according to Pei
Chia-chi, director of the NPTU shelter.
</P>
<P>
The NPTU shelter has also cooperated with its counterpart in
Indonesia, Vietnam and Thailand by sending other great apes there
under a similar reproduction and research program.
</P>
<P>
More than a decade ago, according to Pei, a large number of
orangutans were smuggled into Taiwan to be sold as pets or for other
commercial purposes. However, many of the animals ended up being
deserted by their owners.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, the COA has sponsored the return of 33 orangutans to
their native habitat in Borneo, Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Other abandoned apes have also been sent home to Thailand and
Malaysia over the past five years, Pei said, adding that some 20
abandoned orangutans are still being kept at the NPTU shelter for
wild animals.
</P>
<P>
Only about 140 of the Borneo orangutans in Taiwan are legally
registered with the government, although hundreds more have been
smuggled into Taiwan over the past decade, according to COA
officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
