<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040303.0027" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
RANKING WEF OFFICIAL TO VISIT TAIWAN
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Geneva,  March 2 (CNA)
(By Neil Lu and Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jose Maria Eigueres, co-chief executive
officer of the Geneva-based World Economic Forum (WEF), is scheduled
to visit Taiwan March 7.
</P>
<P>
Figueres will be the highest-ranking WEF official to visit Taiwan
in recent years. The visit is expected to help enhance bilateral
exchanges between Taiwan and the influential international
organization.
</P>
<P>
Figueres' visit will be mainly about promoting the participation
of Taiwan enterprises in the WEF, and strengthening cooperation
between the WEF and Taiwan's academic organizations and think tanks.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day stay in Taiwan, Figueres is also scheduled
to attend two seminars and call on various government officials.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he will meet with Tsai Ching-yen, minister without
portfolio, and other officials in charge of high-tech development to
discuss competition in the high-tech sector and related issues.
</P>
<P>
The WEF is an independent international organization committed to
improving the state of the world, with its members being major
enterprises in the world.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Taiwan Power Company, VIA Technologies,Inc., and
Uni-President Enterprises Corp. are members of the WEF, while the
Cabinet-level Council for Economic Planning and Development has also
maintained cooperative ties with the WEF.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that Taiwan's participation and cooperative ties
in the organization has been limited over the years, Taiwan's
government and academic circles have attached great importance to the
WEF's annual global competitiveness report, regarding it as an index
of Taiwan's overall development. In Taiwan's presidential race this
year, both candidates have on many occasions cited figures and
related information in the WEF report.
</P>
<P>
The WEF holds an annual conference at the Swiss ski resort of
Davos. The conference is considered one of the most important world
forums. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, more than 30 heads of
state, and more than 100 ministerial officials attended this year's
gathering. However, Taiwan has been absent from the conference for
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Figueres, the former Costa Rican president, has visited Taiwan
several times during which he expressed that he was quite impressed
by Taiwan's economic and technological development and that he made a
lot of friends on the island.
</P>
<P>
Shen Lyushun, head of Taipei Representative Office in Geneva
since last May, invited Figueres to visit Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Tsai Ching-yen, while heading a delegation to attend a World
Summit on the Information Society at the U.N. headquarters in Geneva
last December, called on Figueres, who serves as chief of a U.N.
panel on information and communication technology, and also invited
him to visit Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
