<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 3 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Wednesday, March 3, or the third
day of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according to the
lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that have
occurred on this date in the past:

1802: Germany's Ludwig van Beethoven, considered the greatest
composer of his day, publishes his "Moonlight Sonata."

1845: Florida becomes the 27th state of the United States.

1847: Alexander Graham Bell, Scottish inventor who immigrated to
the United States and invented the telephone, is born.

1848: Spurred by hunger, economic depression and the political
demands of a growing middle class, revolution sweeps across Europe.

1857: Britain and France declare war on China, using the killing
of a missionary as a pretext, setting off the so-called "Second Opium
War."

1910: John Davison Rockefeller, the U.S. oil magnate who amassed
great wealth through the Standard Oil Company, donates US$12 million
to set up the Rockefeller Foundation to carry out philanthropic work.

1919: International airmail service is implemented for the first
time in such cities as Washington, D.C., Seattle and London.

1919: Vladimir Ilich Lenin, leader of the Russian Revolution and
first head of the USSR, announces plans to set Europe ablaze with
communist revolution.

1923: Americans with no time to read a daily newspaper can now
buy Time Magazine, which puts the week's news between two covers.

1931: The United States adopts "The Star-Spangled Banner" as its
national anthem.

1932: Republic of China troops are driven back from Shanghai by
invading Japanese forces.

1942: The west coast of the United States is declared a military
zone and 100,000 people are evacuated.

1944: U.S. fighter planes make their first appearance in the
skies over Berlin.

1950: The Republic of China pulls out of GATT (General Agreement
on Tariffs and Trade) in order to make Communist China lose its
rights to reciprocal tariff reductions.

1950: The U.S. Congress votes to admit Alaska as the 49th state.

1955: Foreign Minister George K.C. Yeh and U.S. Secretary of
State John Foster Dulles exchange instruments of ratification of the
Sino-American Mutual Defense Treaty in Taipei.

1962: Defecting mainland Chinese pilot Liu Cheng-shih arrives in
Taiwan aboard his MiG-15 jet fighter.

1974: Dr. Edward Binyah Kesselly, Liberian minister of
information, arrives in Taipei for a five-day visit.

1983: The ROC Ministry of Foreign Affairs announces severance of
diplomatic relations with the Ivory Coast, now called the Republic of
Cote D'Ivoire.

1985: An earthquake in Chile kills more than 150 people.

1988: The ROC Council for Economic Planning and Development
approves the establishment of the US$11 billion International
Economic Cooperation and Development Fund to assist developing
countries.

1988: The times and locations for opening ocean fishing to the
public in Taiwan are announced. Except for 21 military and national
defense areas which are off-limits, fishing will be permitted in all
other areas within a scope of 12 nautical miles.

1991: Queen Elizabeth II sustains an injury to her finger, which
requires three stitches, while trying to break up a dogfight between
corgis on the grounds of Windsor Castle.

1994: U.S. President Bill Clinton signs an executive order that
moves toward retaliatory tariffs on Japanese imports.

2000: Yuan T. Lee, Nobel laureate and president of Academia
Sinica, says that he will not side with Chen Shui-bien, the
presidential candidate of the opposition Democratic Progressive
Party.

2001: Indonesia formally lifts its 23-year ban on importing and
publishing Chinese-language books and magazines, a move highly
welcomed by the Chinese community in the Southeast Asian country.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "Men of intelligence are free from
doubts, moral men from anxiety, and men of courage from fear."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040304.0001" type="multi" >
