<HEADLINE>
SINGAPORE WOOS INTERNATIONAL FIRMS WITH IMPROVED INCENTIVES
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Singapore,  March  4 (CNA)
(By Sherman Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There are currently six to seven
thousand international companies in Singapore, of which about half
have been given regional HQ status by the government.
</P>
<P>
To woo more firms to set up shop in Singapore, the government has
extended the pioneer incentive from 10 years to 15 years. Companies
with pioneer status pay zero tax.
</P>
<P>
Millward Brown, one of the world's top 10 market research firms,
set up its regional headquarters in Singapore just last year.
</P>
<P>
The regional HQ incentive, which is awarded to smaller companies,
allows Millward Brown to enjoy a concessionary tax rate of 15 percent
for up to three years.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Economic Development Board says tax incentives are
just the icing on the cake, pointing out that investors are also
drawn by Singapore's infrastructure and its political and legal
system. Last year, the board attracted 27 firms with its HQ
incentive.
</P>
</TEXT>
