RECORD NUMBER OF OVERSEAS CITIZENS ELIGIBLE TO VOTE IN ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 4 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A record high of 9,431 overseas citizens of
the Republic of China have been approved to vote in the March 20
presidential election, an official from the Central Election
Commission (CEC) said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics compiled by the CEC, there were 5,896
overseas Taiwanese approved to vote in the 1996 presidential
election, although only 2,515 did so. The numbers dropped to 5,065,
and 2,849 in the 2000 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
These overseas voters should cast their ballots in constituencies
where they last resided in Taiwan and should present their Republic
of China passports instead of identification cards at the polling
stations, said the CEC official.
</P>
<P>
The island has 16 million adults, but eligible voters in the
presidential election would be a little bit less than that.
</P>
