<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040304.0007" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT ASSUMES CHAIRMANSHIP OF ASIAN DEMOCRATIC ORGANIZATION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Kaohsiung,  March  4  (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian formally
assumed the rotating chairmanship of the Council of Asian Liberals
and Democrats (CALD) at a changeover ceremony held in the southern
city of Kaohsiung Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chen, who serves concurrently as chairman of the ruling
Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), succeeded Sukhumbhand Paribatra,
a member of the Thai Parliament and of the Democrat Party. The DPP
term as CALD chair will end on Dec. 31, 2005 and will be succeeded by
the Liberal Party of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Chen said that his taking up the CALD
chairmanship represents not only an honor but also a responsibility
for the 23 million people of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that last Saturday, around two million Taiwan residents
participated, with a joyful mood, in a "hand-in-hand" activity to
form a 500-kilometer human chain throughout the island to express
their strong desire of pursuing peace and democracy.
</P>
<P>
"Tonight, I am very glad to see so many CALD partners from
Taiwan, the Philippines, Thailand, Malaysia, Myanmar, Cambodia,
Singapore and Sri Lanka get together in Kaohsiung to form another
'chain of democracy and freedom,'" Chen added.
</P>
<P>
"As a CALD rotating chairman, " Chen pointed out, "I will do my
utmost to achieve three goals -- expanding the organization's scale
and interactions among member parties, establishing a platform for
exchanges of views on democracy, freedom and human rights, and
boosting the partnership between the CALD and other global
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Chen further said that he will join hands with the CALD, the
Liberal International (LI) and other democratic foundations in the
United States and Germany to forge a global alliance to help promote
democratization and human rights improvement in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The DPP is a co-founding member of the CALD, which was founded in
1993 to promote regional peaceful development and economic
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
A three-day meeting of the CALD executive committee opened in
Kaohsiung Thursday. While here, all meeting participants will also
call on several ranking government officials and visit the DPP
campaign headquarters in Kaohsiung to gain a better understanding of
campaign techniques. President Chen is seeking re-election.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, LI is also holding an Asian forum in conjunction with
the CALD conference, with over 100 representatives from 30-odd
countries participating.
</P>
<P>
LI is a London-based organization that groups more than 80
liberal democratic parties in 63 countries around the world. The DPP
formally joined the alliance in 2002. As an organization very
friendly toward Taiwan, LI has adopted a resolution to support
Taiwan's entry into the World Health Organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
