<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY FILES LIBEL SUIT AGAINST FUGITIVE TYCOON
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 4 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
First lady Wu Shu-chen filed a libel suit
against a fugitive tycoon Thursday after he told local news media
that he had used her to funnel undeclared campaign funds before her
husband, Chen Shui-bian, was elected president in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The wheelchair-bound first lady said after filing the suit
against former Tuntex Group Chairman Chen You-hao with the Taipei
District Court that she doesn't like suing people.
</P>
<P>
"But whenever there is an election, there will be these smear
campaigns. If I keep quiet, it may look as if I am conceding, " Wu
told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Chen You-hao, who fled Taiwan in 2002 while awaiting trial on
charges of embezzling corporate funds, claimed in media interviews in
San Francisco earlier this week that he can prove he handed a total
of NT$6 million in under-the-table donations to Wu in 1994 when her
husband was running for Taipei mayor and in 2000 for the presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
Wu said she feels deep regret that Chen You-hao has repeatedly
claimed that she had taken NT$6 million from him. "I've repeatedly
said I did not, but he still continues the false accusations against
me. I cannot but take the case to the court to clear my name."
</P>
<P>
Wu recalled another negative campaign when her husband was
running for re-election in the 1998 Taipei mayoral race. Rumors
circulated that her husband secretly visited Macau to solicit
prostitutes when in fact he was on a visit to Singapore.
</P>
<P>
"I feel so sad about our election culture," Wu said.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's suit marked the second time the first lady has filed a
defamation case during this presidential campaign. She filed a
slander suit against Lien Chan in January after the opposition
presidential candidate hinted the president's wealth was accumulated
through corruption.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yu-hao's accusations are the latest in a series of
allegations by the former head of the financially troubled Tuntex
Group. He published several open letters in local newspapers in early
February saying two of the president's aides had taken undeclared
donations from him without giving a receipt during the 2000
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
President Chen, locked in a close race with his sole challenger
Lien Chan for the March 20 presidential election, has denied all of
Chen You-hao's accusations, saying they are an attempt by the
opposition to discredit him and undermine his re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
Chen You-hao used to be an influential businessman during former
President Lee Teng-hui's era. His Tuntex Group was involved in a
number of lines of business, including textiles, cement,
construction, petrochemicals, travel and telecommunications. His
business empire failed in the late 1990s due in part to a botched
land development project. He has been indicted on charges of breach
of trust and corporate funds embezzlement. He has been put on a list
of Taiwan's most wanted fugitives.
</P>
<P>
Describing himself as a new "political refugee, " Chen You-hao
said in his open the letters published earlier that he began to doubt
President Chen's promise to wipe out corrupt "black gold" politics
after having "close dealings" with two of President Chen's confidants
-- Chen Che-nan, who is now a Presidential Office deputy
secretary-general, and Chang Ching-sen, an incumbent vice chairman of
the Council for Economic Planning and Development (CEPD).
</P>
<P>
Chen You-hao claimed that he had offered bribe money to both Chen
Che-nan and Chang Ching-sen in exchange for their assistance in
resolving his business group's debt problems.
</P>
<P>
Both Chen Che-nan and Chang Ching-sen dismissed the allegations
as lies and filed separate libel suits against Chen You-hao with the
Taipei District Court on Thursday afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040304.0013" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN TO TAKE PART IN PANAMA, HONDURAS TRADE FAIRS IN MARCH
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  4 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs will
commission the Taiwan External Trade Development Council (TETRA) to
take part in 24 international trade fairs this year, and there will
be two such events this month, Colvin J.T. Liu, director of the
foreign ministry's Department of Economic and Trade Affairs, said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that to promote trade through diplomacy, and cement
diplomacy through trade, the foreign ministry has commissioned TETRA
to sponsor or take part in international trade fairs every year.
</P>
<P>
He said that the participation will strengthen the diplomatic and
trade relations between Taiwan and its allies, and will help Taiwan
businessmen seeking trade opportunities overseas.
</P>
<P>
Liu said the trade fairs this month will be an international
trade fair in Panama March 3-7, and a Republic of China Trade Fair
2004 in Honduras March 11-14, adding that 27 domestic manufacturers
in food processing, jewelry and trinkets, parts and components of
cars and motorcycles, daily necessities, and medical and sports
equipment will take part in the trade fairs.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that at the trade fair in Panama last year 30,000
people attended and Taiwan businessmen secured business worth
US$16.91 million.
</P>
<P>
At the trade fair in Honduras last year, 6,000 attended and
transactions amounted to US$6.83 million, he added.
</P>
