<HEADLINE>
FIRST-PHASE WATER RESTRICTIONS COULD BE LIFTED: WRA
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  4 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
If the rainfall in March reaches the
average level for the same period of previous years, the government
will consider lifting the first-phase water restrictions that have
been in place for the past several months, Chen Shen-hsien, director
of the Water Resources Agency (WRA) under the Ministry of Economic
Affairs, disclosed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to three consecutive days of rain, the Feitsui reservoir
-- the major source of water for the greater Taipei area -- has
received 72 millimeters of rainfall since March 1, while the Shihmen
reservoir, the main source for the Taoyuan area -- has received 45
millimeters, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that the rainfall received by the two reservoirs has
reached one-third of the average level of rainfall for the same
period of previous years and added that if both reservoirs continue
to receive sufficient rainfall for the rest of the month, the WRA
will discuss the possibility of lifting the first-phase water
restrictions in early April.
</P>
<P>
The first-phase water restrictions in place in the Taipei-Taoyuan
area since last May calls for reduced water pressure at off-peak
times.
</P>
</TEXT>
