<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN JOURNALISTS COMING TO COVER PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  4 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More than 400 foreign journalists have
applied to cover the March 20 presidential election and the
first-ever nationwide referendum to be held simultaneously,
government sources said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the international community has
traditionally paid great attention to Taiwan's presidential
elections. This time around, the sources said, international society
has shown even more concern about the election as a result of the
controversial referendum.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all major foreign news organizations have filed
applications to cover the election, the sources said, adding that
journalists intending to cover the event include correspondents
stationed at U.N. headquarters, in mainland China, in Japan and in
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The sources said 711 foreign journalists covered Taiwan's
first-ever direct presidential election in 1996, when mainland China
lobbed missiles and conducted live-fire military exercises on
Taiwan's doorstep in an attempt to influence the election result. In
2000, 600-plus foreign reporters traveled to Taiwan to cover the
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
A Government Information Office (GIO) official said that the
number of foreign newsmen applying to cover the hotly contested
election will continue to increase in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
The results of many public opinion polls show that the race
between the ticket of President Chen Shui-bian and Vice President
Annette Lu of the ruling Democratic Progressive Party and the
opposition "pan-blue alliance" ticket of Kuomintang Chairman Lien
Chan and People First Party Chairman James Soong is still too close
to call.
</P>
<P>
The GIO official said the Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MOFA) and
the GIO have jointly worked out a common itinerary for all arriving
foreign journalists.
</P>
<P>
According to the itinerary, the foreign press corps will visit
the Chen-Lu campaign headquarters March 16 and the Lien-Soong
campaign headquarters March 17.
</P>
<P>
On March 18, they will be offered the chance to interview
Mainland Affairs Council Chairwoman Tsai Ing-wen. The presidential
election, the referendum and cross-Taiwan Strait relations are
expected to be the main focus of the interview.
</P>
<P>
In the afternoon of election day, the press group will be taken
to the Central Election Commission to observe the vote-counting
process.
</P>
<P>
The following day, a seminar will be held for foreign journalists
and local academics to discuss the outcome of the election and the
referendum results.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the MOFA said it has invited the Association of Asian
Election Authorities (AAEA) to organize a delegation to Taiwan to
observe the election and witness the ROC's progress in political
democratization and electoral system advancement.
</P>
<P>
The AAEA was formed in 1997 to promote and institutionalize open
and transparent elections, independent and impartial election
authorities, the professionalization of Asian election authorities,
citizen participation in the electoral and civic process, information
sharing and the development of resources for election-related
information and research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
