<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040304.0021" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
COA DECIDES TO ENLIST MORE RESCUERS TO HELP STRANDED DOLPHINS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  4 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Council of Agriculture (COA) has
decided to mobilize more rescuers to help three dolphins presently
living in the Tamshui river back to sea after being alerted that the
health of the trio might be deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
Taipei residents first reported the dolphins Feb. 11 near the
Kuandu bridge. Taipei city and county authorities, as well as Taiwan
Cetacean Society, immediately joined hands to track down the
dolphins.
</P>
<P>
COA Vice Chairman Tai Cheng-yao said that the three dolphins have
now moved into the upper reaches of the river. Members of the Taiwan
Cetacean Society who got close to the animals have identified them as
rough-toothed dolphins that might have gone astray while pursuing
fish, as they appeared healthy at that time.
</P>
<P>
The city government invited officials from the COA, the county
government and wildlife protection groups to discuss the matter at a
meeting and concluded that they should observe and record the
dolphins' behavior and refrain from any follow-up action to avoid
disturbing them. Two other meetings were held.
</P>
<P>
Society members then reported that the dolphins, instead of
moving toward the sea, had actually traveled upstream about 10
kilometers from the mouth of the Tamsui river.
</P>
<P>
The city government held another meeting March 2 in which experts
concluded that the dolphins had been in the river for too long and
that their health will deteriorate unless they are rescued without
delay.
</P>
<P>
The COA held a fifth meeting Thursday and decided to enlist the
council, Taipei city and county governments in the rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
As such a rescue attempt is without precedence in the world, the
COA has requested support from the coast guard, the military and the
Tamsui Fishermen's Association to try to minimize the risk to the
animals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040304.0022" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT ENVISIONS CLEANER, MORE BEAUTIFUL TAIWAN
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  4 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The government hopes that some Taiwan
cities can make it onto the list of the top five cleanest cities in
the world with more recycling and less garbage generated, a
government official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Liu Shih-fang, secretary-general of the Executive Yuan, made the
remarks when she presided over a seminar in Taichung, central Taiwan.
Attending the meeting were local and central government environmental
officials and grassroots street-cleaning chiefs.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of Premier Yu Shyi-kun, Liu expressed the hope that all
relevant agencies will work toward the goal set by the Environmental
Protection Administration, which has designated 2004 as "full
recycling and zero waste-dumping year."
</P>
<P>
Liu noted that in the 1960s and 1970s it was fairly common to see
large amounts of garbage dumping alongside rivers. But after years of
efforts, she claimed, recycling efforts have effectively reduced such
dumping.
</P>
<P>
She said that the concept of garbage disposal must be changed
from end-stage disposal to the cutting of garbage generation at the
source and that partial recycling will be expanded to full recycling
to help create cleaner and more beautiful cityscapes.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu, if everyone on the island works with the
environmental authorities, there will be a chance for some cities to
become among the top five cleanest cities in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
