<HEADLINE>
EVA AIRWAYS OPENS TAIPEI-OSAKA CARGO SERVICE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 3 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EVA Airways opened a full cargo service
between Taipei and Osaka Thursday in an effort to provide more
comprehensive services in Northeast Asia, according to a spokesman
for the Taipei-based aviation company.
</P>
<P>
EVA Air uses B747-400 cargo planes on the once-weekly route every
Thursday in the initial stage, enabling the carrier to transport 340
tons of cargo between the two cities per week in conjunction with its
additional cargo capacity coming from existing passenger flights, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
EVA Air will in the future consider increasing its service on the
route in cooperation with a Japanese carrier through code-sharing,
depending on market demand, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the Taipei-Osaka cargo service is the beginning of
the Taiwan's second-largest carrier launch of full cargo business to
a Japanese destination and it forms part of the airline's efforts to
set up a global cargo transport network, the official added.
</P>
<P>
Biotech products, electronics parts and components, as well as
car accessories and fresh agricultural and farm produce form the bulk
of outbound and inbound shipments between Taipei and Osaka, which can
be delivered in just one day.
</P>
<P>
EVA Air started its full cargo service in 1995 with its first
MD-11 cargo plane. Today, it provides full cargo services to 12
destinations and operates 33 cargo-passenger routes around the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
