<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040304.0033" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 4 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Thursday, March 4, or the
14th day of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according
to the lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that
have occurred on this date in the past:

1193: Saladin, sultan of Egypt and Syria and legendary Muslim
commander during the Crusades, dies in Damascus at the age of 56. He
captured Jerusalem and defended it during the Third Crusade.

1394: Henry the Navigator, prince of Portugal, is born. He
established an observatory and school of navigation as well as
directed voyages that spurred the growth of Portugal's colonial
empire.

1791: Vermont becomes the 14th state of the United States.

1861: Abraham Lincoln is sworn in as the 16th president of the
United States, which is a country on the threshold of civil war.

1913: Democrat Woodrow Wilson becomes the 28th president of the
United States.

1917: The German army begins a major retreat along the Western
Front during World War I.

1933: Franklin D. Roosevelt is sworn in as the 32nd president of
the United States.

1941: German leader Adolf Hitler meets with Prince Paul in
Belgrade to ask Yugoslavia to join the Axis powers led by Germany and
Italy.

1942: Gen. Joseph Stilwell arrives in Chungking to assume office
as chief of staff of the China Theater of War and also to take
command of all American armed forces in China, Burma and India.

1945: Gen. Douglas MacArthur returns to the Philippines, where
the capital Manila has been taken by his troops after months of heavy
fighting against Japanese occupying forces.

1951: The first Asian Games opens in New Delhi, India.

1966: A Canadian DC-8 airliner crashes near Haneda airport in
Japan, killing 64 people and injuring eight others.

1968: Professional tennis players are allowed to compete at
Wimbledon, the world's oldest amateur tennis tournament.

1970: The French submarine Euridice is lost along with all 57
people onboard in the Mediterranean Sea off the coast of Toulon.

1971: Pierre Trudeau, the 52-year-old prime minister of Canada,
secretly marries 22-year-old Margaret Sinclair.

1973: The U.S. ambassador-at-large, David M. Kennedy, arrives in
the Republic of China for a four-day visit and talks with officials
on trade and monetary problems.

1973: Simon Pierre Kibanda arrives in Taipei to assume office as
the Central African Republic ambassador to the ROC.

1974: Labor leader Harold Wilson becomes prime minister after his
party wins the British elections.

1975: Charlie Chaplin, the British-born actor, director and
producer who gained fame for his role as a tramp in baggy trousers
and a bowler hat, is knighted at Buckingham Palace.

1975: The first Pan American World Airways flight to serve Taiwan
touches down at Taipei International Airport.

1976: The Importers and Exporters Association of Taipei enters
into sisterhood ties with the Overseas Chinese Exporters and
Importers Association of the United States.

1977: An earthquake rocks Romania, killing 1,541 people and
injuring 1,200 others.

1991: Idriss Deby becomes the new president of Chad.

1994: Beijing authorities arrest Chinese democratic activist Wei
Jingsheng.

1996: British Prime Minister John Major says all of Hong Kong's
permanent residents will be allowed visa-free entry into Britain
after Communist China takes over the British colony in 1997.

2000: Wu Ta-you, an internationally renown physicist and former
president of Academia Sinica, dies of illness at National Taiwan
University Hospital at the age of 95.

2001: National Palace Museum Director Tu Cheng-sheng offers to
help preserve the priceless ancient Buddha statues in Afghanistan
that face possible destruction on religious grounds by the Taliban
regime.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "I do not expect to find a saint
today. But if I find a gentleman, I shall be quite satisfied."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040305.0001" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WOULD LIKE TO SEE AN EARLY RESUMPTION TO CROSS-STRAIT TALKS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 5 (CNA)
(By P.C. Tang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A senior U.S. State Department official
said Thursday that whoever wins Taiwan's presidential election,
Washington would like to see an early resumption to talks between
Taipei and Beijing, according to a report by Hong Kong-based Phoenix
TV.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Randall G. Shriver, deputy assistant
secretary of state for East Asia and Pacific Affairs, made the
comments while attending a hearing held by the East Asia and Pacific
Affairs Subcommittee of the U.S. Senate Committee on Foreign
Relations to examine Hong Kong's state of democracy.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that Beijing should pay attention to the will of the
Hong Kong people, Shriver said that the United States and other Asian
countries are concerned about mainland China's policy in dealing with
its special administration zone's affairs.
</P>
<P>
Talking about cross-strait relations, the official said that
whoever wins the presidency in Taiwan, the United States hopes to see
progress made in the resumption of talks between the two sides of the
Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
The island is set to hold its presidential election March 20,
with a national referendum also scheduled to be held the same day.
</P>
<P>
U.S. foreign policy treats Taiwan and Hong Kong as two different
issues, Shriver said. Although the policies are guided by Congress,
with some policies decided by U.S. law, he said, the relationship
that Washington can develop with Hong Kong is quite different from
the relationship that it can develop with Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
