<HEADLINE>
PARTICIPANTS OF LIBERAL INTERNATIONAL MEETING SUPPORT REFERENDUM
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 5 (CNA)
(By Huang Kwang-chun)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Participants of the Liberal International
Asian Conference being held in Kaohsiung, southern Taiwan, expressed
their support Friday for Taiwan's planned referendum to be held March
20 alongside the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
In discussion sessions on the role of political parties in
consolidating democracy and public participation, the participants
said that the holding of referendums allows the people to directly
make decision on public affairs. It is a universal value of direct
democracy, they noted.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's March 20 referendum will further cement the country's
democracy, they claimed.
</P>
<P>
Boris Dittrich, a Dutch parliamentarian and chairman of the D66
party, said that referendum is normal practice in a democratic
society and a very important mechanism. It is very popular and has
been frequently practiced around the world, he added.
</P>
<P>
Lili Nabholz-Haidegger, a member of the Swiss Liberal Democratic
Party and a member of the European Parliament, said that the holding
of a referendum is a symbol of a free and democratic nation. She
suggested that the people of Taiwan should appreciate their first
referendum.
</P>
<P>
Lee Ying-yuan, deputy secretary-general of Taiwan's ruling
Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), said that the March 20 referendum
initiated by President Chen Shui-bian is the first of its kind in the
country's history and will mark a milestone in Taiwan's democratic
development.
</P>
<P>
Chen has placed two questions on the referendum: Should the
government buy new anti-missile systems to counter the growing
mainland Chinese missile buildup? And should the government open
talks with Beijing to establish a framework for cross-Taiwan Strait
peace and stability interaction?
</P>
<P>
The LI is holding an Asian forum in conjunction with the
conference of the Council of Asian Liberals and Democrats (CALD) in
Kaohsiung, with over 100 representatives from 29 countries around the
world participating.
</P>
<P>
LI is a London-based organization that groups more than 80
liberal democratic parties in 67 countries around the world. The DPP
formally joined the alliance in 2002.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which opened Thursday, will run through March 6.
Kaohsiung Mayor Frank Hsieh hosted a dinner cruise on the city's Love
River Friday evening to entertain the participants.
</P>
<P>
Chen, who doubles as DPP chairman, assumed the rotating
chairmanship of the CALD Thursday at the opening ceremony of the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Annette Lu gave a keynote speech to the meeting
Friday, in which she said that Taiwan will continue to play an
indispensable role in defending peace and democracy in the future and
urged the world not to tolerate the mainland Chinese missiles aimed
at Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Minister of Foreign Affairs Eugene Chien urged foreign
friends of Taiwan to support its campaign against the mainland
Chinese missile threat and its pursuit of peace in the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040305.0006" type="story" >
