<HEADLINE>
VICE PRESIDENT OPENS INTERNATIONAL ORCHID EXPOSITION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 5 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Vice President Annette Lu presided Friday
over the opening of the 8th Asia Pacific Orchid Conference (APOC) at
Jenteh township in southern Tainan County.
</P>
<P>
Describing the orchid as a symbol of Taiwan's technology and
natural beauty, Lu encouraged local growers to continue cultivating
fine-quality orchids with their high-end expertise to help locally
cultivated flowers become a top seller in the international market.
</P>
<P>
The 8th APOC will officially begin Saturday and run through March
14, in which more than 50,000 pots containing various species of
orchid from 22 countries and areas will be on display. A three-day
meeting on orchid cultivation technology will also kick off Saturday
at a local hotel, in which 45 research reports will be presented.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that Taiwan has held such an international
orchid expo and it is also the first time for the APOC to be held by
a country that is not and an APOC member.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile that day, Taiwan orchids, out of a total of 5,000
submissions in a competition held at the venue, won the championship
and the top prizes in all sub-division group contests.
</P>
<P>
The exposition venue is in a recently completed 23-hectare
compound that will form the first part of a planned 200-hectare
first-ever biotechnology park in Taiwan designed specifically to be
one of the world's leading orchid cultivation facilities, which will
create a competitive mechanism for Taiwan's production, marketing,
research and sales of the popular flowers in the global market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040305.0013" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PREMIER: VICE PRESIDENT SHOULD NOT SERVE CONCURRENTLY AS PREMIER
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  5 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It would be inappropriate for the vice
president to serve concurrently as the premier, Premier Yu Shyi-kun
said at the Legislative Yuan Friday.
</P>
<P>
Citing an opinion of the Council of Grand Justices, the premier
said that although the Constitution does not prohibit the scenario,
putting the Executive Yuan under the charge of the vice president
would be inconsistent with the original intention of the
Constitution, which is to provide separate jobs for the vice
president and the premier.
</P>
<P>
"If the vice president can be put in charge of the Executive
Yuan, why not the president -- who is head of the whole country and
would be a more appropriate choice for chief of the Executive Yuan
than the vice president? " Yu asked rhetorically to stress his
viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement in response to Legislator Lee Chen-nan of
the ruling Democratic Progressive Party, who asked Yu his opinion on
the voices among opposition Kuomintang lawmakers asking James Soong,
who is running as KMT Chairman Lien Chan's running mate in the March
20 presidential election, to promise that he will not double as
premier if elected. Soong rejected the demand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040305.0014" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PREMIER VISITS LEGISLATIVE REFORM ACTIVISTS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 5 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Premier Yu Shyi-kun paid a visit to a group
of demonstrators in front of the Legislative Yuan Friday to show his
support for a proposal to halve the number of legislative seats.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators, led by Lin Yi-hsiung, a former chairman of the
ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), launched a 240-hour relay
fast in the legislature courtyard Monday to push for the passage of a
constitutional amendment bill before the March 20 presidential
election, to pave the way for the much-anticipated reduction in the
number of legislative seats.
</P>
<P>
Yu arrived at the demonstration site at noon and shook hands with
Lin and other legislative reform activists to show his regard and
support for them.
</P>
<P>
He also signed a petition jointly initiated by Lin and Academia
Sinica President Lee Yuan-tseh demanding that the number of seats be
halved.
</P>
<P>
Noting that legislative reform has been a long-term goal of the
DPP, Yu said he hopes lawmakers of different political stripes can
work together to realize this goal as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
During the 2001 legislative election campaign, Yu recalled that
candidates from across the political spectrum backed the legislative
downsizing proposal.
</P>
<P>
"More than two years have passed; the proposal remains on the
drawing board, " Yu lamented, adding that he hopes the opposition
"pan-blue alliance" of the Kuomintang (KMT) and the People First
Party (PFP), which controls a majority in the legislature, will take
concrete action to deliver on their promises to halve the number of
legislative seats.
</P>
<P>
According to the existing regulations, legislative downsizing
requires amendments to the Constitution. Although the legislature has
formed a special committee in charge of Constitution-amending
affairs, the committee has yet to call its first meeting.
</P>
<P>
Former DPP Chairman Lin and Academia Sinica President Lee will
hold a joint news conference Saturday to expound on their appeal for
legislative downsizing as a first step toward legislative reform.
They want the legislature to pass a relevant constitutional amendment
proposal before the March 20 presidential poll to speed up the
legislative reform procedures.
</P>
<P>
The 10-day sit-in relay fast, organized by the Nuke-4 Referendum
Initiative Association (Nuke-4 RIA) , is being conducted in 24-hour
shifts. Most of the demonstrators are opponents of the island's
controversial fourth nuclear power plant now under construction in
Taipei County.
</P>
<P>
Saying that the Nuke-4 RIA's present campaign is aimed at
promoting the establishment of a more refined political culture
characterized by honesty and credibility, Lin said he hopes all
domestic political figures will faithfully honor their campaign
promises.
</P>
<P>
Two legislators from the opposition Taiwan Solidarity Union, Chen
Chien-ming and Hsu Teng-kung, threw their support behind Lin's
campaign Friday by joining the peaceful relay fast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040305.0015" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
MAC KEEPING CLOSE WATCH ON NPC MEETING IN BEIJING: OFFICIAL
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 5 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Cabinet-level Mainland Affairs Council
(MAC) is keeping a close watch on the developments in two important
meetings being held in Beijing, a senior official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular news conference, MAC Vice Chairman Chen
Ming-tung said that even though Taiwan affairs are not a focus of the
ongoing second plenary session of the 10th National People's Congress
(NPC) -- mainland China's rubber-stamp parliament -- and the annual
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, the Beijing
leadership will be sure to take advantage of the two events to try to
sway Taiwan voters ahead of the March 20 presidential election and
its first-ever referendum.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on mainland Chinese Premier Wen Jiabao's offer to
resume dialogue with Taiwan under the "one-China" principle in his
administrative report to the NPC delivered earlier in the day, Chen
said the biggest obstacle to cross-Taiwan Strait rapprochement lies
in Beijing's refusal to recognize the Republic of China's existence
as an independent sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Beijing's "one-China" principle, which downgrades
Taiwan to a province under mainland jurisdiction, is unacceptable,
Chen said that only when the mainland is willing to face up to the
ROC's existence pragmatically and recognize the people of Taiwan's
commitment and determination to pursue peace can the two sides of the
strait forge constructive interaction.
</P>
<P>
Touching on reports by pro-Beijing Hong Kong daily Sing Tao
Jihpao that the mainland has secretly stepped up its military
deployment against Taiwan, Chen said he was not surprised by the Sing
Tao reports because Beijing has long listed Taiwan's indefinite
postponement of negotiations for unification as one of the five
conditions under which it might use force to take over Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Chen further said that the mainland's saber-rattling and military
threats are the reasons behind President Chen Shui-bian's decision to
hold a referendum March 20 alongside the election.
</P>
<P>
Voters will be asked two questions in the referendum -- whether
Taiwan should buy more anti-missile batteries in the face of the
mainland missile threat and whether Taiwan should negotiate a viable
mechanism with Beijing for cross-strait peaceful interaction.
</P>
<P>
Chen said Taiwan has no intention of igniting a cross-strait arms
race. "But we must beef up our defense capabilities, as Beijing still
refuses to renounce the option of using force against Taiwan, " he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Chen went on, war cannot resolve cross-strait
issues. "This is the rationale of the second question to be asked in
the referendum. The government hopes to obtain a mandate to negotiate
with Beijing for peaceful cross-strait engagements."
</P>
<P>
Chen urged the mainland authorities to understand the
significance of the referendum and to respect Taiwan's desire for
peace, stability and prosperity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040305.0016" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN FOREIGN EXCHANGE RESERVES GROWING FAST
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 5 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan's foreign exchange reserves had
snowballed to a record high of US$224.803 billion as of the end of
February, up by US$9.877 billion from the end of January, the Central
Bank of China (CBC) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to CBC statistics, the increase also represents a
historic monthly rise, helping Taiwan maintain its position as the
world's third-largest holder of foreign exchange reserves behind only
Japan and mainland China.
</P>
<P>
CBC officials attributed the increase to a huge influx of foreign
capital -- some US$1.5 billion in February -- and an appreciating new
Taiwan dollar. However, they warned that the foreign capital funneled
into Taiwan could be remitted out at any time.
</P>
<P>
Japan held US$776.857 billion worth of foreign exchange reserves
as of the end of February, ahead of the mainland in second place with
US$415.72 billion posted in late January.
</P>
<P>
South Korea held US$163.007 billion in foreign exchange reserves
as of late last month, while Hong Kong and Singapore enjoyed forex
reserves of US$123.643 billion and US$98.564 billion, respectively,
in late January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040305.0017" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT DECORATES 99-YEAR-OLD BUDDHIST ELDER
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  5 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian decorated a
Buddhist elder, Ying Shun, in Taiping, Taichung County, central
Taiwan, Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a brief ceremony, the president decorated the 99-year-old
elder with the Order of Propitious Clouds with Grand Cordon to honor
his contribution to society.
</P>
<P>
Born in Haining County, Zhejian province in 1906, Elder Ying Shun
converted to Buddhism in 1930 and devoted himself to the studies of
Buddhist theory.
</P>
<P>
He moved to Taiwan in 1953 to promote Buddhism, urge his
followers to live out Buddhism in their daily live, and has been
lauded as the most knowledgeable Chinese Buddhist master after Hsuan
Chang, a Buddhist master who lived from A.D.602 to A.D.664.
</P>
<P>
Ying Shun was known for lodging in his temple in Hualien a young
runaway woman in 1963 and made her an apostle named Cheng Yen who
later founded the well-known Tzu Chi Buddhist Compassionate Relief
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
President Chen has decorated Cheng Yen with the Order of
Brilliant Star last December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040305.0018" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT GROWS FOR FAST RELAY TO DRUM UP SUPPORT FOR HALVING LAWMAKERS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  5 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Government officials, legislators and
scholars visited the participants of a 240-hour fast relay activity
Friday, which was in its fifth day to drum up support for the halving
of the 225-seat Legislative Yuan.
</P>
<P>
Lin Yi-hsiung, former chairman of the now-ruling Democratic
Progressive Party (DPP) , and activists of the Nuke-4 Referendum
Initiative Association (Nuke-4 RIA) started the 240-hour fast relay
March 1, with each team fasting for 24 hours over a 10-day period.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan Society North, Taiwan Society Central, Taiwan Society
South, Taiwan Society East, the Taiwan Association of University
Professors, legislators Lo Chi-ming and Chen Chien-ming of the Taiwan
Solidarity Union as well as Premier Yu Shyi-kun came to the
pedestrian walkway in front of the Legislative Yuan to greet the
participants and lend support to their cause.
</P>
<P>
After the visit, representatives from the Taiwan Association of
University Professors and the four societies held a press conference
during which they said that if the ruling and opposition camps cannot
reach a consensus before March 20, they will "follow the step of
Gandhi, and fight to the end using non-violent methods."
</P>
<P>
Wu Chien-kuo, office director of Nuke-4 RIA, urged full support
from the public for their campaign cause so as to prod the
legislature to take action.
</P>
<P>
"During this energetic presidential campaign, members of the
association have decided to use the most low key way of expression --
holding a sit-in and abstaining from food and talking to express the
voice of the public," Wu added.
</P>
<P>
Noting that all parties promised to cut the number of legislative
seats three years ago, Wu said they should honor their words to help
end the current chaotic situation in the legislature.
</P>
<P>
He urged the public to throw their support behind the cause,
noting that they should use every possible way to prod the political
parties and the legislators to deliver on their "cut in half"
promises.
</P>
<P>
"The promises should serve as a criterion to inspect whether a
political party or figure will honor their words," he added.
</P>
<P>
Yeh Po-wen, executive director of the Nuke-4 RIA, said that the
association called on the caucuses of various parties in the
legislature recently. The ruling Democratic Progressive Party and its
ally, the Taiwan Solidarity Union, agreed to do so.
</P>
<P>
But no legislators of the Kuomingtang and its ally, the People
First Party, have signed to express support for the proposal, Yeh
added.
</P>
<P>
He said the association does not want empty promise, but will ask
for action and results, hoping that every political party will ask
its members to strictly toe the party line so that a proposal to
amend the Constitution to cut the number of legislative seats can be
passed by the March 20 presidential election.
</P>
</TEXT>
