<HEADLINE>
KAOHSIUNG FISHING-RELATED BUSINESSES SEEKING RELIEF FROM COMPETITION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Kaohsiung,  March 5 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As a deep sea, inshore and aquaculture
fishery stronghold in southern Taiwan, many related businesses based
in Kaohsiung are still mired in difficulties resulting from market
exploration and overseas sales, industry sources said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Although Taiwan's largest port city has long enjoyed fame thanks
to its handsome and diversified fish catches and aquaculture produce
such as eels and shrimps, sources from the local fishery industry are
concerned about sales and market exploration both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Despite the efforts made by the Kaohsiung City Government and
many related businesses to help local fishermen increase their
income, the sources said, for instance, that Taiwan-made frozen fish
products are facing robust competition from similar but cheaper goods
from mainland China and Southeast Asian countries in foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
In view of Taiwan's higher production coasts, Taiwan's related
businesses must further sharpen their competitiveness by varying
their products, enhancing their quality and using e-commerce
marketing networks to expand sales overseas and to edge into new
markets abroad, they suggested.
</P>
<P>
According to a frozen food processor operating in Kaohsiung,
frozen processed fish products have become more and more popular in
Taiwan because of the larger number of people who usually eat out.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that the problem of chemical overuse by
some domestic fish raisers is really a big headache for them and has
dealt a blow to their businesses, as frozen food made of locally
raised fish were once detected to have contained excessive chemical
substances.
</P>
<P>
As one of the food processors who uses local raw materials, he
said they felt deeply frustrated over these problems. The frozen food
processor called on relevant government agencies to step up
management and control to wipe out the illegal drug use on natural
produce by some raisers to ensure greater security for the public.
</P>
<P>
At a time when many frozen fish processors headquartered in
Kaohsiung are seeking to expand into new foreign markets in mainland
China, Japan, the United States and the Middle East, the chemical
overuse issue is a big problem that all parties concerned cannot
afford to ignore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
