<HEADLINE>
MORE PEOPLE BUSTED FOR OFFERING WAGERS ON PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 5 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More people were apprehended over the past
two days in the government's campaign to eliminate gambling on the
outcome of the March 20 presidential election, the Criminal
Investigation Bureau (CIB) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under the "Leiting 30" campaign launched Wednesday to crack down
on underground gambling groups, particularly those applying the Hong
Kong horse racing lottery mechanism to offer bets, police have
arrested 149 people suspected of being involved in 135 cases of
illegal gambling over the election.
</P>
<P>
Last week, under the "Leiting 29" campaign, the police detained
242 people in 188 cases of illegal betting on the election, CIB
officials reported.
</P>
<P>
The CIB authorities were tipped off in the recent month that
wagers on the outcome of the presidential election have been rampant
islandwide, particularly in central and southern Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Betting, like other forms of gambling, is illegal in Taiwan and
betting on elections is especially rare. The "Leiting 29" and
"Leiting 30" drives were launched to stop underground gambling rings
from manipulating the presidential election by offering big stakes,
CIB officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
