<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT URGED TO SCRAP FINANCIAL GUARANTEE FOR MAINLAND SPOUSES
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 5 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dozens of mainland Chinese women married to
men from Taiwan took to the streets Friday along with women's rights
activists to protest the government's decision that "marriage
immigrants" must provide financial guarantees that the protesters say
are unreasonably high.
</P>
<P>
The groups handed an appeal to a representative of the Executive
Yuan, asking the government to repeal the new NT$5 million
(US$150,600) financial guarantee regulation for mainland Chinese
spouses applying for permanent residence or ROC citizenship.
</P>
<P>
Although the Ministry of the Interior made an abrupt policy
about-face Thursday on the regulation passed March 1 and lowered the
residence threshold to a much lower NT$380,160 (US$11,450) , the
demonstrators asked the government to scrap the regulation
altogether, calling it "a hostile and discriminatory immigration
policy."
</P>
<P>
Li Mingfang, 56, who came to Taiwan to live after marrying her
75-year-old Taiwan husband, said her family cannot afford the
financial guarantee, even if at a low of NT$380,160, given their
difficult financial situation with her NT$20,000 monthly income
working as a dishwasher and her husband being chronically ill.
</P>
<P>
Chao Yen-ning, a consultant to the Alliance for Human Rights
Legislation for Immigrants and Migrants, said that regardless of
whether the financial guarantee was NT$5 million or NT$380,160, it is
a regulation demanding certification of an account balance, which
would be seen as ridiculous in an advanced country.
</P>
