<HEADLINE>
AGREEMENT TO LEGISLATURE RECESS PRIOR TO ELECTION IN LIMBO
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  5 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An agreement between the ruling and
opposition parties in the Legislative Yuan Friday to recess for one
week before the March 20 presidential election was thrown into
uncertainty Friday after each side accusing the other of failing to
honor their words.
</P>
<P>
The ruling and the opposition parties discussed the legislative
agenda before the election, and Legislative Yuan President Wang
Jin-pyng later announced that both sides had agreed to change the
general interpellation session scheduled for March 12 to the
screening of bills, with the draft version of the political donations
bill topping the agenda.
</P>
<P>
The legislature and committee meetings will also recess between
March 13 and 19, Wang said, adding that the session will reopen after
the election.
</P>
<P>
But Ker Chien-ming, party whip of the ruling Democratic
Progressive Party, said a floor meeting should not only screen the
political donations bill, but the political party bill, and the
revised financial reconstruction fund bill as well.
</P>
<P>
He also said that since all political parties have expressed the
desire to push for the halving of the 225-seat legislature, then the
coordination among all parties should at least be completed before
the legislature goes into recess.
</P>
<P>
The legislators will continue to discuss whether to recess and
what bills should screened next Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Kuomintang (KMT) caucus in the legislature pointed
out that the "pan-green" camp, meaning the ruling DPP and its ally,
the Taiwan Solidarity Union (TSU), must take full responsibility for
the breakdown of the agreement and for the failure of the political
donations bill to clear the legislature.
</P>
<P>
Liao Feng-teh, KMT party whip in the legislature, said that the
"pan-blue alliance, " meaning the KMT and the People First Party,
reached an initial agreement with the "pan-green" camp, but the DPP
and the TSU later made changes to the original agreement.
</P>
<P>
Liao pointed out that the legislature had agreed to put the
discussion of the political donations bill on a priority list at the
March 12 floor meeting, but the "pan-green" camp added another two
bills -- the political party bill and the revised financial
reconstruction bill.
</P>
<P>
The "pan-green" camp also added that all parties should complete
the coordination process on halving the legislative seats, Liao
added.
</P>
<P>
He believed that because of the "technical boycott" by the
"pan-green" camp, it should take responsibility for the breakdown of
the agreement.
</P>
