<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040305.0029" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
DPP WORRIED ABOUT POSSIBLE LOW VOTER TURNOUT IN UPCOMING REFERENDUM
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  5 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The legislative caucus of the ruling
Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) said Friday it is worried about a
possible low voter turnout in Taiwan's first-ever nationwide
referendum to be held March 20 alongside the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The DPP legislative caucus made the remarks after a recent public
opinion poll found that only 33 percent of the respondents said they
would definitely cast ballots in the upcoming referendum.
</P>
<P>
The telephone survey, conducted by SANLIH Entertainment
Television March 1-2, was aimed at exploring the support ratings of
the two presidential tickets and public opinion about the
controversial referendum. A total of 1,058 valid samples were
collected in the survey, with a margin of error of 3.07 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, the respondents were divided about the
referendum, with 33.1 percent saying they will certainly go and vote;
11.4 percent saying they will probably cast ballots in the
referendum; 31.21 percent saying they will definitely not cast
referendum ballots; and 11.5 percent saying they will probably not
cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
DPP legislative whip Tsai Huang-lang said the findings were
worrisome as they indicated that local voters were not keenly
interested in the historic referendum.
</P>
<P>
Voters will be asked two questions in the nation's first-ever
referendum -- whether Taiwan should buy more anti-missile batteries
in the face of mainland China's intensified military threat and
whether Taiwan should negotiate with mainland China for the
establishment of a viable mechanism for peaceful bilateral
interaction.
</P>
<P>
Mainland China has dismissed the referendum as a move to promote
Taiwan independence and Taiwan's major trading partners, including
the United States and Japan, have also expressed concern about the
vote.
</P>
<P>
Tsai said what the international community is concerned about is
the referendum results. "If less than 50 percent of eligible voters
cast ballots in the upcoming referendum, it will send the wrong
message -- that the people of Taiwan are not united in the face of
mainland China's missile threat. Should that be the case, it would be
a big flop for our country," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
As far as the presidential election is concerned, 36 percent of
those interviewed said they would vote for the DPP ticket of
President Chen Shui-bian and Vice President Annette Lu, while 35.7
percent said they would vote for the opposition "pan-blue alliance"
ticket of Kuomintang (KMT) Chairman Lien Chan and People First Party
(PFP) Chairman James Soong, and 23.2 percent would not reveal their
choice.
</P>
<P>
Analyzing the results, Tsai said he is optimistic about the
Chen-Lu ticket's re-election bid as its poll numbers have
consistently exceeded that of the Lien-Soong team. In terms of
previous experiences, Tsai said, about 70 percent of those who refuse
to disclose their support target were DPP core supporters.
</P>
<P>
Against this backdrop, Tsai said he is confident that the Chen-Lu
ticket will win.
</P>
<P>
By constituency, Tsai said, the Chen-Lu ticket lagged far behind
behind the Lien-Soong ticket in northern Taiwan, particularly in the
Hakka stronghold of the Taoyuan-Hsinchu-Miaoli area.
</P>
<P>
According to the SANLIH survey, the Lien-Soong support rating in
the Taoyuan-Hsinchu-Miaoli constituency reached 43.5 percent, far
higher than the Chen-Lu's 24.6 percent. And 31.9 percent remained
undecided.
</P>
<P>
The poll also found that the Chen-Lu ticket enjoyed a comfortable
lead over the Lien-Soong ticket in central and southern Taiwan
constituencies. Tsai attributed this trend mainly to the historic
"hand-in-hand" rally on Feb. 28 when more than one million people held
hands to form a 500 kilometer human chain that stretched the length
of Taiwan.
</P>
