<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040305.0035" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TWO OF THREE DOLPHINS IN TAMSHUI RIVER RESCUED: OFFICIALS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  5 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two of the three "stray" rough-toothed
dolphins that have been living in the Tamshui River over the past
three weeks have been captured, while the third remains "at large, "
officials from the Council of Agriculture (COA) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The two captured dolphins, suffering from tilted dorsal fins,
were being transported to Sea World in Yeliu, Taipei County, as of
press time, for medical treatment and observation, COA authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
The COA authorities decided Thursday to mobilize more rescue
workers to help the trio of dolphins return to the sea after being
alerted that the health of the sea mammals might be deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
Taipei residents first reported sightings of the dolphins Feb. 11
near the Kuandu Bridge. Taipei city and county authorities, as well
as Taiwan Cetacean Society officials, immediately joined hands to
track down the dolphins.
</P>
<P>
The city government invited officials from the COA, the county
government and wildlife protection groups to discuss the matter at a
meeting in February, and concluded that they should observe and
record the dolphins' behavior and refrain from any follow-up action
to avoid disturbing them.
</P>
<P>
The COA authorities and specialists from the Taiwan Cetacean
Society later decided after convening five meetings that the dolphins
must be captured and returned to where they came from before long.
The decision was based on considerations of the deteriorating health
of the dolphins and the fact that the animals seemed unable to find
their way back to sea.
</P>
<P>
The COA has also requested support from the coast guard, the
military, the Tamsui Fishermen's Association and even a Japanese
cetacean expert to try to minimize the risks to the dolphins in the
rescue efforts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040305.0036" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRICES DOWN ON TAIPEI STOCK MARKET
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, Mar. 5 (CNA)
(By Ben Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Share prices opened high but closed lower on
the Taiwan Stock Exchange (TAIEX) on Friday, with the weighted index,
the market's key barometer, moving down 90.42 points to close at
6,943.68.
</P>
<P>
The bourse opened at 7,106.31 and fluctuated between 7,135 and
6,943.47 during trading.
</P>
<P>
A total of 11.56 billion shares changed hands on a market
turnover of NT$ 253.7 billion (US$7.6 billion), an increase from the
previous trading session which saw 10.09 billion stocks traded on
amarket turnover of NT$226.55 billion (US$6.79 billion).
</P>
<P>
Only one of the eight major stock categories posted gains, with
pulp and paper issues moving up 3.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The other major stock categories lost ground, with construction
stocks moving down the most at 4.4 percent, followed by bank and
insurance shares at 3.4 percent, foodstuff shares at 2.4 percent,
cement stocks at 2 percent, plastics and chemical shares at 1.7
percent, textile issues at 0.7 percent, and electrical stocks at 0.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Losers outnumbered gainers 532 to 322, with 111 stocks remaining
unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
