<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 5 (CNA)
(By David Hsu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Friday, March 5, or the 15th
day of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according to the
lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that have
occurred on this date in the past:

1534: Antonio Corregio, Italian Renaissance painter of sensuous
mythological scenes who was known for his use of chiaroscuro, dies at
the age of 40.

1751: James Madison, the fourth president of the United States
and sponsor of the first 10 amendments to the U.S. Constitution, is
born.

1770: British troops open fire on a hostile crowd in Boston,
killing five Americans. The incident, which was dubbed the "Boston
Massacre," hastens the approach of the American Revolutionary War.

1898: Soong Mayling, better known as Madame Chiang, the wife of
late Republic of China President Chiang Kai-shek and the president
and founder of the National Women's League of the Republic of China,
is born.

1916: The Spanish ocean liner Principe de Asturias sinks off the
coast of Brazil, killing 445 people.

1933: The Nazis and their allies win 52 percent of the seats in
the Reichstag in German elections, with Chancellor Adolf Hitler
gaining dictatorship.

1936: The Spitfire, a fighter plane produced by Britain's
aircraft industry to counter the startling build-up in the number of
military aircraft in Hitler's Germany, makes its maiden flight in
Southamton.

1940: Tsai Yuan-pei, president of Academia Sinica, dies in Hong
Kong at the age of 74.

1945: China, the United States, the United Kingdom and the Soviet
Union issue joint invitations to the United Nations Conference in San
Francisco on April 25.

1946: The Ministry of Foreign Affairs announces that China has
rejected Soviet claims to all Japanese military enterprises in
Manchuria.

1946: British Prime Minister Winston Churchill calls for joint
Anglo-American efforts to face the Russian threat in his tour of the
United States by saying that "an Iron Curtain has descended across
Europe."

1953: Joseph Stalin, who forged the Soviet Union into a global
superpower via an oppressive regime which killed millions of
citizens, dies of a brain hemorrhage in Moscow at the age of 73.

1960: Indonesian President Sukarno suspends the country's
parliament.

1965: Vice President Chen Cheng dies of liver cancer at the age
of 68.

1966: A British Airways' Boeing 707 passenger plane crashes on
Japan's Mount Fuji, killing all 124 people aboard.

1970: The Ministry of Transportation and Communications selects
the route of the South Link Railway. Construction of the 97-kilometer
railway from Fangliao to Pinan was scheduled to be completed in 1990.

1974: World Campus Afloat, a shipboard program sponsored by
Chapman College of Orange, California, arrives at Keelung for a
four-day visit.

1974: Dr. Choi Hyung Sup, Korean minister of science and
technology, arrives in Taipei for a five-day visit.

1975: The Executive Yuan of the Republic of China announces the
appropriation of an additional NT$500 million to accelerate rural
development in the first half of 1975.

1976: More than 3,000 Boy Scouts and Girl Scouts gather at
Taipei's Youth Park to celebrate Chinese Scout Day.

1977: In the first presidential phone-in, U.S. President Jimmy
Carter answers questions from listeners from over 26 states.

1990: Soviet reformist leader Boris Nikolayerich Yeltsin is
elected as a representative to the Russian parliament.

1994: Mainland China's Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress formally approves the "Taiwan Compatriot Investment
Protection Act."

1994: Gratified by Beijing's release of democracy campaigner Wei
Jingsheng, the United States presses for an explanation of the
troubling events that led to his arrest.

2000: The Republic of China embassy in Palau is inaugurated, with
ROC Foreign Minister Chen Chien-jen and Sabino Ansatacio, a Palauan
cabinet minister, jointly presiding over the opening ceremony.

2001: President Chen Shui-bian formally becomes the new chief of
the National Council of Scouts of the Republic of China in a ceremony
held at the Presidential Office.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "Men of the last generation, in
matters of the arts and refinement, are considered to have been rude;
men of the present generation are, in those matters, considered
polite. But in my practice, I prefer men of the last generation."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040306.0001" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
DOMESTIC PILOTS HOPE TO BE ALLOWED TO WORK IN MAINLAND CHINA
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 6 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An association representing Taiwan's pilots
has asked the Civil Aeronautics Administration (CAA) to modify
regulations to allow local pilots to fly for mainland Chinese
carriers, a situation which is currently forbidden.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Chinese Pilots Association said that the
aviation industry in the mainland is expected to expand rapidly over
the next 20 years, and the number of civilian airplanes will increase
four fold from the current 500 to 2,000. Job opportunities in the
mainland look quite promising, they added.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, the development of civil aviation in Taiwan has
stalled, and pilots have to find employment in a very limited market,
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that aviation is an international enterprise and
that local pilots should not be confined to Taiwan, but must be
allowed to branch out internationally.
</P>
<P>
Under the current Statute Governing the Relations Between the
People of the Taiwan Area and the Mainland Area, local pilots are
prohibited from working in the mainland, association officials said.
</P>
<P>
They argued, however, that the nature of a pilot's work does not
undermine national security or interests. The association, therefore,
has applied to the CAA to devise a method by which Taiwan pilots
could fly for mainland carriers.
</P>
<P>
The CAA has yet to respond to the request, believing that
anything involving cross-Taiwan Strait affairs must be treated with
caution.
</P>
<P>
The association is in the process of determining how many Taiwan
pilots are interested in working in the mainland. The association has
distributed questionnaires to its members in this regard and the
survey is expected to be completed by March 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040306.0002" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
AEGIS-EQUIPPED WARSHIPS SALES TO TAIWAN UNDER CONSIDERATION: PENTAGON
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Washington,  March 5 (CNA)
(By Jay Chen and P.C. Tang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A U.S. Defense Department spokesman
said Friday that a newspaper was incorrect when it reported that the
Pentagon has agreed to sell warships equipped with the advanced Aegis
radar system to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The Friday Washington Times report also said that it was the
first time that the Bush administration had agreed to the sale of
such advanced warships to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the Pentagon spokesman said that selling warships
equipped with the advanced Aegis radar system to Taiwan is "still
under consideration" and that the Defense Department has not yet
approved such arms sales to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that even if the Pentagon agrees to sell the
warships, the sale would need a joint endorsement by the White House
Security Council, and the departments of state and defense.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper also reported that such arms sales could be
controversial since Aegis-equipped warships are the foundation of
U.S. anti-missile systems, which are expected to be deployed next
year.
</P>
<P>
The report said that because of mainland China's deployment of an
increasing number of missiles aimed at Taiwan, the island is anxious
to seek anti-missile defense weapons.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's defense authorities have long hoped to buy warships
equipped with the advanced Aegis radar system, but mainland China has
strongly opposed the sale because of concerns that the sale could
neutralize the deterrence of its missiles aimed at Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Beijing also worries that a U.S. sale of such warships to Taiwan
could represent a reinforcement of military contacts and cooperation
between Taipei and Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040306.0003" type="multi" >
