<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040306.0008" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
NEARLY 70 PERCENT OF TAIWAN PEOPLE FOR HALVING OF LEGISLATIVE SEATS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 6 (CNA)
(By Huang Kwang-chun)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nearly 70 percent of the people of Taiwan
support halving of the 225-seat Legislative Yuan, Lin Yi-hsiung, a
former chairman of the ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a press conference he jointly called with Lee
Yuan-tseh, president of Academia Sinica, Lin cited results of a poll
conducted by Focus Survey Research Feb. 28-29, saying that 68.1
percent of the respondents were in favor of cutting the number of
seats in the legislature, against 10.2 percent in opposition and 21.7
percent having no idea about the issue.
</P>
<P>
The poll, commissioned by Taiwan Thinktank, also showed that 58.4
percent of the respondents were not satisfied with the performance of
the Legislative Yuan over the past six months, while only 17.6
percent were satisfied with the law-making body's performance and 24
percent had no idea.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 55.8 percent of the respondents believed that the
downsizing of legislature will help improve the lawmaker's
performance, against 16.9 percent of the pollees who took the
contrary position and 27.2 percent who had no idea.
</P>
<P>
Lin and Lee issued a joint statement Feb. 20, urging the two
presidential tickets to push lawmakers to pass a constitutional
reform bill ahead of the March 20 election to pave the way for
halving the number of legislative seats. They also called on the
general public to endorse their joint appeal.
</P>
<P>
Lin also started a 10-day fast relay March 1 together with
members of an anti-nuclear power group -- Nuke-4 Referendum
Initiative Association -- in front of the Legilstive Yuan building to
press for reduction of the number of legilative seats.
</P>
<P>
As of March 5, Lin said, a total of 35,563 individuals, including
President Chen Shui-bian, Premier Yu Shyi-kun, Taiwan Solidarity
Union (TSU) Chairman Huang Chu-wen, DPP Secretary-General Chang
Chun-hsiung, 87 DPP legislators and 12 TSU lawmakers, had endorsed
their appeal.
</P>
<P>
Lee Yuan-tseh, co-winner of the 1986 Nobel Prize in Chemistry,
called on the ruling and opposition parties to pass a constitutional
reform bill for halving the number of legislative seats by March 20.
</P>
<P>
The passage of the political party law, political donation law
and an amendement to the existing Election and Recall Law for
establishing a "single-seat constituency and two-vote system" should
be followed, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040306.0009" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
LIEN-SOONG TICKET LEADING PRESIDENTIAL RACE: POLLS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 6 (CNA)
(By Huang Kwang-chun)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ticket formed by opposition Kuomintang
Chairman Lien Chan and his running mate, People First Party Chairman
Janes Soong, is leading the upcoming presidential election by a
narrow margin, according to results of two polls published Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The polls were conducted jointly by Shih Hsin University and a
marketing consultant company -- InsightXplorer Ltd. -- from Feb. 29
to March 1 by randomly selected telephone numbers and from Feb. 28 to
March 3 via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
If tomorrow were election day, 41.1 percent of the telephone
respondents and 42.6 percent of the Internet respondents said that
they would vote for the Lien-Soong ticket, while 37.5 percent and
34.4 percent were in favor of the ticket formed by incumbent
President Chen Shui-bian and Vice President Annette Lu, the surveys
showed.
</P>
<P>
With regard to who is likely to win the presidential race, 39.1
percent of the telephone respondents and 42.3 percent of the Internet
respondents chose the Lien-Soong ticket against 25.1 percent and 19.4
percent for the Chen-Lu ticket, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 45.06 percent of the telephone respondents and 51.5
percent of the Internet respondents were looking forward to a second
transfer of the country's political power, against 40.8 percent of
the telephone respondents and 36.8 percent of the Internet
respondents in favor of Chen-Lu's re-election.
</P>
<P>
Both of the polls showed that about 80 percent of the respondents
will vote in the presidential election. However, only 38.3 percent of
the telephone respondents and 33.1 percent of the Internet
respondents said that they would cast votes in the referendum called
by President Chen slated for March 20 alongside the presidential
election, against 42 percent and 44.1 percent for those who will not
vote in the referendum, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The telephone survey had a margin of error of 2.96 percent with
1,097 valid samples and the poll conducted via the Internet had a
margin of error of 2.61 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040306.0010" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
LIEN VOWS TO ESTABLISH CLEAN, CAPABLE GOVERNMENT IF ELECTED
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 6 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Opposition presidential candidate Lien Chan
on Saturday vowed to establish a "clean, capable and professional
government" if elected in the March 20 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Lien made the remarks when he spoke in a 30-minute platform
presentation of the presidential candidates sponsored by the Central
Election Commission. Local terrestrial TV station China Television
Company carried the presentation live.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the largest opposition party, the Kuomintang,
said that he is committed to establishing a clean government, adding
that, "No one will be able to come to my house to ask for positions
or any special favors."
</P>
<P>
He also promised not to condone the actions of anyone,
"especially my subordinates, when there is evidence of criminal
wrongdoing against them, " alluding to the recent allegations by a
disgraced fugitive tycoon against the ruling Democratic Progressive
Party, a ranking presidential aide and a Cabinet-level official.
</P>
<P>
If elected, he said, "I will donate my salary over the four-year
term and government subsides for presidential candidate to help
youngsters who can't afford to pay tuition, those who can't afford to
buy healthy lunches at school, and the elderly. This money will also
go to middle-to-low income families and the disabled who can't afford
to see doctors."
</P>
<P>
Stressing that this is not about money, Lien said that this will
be his way of telling himself that "being president is a social
service, and a president is one who has made up his mind to serve as
a volunteer."
</P>
<P>
Only by using this guideline can the presidential office avoid
becoming a conniving center for power and special interest groups,
and it is the way that Taiwan can be saved, Lien said.
</P>
<P>
On cross-Taiwan Strait relations, Lien said the basic stance of
his camp is that the Republic of China is an independent sovereign
country, and that cross-strait relations must be conducted under the
principles of "maintaining the status quo as well as Taiwan first."
</P>
<P>
He elaborated that insisting on the status quo is to safeguard
the dignity of the Taiwan people, so that Taiwan will not be
swallowed or unified by mainland China.
</P>
<P>
He also lashed out at his rival, incumbent President Chen
Shui-bian, for being fickle in his stance toward cross-strait
relations, wavering from his middle-of-the-road approach in 2000 to
the present "one country on each side of the Taiwan Strait."
</P>
<P>
Turning to the national pension plan which his camp has promoted
for a long time, he said it should be put into practice in four years
to ensure that every citizen can live in dignity after retirement.
</P>
<P>
Before the system is put in force, he said that half of the
retirement payments for laborers will receive a premium deposit rate
of 18 percent according to his plan.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he will promote a negative return tax system,
meaning that if the annual income of the people does not reach the
level of minimum income, the government will subsidize the shortfall.
</P>
<P>
His camp will also "promote ethnic equality and harmony, " and
those political figures who try to drive a wedge between ethnic
groups and polarized them will be disciplined according to the law,
Lien said.
</P>
<P>
He also vowed to uphold and promote Hakka culture, establish a
world-class Hakka museum, increase budgets for the Cabinet-level
Council for Hakka Affairs, nurture and groom Hakka political talents
with the ratio of Hakka people in politics no less than the ratio of
Hakka people among Taiwan's total population.
</P>
<P>
He again promoted his ideal of a recruit system for the military,
saying that today's warfare has changed, and the focus should be put
on high-technology weaponry and high-quality military men.
</P>
<P>
As the strategy of the nation in the event of war is to defend
and to deter, he said the current military structure should be
adjusted.
</P>
<P>
He advocated that all conscripts, after three month of compulsory
military training, become reservists. On the other hand, around
120,000 soldiers, 80,000 officers and 50,000 cadets from all levels
of military schools will form a 250,000 force to receive more
comprehensive training and become a credible defense force.
</P>
<P>
He said that the recruitment and conscription systems should
co-exist in the beginning, but the recruitment system can begin in
2008 after the government passes the appropriate law and NT$60
billion (US$1.8 billion) budget this year.
</P>
<P>
On education, Lien vowed to increase its budget to 6 percent of
the gross national product from the present 4.39 percent, or up
NT$160 billion. Among the most important things is to protect the
rights of impoverished young men to receive an education, he added.
</P>
<P>
Regarding Women's Day on March 8, Lien said that women would like
to see the nation develop and the jobless rate fall. They are also
interested in better social order and improving the education system,
he claimed.
</P>
<P>
He vowed to provide equality in the workplace, especially in
politics, so that the number of women nominees for government posts
or elections will be no less than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Lien said that the nation has come to a "threshold, " where the
president must take responsibility and deliver on his promises,
adding that "a second political power transfer must take place now"
to change the past and to provide hope to the nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
