<HEADLINE>
TAICHUNG AIRPORT SHOULD BOOST AIR TRAVEL TO EASTERN TAIWAN, ISLANDS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 6 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Despite strong public skepticism over the
market prospects and the security of the newly opened airport at
Chingchuankang in Taichung, central Taiwan, various domestic carriers
are optimistic about air travel business from central Taiwan to
eastern regions and outlying islands.
</P>
<P>
Both UNI Airways Corp. and Mandarin Airlines -- the only two
aviation companies that have set up service counters at
Chingchuankang Airport -- said that they are confident of good
business, although a high-speed railway system under construction is
slated to start operations next year.
</P>
<P>
The operations of the north-south high-speed railway will
undoubtedly deal a blow to Taipei-Taichung air travel, but the
railway system will cause no impact on the air travel market from
central Taiwan to eastern Hualien, Taitung and various outlying
islands because of their tourism potential, officials of the two
aviation companies said.
</P>
<P>
According to UNI Airways officials, a special air-sea transport
package designed by the carrier to help mainland-based Taiwan
businessmen return home to Taiwan proper via the "mini three links"
has received positive response since its inception last month, while
it also runs 14 flights from Taichung to the frontline island of
Kinmen each day.
</P>
<P>
UNI Airways also conducts the Taichung-Makung (on Penghu Island)
and the Taichung-Taipei and Taichung-Hengchun routes, while Mandarin
Airlines flies from Taichung to Taipei, Taitung, Hualien and Makung.
</P>
<P>
Although many people have had doubts over the future and what
some call inadequate facilities at Chingchuankang Airport, which was
inaugurated on Friday by the government in the run-up to the March 20
presidential election to replace the old Shuinan Airport, its
operations have proceeded smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Both UNI Airways and Mandarin Airlines said passenger loads on
board flights departing from the central Taiwan airport to
destinations in other regions are similar to levels registered in the
past.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, one of the three historic charter flights organized by
the Taichung Chamber of Commerce (TCC) in cooperation with China
Airlines to mark the airport's opening left from Taichung for Tokyo
Friday morning and arrived at Narita Airport later the same day with
158 passengers.
</P>
<P>
TCC Chairman Lai Cheng-i said he strongly believes that the
airport will give a boost to central Taiwan's tourism and traffic
development and he expressed the hope that it could launch regular
commercial flights as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
The airport, which recently completed its first phase of
construction, will only handle domestic and outbound charter flights
in the initial stage despite its status as an international airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
