<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040307.0010" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
REFERENDUM SUPPORTERS, OPPONENTS EXPOUND ON STANCES IN TV DEBATES
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 7 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The fifth and sixth of 10 rounds of live TV
debates on the two questions to be put forth in the March 20
referendum were staged Sunday, with representatives of the
affirmative and negative sides trying hard to sway voters with their
eloquence.
</P>
<P>
The fifth televised debate focused on the first referendum
question regarding whether the country should strengthen its
missile defense capability in the face of Beijing's
intensified missile threat.
</P>
<P>
In this round of debate, Yeh Yao-peng, a former Control Yuan
member who used to be a founding member of the ruling Democratic
Progressive Party (DPP) represented the "nay" side, while Legislator
Lo Chih-ming of the pro-independence Taiwan Solidarity Union (TSU)
represented the affirmative side. The TSU is the DPP's ally in the
opposition-controlled Legislative Yuan.
</P>
<P>
In the hour-long debate, Yeh claimed that the upcoming
referendum was illegal and unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
"The referendum to be held alongside the presidential election is
just President Chen Shui-bian's campaign ploy to boost his
re-election bid," Yeh said in his eight-minute opening remarks.
</P>
<P>
Under the Referendum Act, Yeh said, the president can hold a
referendum only when the nation's sovereign status is threatened.
Claiming that mainland China is not strong enough to attack Taiwan,
Yeh said, Chen has violated the Constitution and the Referendum Act in
calling the upcoming referendum.
</P>
<P>
"Even if mainland China can attack Taiwan, it dare not do so
because it is afraid of U.S. interference and flight of
foreign capital from the mainland," Yeh claimed. "Therefore, I urge
our voters to boycott this unconstitutional and illegal referendum.
Don't cast ballots in the referendum."
</P>
<P>
As to whether Taiwan should buy more anti-missile batteries, Yeh
said it's a complicated issue requiring enormous professional
expertise to answer. Voters should not be asked to make a judgment
on this kind of professional issue.
</P>
<P>
Yeh further said Taiwan's security is an integral part of world
security. "Taiwan should join forces with other peace-loving
countries to work for world peace and Taiwan's leader should not
provoke confrontation simply for electoral campaign purposes."
</P>
<P>
For his part, Legislator Lo defended President Chen's decision
to call a referendum alongside the presidential poll to save
voting cost.
</P>
<P>
Lo claimed that Yeh's opposition to the upcoming referendum
was mainly a tactic to help the opposition "pan-blue alliance"
presidential candidate -- Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan -- to
embarrass the DPP administration and undermine President Chen's
re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
"If the opposition camp really thinks the referendum is
unconstitutional and illegal, why it would not asked the Council
of Grand Justices to interpret," Lo said, adding that the
constitutionality and legality of the upcoming referendum is
actually beyond question and undisputable.
</P>
<P>
Given the fact that Beijing has deployed nearly 500
missiles against Taiwan, Lo said, President Chen is
eligible to call a referendum to protect Taiwan's present status
quo from being changed.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Lo said, referendum debate can help enhance local
people's "psychological defense" against mainland China's threat.
</P>
<P>
He further said the TSU which has 12 seats in the Legislature
supports procurement of advanced weaponry systems to beef up
Taiwan's defense capabilities.
</P>
<P>
In the sixth-round referendum debate, DPP Legislator Chiu
Tai-shan and Ting Ting-yu, a National Taiwan University sociology
professor, focused their debate on the second referendum question
-- whether Taiwan should negotiate with Beijing for the establishment
of a viable mechanism for peaceful interaction.
</P>
<P>
Chiu said this referendum can help forge a national consensus and
thus give the government a mandate to negotiate with mainland
China.
</P>
<P>
He urged local voters to cast a "yes" vote in this referendum to
boost Taiwan's clout in negotiating with mainland China on the
principle of parity and reciprocity to ensure permanent peace in the
Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
"Solidarity is strength. We should show Beijing and the world
society through this referendum that the people of Taiwan are
united," Chiu said.
</P>
<P>
However, Ting questioned the wisdom of holding the
referendum.
</P>
<P>
"Why should we hold political negotiations with Beijing at this
moment? It is dangerous to negotiate political issues with the
Chinese Communist Party. Taiwan's best strategy is to focus on
economic exchanges with mainland China for the moment. We can
use the vast mainland market to sustain our economic
development. The longer the better. We should separate political and
economic issues in dealing with mainland China," Ting said.
</P>
<P>
In his view, Ting went on, mainland China will not touch on the
Taiwan issue in the coming 20 to 30 years so long as Taiwan does not
pursue de jure independence. "And the best way to love Taiwan is
to win the U.S. support and trust," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040307.0011" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
RIVAL CAMPS PLAN MASSIVE CAMPAIGN RALLIES FOR MARCH 13
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 7 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With only 13 days to go before the March 20
presidential election, the two rival camps are planning elaborate
campaign rallies this coming Saturday on the last weekend before the
vote to drum up support for their candidates.
</P>
<P>
While the opposition "pan-blue alliance" of the Kuomintang (KMT)
and the People First Party (PFP) plans to mobilize at least 2.5
million people to take to the streets March 13 in a show of support
for its ticket, the ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) is also
planning a massive parade in the southern port city of Kaohsiung
on the same day to rally support for President Chen Shui-bian's
re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
PFP Legislator Lee Yung-ping told a news conference that the
"pan-blue alliance" will organize street marches in Taiwan's three
largest metropolises in the northern, central and southern parts of
the island -- Taipei, Taichung and Kaohsiung, respectively -- on
March 13 to whip up support for its ticket of KMT Chairman Lien Chan
and PFP Chairman James Soong.
</P>
<P>
"We'll express our dissatisfaction with the DPP administration's
poor performance over the past four years and our desire for a second
transition of power in the upcoming presidential poll, " Lee said,
adding that the large parades in various parts of the island will
carry the theme of "Change the President, Save Taiwan and Down with
Chen Shui-bian."
</P>
<P>
In addition, Lee said, the upcoming campaign rallies will also
highlight the "pan-blue alliance's" goal of "striving for
economic prosperity and peace."
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the same occasion, KMT Legislator Hung Hsiu-chu said
the March 13 rallies were originally designated as "anti-corruption"
events against "black gold politics."
</P>
<P>
"But we have changed our plan with a view to broadening the scope
of our appeal, " Hung said, adding that anti-corruption is still one
of the alliance's major concerns.
</P>
<P>
Hung said the "pan-blue alliance's" grass-roots supporters have
pushed the Lien-Soong campaign headquarters to organize massive-scale
rallies to consolidate voter support after the "pan-green camp" of
the DPP and other pro-independence groups successfully organized a
"hand-in-hand" rally on Feb. 28 when more than 2 million people held
hands together to form a 500-km human chain that stretched the length
of Taiwan in a show of support for Chen's re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
"Our grass-roots supporters are worried that the 'hand-in-hand'
rally might mislead pundits and ordinary citizens into believing that
the 'pan-green camp' really outweighs our alliance in terms of
support rate, "Hung said. "I'm convinced that we'll be able to rally
an even larger number of supporters for the March 13 street marches."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the "pan-blue alliance's" plan, DPP Legislator Chen
Ching-chun said the opposition camp might be wise to drop its
original designation for its March 13 street rallies.
</P>
<P>
"The results of many public opinion polls have consistently shown
that more than 45 percent still consider the 'pan-blue alliance' as
the epitome of corrupt 'black gold' politics, " Chen Ching-chun
claimed. "We feel regret that the 'pan-blue alliance' still resists
reforms, including hindering the much-anticipated down-sizing of the
Legislative Yuan."
</P>
<P>
Chen Ching-chun further said if the "pan-blue alliance" truly
supports reform, the KMT should return its ill-gotten huge party
assets to the people as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that reform and anti-"black gold politics" have been
the gist of President Chen's campaign platform, Chen Ching-chun said
the DPP has planned a large parade in Kaohsiung for this coming
Saturday to reaffirm the party's commitment to establishing
clean politics and to rally support for the president's re-election
bid.
</P>
</TEXT>
