<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040307.0012" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT URGES SUPPORTERS TO NOT LET DOWN THEIR GUARD
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taoyuan County,  March 7 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian urged his
supporters Sunday to not let down their guard in the presidential
race despite his lead over opposition Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan
in recent public opinion surveys conducted after the Feb. 28
"hand-in-hand" human chain event.
</P>
<P>
Chen, who is seeking re-election, made the appeal while speaking
at a series of campaign rallies held in the northern county of
Taoyuan.
</P>
<P>
Noting that he is fairly optimistic about winning the March 20
election, Chen said that following the successful mobilization of
more than one million people to form a colossal human chain across
the island, the ruling Democratic Progressive Party's ticket enjoyed
a clear lead over the "pan-blue alliance" ticket of Lien and James
Soong, chairman of the People First Party, in two polls.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey conducted by the DPP Feb. 29 and March 1,
the support rate for Chen and Vice President Annette Lu was 39.5
percent, while that for Lien and Soong was 36.2 percent. Another
survey conducted by a local public opinion survey company also showed
that the DPP ticket is in the lead.
</P>
<P>
However, Chen said the election outcome will be very close, with
the margin of victory being only between 30,000 and 50,000 votes.
"I'm hopeful that all of our supporters will not let down their guard
and will persist until we win the election," he said.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Chen also hailed Lu as an able woman and voiced
the hope that the first female vice president of Taiwan will be
re-elected March 20 to set another milestone in the nation's
democracy.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of Women's Day, which falls on March 8, the president
gave his salute to all the women of Taiwan and claimed that the DPP
was the first party in Taiwan to nominate women candidates to compete
in mayoral and county magistrate elections.
</P>
<P>
As for the "pan-blue alliance's" plan to mobilize one million
supporters to participate in a mass "anti-corruption" rally slated
for March 13 to reduce the impact of the Feb. 28 "hand-in-hand"
event, Chen said that the planned rally will backfire as the former
Kuomintang government was closely linked to the so-called "black
gold" politics.
</P>
<P>
Acording to Legislative Yuan President Wang Jin-pyng, who is also
chairman of the "pan-blue alliance" national campaign headquarters,
the opposition group will organize a mass rally of one million people
March 13 in northern, central and southern Taiwan to voice their
strong desire for clean politics and love for Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040307.0013" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN SHIFTS INTO HIGH GEAR AS ELECTION DAY APPROACHES
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 7 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With less than two weeks to go before the
presidential election, the ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP)
is trying to extend its supporters' enthusiasm for the "protect
Taiwan" campaign to election day, while the opposition "pan-blue
alliance" is seeking to consolidate its support among its core
supporters.
</P>
<P>
After the successful mobilization of more than one million people
to form a mammoth human chain across Taiwan to mark 2-28 Peace
Memorial Day, the "pan-green camp" of the DPP and its ally -- the
Taiwan Solidarity Union (TSU) -- is hoping its presidential
candidate, President Chen Shui-bian, can ride the success of the
"hand-in-hand" activity and win the upcoming election.
</P>
<P>
Legislator Tsai Huang-lang, the DPP whip at the Legislative Yuan,
said the Feb. 28 rally aroused the public's patriotism and raised
their awareness about Taiwan's separate identity. He voiced the hope
that the passion of DPP supporters will extend to the March 20
presidential poll.
</P>
<P>
In the coming two weeks, Tsai said, the DPP will continue to
organize a series of large-scale campaign rallies around the island
in a bid to maintain the people's zeal to defend the country and
translate this strong feeling into support for Chen in the election.
</P>
<P>
Tsai said that the Executive Yuan, for its part, should seek to
boost its administrative performance so that people may recognize all
the efforts made by the ruling party over the past four years, and
forge prospects of reform to win support from the majority of voters.
</P>
<P>
Tsai further said that the planned first-ever nationwide
referendum and the "Taiwan 100" campaign are also DPP's major appeals
for people's support for Chen's re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
The "Taiwan 100" campaign is aimed at urging voters to choose the
No. 1 candidate -- Chen Shui-bian -- in the election and to vote
"yes" for both referendum questions.
</P>
<P>
In addition to electing a president and vice president, voters
will also cast two additional ballots for the two questions put forth
in the referendum to be held alongside the presidential poll. The
questions are whether Taiwan should increase its anti-missile
defenses if mainland China refuses to remove its deployed missiles
aimed at Taiwan, and whether the government should negotiate with
Beijing for the establishment of an interaction mechanism for peace
across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
In the face of the series of DPP-staged strong campaign
offensives, Legislative Yuan President Wang Jin-pyng, who is also
chairman of the "pan-blue alliance" national campaign headquarters,
said that the opposition group will organize a mass rally of one
million people March 13 to voice their strong desire for clean
politics and love for Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the large-scale rally to be held in northern, central and
southern Taiwan will help lift the morale of the "pan-blue alliance"
after the DPP succeeded in organizing the "hand-in-hand" human chain
activity on Feb. 28 to say "no" to Beijing's missile threat against
the island," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The legislative head added that the "pan-blue alliance" will
boost its campaign strategy by "emphasizing reforms, bringing
forward concrete economic development policies and highlighting
the presidential candidate's personality and characteristics" in the
coming two weeks.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Legislator Huang Yi-chiao, who is also the PFP
spokesman, said the opposition alliance will also try to emphasize
that a "change" in Taiwan's leadership "will bring a brighter future
for Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
The presidential race has been too close to call for weeks, but
the 2-28 human chain rally seemed to give President Chen a boost,
with a DPP poll conducted Feb. 29 and March 1 showing his support
rate at 39.5 percent, ahead of his challenger KMT Chairman Lien
Chan's 36.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Chen pulled ahead by nearly 20 percentage points in southern
Taiwan, traditionally the DPP's stronghold. The ruling
ticket also led by four percentage points in central Taiwan and by up
to seven percentage points among younger voters, according to the
DPP poll.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040307.0014" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
BOTH CAMPS TARGET WORKERS AS ELECTION DAY APPROACHES
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 7 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With the March 20 presidential election
just around the corner, the two rival camps' efforts to broaden their
respective support bases, particularly among laborers, have
intensified.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of both President Chen Shui-bian's "pan-green camp"
and those of the opposition Kuomintang (KMT) Chairman Lien Chan's
"pan-blue alliance" have claimed that they have the support of labor.
</P>
<P>
While the "pan-blue alliance" has claimed that 70 percent of the
country's workers will vote for Lien and his running mate, People
First Party (PFP) Chairman James Soong, the "pan-green camp" has said
it has the support of at least 60 percent of the working vote.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) , which was an
influential force behind Taiwan's labor, social and aboriginal
activist campaigns when it was the major opposition party, has
recently regained its confidence in consolidating its support among
people from all walks of life after it sponsored the "one million
people hand-in-hand" human chain campaign on Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
Lai Ching-teh, director of the DPP's Department of Labor Affairs,
said that although some labor activist groups have called for their
members to boycott the March 20 election to show their displeasure
with both candidates, the DPP is confident it will win some 60
percent of the workers' votes.
</P>
<P>
Lai said KMT Chairman Lien Chan's advocacy of a national pension
plan in which he promises a high premium deposit rate of 18 percent
for retired laborers is doomed to fail.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Lien-Soong ticket's insistence on the
pro-unification "92 consensus" would also be catastrophic for the
country's workers if the pair is elected, whereupon pro-China
policies would be carried out, including the introduction of mainland
Chinese laborers into Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Still, Lin Hui-kuan, president of the Chinese Federation of
Labor, who is also an opposition PFP legislator, said that the DPP's
support rating among workers has continued to decline as a result of
the DPP administration's approval of a change to regulations to allow
foreign laborers to extend their work period in Taiwan for up to
three years. The previous maximum extension was two years.
</P>
<P>
According to Lin, the "pan-blue alliance" ticket's support rate
in southern Taiwan is about 55 percent, ahead of the "pan-green
camp's" 45 percent, and its support rate in northern Taiwan is around
70 percent, compared to the "pan-green camp's" 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cheng Chun-chi, former director of Taipei City's Labor
Affairs Bureau and current head of the blue-collar activists group
Action Committee for Labor Legislation, said his group's advocacy of
having one million null ballots cast in the March 20 referendum
initiated by President Chen remains on target.
</P>
<P>
Chien Hsi-chieh, a former DPP legislator and now one of the
decision makers of the "pan-purple alliance" made up mainly of
disadvantaged and social welfare groups, said supporters of the
alliance will boycott the March 20 presidential election altogether
to convey the message that both candidates are "bad apples" that are
not qualified to win any votes from the people.
</P>
</TEXT>
