<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040307.0015" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 7 (CNA)
(By Ben Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Sunday, March 7, or the 17th day
of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according to the lunar
calendar. Following is a list of important events that have occurred
on this date in the past:

1573: War between Turkey and Venice ends with the Treaty of
Constantinople.

1850: Tomas Garrigue Masaryk, the Czechoslovakian politician who
served as the first president of independent Czechoslovakia, is born.

1876: Scottish-born American inventor Alexander Graham Bell
receives a patent for his invention of the electric voice telegraph,
or telephone. Bell also invented the audiometer, an early hearing
aid, and improved the phonograph.

1918: The Bolsheviks change their name to the Russian Communist
Party.

1932: French Prime Minister Aristide Briand dies at the age of
70. He drew up the Kellogg-Briand Pact and shared the 1926 Nobel
Peace Prize as well as pioneered the idea of a United States of
Europe.

1936: In contempt of the Versailles Treaty imposed after World
War I, German Chancellor Adolf Hitler marches his troops into the
demilitarized zone east of the Rhine.

1942: Japanese forces land on New Guinea while other Japanese
troops begin to enter the Burmese capital of Rangoon after the
British evacuation from the city.

1945: Chinese expeditionary forces recapture Lashio in northern
Burma.

1945: Britain's 14th Army enters Mandalay in Burma.

1950: Republic of China President Chiang Kai-shek nominates Gen.
Chen Cheng as premier.

1951: Iran's Premier Ali Razmara is assassinated by a religious
fanatic in a mosque in Tehran.

1957: The Gaza Strip, which was administered by Egypt under the
cease-fire agreements following the Arab-Israeli war of 1948, comes
under U.N. rule.

1971: Swiss men vote to give women the right to vote and hold
federal office.

1973: Forty-two agriculturists from 12 African countries attend
the opening of the 14th Agricultural Seminar for African Technicians.

1974: ROC Vice President C.K. Yen leaves for Latin America to
attend the inaugurations of President Ernesto Geisel of Brazil and
President Carlos Andres Perez of Venezuela.

1974: The 3rd Pacific Area Travel Association Regional Conference
opens in Taipei with more than 20 delegates attending from Hong Kong,
Indonesia, Japan, Korea, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore,
Thailand and the ROC.

1974: A Sino-Saudi Arabian trade cooperation agreement is signed
in Taipei by Wu Kwan-hsiung, secretary-general of the China External
Trade Development Council, and Sand M. Al-Joajil, president of the
Chamber of Commerce and Industry of the Eastern Provinces of Saudi
Arabia.

1978: President Ne Win of Burma is re-elected for a second term.

1989: Communist China declares martial law in Lhasa following
three days of rioting in which hundreds of Tibetans were reportedly
gunned down by Communist Chinese security forces.

1989: A convicted murderer in South Carolina who successfully
appealed against being sent to the electric chair is electrocuted
accidentally while sitting on the toilet mending a pair of earphones.

1990: The KMT Central Standing Committee passes a draft revision
of the Temporary Provisions Effective During the Period of National
Mobilization for Suppression of the Communist Rebellion.

1992: Nicaraguan President Violeta Barrios de Chamorro and ROC
President Lee Teng-hui sign a join communique in Taipei for stronger
bilateral relations.

1996: Three U.S. servicemen are convicted in Japan and sentenced
to six-and-a-half to seven years in prison for the abduction and rape
of a 12-year-old Okinawa schoolgirl in 1995.

2000: ROC Foreign Minister Chen Chien-jen and Palauan State
Minister Sabino Anastacio sign a joint statement with the aim of
boosting bilateral cooperation in a wide range of areas.

2001: Taiwan's religious community joins in the worldwide chorus
of condemnation of the decision by the Taliban, Afghanistan's
hardline Islamic regime, to destroy ancient Buddhist statutes in
Afghanistan.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "An honest man does not want,
neither does he profess, esotericism. Men now are earnest in what
they profess. Are they really good and wise men? Or are they serious
only in appearance? That is what I should like to know."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040308.0001" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL HEADLINE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Manila, March 8 (CNA)
