<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040308.0006" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES NECK-AND-NECK AMONG UNIVERSITY STUDENTS: POLL
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 8 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The two presidential candidates --
President Chen Shui-bian and opposition Kuomintang Chairman Lien
Chan, are running neck-and-neck in terms of popularity among Taiwan's
university students, according to the results of a survey released
Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the opinion poll conducted by Shih Hsin University in Taipei,
27.3 percent of 801 students who have the right to vote and were
interviewed in the survey favor the presidential ticket of Chen and
his running mate, Annette Lu, while 27.1 percent support Lien and his
running mate, James Soong. Some 30 percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
They were also evenly divided on the first of two questions in
the proposed referendum -- whether the country should strengthen its
missile defense capability -- with 31.1 percent saying "yes, " as
advocated by Chen and Lu, against 29.2 percent who said they will
follow the suit of Lien and Soong in boycotting the referendum. Nine
percent said they will vote "no" and 24.3 percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
The second question in the referendum -- whether the country
should negotiate for peace with the mainland -- is less
controversial, with 40.2 percent saying "yes, " 27.8 percent saying
they will boycott the vote, 3.2 percent saying they will vote "no"
and 24.1 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
Students with right to vote for the first time accounted for
about 40 percent of the students interviewed and 64.9 percent said
they will vote in the March 20 presidential election, which is 14.6
percent higher than that of those who are not first-time voters.
</P>
<P>
Of all the students with the right to vote, about 60 percent said
they will vote in the election, against 20 percent who said they
won't.
</P>
<P>
Among the total of 1,152 students interviewed, however, 33.4
percent said they believe Lien and Soong will win the election
against 16.6 percent for the Chen-Lu ticket and 38.9 percent who said
the outcome is "unpredictable."
</P>
<P>
The survey was carried out between Feb. 27 and March 2 through
face-to-face interviews with students from 22 universities and
colleges in northern Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
No margin of error was revealed by the author.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040308.0007" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC EXPANSION INDEX TO REACH 58.13 PERCENT IN FIRST QUARTER
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 8 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fueled by a rebounding global economy as
well as continued growth of domestic exports and manufacturing sector
production, the economic expansion index in the first quarter of this
year is expected to reach 58.13 percent, up 4.4 percent from the
fourth quarter of 2003, according to a report released Monday by the
Ministry of Economic Affairs (MOEA).
</P>
<P>
An MOEA official said that the ministry issued the report after
analyzing the results of a survey conducted among 9,700 manufacturers
Feb. 10-25 to gain a better understanding of their viewpoints on the
domestic economic climate and trends. A total of 8,264 responses were
received, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector's business growth index topped the list
at 65.4 percent, the highest level since 2000, followed by the
wholesale and retail sectors at 55.77 percent and the leasing and
technical service sectors at 55.25 percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to being optimistic about Taiwan's economic recovery,
as many as 73.2 percent of those polled said they had invested in
fixed assets last year. In terms of investment value, the information
and electronic sectors topped the list at NT$269.2 billion (US$8.08
billion), accounting for 78 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 885 manufacturers said that they are planning to
invest in fixed assets this year, up by 50 from the year-earlier
level, the report pointed out. The total investment value is
estimated at NT$300.8 billion, representing an annual growth of
NT$101.4 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040308.0008" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
KMT CHIEF ADVOCATES CROSS-STRAIT STATUS QUO
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 8 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Opposition presidential candidate Lien Chan
said in a recent interview with Time magazine that his camp believes
in maintaining the status quo in regard to relations between the two
sides of the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
Lien, who is the sole challenger of President Chen Shui-bian in
Taiwan's March 20 presidential election, noted that the Republic of
China has been in existence for 93 years and said that his "pan-blue
alliance" of the opposition Kuomintang and its ally the People First
Party, opposes Taiwan independence and does not see unification with
mainland China likely in the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
Lien said that if the mainland insists on the resumption of
cross-strait talks under the "one China" principle, then it will be
difficult for such talks to resume.
</P>
<P>
This is because for the "pan-blue alliance, " "one China" means
the Republic of China, Lien said, a concept that Beijing refuses to
acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
He also said that if elected March 20, he will embark on a "peace
journey" to the mainland before his May 20 inauguration and will
propose to Beijing that it gradually dismantle the missiles it has
deployed against Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
He said he has no way of knowing if Beijing would welcome such a
visit, or its attitude toward resuming cross-strait talks.
</P>
<P>
But he said Beijing should know that it will be different dealing
with his alliance than with the ruling Democratic Progressive Party,
because while his alliance will insist on the sovereignty of the ROC,
it will not promote Taiwan independence.
</P>
<P>
He also said that if confrontation between the two sides of the
Taiwan Strait continues, it will become more and more difficult for
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The disputes over sovereignty will not be resolved in the
foreseeable future, but there are many issues concerning the common
interests of the two sides of the Taiwan Strait, Lien observed,
adding that cross-strait relations are a self-imposed blockage. By
this, he meant that cross-strait political relations are stalled, but
in all other ways, exchanges are brisk.
</P>
<P>
With the strengthening of Taiwan's democracy, the consciousness
