<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040308.0012" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION CAMP PRESENTS DRAFT BILL ON VOLUNTARY MILITARY SERVICE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 8 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The legislative caucuses of the opposition
Kuomintang (KMT) and the People First Party (PFP) jointly presented a
draft bill on voluntary military service Monday for deliberation in
the Legislative Yuan.
</P>
<P>
KMT legislative whip Liao Feng-teh and PFP legislative whip Hsieh
Chang-chieh said at a joint news conference that the draft statute
contains elaborate provisions for implementing an enlistment-based
military service system.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a televised presidential campaign forum sponsored by
the Central Election Commission last weekend, KMT Chairman Lien Chan,
who teams up with PFP Chairman James Soong to challenge President
Chen Shui-bian's re-election bid, said if he wins the March 20
election, his administration will complete military service reform by
2008.
</P>
<P>
"The voluntary military service draft bill is the first
step to realize Lien's campaign promise," Liao said, adding that the
KMT-PFP alliance, better known as the "pan-blue alliance," will
push for inclusion of the bill into the legislature's screening
agenda at Tuesday's Steering Committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Liao said, the "pan-blue alliance," which controls a
majority in the legislature, hopes to complete legislation of the
voluntary military service statute before the presidential poll to
betray its presidential candidate's determination to deliver on his
campaign promise.
</P>
<P>
The "pan-blue alliance"-drafted bill encompasses five chapters
with a total of 54 articles, regulating the enlisted targets,
qualifications, enlisted troop rankings, duration of service, salary
and fringe benefits, scholarship, welfare benefits for their
families, pension and other compensation.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the "pan-blue alliance's" move, Tsai Huang-lang, the
legislative whip of the ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP),
said military service reform is a rather serious issue that should not be
addressed in a hasty, perfunctory manner.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Tsai said, the "pan-blue alliance's" proposal is just
a ploy to court young voters.
</P>
<P>
In last Saturday's TV speech on his platform, Lien said if he
wins the presidency, his administration will facilitate the passage
of a bill creating a fully professional military service system
within one year and pass a special budget of NT$60 billion to put the
policy into effect as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
According to Lien's plan, Taiwan's fully voluntary or
professional military would require 120,000 troops, 80,000 officers
and non-commissioned officers and 50,000 graduates of military
schools to make up a high-quality, defensive force.
</P>
<P>
Lien's plan also requires all young men of draft age participate
in a military training course lasting three months.
</P>
<P>
In the same TV forum, President Chen said a fully voluntary
military is a goal that can be achieved only in a gradual manner,
rather than in what he called an improvised manner as Lien's.
</P>
<P>
Chen claimed that Lien's plan could lead to "hollowing out"
of Taiwan's national defense base.
</P>
</TEXT>
