<HEADLINE>
KAOHSIUNG CITY KICKS OFF MECHANISM TO WARD OFF DENGUE FEVER
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  8 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A set of mechanisms worked out by the
Kaohsiung city government to fend off dengue fever officially kicked
off Monday following an announcement by Vice Mayor Lin Yung-chien.
</P>
<P>
Lin made the announcement at a municipal meeting in which it was
decided that from March 11, all city government agencies, schools and
residents must conduct self-control management to clean up their
environment every Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It was also announced that Kaohsiung and Pingtung counties will
announce in a coordination conference next week their joining with
Kaohsiung City every Thursday to combat the mosquito-borne disease to
prevent its spread in all three areas.
</P>
<P>
According to Lin, there was only one dengue fever case in
Kaohsiung City during the Jan. 1-March 7 period and this was proven
to be an infection picked up overseas.
</P>
<P>
The Kaohsiung citizen was confirmed to have contracted dengue
fever after developing diarrhea, headache and fever following a trip
to Thailand from Jan. 18 to Feb. 8. The patient made a full recovery.
</P>
<P>
Lin added that after continued tracing and monitoring via
telephone by municipal health workers of citizens who have come back
from countries in Southeast Asia, no further cases have been
discovered.
</P>
<P>
From April 14, the municipal environmental protection personnel
will begin disinfection work in city streets with the onset of hotter
summer weather in an effort to help wipe out the disease.
</P>
</TEXT>
