<HEADLINE>
SINGAPORE HEALTH CARE SYSTEM AMONG MOST EFFICIENT IN WORLD: SURVEY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Singapore,  March 8 (CNA)
(By Sherman Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Singapore's health care system is among
the most efficient in the world, according to the results of a survey
of developed countries by Singapore's Health Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry published the survey results Saturday to show
that the co-payment system in Singapore has led to more efficient
choices in terms of health care services.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's co-payment system, where patients bear at least 20
percent of the bill, was defended by the Health Ministry as a
necessary measure to keep the health care system efficient.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Health Balaji Sadasivan said that "there
must be co-payment for health care so that the demand for health care
services is brought under control. However, the co-payment amount
must be reasonable so that people can afford."
</P>
<P>
Among all the countries surveyed, patients in Singapore have the
shortest average hospital stay at 4.8 days, or almost half of
Holland's average of nine days.
</P>
<P>
The number of patients being admitted to hospitals has also been
falling steadily in Singapore since 1991. And in 2000, the number of
people being admitted into Singapore hospitals was among the lowest
among developed countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
