<HEADLINE>
NOBEL LAUREATE HECKMAN INVITED AS ECONOMIC ADVISER TO LIEN
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 8 (CNA)
(By Eric Liu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Presidential candidate Lien Chan of the
"pan-blue alliance" announced Monday that Nobel Prize winner James
Heckman will be an economic adviser to the new government after May
20 if the "pan-blue alliance" wins the March 20 election.
</P>
<P>
Heckman is the second Nobel laureate to be on the advisers list
with three others to be offered possible future positions.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the National Policy Research Foundation, a
Kuomintang (KMT) -run think tank, invited Nobel Prize-winner Laurence
R. Klein last week to be an economic adviser, and that Heckman has
expressed an interest in helping as well shows that the "pan-blue
alliance" is determined to boost the economy, Lien said.
</P>
<P>
Heckman spoke Monday on the revolution that has taken place in
the global labor market and Taiwan's future development. Also
attending the meeting were Vice President of the Legislative Yuan P.
K. Chiang, former Minister of Foreign Affairs Chao Yao-tung and other
scholars.
</P>
<P>
According to Heckman, an open economic system in the long term
has more potential, whereas a closed one is susceptible to adverse
impacts. New incentives will step up productivity while isolated
policies will downgrade productivity. He went on to say that
restrictive measures will lower the migration of laborers. Political
leaders should be aware of the importance of changing economic
trends.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Taiwan's strength is stimulating mainland
China's economic revolution, openness and growth. However, protective
policies may be needed in Taiwan during this transition period, but
decent policies need to be carried out to avoid unfairness to future
generations and to avoid slowing down economic advancement.
</P>
<P>
Lien said after the meeting that the negative impact on the
self-confined attitude toward the Taiwan-mainland China relationship
needs to be further evaluated; he also noted that Taiwan has
succeeded before in keeping the unemployment rate below 3 percent,
but it has increased dramatically in the last four years and poses a
serious threat to society.
</P>
<P>
Heckman was the 2000 Nobel Prize winner in economics, and
specializes in econometrics and microeconomics, with extended
experimental studies in labor supply, salary allocation and auxiliary
plans in the labor market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
