<HEADLINE>
MOFA TO STRENGTHEN CONTACTS WITH U.S. OVER HONG KONG ISSUE: OFFICIAL
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  8 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs will
strengthen contacts with the United States over Hong Kong's
democratic development issues, Vice Minister of Foreign Affairs
Michael Ying-mao Kau said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Kau said, the foreign ministry will give moral support
to Hong Kong's pursuit of full democracy.
</P>
<P>
Kau made the remarks while fielding questions at a meeting of the
Legislative Yuan's Foreign Affairs Committee.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Legislator Parris Chang of the ruling
Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) said Hong Kong's prominent
dissident lawmaker Martin Lee testified before a U.S. Senate hearing
last Friday on the former British colony's demand for full democracy.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the hearing reflected increasing U.S. concern about
Hong Kong's democratic development, Chang suggested that the foreign
ministry issue a statement in support of Hong Kong's democratization.
</P>
<P>
In response, Kau said the foreign ministry seldom deals with
politically sensitive issues. Nevertheless, he said, the foreign
ministry will reinforce contact with U.S. authorities over issues
regarding Hong Kong's democratization.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kau said, the foreign ministry-operated Taiwan
Foundation for Democracy will serve as a platform for promoting
democratic diplomacy with other parts of the world, including Hong
Kong and mainland China.
</P>
<P>
To facilitate realization of this goal, Kau said the foundation
has launched a quarterly as a forum for academic exchanges among
Chinese societies around the world.
</P>
<P>
"The inaugural issue, published early this month, contains
articles written by eight scholars at home and abroad. The articles
address issues regarding Taiwan's democratic experiences as well as
its plight and challenges," said Kau, who concurrently serves as the
foundation's chief executive. "We'll invite scholars and experts in
mainland China, Hong Kong and Singapore to contribute papers or
articles to our new publication," Kau said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040308.0027" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL RACE IN STATISTICAL DEAD HEAT: THINKTANK-SPONSORED POLL
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  8 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The race in Taiwan between the two
candidates for president is a statistical dead heat with less than
two weeks before the March 20 election, a poll released Monday shows.
</P>
<P>
The poll was conducted by Focus Survey Research under the
consignment of Taiwan Thinktank. Taiwan Thinktank is an organization
friendly to the ruling Democratic Progressive Party.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll, President Chen Shui-bian's support rate
was 40.4 percent. Opposition Kuomintang candidate Lien Chan's support
stood at 39.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Hsu Yung-ming, an assistant researcher at Academia Sinica's
Institute of Social Sciences, said although the support rate for Chen
and his running mate, Vice President Annette Lu, has reached a record
high -- surpassing the 40 percent mark for the first time -- the
ticket's lead has also narrowed, down 0.7 percent from last week.
</P>
<P>
With the campaign shifting into high gear as the election
approaches, both camps of Chen and Lien, commonly known as the
"pan-green" camp and the "pan-blue alliance, " respectively, have
pulled out all the stops to try to win the support of different
groups, particularly undecided voters.
</P>
<P>
The poll found that 20.10 percent of those surveyed would not
make their affiliations known or remain undecided, Hsu said.
</P>
<P>
As a majority of the undecided are young men and women, young
people will be the key to deciding which candidate will win, Hsu
said.
</P>
<P>
Both camps have been focusing their campaigns on the 1.5 million
young men and women who have turned 20 within the last four years and
are eligible to vote in the upcoming presidential election for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
While the 2-28 human chain rally gave an evident boost to
President Chen re-election bid, Lien has tried to win the hearts and
souls of young men by advocating an all-recruit military and only
three months of compulsory military service.
</P>
<P>
The latest survey, conducted over the weekend, has a margin of
error of 2.92 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
