<HEADLINE>
MATSU URGES UNI AIRWAYS TO OPEN ROUTES TO CENTRAL, SOUTHERN TAIWAN
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  8 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Matsu authorities have urged the sole
carrier flying between the outlying island and Taiwan proper to open
routes to destinations in central and southern Taiwan as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
The authorities made recently an official request to Taipei-based
UNI Airways Corp. -- the sole carrier approved by the Civil
Aeronautics Administration (CAA) to operate routes between Matsu and
Taiwan-- to open the Matsu-Taichung and Matsu-Kaohsuing routes by
April 1.
</P>
<P>
UNI Airways Chairman Cheng Kuang-yung made a promise during a
visit in November to Matsu that the two routes would be opened in
mid-February, but so far nothing has been done.
</P>
<P>
According to Matsu authorities, the postponement of the two
routes has caused discontent and misunderstanding of the Matsu people
and many mainland-based Taiwan businessmen who have long hoped for the
opening, especially after the direct trade and transport service --
the so-called "mini three links" -- were set up in Jan. 2001.
</P>
<P>
The CAA apparently told Legislator Chao Yuan-Jhang that two
routes would open on April 1, but business sources pointed out that
UNI Airways has yet to agree to the prices set by the CAA.
</P>
</TEXT>
