<HEADLINE>
WOMEN ACCOUNT FOR 12 PERCENT  OF SENIOR ADMINISTRATION OFFICIALS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 8 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Women account for about 12 percent of all
senior-level decision-making officials at the Executive Yuan and its
subordinate agencies, Executive Yuan Secretary-General Liu Shih-fang
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Liu said, 32 percent of intermediate-level
decision-making officials at all central government agencies are
women.
</P>
<P>
"These two figures indicate that Taiwan has made progress in
admitting women to join its policy-making process, " Liu said, adding
that there is still ample room for Taiwan to promote more female
civil servants to management or leadership posts.
</P>
<P>
Liu made the remarks at the 2004 Golden Carnation Awards
presentation ceremony in celebration of Women's Day, which is March
8.
</P>
<P>
Under Taiwan's administrative system, civil servants are
classified into senior (grades 10-14) , intermediate (grades 6-9) or
junior (grades 1-5) levels. The 14 levels of administration reflect
an employee's abilities, experience and seniority.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Yuan or Cabinet set up the Golden Carnation Awards
in 2003 to encourage heads of administrative agencies to promote more
women civil servants to take part in the policy-making process.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ceremony, Liu said President Chen Shui-bian has
attached great importance to gender equality in government service
and has directed the Central Personnel Administration (CPA) to hammer
out elaborate measures to substantiate that goal.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment of the Golden Carnation Awards is part of the
government's efforts to promote gender equality in civil service, "
Liu said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 20 government agencies, including the CPA, the
Department of Health (DOH) and the National Youth Commission (NYC) ,
received the awards for having promoted many women bureaucrats to
senior- or intermediate-level management posts.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Ministry of the Interior, the Kaohsiung City
Government, the Hualien County Government's Land Administration
Office and the government-owned Taipei Veterans General Hospital were
presented special awards for having adopted special measures to
improve facilities and services for their women employees.
</P>
<P>
Quoting the results of a U.N. survey, Su Chien-ling, a
commissioner of the Cabinet's Women's Rights Promotion Commission,
said Taiwan ranks among the frontrunners in Asia in terms of gender
equality in political participation, but still lags many advanced
countries in this regard. The top five in the world rating are all
Scandinavian countries, she said.
</P>
<P>
Many women political appointees in President Chen's
administration, including Chairwoman Chang Fu-mei of the Overseas
Chinese Affairs Commission, Taiwan Provincial Consultative Council
Speaker Yu Ling-ya and Deputy Chairwoman Chang Chin-hua of the
Council of Hakka Affairs, attended the presentation ceremony to show
their support for promotion of more women civil servants to
management posts in government agencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
