<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN MISSION TO WTO OPENS ITS WEBSITE TO THE PUBLIC
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Geneva,  March 8 (CNA)
(By Neil Lu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan's permanent mission to the World
Trade Organization (WTO) on Monday officially opened its website to
the public, symbolizing that the island's participation in the global
trade regulatory body's activities has entered a new stage.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the opening up of the website, Yen Ching-Chang,
Taiwan's permanent representative to the WTO, said that the people of
Taiwan will be able to directly obtain WTO information and to better
their understanding about the government's efforts in pushing
multilateral trade affairs by visiting the website.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's economic and trade development has benefited greatly
from the island's participation in the WTO, Yen said, adding that
close cooperation between his mission and government agencies on
relevant issues has helped the mission's performance within the WTO.
He said this not only protects the nation's economic and trade
interests through the multilateral mechanism, but also creates global
business and trade opportunities for Taiwan industries and
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In order to help the Taiwan people and relevant organizations
better their understanding regarding the WTO's operations as well as
the mission's activities in the organization, the mission decided to
set up a website at the end of last year. The main contents of the
newly-established website also include the "Doha Round" trade talks
developments and explanations of international trade rules.
</P>
<P>
Yen said that his mission's work will become easier if the
opening up of the website draws more attention and participation from
the Taiwan people and relevant institutions regarding the WTO
affairs.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the hope that the Taiwan academic and business
circles as well as the general public will fully use the website as
well as give suggestions to the mission and strengthen interactions
with it.
</P>
<P>
The website address of the mission is "http://www.taiwanwto.ch".
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040308.0037" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 8 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Monday, March 8, or the 18th
day of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according to the
lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that have
occurred on this date in the past:

1702: Queen Anne accedes to the British throne after the death of
her brother-in-law, William III, in a riding accident.

1765: Britain's House of Lords passes the Stamp Act to tax
American colonies.

1874: Millard Fillmore, the 13th president of the United States,
dies at the age of 74. He struggled to keep the nation united but
lost the support of his Whig Party by attempting to enforce the
Fugitive Slave Act in the North.

1879: Otto Hahn, German chemist who won a 1944 Nobel Prize for
his work on atomic fission, is born.

1898: The United States refuses to back Britain in its conflict
with Russia over a loan to China.

1906: The British government publishes the latest "Blue Book,"
telling how -- in theory -- it is now possible to travel around the
world without leaving the dominion of Great Britain, which now has a
population of 400 million people and covers 12 million square miles.

1917: Count Ferdinand von Zeppelin, the German inventor who
designed and manufactured the first motorized, rigid-frame dirigible
balloon, or airship, dies at the age of 79.

1930: William Howard Taft, the 27th president of the United
States, dies at the age of 73. His term was marked by passage of the
Payne-Aldrich Tariff Act. He also later served on the U.S. Supreme
Court as chief justice of the United States.

1942: Japanese forces capture Java after 100,000 defenders
surrendered.

1949: France recognizes Vietnam under the rule of Bao Dai as an
independent state within the French Union.

1950: The Republic of China's Legislative Yuan approves the
nomination of Gen. Chen Cheng as premier.

1952: The Pentagon announces that even after the end of the
Korean War, the United States will continue defending Taiwan and the
Philippines, which are listed as being under the protection of the
U.S. Pacific Fleet.

1954: The United States signs a mutual defense agreement with
Japan.

1965, The United States sends 3,500 Marines, the first batch of
American combat forces, to join the Vietnam War.

1969: The Soviet Union puts its Far East Army on alert as a
warning to Communist China after a frontier clash on Chen Pao Island
in the Ussuri River.

1971: In a historic world heavyweight title fight, Joe Frazier
defeats Mohammed Ali in 15 rounds.

1976: The first session of the Sino-Saudi Arabian Permanent Joint
Committee on Economic and Technical Cooperation opens with Chang
Kwang-shih, ROC economic affairs vice minister, and Mansoor Al-Turki,
Saudi Arabian deputy minister of finance and national economy, as
co-chairmen.

1981: Twenty-eight people are killed and more than 100 others
injured when an express train derails near Touchien River in Hsinchu
County.

1989: Communist Chinese troops converge on Lhasa to enforce
martial law after three days of rioting in the Tibetan capital.

1993: South Korean President Kim Young Sam fires two key generals
in a move to establish civilian control of the army.

1996: Mainland China begins eight days of test-firing
surface-to-surface missiles in waters close to major ports in
northeastern and southwestern Taiwan, timed to last until the
island's first direct presidential election.

1999: New York Yankees baseball legend Joe Dimaggio dies at the
age of 84.

1999: A Taiwanese-born scientist, suspected of handing over
nuclear missile technology to Beijing in the 1980s, is fired by the
U.S. Energy Department.

2000: President Lee Teng-hui, in his capacity as Kuomintang
chairman, orders the all-out mobilization of party members in support
of Vice President Lien Chan, the KMT candidate in the presidential
election just 10 days away.

2001: Premier Chang Chun-hsiung unveils an ambitious plan to
spend NT$810 billion (US$25 billion) this year to catapult Taiwan
into "a new era."

Confucius' lesson of the day: "Renounce yourself and conform to
the ideal of decency and good sense."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040309.0001" type="multi" >
