<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040309.0002" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-REFERENDUM ELECTION SUPERVISORS URGED TO RESIGN
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 9 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Election administrators and supervisors who
have publicly advocated a boycott of the March 20 referendum should
resign immediately in order to maintain the neutrality of the system
in voting affairs, civic groups said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Senior executives from several prominent civic groups, including
the Judicial Reform Foundation (JRF) and the Taipei Society, made the
call after a group of self-proclaimed members from various levels of
election commissions and supervisory panels ran advertisements in
local newspapers last week urging the electorate not to cast ballots
in the upcoming referendum.
</P>
<P>
Hung Yu-hung, president of the Taipei Society, said at a joint
news conference that the move by the officials has seriously violated
the cardinal principles of neutrality and impartiality in voting
administration and supervision.
</P>
<P>
"If those who are responsible for referendum-related
administrative affairs can publicly advocate a boycott of the
referendum, who will believe in the credibility of the voting
mechanism?" Hung asked.
</P>
<P>
Individual members of the central, city and county election
commissions and election supervisory panels definitely can have their
own stances and choices, Hung said. "However, since they have taken
up those posts, they should recognize the importance and sacredness
of their jobs. They should understand that their inability to perform
their duty impartially will sabotage and even destroy our democratic
system," he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that individual election administrators and supervisors
must serve as guardians and impartial executors of the nation's
electoral system, Hung said they are not entitled to publicly
advocate a boycott of the referendum in their official capacity.
</P>
<P>
Those who have signed their names in the "Say No to Referendum"
advertisements mostly come from the election commissions and
supervisory panels in the opposition Kuomintang-controlled
constituencies, such as Taipei City, Taoyuan County and Taichung
City.
</P>
<P>
A JRF spokesman said their public anti-referendum advocacy has
hurt Taiwan's democratic development and has invited suspicions about
the neutrality and impartiality of those election administrative and
supervisory commissions in handling the upcoming referendum.
</P>
<P>
To protect the image of those bodies, the spokesman said, all the
election administrators and supervisors who have joined the public
anti-referendum drive should resign immediately.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also expressed regret that the advertisements carry
many misleading allegations, including that the Referendum Act
prohibits the simultaneous holding of a referendum and a presidential
election and that those who administer or cast ballots in what the ad
calls the "illegal and unconstitutional" referendum could be
performing a criminal act.
</P>
<P>
Even if the court rules that the referendum is invalid due to low
voter turnout, the spokesman said, neither voters nor election
administrators will be charged with committing a crime. "This is
common sense. Those election administrators and supervisors should
not use such misleading allegations to intimidate or sway voters."
</P>
<P>
As to the issues of the legality and constitutionality of the
referendum, the spokesman said, opponents should ask the Council of
Grand Justices to clarify the disputes, and should not pass judgment
on their own instead.
</P>
<P>
In the nation's first-ever nationwide referendum to be held
alongside the presidential election on March 20, voters will be asked
two questions -- whether Taiwan should buy more anti-missile
batteries in the face of Beijing's missile threat and whether Taiwan
should negotiate a viable interactive mechanism with Beijing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040309.0003" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
MORE STOLEN CARS SEIZED BEFORE HEADING ABROAD
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 9 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Officers from the Criminal Investigation
Bureau (CIB) raided a container depot in Taoyuan, northern Taiwan
Monday and discovered four Toyota Camry cars inside a container that
was queued for transport to Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
According to the container depot operators, the container with
the four Camry cars was registered as a shipment of scrap iron
destined for Cambodia, CIB authorities reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The police found that the company that sponsored the export of
the scrap iron is related to Chou Cheng-hsu, 26, a former worker with
a major Mercedes-Benz car dealer in Taipei, who was arrested Feb. 16
for his alleged involvement in a cross-border car theft ring.
</P>
<P>
Chou and Cheng Fu-hsiang, 42, were arrested in Taoyuan and
Taipei, respectively, on Feb. 16 on charges of fraud and theft. The
pair are believed to be the masterminds behind a cross-border car
theft ring.
</P>
<P>
CIB investigators said they possess evidence showing that Chou
and Cheng have operated a ring that steals new Mercedes-Benz, BMW and
Toyota Camry cars in Taiwan and then ships the stolen vehicles to
southeast Asia for sale.
</P>
<P>
Although the CIB officials thought that the arrest of the pair
would help police stem the cross-border trade in stolen cars,
Monday's discovery of four more stolen Camry cars in the container
bound for Cambodia alerted police that the operations of the
cross-border car theft ring have never ceased.
</P>
<P>
Over the past months, CIB officials discovered that members of
the group have created a tight network where division of labor is
key. For example, the individuals responsible for stealing, container
loading, shipping and overseas sales do not know each other,
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
According to the investigators, Chou was also involved in a
series of fraudulent withdrawals from automatic teller machines
islandwide during the Oct. 10 National Day holiday last year.
</P>
<P>
In August 2003, the CIB successfully had 12 stolen new Toyota
Camry cars shipped back to Taiwan from Singapore through the joint
efforts of police, customs and immigration authorities from the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The CIB was tipped off in early July 2003 that a car theft ring
was planning to ship stolen cars to Thailand and Cambodia via
Singapore for sale.
</P>
<P>
After scrutinizing a large stack of container loading documents,
shipping firms' data and customs clearance reports, investigators
uncovered two containers holding eight new Camrys at a container
terminal at Keelung Harbor in late July last year.
</P>
<P>
Through a further analysis of relevant documents, they concluded
that three other containers holding 12 stolen cars had been shipped
to Singapore's Keepel Port.
</P>
<P>
The CIB asked Singaporean customs to assist in intercepting the
containers. CIB and local customs officers then traveled to Singapore
to arrange for shipment of the cars back to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
According to CIB investigations, the 20 new Camrys were stolen in
Tainan, Taichung, Hsinchu and Taoyuan between July 4 and July 9 last
year.
</P>
<P>
Reports also said that many Mercedes-Benz were stolen from the
roads of Taiwan and then packed into containers heading to mainland
China.
</P>
<P>
One report recalled the ordeal of a man in Taiwan who had a bit
too much drink one night. Instead of driving home, he parked his
black Mercedes S320 to sleep it off. He later awoke to find himself
inside his car, which was inside a container headed to the mainland's
Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
Another report told of a wealthy Taiwan businessman going to
Chengdu, the capital city of the southwestern province of Sichuan,
where he spotted a Mercedes that looked exactly like the one that was
stolen from him in Taiwan. He was shocked to find that, in fact, the
car thieves had not even bothered to remove the licence plate -- it
was the man's car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040309.0004" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN BECOMES MEMBER OF ADVISORY CENTER ON WTO LAW
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Geneva,  March 9 (CNA)
(By Neil Lu and P.C. Tang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan became a member of the Advisory
Center on WTO Law (ACWL) Monday under the name of "Taiwan, Penghu,
Kinmen, Matsu Separate Customs Territories" when the island's chief
delegate to the World Trade Organization signed an accession protocol
with senior officials from the center.
</P>
<P>
The ACWL membership is significant for Taiwan in terms of dealing
with legal affairs within the WTO, particularly affairs related to
trade dispute settlement issues.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan government and its permanent mission to the WTO
decided to join the ACWL because they consider that reinforcing the
island's capability in dealing with WTO legal affairs is vital for
the island's rights and interests within the WTO.
</P>
<P>
The ACWL, a public international organization independent of the
WTO, was established in 2001 to provide legal advice on WTO law to
developing countries and customs territories, countries with
economies in transition, and least developed countries. Taiwan had to
pay an accession fee of US$30,000 to join the center.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, Yen Ching-chang, Taiwan's
permanent representative to the WTO, said Taiwan has achieved its
"win-win" goal since becoming a WTO member in January 2002. He noted
that the island has not only benefited from its WTO membership, but
that it has also made a lot contributions to the organization's
multilateral trade systems.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that in facing the WTO's complicated and many trade
rules as well as the unclear future of the "Doha Round" trade talks,
Taiwan still has plenty of room for improvement within the WTO, Yen
said that this is why the island attaches great importance to its
cooperation with the ACWL.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the ACWL's legal service will play an important
role in the Taiwan government's decision-making process," he added.
</P>
<P>
In response, Frieder Roesler, the center's executive director,
warmly welcomed Taiwan to the ACWL and guaranteed that the center
will provide the island with the best legal services. He also said
that the center is confident about helping Taiwan to obtain the best
results in any future trade dispute settlement proceedings.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan lacks experience in terms of the WTO's trade dispute
mechanism as it has never been directly involved in the mechanism.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that after joining the ACWL, Taiwan will obtain
legal advice from the center on WTO laws as well as acquire support
in WTO dispute settlement proceedings and receive assistance in the
training of government officials in WTO law.
</P>
<P>
As of Jan. 1, 2004, the ACWL already had 20 developing country
members entitled to the services of the center, and nine developed
country members. The center has also provided legal services to
developing countries in 16 WTO trade dispute settlement cases since
the center was established.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040309.0005" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
KMT FILES LIBEL SUIT AGAINST TAIWAN PINEAPPLE CHIEF
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,   March   9  (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The opposition Kuomintang (KMT)
commissioned a lawyer Tuesday to file a libel suit against a vice
chairman of Taiwan Pineapple Corp. after he claimed in an open letter
that the party had accepted NT$100 million (US$3 million) from him as
apolitical donation in 1998.
</P>
<P>
After filing the suit against Huang Tsung-hung with the Taipei
District Court, lawyer Lin Fu-hung said that Huang circulated a
letter among local media charging the KMT with extorting a NT$100
million political donation from him via Liu Tai-ying, former chairman
of the KMT Investment Commission.
</P>
<P>
Huang further said in his letter that he obtained a NT$3 billion
loan from Chang Hwa Commercial Bank through arrangements by former
Pingtung County Magistrate Wu Tze-yuan and alleged that he gave Wu 30
percent of the bank loan as a rebate to be used for KMT Chairman Lien
Chan's 2000 election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Describing Wu's accusations as false, the lawyer said that the
alleged NT$100 political donation has been confirmed by the Taipei
Prosecutor's Office during its investigation of an investment project
by Zanadau Development Co. to be a rebate for Liu himself.
</P>
<P>
He said that the rebate was used by Liu for political purposes
and had nothing to do with Lien, who is contesting the re-election of
President Chen Shui-bian.
</P>
<P>
The lawyer further said that Huang's application for a bank loan
was rejected because it did not satisfy relevant requirements and
added that the two cases are unrelated.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Investigation Bureau issued a news release to say
that it has probed the alleged NT$3 billion bank loan case and that
the political donation case involving Liu had been finalized by the
Taipei Prosecutor's Office.
</P>
