<HEADLINE>
ACWL IS GOOD ACCESS FOR TAIWAN IN TRADE DISPUTE SETTLEMENTS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 9 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan's membership of the Advisory Center
on WTO Law (ACWL) will provide the country with good access for
settling trade disputes with other countries under the framework of
the World Trade Organization (WTO) , a government official said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Bureau of Foreign Trade Deputy Director-General Chu
Wei-cheng, Taiwan's membership of the ACWL will allow the country to
enjoy legal consultation and services provided by the organization
when it encounters trade disputes with other WTO member nations.
</P>
<P>
As Taiwan joined the ACWL in its capacity as a developing
country, Chu said, the country will be able to enjoy a certain number
of hours of legal consultancy and services provided by ACWL
specialists in case of trade disputes.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, ACWL membership will also help Taiwan train
its own officials in international trade, economics and legal
affairs, giving a boost to these areas, in which he said Taiwan has
long been uncompetitive.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan became the ACWL's 35th member state a day earlier after
its permanent representative to the WTO, Yen Ching-chang, signed an
accession protocol with senior ACWL officials in their Geneva
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The ACWL, which was set up in 1999 and formally began operations
in July 2001, is a public world body independent of the WTO. The
purpose of its establishment is to offer legal advice on WTO law to
developing countries, less-developed countries and customs
territories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
