<HEADLINE>
NO ELECTION-RELATED POLLS ALLOWED IN 10 DAYS AHEAD OF MARCH 20: CEC
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 9 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Starting from Wednesday, no one will be
allowed to publish survey results related to the presidential
election prior to the March 20 poll, the Central Election Commission
(CEC) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
CEC officials said violators will be fined between NT$500,000 and
NT$5 million (US$15,060-US$150,600.)
</P>
<P>
The officials said that according to Article 52 of the
Presidential and Vice Presidential Election and Recall Law, no
political parties or other organizations or individuals can publish
survey results regarding presidential candidates or election in the
10-day period ahead of an election. They also cannot report,
distribute, comment or quote such survey results.
</P>
<P>
One noteworthy aspect of the law is that even poll results
published prior to the 10-day period cannot be quoted in the 10 days
ahead of the election.
</P>
<P>
The CEC reminder comes at a time when the latest polls have shown
President Chen Shui-bian and his sole challenger, Kuomintang Chairman
Lien Chan, running in a dead heat.
</P>
</TEXT>
