</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  9 (CNA)
(By Eric Liu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Bureau of Animal and Plant Health
Inspection and Quarantine under the Cabinet-level Council of
Agriculture announced Tuesday that a poultry farm in southern
Pingtung County has been found to be infected with the H5N2 strain of
the avian flu virus and that 12,000 chickens will be culled.
</P>
<P>
According to a bureau official, the disease is limited to one
poultry farm and sampling by the Animal Disease Control Center of
Pingtung County March 1 confirmed Tuesday that the farm was not
infected by the potentially deadly H5N1 strain of the virus but the
less virulent H5N2 strain.
</P>
<P>
To avoid further outbreaks, other preventive measures will also
come into effect for the next six months, such as vaccinations,
surveillance and increased care, on poultry farms surrounding the
affected farm within a three-kilometer radius.
</P>
