<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT, VICE PRESIDENT  CALL ON VOTERS TO CAST REFERENDUM VOTES
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  9 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Both President Chen Shui-bian and Vice
President Annette Lu called Tuesday for elegible voters to cast
ballots in Taiwan's first nationwide referendum, to be held in
conjunction with the March 20 presidential election, claiming that
this will allow their voices to be heard by the international
community.
</P>
<P>
Chen made the appeal after hearing a report delivered by Minister
of the Interior Yu Cheng-hsien on how to maintain social order and
crack down on vote-buying in the run-up to the election, and another
report on the "peace referendum" delivered by Minister without
Portfolio Hsu Chih-hsiung during a weekly meeting of the Central
Executive Committee of the ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP).
</P>
<P>
Chen, who also doubles DPP chairman, said that with great
confidence in Taiwan and insistence on reforms, the ruling party will
spare no efforts to pursue democratization.
</P>
<P>
With Taiwan's impressive political developments over the decades,
such as the lifting of martial law in 1987, the first direct
presidential election in 1996 and the peaceful transition of power
between different political parties in 2000, the DPP is poised to
carry out the referendum in cooperation with the people, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
"Referendum is not only a universal value of democracy but also a
basic civil right, " Chen noted. "As the planned referendum is the
first to be held in Taiwan's history, the opposition camp dare not
publicly oppose the referendum, but they have called on their
supporters to refrain from casting referendum ballots as a boycott of
the event," Chen added.
</P>
<P>
Saying that the Central Election Commission decided to hold the
referendum in conjunction with the presidential election according to
the regulations, Chen claimed that the decision does not infringe
upon any laws.
</P>
<P>
"The opposition camp's statement that the referendum is illegal
is obviously nothing but an electoral campaign strategy because they
have been reluctant to come up with a proposal for the Council of
Grand Justices to interpret the issue," according to the president.
</P>
<P>
Describing the referendum as a "democratic banquet" to be shared
by all the people of Taiwan, Chen said that the international
community is closely watching the developments of Taiwan's democratic
development and he voiced the hope that all voters will turn out to
cast a "yes" vote for both referendum questions.
</P>
<P>
In addition to electing a president and vice president, voters
will also cast two additional ballots for the two questions put forth
in the referendum. The questions are whether Taiwan should increase
its anti-missile defenses if mainland China refuses to remove the
missiles it has aimed at Taiwan, and whether the government should
negotiate with Beijing for the establishment of an interaction
mechanism for peace across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lu said in a pre-taped TV interview that the
referendum will be conducive to highlight Taiwan's separate identity
from mainland China and intensify public awareness of defense issues
in the face of the growing missile threat from the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Saying that in the face of Beijing's continued deployment of
missiles targeting Taiwan, casting referendum ballots is not only a
right but also an obligation, Lu urged all elegible voters to cast a
"yes" vote for the two questions.
</P>
</TEXT>
