<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN SELLS WELL AT TOKYO INTERNATIONAL FOOD EXHIBITION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Tokyo,   March  9  (CNA)
(By C.C. Huang and Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan's agricultural products and
speciality foods enjoyed a keen reception from the public Tuesday on
the opening day of the four-day 2004 Tokyo International Food
Exhibition.
</P>
<P>
National Policy Advisor and Taiwan Confectionery Biscuit and
Floury Food Industry Association Chairman Fang Jen-hui, who led the
Taiwan delegation composed of more than 150 representatives from 59
companies, said he is confident that Taiwan-made high-quality
foodstuffs will become more and more popular in Japan.
</P>
<P>
According to Fang, Taiwan-produced tea, vegetables and processed
foods are much improved in quality and representation this year and
are well-placed to court quality-conscious Japanese customers.
</P>
<P>
A variety of Taiwan vegetables, fruit, tea, processed produce and
alcoholic beverages are on display in a number of booths decorated in
an eye-catching livery of yellow, green and orange at the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan Trade Center (TTC) in Tokyo also sponsored a news
conference earlier that same day to introduce Taiwan's progress and
achievements in food safety.
</P>
<P>
Wang Ming-lai, director of the International Cooperation
Department under the Cabinet-level Council of Agriculture (COA) ,
hailed Taiwan fruit such as bananas, pineapples, dates and bell fruit
as "the world's top delicacies."
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that exports of these fruits to Japan are
blocked because of a spate of quarantine requirements imposed by
Japan. Taiwan will continue to negotiate with Japan over the issue,
the COA official said.
</P>
<P>
Wang also noted that the COA is planning to earmark about NT$2.2
billion (NT$66 million) over the next three years to help Taiwan
agricultural and farm groups take part in international promotion
campaigns and set up marketing and distribution centers overseas.
</P>
<P>
According to TTC Director Huang Hsiao-kuan, it is very important
for Taiwan to open a distribution and sales center in Tokyo, on the
grounds that Japan is the largest outlet for Taiwan-produced
agricultural and farm produce. He claimed that such establishments
will be seen in Tokyo this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040309.0021" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT CLARIFIES REMARKS ABOUT APPOINTING WOMAN PREMIER
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 9 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian said Tuesday that
he has no intention of immediately appointing a woman to serve as
premier if he is elected in the March 20 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The president was responding to questions about his remarks on
Women's Day when he was interviewed by TVBS, a local cable television
station, where he said he was keeping an eye out for a suitable woman
to fill the post of premier.
</P>
<P>
The president denied that his remarks were "a spur of the moment
whim, " saying that as a national leader, he has to be "careful with
his words and deeds."
</P>
<P>
He said, "To let women have more and better chances to take part
in public affairs has long been my thinking, " citing as an example
his choice of Annette Lu as his running mate this year as well as in
the previous presidential election in 2000.
</P>
<P>
"Inviting a woman to serve as premier has been a long-term
consideration, but will not be immediately acted upon," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that having a woman premier will first need proper
grooming and preparations. Chen also said, "I have no specific
candidate in mind, and, at any rate, nothing will be done about this
immediately following my re-election."
</P>
<P>
Moreover the president said, Premier Yu Shyi-kun is doing fine
and the March 20 presidential election will also be a vote of trust
for Yu's Cabinet.
</P>
</TEXT>
