<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040309.0022" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT CHEN PROUD OF HIS  INTEGRITY, MORALS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 9 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian said Tuesday what
he is most proud of in his more than 20-year political career is his
integrity and moral character.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with the TVBS cable television station,
Chen said he can withstand the most stringent integrity and moral
examinations.
</P>
<P>
"Integrity is my self-discipline. Otherwise, I could not have won
the presidency. And I have required my working partners to meet the
same integrity and moral standards," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
For him, Chen went on, moral character and integrity are more
important than capabilities.
</P>
<P>
"I have full confidence and trust in individual members of my
administrative team. If any of them has integrity problems, I would
not wait until detractors launched an attack. I would take action
immediately after I detected the problems," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
During his tenure as Taipei mayor from 1994 through 1998, Chen
recalled that some of his close aides were accused of having taken
bribes. "But judicial authorities have cleared their names. None of
them have ever been convicted of corruption or wrongdoing."
</P>
<P>
Since he took the presidency, Chen said his administrative team
has also passed scrutiny. "Over the past four years, I have taken
pride in the fact that all members of my administrative team have
withstood the harshest integrity tests."
</P>
<P>
As the ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) doesn't have any
party enterprises or assets, Chen said, he has had to rely on
political contributions to finance his campaign for city council and
legislative seats, mayorship and the presidency over the past two
decades.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that he is a principled man, Chen said donations must
be based on support for his political ideals or vision. "Donations
should not have any conditions. Otherwise, I would not accept them.
Donations can never be used as a tool to gain illegal benefits. I'm
unlikely to coddle donors' irregularities," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chen said he thinks it is inappropriate for his wife
to conduct stock trading.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, I have made a public apology for her stock trading
activities. Nevertheless, this doesn't mean that she has done
anything wrong in her stock trading deals. It's not an issue of
legality or unlawfulness. I have made an apology mainly because I
don't want the controversy to continue raging," Chen explained.
</P>
<P>
Chen apologized for the first lady's stock trading activities in
a televised debate with opposition Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan, the
sole challenger to his re-election bid, in February. He also promised
that his wife will not engage in any stock trading deals before the
March 20 presidential election and that his family assets will be put
into "blind trust" after the election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
