<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES POISED TO ADD FLIGHTS TO RETURN TAIWAN BUSINESSMEN TO VOTE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 9 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With the March 20 presidential election
approaching, carriers plying routes between Taiwan and Hong Kong and
Macau are poised to add flights to carry mainland-based Taiwan
businessmen to return home to vote, according to industry sources.
</P>
<P>
To cope with a larger number of Taiwan businessmen expected to
return home for the presidential vote this year, airlines will set
their eyes particularly at the business opportunities generating from
the southern Pearl River Delta area, where many Taiwan businessmen
are also clustered now, in addition to the greater Shanghai area
surrounding the Yangzhijiang River Delta in central Jiangsu province.
</P>
<P>
China Airlines and Cathay Pacific Airways Ltd. have respectively
launched joint air-land and air-sea transport packages to carry
Taiwan businessmen who arrive in Hong Kong or Macau from mainland
China back to Taiwan in the run-up to the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
EVA Airways Corp. said it is planning to add nine flights on its
Hong Kong-Taiwan and Macau-Taiwan routes prior to the presidential
election to serve the many homecoming Taiwan businessmen and overseas
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
CAL said booking for seats on board flights back to Taiwan from
North America, Hong Kong and Macau before the March 20 presidential
election day are about 80 percent full, a level similar to its
average passenger load.
</P>
<P>
For the time being, some Taiwan businessmen and their families
based in Suzhou and Kunshan in Jiangsu province have already returned
to Taiwan in order to cast their ballots in the presidential
election. Some of them bought airplane tickets at lower rates.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, many Taiwan business people
with operations in mainland China had voiced the hope for airlines to
launch special charters or additional flights to carry them back home
to vote.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that around 100,000 mainland-headquartered Taiwan
businessmen will go back to Taiwan for that purpose.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Transportation and Communications Lin Ling-san also
suggested recently that Taiwan businessmen can come home via the
"mini three links"-- direct trade and transport service maintained
between Taiwan-held Kinmen and Matsu islands and two ports in Fujian
province from Jan. 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
The "mini three links" facilities on the two outlying islands are
capable of allowing in 200,000 people in three days, Lin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
