<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040309.0026" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
CHEN-LU TICKET ENJOYS NARROW LEAD: DPP POLL
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 9 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ticket of President Chen Shui-bian and
Vice President Annette Lu enjoyed a narrow lead over the opposition
"pan-blue alliance" ticket in the latest public opinion poll, the
ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The DPP conducted the telephone survey of adult residents
in various parts of the island from March 6-7. A total of
1,864 valid samples were collected. The poll has a margin of
error of 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
It was the last opinion poll to be conducted by the DPP ahead of
the March 20 presidential election. According to the election law, no
one is allowed to public opinion poll results within 10 days before
the presidential election day.
</P>
<P>
Poll results showed that the Chen-Lu ticket has a support
rating of 39.1 percent, compared to 38 percent for the "pan-blue
alliance" ticket of Kuomintang (KMT) Chairman Lien Chan and
People First Party Chairman James Soong.
</P>
<P>
Without mentioning their running mates, Chen's support rating was
37.6 percent, compared to Lien's 36.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
As the Chen-Lu ticket's 1.1 percent lead over the Lien-Soong
ticket fell with the margin of sampling error, DPP spokesman Chen
Chun-lin said, the presidential race is still too close to call.
</P>
<P>
Chen Chun-lin said the DPP expects that the voter turn out
to reach 81 percent this year, compared to 82 percent in the 2000
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
"We also estimate that the Chen-Lu ticket will garner 51.1
percent of the vote, or 6.8 million ballots, compared to the
Lien-Soong's 48.9 percent, or 6.5 million votes," predicted Chen
Shun-lin.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll, 30.3 percent said they believe the Chen-Lu
ticket will be re-elected, while 36.3 percent said they think
that the Lien-Soong will win.
</P>
<P>
"In the series of DPP polls, the Chen-Lu ticket had consistently
trailed the Lien-Soong ticket by more than 20 percent in
success probability. This time around, the gap has narrowed to 6
percent," Chen Chun-lin claimed.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that 90.4 percent of the respondents said they
will definitely or probably cast ballots in the presidential election
and only 8.4 percent said they will definitely or probably not go to
the polls.
</P>
<P>
As to the referendum to be held alongside the presidential
election, only 51.9 percent said they will definitely or probably
take part in the referendum, while 42.2 percent said they will
definitely or probably not cast referendum ballots.
</P>
<P>
A cross-analysis of poll results showed that nearly 90 percent of
supporters of various political parties have expressed their
choices, Chen Chun-lin said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the poll found that the gap between Hakka people's
support ratings for the two tickets has narrowed to 4 percent,
with the 36.8 percent of Hakka respondents throwing support for
the Chen-Lu ticket and 40.8 percent backing the Lien-Soong
ticket.
</P>
<P>
Among voters in the 20-29 age group, 46.9 percent said they will
vote for the Chen-Lu ticket, compared to 39.8 percent who said
they support the Lien-Soong ticket.
</P>
<P>
By constituencies, the support ratings of the Chen-Lu and
Lien-Soong tickets were 37.9 percent vs. 39.3 percent in the Taipei
City-Taipei County constituency; 31.1 percent vs. 44.5 percent in the
Taoyuan-Hsinchu-Miali area; 38.3 percent vs. 36.4 percent in the
Taichung-Changhua-Nantou region; 45 percent vs. 30.7 percent in
the Yunlin-Chiayi-Tainan constituency; 47.6 percent vs. 37.7
percent in the Kaohsiung City-Kaohsiung County-Pingtung County area;
and 28.2 percent vs. 42.3 percent in the eastern Taiwan region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040309.0027" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN WILL CONTINUE TO PUSH FOR WHO ENTRY EVERY YEAR: MOFA
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 9 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan will continue to push to join the
World Health Organization (WHO) every year, an official of the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MOFA) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Lu Ching-lung, deputy head of MOFA's Non-governmental
Organization Affairs Committee, spoke in the wake of President Chen
Shui-bian's recent remarks that he will work to have Taiwan included
in the world health body within two years if he is re-elected.
</P>
<P>
Lu said that he himself traveled to Geneva, Switzerland several
times on behalf of the government to attend the WHO's annual
conference to lobby WHO members to support Taiwan's bid. He was happy
to hear President Chen's announcement, adding that MOFA and the
Department of Health will work toward achieving the goal.
</P>
<P>
Lu noted that the international community has formed a consensus
on Taiwan's bid to join the United Nations'-affiliated organization.
Though mainland China will continue to relentlessly squeeze Taiwan,
Lu said it will be impossible to shut Taiwan out of the WHO.
</P>
<P>
He said MOFA has solicited the support of WHO members using every
possible channel, and has received positive responses.
</P>
<P>
Though Taiwan's chances of joining the WHO is greater now than
before, he said he wants to remind the public to refrain from
unreasonable expectations, adding that whether Taiwan can join the
WHO will depend on getting the most support from WHO members.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that though it is important to provide medical
resources and talent to the world, the more important thing is the
adherence to ideals, adding that Taiwan will continue to promote its
bid to join the WHO every year.
</P>
</TEXT>
