<HEADLINE>
TAICHUNG, TAIPEI MAYORS TAKE LEAVE TO FOCUS ON MARCH 20 ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taichung, central Taiwan, March 9 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taichung City Mayor Jason
Hu, a stalwart of the opposition Kuomintang (KMT) , took a 10-day
leave beginning Tuesday to stump for the "pan-blue alliance"
presidential candidate KMT Chairman Lien Chan.
</P>
<P>
Hu, formerly a government spokesman and a foreign affairs
minister during the era of KMT rule, will meet with Lien Tuesday
afternoon in Taichung City, where the candidate and his supporters
will stage another campaign rally to try to broaden their support
base in central Taiwan ahead of the March 20 election.
</P>
<P>
Hu's decision to take a leave from his office has deflated rumors
that he has been sympathetic to the "pan-green camp" of President
Chen Shui-bian.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Taipei City Mayor Ma Ying-jeou announced Tuesday that
he will take a 10-day leave beginning Wednesday so that he can focus
on campaign affairs in the run-up to the election in his capacity as
a KMT vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
Ma, also a campaign manager for Lien and his running mate, People
First Party Chairman James Soong, said he will not be at Taipei City
Hall until the morning of March 20.
</P>
<P>
Although he will not be at his office, Ma said he will still be
head of the "3-20 Crisis Management" task force to be activated by
Taipei City Government.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang Cho-chiun, director of the Taipei Municipal
Police Department, a host of crisis management measures to deal with
any accidents or social unrest around Taipei City in the lead up to
the election as well as the election day have been mapped out and
will be activated shortly.
</P>
<P>
On election day, Wang said, 17 points around the city will be
"key" locations where the police presence will be reinforced.
</P>
</TEXT>
