<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 9 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Sunday, March 9, or the 19th day
of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according to the
lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that have
occurred on this date in the past:

1454: Amerigo Vespucci, the Italian navigator who discovered the
mouth of the Amazon River and gave his name to America, is born.

1562: In Naples, Italy, kissing in public is made punishable by
death.

1796: Twenty-seven-year-old Napoleon Bonaparte, the brilliant
young French commander of the Army of the Interior who later became
king, weds Josephine, 33, a widow since her first husband the Vicomte
de Beauharnais was guillotined in 1794.

1831: The French Foreign Legion is formed by King Louis Philippe,
with its headquarters in Algeria, to serve in France's African
colonies.

1846: Kashmir is ceded to the British East India Company in the
Treaty of Lahore.

1905: Japanese forces defeat the Russians at Shenyang (Mukden) in
northern China.

1923: Vladimir Ilyich Lenin suffers a massive stroke and resigns
as leader of the Soviet Union.

1932: "Manchukuo," the name given to Japanese-controlled
Manchuria, is formally founded at a ceremony held in Changchun, with
Henry Pu Yi, the last emperor of the Manchu dynasty, installed as
president.

1933: A strong earthquake rocks California, killing 123 people
and injuring more than 4,150 others.

1942: Japan finally takes the Dutch island of Java in Indonesia
after the surrender of Allied forces.

1945: A power plant at Taiwan's Sun Moon Lake is bombed and
destroyed by Allied planes during World War II.

1945: The U.S. Army captures the German city of Bonn near the end
of World War II.

1955: The Commission for Examining Foreign Exchange and Trade
under the Executive Yuan decides that the nominal quotation of
exchange settlements in Taiwan banks should be US$1 to NT$6.

1959: King Hussein of Jordan arrives in Taipei for an eight-day
state visit.

1975: The Honduran Consulate in Taipei reopens.

1976: Education Minister Y.S. Tsiang presents a certificate to
John M. King of Cornell University for his contribution to hog
research in Taiwan.

1978: Shih Ming-chen, a crew member on a China Airlines flight
from Taipei to Hong Kong, is killed after a failed attempt to hijack
the plane to Kwangchow (Canton).

1987: Iraq is accused by Iran of using chemical weapons in the
ongoing war between the two countries.

1990: East Germany and West Germany begin preliminary
reunification talks.

1991: The Straits Exchange Foundation formally begins operations.

1992: Menachem Begin, former Israeli prime minister who won the
Nobel Peace Prize in 1978 for his part in the Camp David settlement
with Egyptian President Anwar Sadat, dies of a heart attack in Tel
Aviv at the age of 78.

1995: The United States signs a deal with its allies to supply
North Korea with two nuclear reactors.

1996: George Burns, one of America's best loved and most enduring
entertainers, dies at the age of 100.

1997: Two astronomical phenomena -- rarely enough occurring on
their own -- happen simultaneously. A full solar eclipse occurs at
the same time a comet is visible in the atmosphere over the Mo River
near Heilungkiang on the Chinese mainland. Such coincidences occur on
average once every 2,500 years.

2000: The Executive Yuan approves a two-year extension of the
Technology Cooperative Agreement between the Republic of China and
the Republic of Panama.

2001: The Taipei-based Straits Exchange Foundation celebrates the
10th anniversary of its founding and calls for the early resumption
of cross-Taiwan Strait dialogue.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "If one could only live a moral
life, renouncing himself and conforming to the ideal of decency and
good sense for one single day, the world would become moral. To be
moral, a man depends entirely upon himself and not upon others."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040310.0001" type="multi" >
