<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040310.0003" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION PUSHES FOR LEGISLATIVE REFORMS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 10 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Legislators from the opposition "pan-blue
alliance" of the Kuomintang and the People First Party on Wednesday
pushed for three constitutional and legislative reform programs in
the first meeting of the newly-established Committee for
Constitutional Amendment.
</P>
<P>
The "pan-blue alliance" lawmakers pushed for a "single seat, two
votes" electoral system in order to strengthen the country's
democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
Under a "single seat, two votes" system with smaller electoral
districts, there is only one parliamentary seat up for grabs in each
constituency, and a voter can cast two ballots -- one for an
individual candidate and one for a political party.
</P>
<P>
The "pan-blue alliance" lawmakers also pushed for passage of the
proposal to halve the number of seats in the Legislative Yuan to 113
seats -- a proposal that both the ruling Democratic Progressive Party
(DPP) and the opposition camp have agreed to.
</P>
<P>
The "pan-blue alliance" legislators also pushed a proposal that
would be conducive to increasing the ratio of women lawmakers in the
Legislative Yuan to about one-third, labeling this as "genuine gender
equality."
</P>
<P>
Legislator Tsai Huang-lang, the legislative whip of the ruling
Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) , said the day before that it is
hoped that the proposal to halve the number of seats in the
Legislature will be passed before the March 20 presidential election
now that both the ruling DPP and the opposition parties have reached
consensus on it.
</P>
<P>
Other details of the amendment can be discussed after the
presidential election, Tsai added.
</P>
<P>
KMT Legislator Liao Feng-teh said that the amendment needs to be
debated thoroughly and that legislators should be allowed to air
their views freely.
</P>
<P>
Legislator Hsieh Chang-chieh, PFP convener at the Legislative
Yuan, said the chaos in the Legislature cannot be addressed simply by
cutting the number of legislators and added that other issues, such
as the length of terms for lawmakers and the relationship between the
executive and legislative branches, should also be attended to.
</P>
<P>
Hsieh said he opposes the DPP's idea of tying constitutional
reform to the presidential election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
