<HEADLINE>
JOB MARKET LOOKING UP FOR NEW GRADUATES IN SINGAPORE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Singapore,  March 10 (CNA)
(By Sherman Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The tide may be turning for the better
for new university graduates in Singapore, as job recruitment began
picking up last year.
</P>
<P>
Of the 6,000 National University of Singapore graduates last
year, 76 percent found work within six months of their final
examinations in May, compared with 70 percent in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Starting pay was also higher, with the average salary being
S$28,322(US$16,660) per year, or S$369 more than in 2002, according
to the results of an employment survey released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Arts, science and business graduates with general degrees fared
better in 2002 than in the previous year, but still lagged behind
graduates in several other fields.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040310.0006" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
FINES METED OUT FOR PUBLISHING POLLS ON PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 10 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two media organizations will be fined at
least NT$500,000 (about US$15,000) for publishing opinion polls on
presidential election Wednesday, according to the Central Election
Commission.
</P>
<P>
The Election and Recall Law prohibits the publishing or reporting
of any opinion polls about the election in the last 10 days before
the election. The prohibition period began from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Min Chung Daily newspaper and Wealth magazine carried opinion
polls Wednesday and will therefore be fined, according to the CEC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040310.0007" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT REITERATES DETERMINATION TO PURSUE CROSS-STRAIT PEACE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Kinmen,  March 10 (CNA)
(By Huang Kwang-chun)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian reiterated his
determination Wednesday to pursue cross-Taiwan Strait peace and
called on the public to vote in the referendum to be held alongside
the March 20 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Chen, who is seeking re-election in the upcoming presidential
race, said at a campaign rally held on the Taiwan-controlled
frontline island of Kinmen that cross-strait peace is the best
guarantee for the security and prosperity of Kinmen, which is located
only a few kilometers off the southeast coast of mainland China.
</P>
<P>
The main purposes of holding the referendum are to demonstrate
Taiwan people's sentiment against the mainland Chinese missile threat
and their resolve to pursue cross-strait peace, Chen noted.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has deployed 496 missiles targeting Taiwan and continues
to increase the number of missiles at a pace of one every six days,
Chen went on.
</P>
<P>
He urged Kinmen residents to be vigilant against the mainland
Chinese missile threat despite the opening of so-called "mini three
links" with mainland China since January 2001 because Beijing has
never abandoned its hostility toward Taiwan and the island cannot
ward off the missile attacks once a cross-strait war erupts.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that being the country's leader, he wishes to be a
builder of Taiwan-centric consciousness, the terminator of corrupt
"black gold" politics, the initiator of Taiwan's democratic reforms,
the defender of justice and fairness and the maker of cross-strait
peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040310.0008" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
FOURTH REFERENDUM DEBATE PITS LAWMAKER AGAINST SCHOLAR
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 10 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Legislator Chuo Jong-tai of the Democratic
Progressive Party debated Juan Ming, a professor at Tamkang
University on Wednesday over the second question in the referendum:
whether the country should negotiate with Beijing for peace.
</P>
<P>
Although Juan claimed afterward the event that he was the only
"real" debater on the opposition side of the four rounds of debates
held up to now since all the previous opposition speakers disputed
the legal basis for the whole referendum rather than the questions
asked in it. Chuo said he considered himself fortunate to debate
against the ex-aide to Beijing's defamed leader, Zhao Ziyang, because
"we share more points of view than we differ on."
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Chuo made a strong case for the legality of the
referendum, saying that Beijing's 496 missiles targeting Taiwan are a
persistent threat to the country and are a justification for the
president's initiation of a referendum on the issue.
</P>
<P>
He denounced some critics' calls to boycott the referendum,
saying that to refuse to vote in the referendum would be a slap in
face to a hard-earned right, and a travesty to democracy.
</P>
<P>
Claiming that the whole world is looking to the results of the
March 20 referendum, Chuo said a "yes" vote on this question will
send a strong message across the world that the country loves peace,
and resents Beijing's missile threat.
</P>
<P>
Chuo said talking with Beijing on an equal footing is the only
option for the country, adding that he believes his party has the
capability to carry this out, and looks forward to the day when
President Chen Shui-bian and Beijing's leader, Hu Jingtao, will shake
hands on an international occasion and talk about the future of
Taiwan and the mainland. When that day comes, Chen and Hu will be the
favorite candidates for the Nobel Peace Prize, Chuo claimed.
</P>
<P>
Juan agreed with all of Chou's views about the legality and
necessity of the referendum and only took issue with any suggestion
of talking with Beijing for peace, claiming "this will only lead to
Taiwan falling into Beijing's 'one-China' trap."
</P>
<P>
He claimed that the Chinese Civil War took place on the mainland
between the communists and the Kuomintang (KMT) and has nothing to do
with Taiwan, which is an independent democratic country. Taiwan is
not in a belligerent state with mainland China and accordingly there
is no point in talking about setting up a peaceful framework with
Beijing as the question in the referendum asks.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Juan claimed Taiwan wouldn't succeed in negotiating
peace with Beijing because Beijing would demand Taiwan accept its
territorial claim to the island and, as with any military hegemony,
would not bother to fulfill its own commitment, should it make any,
to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Without mentioning the name of KMT presidential candidate Lien
Chan, he called the idea advocated by Lien dangerous, that of
negotiations with Beijing by setting aside the thorny issue of
Taiwan's sovereignty, because, he said, it will inevitably undermine
Taiwan's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
A more practical way would be to negotiate with Beijing regarding
the economy, and environmental protection and culture, with the
purpose of improving people's wellbeing, Juan said.
</P>
<P>
In the long term, Taiwan's only hope for peace with mainland
China is the democratization of the mainland, then Taipei can start
to negotiate with Beijing for peace.
</P>
<P>
Although opposing the idea of negotiating with Beijing, Juan said
he supports the referendum itself, saying it is a way of gauging
public opinion.
</P>
<P>
With this right in hand, Juan said, the people can force the
government to change its policy towards mainland China to better
serve the country's interests, Juan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040310.0009" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL SEMINAR ON ISLAM TO BE HELD IN TAIPEI  MARCH 15-16
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 10 (CNA)
(By Huang Kwang-chun)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An international seminar on Islam will be
held in Taipei March 15-16, officials of the MInistry of Foreign
Affairs said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, which will be jointly sponsored by National
Chengchih University and the World Muslim League, is aimed at
promoting exchanges between Taiwan and the Islamic world as well as
bettering Taiwan people's understanding of Islamic culture.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the meeting will be "Islam in East Asia --
