<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040310.0012" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
225-SEAT LEGISLATURE TO BE REDUCED TO 113 SEATS IN 2008
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 19 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Responding to repeated calls for changes
and reforms in the Legislative Yuan, a committee at the legislature
on Wednesday passed a draft constitutional amendment to halve the
current 225-seat legislature, although the decision will only be put
into practice in 2008.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft amendment, starting from 2008, the current
225 seats in the legislature will be cut to 113, and the number of
legislators elected in the year-end election this year will not be
affected.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the current practice of multiple legislators elected
from a single constituency will be changed to a "one seat, two votes"
system, meaning one vote for an individual candidate and another vote
for a political party.
</P>
<P>
The at-large and overseas Chinese seats will be set at 34, women
legislators make up no fewer than 34, and the term of the
legislators will be lengthened to four years from the current three
years.
</P>
<P>
The committee, which held its first meeting Wednesday, reviewed
12 constitutional amendment proposals. Legislative terms, the number
of seats in the legislature, and the adjustment of constituencies
were high on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
This is the first of nine issues to be dealt with concerning
constitutional reform and the committee will continue to review the
other eight, which include the presidential election system and the
confirmation of the premier. After the completion of the review of
the nine issues, they will be sent together to the legislature for a
second and third reading.
</P>
<P>
According to the organization law of the committee, the committee
is in charge of the review of constitutional amendment proposals and
other matters related to the Republic of China Constitution. There
are 114 members in the committee, and there are 11 conveners.
</P>
<P>
The conveners held a meeting last week during which they agreed
that starting from March 10, the committee will hold a meeting every
Wednesday to discuss constitutional amendment proposals.
</P>
<P>
As the committee passed the first reading of the constitutional
amendment to halve the legislative seats, Lin Yi-hsiung, a former
chairman of the ruling Democratic Progressive Party, and his
supporters were staging the last day of their 10-day fast relay
activity outside the legislature.
</P>
<P>
They wanted to highlight their cause to require all political
parties to pass a resolution to ask their members to adhere to party
policy and pass the constitutional amendment by March 20 to allow the
halving of the number of legislative seats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
