<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040310.0014" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TASK FORCE WILL OVERSEE STEEL ISSUES DUE TO DOMESTIC SHORTAGE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 10 (CNA)
(By Eric Liu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ministry of Economic Affairs decided
Wednesday to set up a cross-departmental task force this week to
monitor wholesale prices and supply and demand issues relating to
steel in response to Taiwan's shortage and concerns from downstream
companies.
</P>
<P>
Industrial Development Bureau Director-General Chen Chao-yih said
that the shortage of steel was mainly because of low demand after the
outbreaks of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) early last
year, and the high demand in mainland China recently for
infrastructure needed for construction in the build-up to the 2008
Beijing Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Another contributing factor to the current domestic shortfall of
steel is the fact that the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development (OECD) coordinated with steel-manufacturing countries
three years ago to reduce steel output by five million tons, Chen
said.
</P>
<P>
To address the need for more steel in Taiwan, China Steel Corp.
-- the largest steel producer in Taiwan -- has increased production
from 10.4 million tons in 2002 to 11 million tons in 2004 with the
extra 0.6 million tons earmarked for exclusive use by domestic
companies. Additionally, the corporation's export volume has been cut
this year to 24 percent from the previous level of 30 percent, Chen
added.
</P>
<P>
Chen also pointed out that banning steel exports, a move called
for by some legislators, would be counterproductive since the steel
market is a global one and Taiwan's withdrawal from world trade would
adversely impact the development of the island's international steel
market.
</P>
</TEXT>
