<HEADLINE>
CROSS-STRAIT EXCAVATOR THEFT RING BUSTED
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Kaohsiung,  March 10 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Four men believed to be involved in a
cross-Taiwan Strait excavator theft ring have been nabbed on charges
of theft, fraud and smuggling, Kaohsiung police authorities reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a raid on a warehouse in Kaohsiung's Chiching Port Tuesday
evening, police arrested the four men and seized three excavators and
a 25-ton crane with a combined value of over NT$10 million.
</P>
<P>
The men, all of whom have criminal records, were discovered to
have stolen excavators, bulldozers, cranes and other heavy
construction machinery from all over Taiwan, which they would smuggle
to mainland China via the Republic of China-held outlying island of
Matsu.
</P>
<P>
Operating under the name of a maritime engineering company, the
four men first stole the heavy-duty machines from construction sites
and then smuggled them to Kaohsiung, before shipping them to Matsu,
where the stolen machines would be ferried to the mainland for sale,
according to the police.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 such machines have been stolen in central Taiwan
over the past several months and police believe that all the machines
have ended up on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
The police found that the maritime engineering company has
applied many times to transport excavators, cranes and bulldozers to
Matsu for maritime engineering projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
