<HEADLINE>
3% PAY RAISE FOR MILITARY PERSONNEL, CIVIL SERVANTS, TEACHERS MULLED
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 10 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The government is assessing a pay raise of
3 percent for the nation's military personnel, civil servants and
teachers next year, the Central Personnel Administration (CPA) said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
CPA officials noted that the government last raised the salary by
3 percent for those sectors in 2001, but has not made further
adjustments since because of the sluggish economic situation and
strained financial situation.
</P>
<P>
But after the three-year salary freeze, the government will
consider a pay hike in view of the economic recovery, adding that the
adjustment will take into consideration the salary level of private
enterprises, the fluctuation of the price index, the per capita
income, economic growth as well as the financial burden of the
government.
</P>
<P>
The CPA'a announcement came after opposition presidential
candidate Lien Chan appealed to military personnel, civil servants
and teachers with campaign promises, including a pay raise for
lower-ranking personnel bringing salaries to twice the per capita
income.
</P>
<P>
CPA Director-General Lee Yi-yang lashed out at the proposal,
saying that it would make Taiwan the country with the highest
personnel expenditure, which is "irresponsible" and could "plunge the
country into heavy debt."
</P>
<P>
CPA officials said that statistics released by the Directorate
General Budget, Accounting and Statistics show that per capita income
in Taiwan in 2003 was NT$395,746 (US$11,920) . While lower-ranking
civil servants now get NT$512,474 annually on average if calculated
by 14.5 months of payment, which is 1.29-fold the per capita income,
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Middle-ranking civil servants receive an average of NT$763,606,
or 1.93-fold the per capita income, while high-ranking civil servants
receive an average NT$114.4833, or 2.89-fold the per capita income,
they added.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that if salaries for lower-ranking civil
servants are raised to twice the per capita income, pay for middle-
and high-ranking civil servants will also have to be raised, and even
if counted in the most conservative way, the government would have to
increase its expenditure by NT$190.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that personnel expenses in the central
government currently account for 25.8 percent of the total
expenditure, while personnel expenses in local government is as high
as 54 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an opposition Kuomintang spokesman "elaborated" on
Lien's promise. Tsai Chen-yuan claimed that Lien's promise was
actually that if elected, he will improve the economy and the
benefits of the economic growth will be shared by military personnel,
civil servants and teachers, as well as farmers and laborers.
</P>
</TEXT>
