first big push failed. This time, the industry giants have pint-sized
goals, learning a lesson about China's fractured market that extends
beyond beer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040310.0027" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL COFFERS GREATLY INCREASED IN FEBRUARY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 10 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taxes funnelled into the national coffers
in February totaled NT$71.1 billion (US$2.14 billion) , up by 50.4
percent over the year-earlier level, the Ministry of Finance reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tax revenues generated by stock transaction deals reached NT$10.7
billion last month, a monthly high since February 2002 and
representing a 2.7-fold rise compared to the previous year's record,
which is also a new single-month high since March 2000, ministry
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The officials attributed the big jump in February stock
transaction taxes to a bullish stock market as a result of recovering
business conditions.
</P>
<P>
In addition, land value increment tax revenue also grew by NT$4.2
billion year-on-year to NT$7.5 billion in February thanks to a
government policy that provides a 50 percent cutback in such taxes,
income from which hit a record high of NT$10.05 billion in December
last year.
</P>
<P>
The policy of halving the land value increment tax was originally
to have expired in January, but the Legislative Yuan recently decided
to extend it for another one year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040310.0028" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL BALLOTS NULL AND VOID IF CAST IN WRONG BOXES: CEC
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 10 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Central Election Commission (CEC) is
likely to decide that March 20 presidential election ballots will
become null and void if they are cast in the wrong boxes, such as the
ballot boxes to be used for the accompanying referendum, CEC Chairman
Huang Shih-cheng said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Huang said that although the presidential votes cast in the wrong
boxes are likely to be counted as invalid -- a final decision will be
made Thursday afternoon -- the two referendum votes, designed to let
voters say "yes" or "no" to two referendum propositions -- will be
counted as valid even if they are cast in the wrong referendum boxes.
</P>
<P>
In the nation's first-ever nationwide referendum, voters will be
asked two questions -- whether Taiwan should buy more anti-missile
batteries in the face of Beijing's missile threat and whether Taiwan
should negotiate a viable interactive mechanism with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Huang also said that the CEC might also decide Thursday that
voters' ID cards will be marked only once after they register at
polling stations for ballots, regardless of whether they decide to
receive one or three ballots.
</P>
<P>
The polling station layout will also be designed to allow voters
to accept and cast their presidential ballots and referendum ballots
in two different directions, although at the same polling station,
Huang added.
</P>
<P>
These measures, he said, are designed to facilitate a smooth
election day and speedy vote-counting, Huang stressed.
</P>
<P>
As the presidential election is scheduled to be held in tandem
with the referendum, questions and concerns surrounding electoral
affairs have been rife over the past several months.
</P>
<P>
Confusion over how voters should cast their presidential election
ballots and referendum votes and how the polling stations should be
designed have caused heated debate islandwide over the past month and
even caused Miaoli County Election Commission Chairman Ku Cheng-ching
to resign.
</P>
<P>
Both the ruling Democratic Progressive Party and the opposition
"pan-blue alliance" expressed satisfaction Wednesday with Huang's
remarks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
