<HEADLINE>
WELFARE GROUPS RAISE FUNDS TO HELP FOREIGN BIRD FLU VICTIMS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 10 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A group of Taiwan men married to Thai and
Vietnamese women launched a fund-raising drive Wednesday in
cooperation with several local civic organizations to help their
spouses' next of kin having been affected by recent avian flu
outbreaks in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Chien Chih-jung, a Taiwan citizen with a Vietnamese spouse, said
at a news conference that many families in Vietnam and Thailand have
been affected by the outbreaks due to mandatory culling of their
fowl.
</P>
<P>
For instance, Chien said, his wife's aunt originally made a
living raising 300 chickens. In Vietnam, a single chicken can fetch
NT$21 (US$0.63).
</P>
<P>
"Her family now faces an economic crisis as her chickens have
been culled amid the bird flu scare, " Chien said, adding that many
other families in Vietnam and Thailand face a similar plight.
</P>
<P>
Chien said he will mobilize more Taiwanese men with Vietnamese
and Thai spouses to donate funds to help their foreign in-laws and
other relatives affected by the avian flu outbreak.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Eden Social Welfare Foundation said it has joined
forces with Chien's group and several other local private
organizations to raise funds for avian flu victims in Vietnam and
northern Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The foundation said it has so far raised NT$200,000. Under the
fund-raising program, the foundation plans to offer US$50 to each
Vietnamese and Thai relative by marriage.
</P>
<P>
"For many Taiwan people, US$50 is not a large sum, but it can
finance two months of living expenses in Vietnam and northern
Thailand, " an Eden spokesman said, adding that local citizens are
welcome to contribute funds to the charity campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
