<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040310.0031" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
LIFTING FIRST-PHASE WATER RESTRICTIONS TO BE DECIDED BY LATE MARCH
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 10 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thanks to adequate rainfall from late
January, the water levels of reservoirs nationwide have risen to
normal levels, securing supplies through late May, government water
resources authorities said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a decision made during a national anti-drought
meeting a day earlier called by the Ministry of Economic Affairs
(MOEA), the anti-drought task force will hold a meeting in late March
to decide when to lift the first-phase water conservation measures --
a reduction in water pressure during off-peak hours -- in place in
northern Taiwan and on outlying Penghu Island since early May last
year.
</P>
<P>
The task force members will discuss the issue by that time if
rainfall in the coming days reaches the average level of the past,
officials of the Water Resources Agency (WRA) under the MOEA said.
</P>
<P>
For the time being, the amount of water stored in the major
reservoirs in northern and central regions is a little more than the
year-earlier level.
</P>
<P>
The Feitsui reservoir in Taipei County and the Shihmen reservoir
in Taoyuan County -- the two main providers for northern Taiwan --
have a combined 234 million tons of water, up by more than 100
million tons from the level registered late last year.
</P>
<P>
It has been estimated that water supplies for the greater Taipei
and Taoyuan areas will remain normal through May, while water use in
eastern Ilan and Hualien has also been ensured for the first half of
this year.
</P>
<P>
Supplies for residents in Hsinchu and the neighboring central
region have also been secured through June, as the Yungheshan
reservoir in Hsinchu County has sufficient water, the WRA officials
said.
</P>
<P>
However, they pointed out that reservoirs in southern Taiwan have
fallen short of their normal levels, a situation that has led to the
implementation of a fallow program this spring and a cutback in water
supplies of between 5 percent and 20 percent for heavy users.
</P>
<P>
As for water shortage problems on Matsu and Penghu islands, some
5,000 tons of water will continue to be shipped to the two islands
from Taiwan twice every three days, they noted.
</P>
<P>
As a result of scarce rainfall in recent years, Taiwan, which is
used to abundant rainfall, has been seriously affected by a dry spell
over the past two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
