<HEADLINE>
DPP CALLS FOR DELINKING OF POLITICS AND RELIGION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,   March  10  (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A legislative whip of the ruling
Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) said the party hopes people will
keep religion and politics separate, particularly in the run-up to
the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
DPP Legislator Tsai Huang-lang said everybody in the country has
the constitutionally-protected right to freely express their will and
perspectives. The DPP, however, hopes that people won't bring
religion and politics together, he added.
</P>
<P>
Tsai made the remarks in response to reports that senior Zen
Master Wei Chueh, founder of the gigantic Chung Tai Monastery in
central Taiwan, openly stumped for the opposition "pan-blue alliance"
presidential ticket of Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan and People First
Party Chairman James Soong at a rally held Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Wei Chueh reportedly ridiculed the referendum to be held
islandwide March 20 alongside the presidential election as "a global
joke, " saying that he personally will not accept his referendum
ballot on election day.
</P>
<P>
Wei Chueh openly called for his followers to vote for the
Lien-Soong ticket on March 20.
</P>
<P>
The Zen master also lashed out at a proposed statute governing
religious organizations in Taiwan drafted by the Executive Yuan,
saying that if the proposal were passed into a law, it would be
tantamount to an action aimed at destroying all religions in the
country.
</P>
<P>
By comparison, other notable religious leaders in Taiwan,
including Master Cheng Yen, founder of the Buddhist Compassionate Tzu
Chi Relief Foundation; Zen Buddhism Master Hsing Yun, founder of the
Buddha's Lights (Fukuang) Monastery; and Zen Master Sheng Yen,
founder of the Dharma Drum Mountain Buddhist Association; have all
taken a relatively more obscure or neutral attitude toward politics
and its preachers.
</P>
</TEXT>
