<HEADLINE>
AIRBORNE SERVICE CORPS PREPARATORY OFFICE INAUGURATED
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 10 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ministry of the Interior (MOI) opened
a preparatory office Wednesday to facilitate the integration of
airborne relief operations.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Yu Cheng-hsien said at the inaugural ceremony
that the opening of the office manifests the government's
determination to overhaul the administrative system in order to
upgrade operational efficiency.
</P>
<P>
"The inauguration of the office also symbolizes the start of
integrated airborne emergency rescue and disaster relief services, "
Yu said.
</P>
<P>
According to a provisional organic statute passed by the Cabinet
Feb. 25, the Airborne Service Corps Preparatory Office integrates the
MOI's airborne police and fire squads, the Coast Guard
Administration's airborne surveillance squad, and the airborne
service squad under the Civil Aeronautics Administration.
</P>
<P>
Under the new mechanism, Yu said, airborne relief operations will
be subject to unified command and supervision to save manpower and
financial resources and upgrade administrative efficiency.
</P>
<P>
All relief aircraft will be deployed in line with the principle
that aircraft can reach a specified disaster zone within 30 minutes,
Yu said.
</P>
