<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040310.0043" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 10 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Wednesday, March 10, or the
20th day of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according
to the lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that
have occurred on this date in the past:

1848: Under the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo, the United States
becomes a million square miles larger, thanks to the addition of
California, New Mexico and parts of Texas, the spoils of victory
following the war with Mexico.

1862: The United States issues the "greenback," America's first
true paper money, with all bills the same color and size, whatever
the denomination ($1 to $1,000).

1910: D.W. Griffith, an American film director who pioneered the
use of close-ups, traveling shots and modern editing techniques,
discovers a small town called Hollywood in which to shoot his movie
"In Old California."

1912: Yuan Shih-kai is installed in Peking (Beijing) as
provisional president of the Republic of China.

1922: Mahatma Gandhi is arrested, tried for sedition, and
sentenced to six years imprisonment by the British government of
India.

1942: Japanese forces capture Rangoon, capital of Burma.

1942: The "Flying Tigers," a group of American volunteer aviators
led by Brig. Gen. Claire L. Chennault, becomes the U.S. 14th Air
Force, and Chennault is officially appointed its commander.

1945: Three hundred U.S. B-29 bombers devastate Tokyo, killing
more than 100,000 people.

1947: The ROC government sends Defense Minister Pai Chung-hsi to
Taiwan to handle the aftermath of the Feb. 28 Incident.

1954: The ROC National Assembly votes to impeach Vice President
Li Tsung-jen.

1959: Chinese army forces occupy Lhasa as the Dalai Lama, who led
a failed rebellion against the communist government, flees to India
with more than 10,000 followers.

1969: James Earl Ray pleads guilty to the murder of civil rights
leader Martin Luther King and is sentenced to 99 years in prison.

1972: Lon Nol takes over as Cambodian head of state.

1974: Rodolfo Silva Vargas, Costa Rican communications minister,
arrives in Taipei for a five-day visit.

1974: Ralph P. Davidson, publisher of Time, arrives in Taipei for
a brief visit.

1975: Hanoi troops seize most of South Vietnam's provincial
capital of Ban Me Thuot in the central highlands.

1976: Minister of Finance K.T. Li and Mahsoun Bajhat Jalal, vice
chairman of the Saudi Development Fund, sign an agreement for a US$50
million loan to the ROC.

1976: President Yen Chia-kan receives Suat Erler, commissioner of
the Turkish International Olympics Committee, and Eduardo Hay,
commissioner of the Mexican International Olympic Committee.

1976: The Secretariat of the Asian Peoples' Anti-Communist League
announces the opening of an office in Taipei. A resolution of the
December APACL general meeting transferred the secretariat from
Saigon to Taipei.

1976: Chang Kwang-shih, vice minister of economic affairs, and
Mansoor Al-Turki, deputy minister of finance and national economy of
Saudi Arabia, sign an agreement on Sino-Saudi Arabian economic and
technical cooperation.

1985: The principal line of the 53.85-kilometer Seikan Tunnel,
the world's longest undersea tunnel, which links Japan's main island
of Honshu with the vast northern island Hokkaido, is opened to
traffic after 21 years of construction.

1985: Konstantin Chernenko, general secretary of the Soviet
Communist Party, dies after only 13 months in office. He is succeeded
by Mikhail Gorbachev.

1993: Indonesia's President Suharto is re-elected for a sixth
five-year term of office, becoming one of the longest-serving heads
of state in the world.

1999: Six Libyans, including Colonel Muammar al Qaddafi's
brother-in-law, are sentenced to life imprisonment by a French court
for the 1989 bombing of a French airliner over Africa.

2000: Democratic Progressive Party presidential candidate Chen
Shui-bian wins the endorsement of Academia Sinica President Yuan T.
Lee, as the Nobel laureate agrees to serve as his policy adviser if
Chen is elected president March 18.

2001: On the 40th anniversary of the Tibetan uprising, Tibet's
political and spiritual leader the Dalai Lama throws his weight
behind the idea of a free referendum in Tibet as a way to determine
its future.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "Whatsoever things are contrary to
the ideals of decency and good sense, do not look upon them.
Whatsoever things are contrary to the ideals of decency and good
sense, do not listen to them. Whatsoever things are contrary to the
ideals of decency and good sense, do not utter them. Lastly, let
nothing in whatsoever things you do, act or move, be contrary to the
ideals of decency and good sense."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040311.0001" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT URGES TAIWAN PEOPLE TO HELP IN SEARCH FOR MISSING U.S. MAN
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  11 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian urged local
people Thursday to assist in the search for an American citizen who
went missing in Taiwan last May.
</P>
<P>
Chen made the call in the latest issue of the "A-bian Electronic
Paper," an Internet newsletter named after Chen's nickname "A-bian."
</P>
<P>
Chen said in the weekly online publication that Barbara Klita
sent him a second letter recently asking for his assistance in the
search for her missing son, Fryderyk Mieszko Frontier.
</P>
<P>
In addition to directing relevant government agencies to step up
their search efforts, Chen said he hopes ordinary citizens can also
assist in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
"Those who have leads about Frontier's whereabouts are welcome to
contact relevant government authorities or inform Mrs. Klita, " Chen
said in the newsletter.
</P>
<P>
Klita sent her first letter to President Chen late last year.
Chen published that letter along with Frontier's photo and Klita's
e-mail address -- barbaraklita@collegeclub.com -- in the Dec. 18
issue of the A-bian Electronic Paper.
</P>
<P>
In her second letter to Chen, Klita expressed her gratitude for
the president's assistance and for all those who have assisted in the
search. She also expressed the hope that Taiwan's government and
people can continue to assist in the search.
</P>
<P>
Klita has made several visits to Taiwan to search for her son.
Just last Tuesday, she paid a visit to Taichung Mayor Jason Hu in
central Taiwan to ask for his assistance in her search for her
missing son.
</P>
<P>
Frontier arrived in Taiwan May 20, 2003, to take up an English
teaching job at a branch of the Hess Educational Organization in
Chungho, Taipei County, but did not show up for a pre-job training
program May 25 as originally scheduled.
</P>
<P>
According to a National Police Administration (NPA) probe,
Frontier stayed at a Taipei hostel after his arrival in Taiwan. He
told a hostel information desk staffer that he was going to make a
trip to eastern Taiwan before reporting to Hess for work. Frontier
left his luggage at the Hess Chungho branch before departing for the
eastern county of Hualien.
</P>
<P>
NPA officials said Frontier stayed at the Catholic hostel in
Tienhsiang, in Taroko National Park, from May 21 through May 24. He
checked out of the hostel May 25 and has not been heard from since.
</P>
<P>
The NPA has said on many occasions that it has directed the
Hualien County Police Bureau and the Taroko National Park police to
step up the search for Frontier. Moreover, it urged local citizens to
come forward with any information they might have regarding his
whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
Anyone who has information about the whereabouts of Frontier is
welcome to contact the NPA's foreign affairs office at (02) 2393-0989
or (02) 2394-0238, or the Hualien County Police Bureau at (03)
738-2000.
</P>
<P>
Frontier stands 186 cm tall, weighs 96 kilograms and has curly
brown hair, according to NPA data. He was 28 years old when he came
to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued by the American Institute in
Taiwan in mid-July 2003, Frontier called his former roommate in the
United States May 22, saying that he was going to visit a national
park and return to Taipei May 25. He also expressed an interest in
going hiking and visiting the southern city of Kaohsiung.
</P>
</TEXT>
