<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040311.0004" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
BALLOTS CAST IN WRONG BOXES TO BE COUNTED: ELECTION COMMISSION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 11 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the March 20 presidential election and
referendum, the ballots cast in the wrong boxes will be counted as
valid, the Central Election Commission (CEC) chief said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
CEC Chairman Huang Shih-cheng said that while it is unlikely that
ballots for the presidential election will be cast in the boxes
provided for the referendum ballots, or vise versa, any such vote
will still be counted.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the outcome of the presidential election will have
to be announced twice. The first announcement will be made when all
ballots in the boxes for presidential election are tallied and the
second will be made when the boxes for referendum ballots are
counted, in case any presidential votes are found to have been cast
in the referendum boxes.
</P>
<P>
The CEC also decided not to mark voters' identification cards for
the election and referendum separately, in order to save time and to
prevent anyone from knowing voters' voting patterns.
</P>
<P>
In a related development Thursday, the Executive Yuan told the
CEC that invalid votes should be excluded while deciding the majority
of votes in the referendum, although they should be counted into the
overall turnout rate.
</P>
<P>
That means only the "yes" votes and the "no" votes will be
counted when deciding whether the referendum has passed or not.
</P>
<P>
But when it come to determining whether the referendum has
crossed the threshold of a 50 percent turnout rate needed for a
legally binding referendum, any invalid votes will be included.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
