<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040311.0008" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
SCHEME ROLLED OUT TO BOOST SERVICE INDUSTRY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 11 (CNA)
(By Eric Liu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Science and Technology Advisory Group
under the Executive Yuan rolled out a scheme Thursday designed to
boost the knowledge-type service industry over the next six years.
</P>
<P>
During a press conference, group officials said that after two
seminars between December 2003 and March 2004, strategies and
timetables have been mapped out to promote export-oriented service
industry based on Taiwan's high-tech competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
During the first seminar, three goals were set -- to achieve a
knowledge-type service industry worth NT$6 trillion (US$180.18
billion) by 2010; to create more than 10 leading companies with
brands worth over NT$100 billion in the international market; and to
upgrade labor quality and expand job opportunities in the service
sector to account for 32.5 percent of all labor.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the goals, the government will assign a minister
without portfolio to coordinate and promote related policies, while
the Council for Economic Planning and Development will be responsible
for coordinating the work of related government agencies, the
officials noted.
</P>
<P>
Also, they added, the government will promote a series of
programs, including a supply chain project, a project of research,
development and application of radio frequency identification, a
telecare project, an intergrated medical system and others.
</P>
<P>
During the second seminar, goals were also presented to develop
information service through integration; to upgrade the added value
of the manufacturing industry and the competitiveness of the service
industry; and to promote Taiwan as the main provider of information
services in globally specific areas.
</P>
<P>
To achieve these goals, the government will push forth three to
five flagship development programs by the end of this year and will
promote the Capability Maturity Model Integration (CMMI)
certification system for improving the quality of the information
service industry, the officials added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040311.0009" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
BOFT ISSUES 6-MONTH RESTRICTION ON EXPORTS OF SELECTED STEEL GOODS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 11 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Bureau of Foreign Trade (BOFT) issued
a set of interim restrictions Thursday on exports of 40 types of
steel products in an effort to meet strong demand for these goods in
the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
The restrictions took immediate effect and will run through Sept.
10, during which period, exports of the 40 listed categories of steel
products, including cold rolled steel and scrap steel, must first be
approved and an export license obtained from relevant government
authorities, BOFT officials said, adding that the measures might be
extended if necessary.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the restrictions, the total amount of the
selected steel product exports this year must not exceed their
overall levels posted for the whole of last year, while their monthly
volume of outbound shipments are not allowed to top one-twelfth of
their last year's respective total amounts.
</P>
<P>
However, steel products whose annual outbound shipments are below
the 100-ton level are not subject to the rules, the officials pointed
out.
</P>
</TEXT>
