<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040311.0013" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
VICE PRESIDENT PREDICTS POLITICAL RECONCILIATION AFTER ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  11  (CNA)
(By Huang Kwang-chun)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Vice President Annette Lu predicted
Thursday that there will be a political reconciliation after the
March 20 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting with chief executives of media
organizations in Kaohsiung, southern Taiwan, Lu said that all
political parties should respect the choice made by the people and
give priority to the national interests after the election,
regardless of who wins the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
Lu, who was chosen again by President Chen Shui-bian as his
running mate in his bid to seek re-election, admitted that the
election is a neck-and-neck race. The Chen-Lu ticket is facing a
strong challenge from the opposition "pan blue alliance" ticket
formed by Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan and People First Party
Chairman James Soong.
</P>
<P>
The vice president said that if re-elected, Chen will continue to
promote a new constitution.
</P>
<P>
A task force will be established to elaborate a draft
constitution in one-and-a-half years, Lu said, adding that during the
period, representatives will be sent abroad to collect first-hand
information on the implementation of other countries' constitutions.
</P>
<P>
The new constitution, which will be put to a referendum slated
for Dec. 10, 2006 for final approval, will decide a new governmental
regime and the relationship between the central and local
governments, among others, Lu noted.
</P>
<P>
If approved, the new constitution will be promulgated May 20, 2007
and will go into effect May 20, 2008, she continued.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the governmental regime, the new constitution
should address many other issues, including the halving of the
225-seat legislature, reforms to the current military service system
and adoption of a two-layer or three-layer government, Lu went on.
</P>
<P>
The new constitution also should be in line with government
reforms, she said.
</P>
<P>
Besides political reforms, the vice president said, Taiwan also
needs spiritual, cultural and social reforms in the face of
increasing international competition and challenges.
</P>
</TEXT>
