<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040311.0014" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS ENCIRCLE LEGISLATURE TO DEMAND HALVING OF LEGISLATURE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  11 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thousands of protesters mobilized by
various private groups besieged the Legislative Yuan Thursday,
demanding that the legislature approve a constitutional amendment to
allow a major downsizing of the legislature.
</P>
<P>
The protesters stood hand-in-hand and encircled the Legislative
Yuan to make their demand known -- legislative final approval for the
constitutional revision by the March 20 presidential election in
order to push for halving the number of seats in the 225-member
parliament to 113.
</P>
<P>
Lin Yi-hsiung, a former chairman of the ruling Democratic
Progressive Party (DPP), took part in the rally later the same day by
joining a sit-in and relay fast at the venue. Streamlining the
legislature has been one of the goals long sought by the DPP.
</P>
<P>
Organizers of the protest announced that the demonstrations will
be prolonged through March 19 until their demand is heeded by the
Legislative Yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040311.0015" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
RULING, OPPOSITION PARTIES TO TEST METTLE ON LEGISLATURE REFORMS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 11 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ruling Democratic Progressive Party
(DPP) said Thursday that a floor meeting of the Legislative Yuan
Friday will be a crucial battle for the passage of a draft
constitutional amendment concerning legislative reforms.
</P>
<P>
Tsai Huang-lang, the DPP's legislative whip, noted that a
constitutional amendment committee passed the first reading of a
draft amendment of Article 4 of the Constitution concerning the
legislative term, number of seats and adjustment of constituencies,
which is one step toward responding to a long-urged call for
legislative reforms.
</P>
<P>
Tsai made the remarks as former DPP Chairman Lin Yi-hsiung and
his supporters ended a 240-hour relay fast in front of the
Legislative Yuan to press for the passage of the constitutional
amendment for legislative reforms by March 20 presidential election
day, to halve the number of legislative seats.
</P>
<P>
Tsai said that in Friday's floor meeting, the DPP will propose
that the draft constitutional amendment go to a second reading, with
a third reading to be passed at an extraordinary session March 18.
</P>
<P>
Tsai claimed that the opposition Kuomintang (KMT) and People
First Party (PFP) will only budge under pressure from the public
before the March 20 presidential election if they don't support the
DPP's proposal.
</P>
<P>
"We shall see if the KMT and PFP are really serious about
reforms, or they are only pretending in order to try to woo voters
before the presidential election," Tsai said.
</P>
<P>
On the KMT's remarks that it will not oppose sending the draft
amendment passed Wednesday to a second reading but will ask for
second and third readings of eight other constitutional amendment
proposals, including the abrogation of the National Assembly and an
adjustment of its duties, Tsai expressed hope that this is not just
an opposition facade to boycott the first reading of the
constitutional amendment passed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft amendment, the number of seats in the legislature
will be cut to 113, together with the adoption of "single seat, two
votes" system with one vote for individual candidate in a
constituency and another for a political party, and a lengthening of
the legislative term to four years from the current three.
</P>
<P>
Chen Chien-ming, party whip of the opposition Taiwan Solidarity
Union, an ally of the DPP, said that his party will propose that the
draft constitutional amendment to halve the number of legislative
seats be put to a second reading and that other constitutional
revision proposals be put on hold for the time being.
</P>
<P>
"If all nine constitutional amendment proposals have to be passed
together, the task will be too huge and will not be completed in this
legislature term and everything will start all over again in the next
Legislature," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the party caucuses of the KMT and PFP noted that the
draft constitutional amendment proposal passed Wednesday is only one
of the nine proposals and they proposed that all nine go to a second
reading.
</P>
<P>
Liao Feng-teh, party whip of the KMT, said that all nine must be
passed and claimed that the "pan-green camp's" advocacy of passing
just one of them is "showboating."
</P>
<P>
He said that the KMT and the PFP think that a constitutional
amendment committee, which is in charge of the review of the
constitutional amendment proposals and other matters related to the
Constitution, should be suspended and that Legislative Yuan President
Wang Jin-pyng should preside over consultations to decide all
proposals and then pass the second and third readings in
extraordinary sessions.
</P>
<P>
Hsieh Chang-chieh, PFP legislative whip, also said that the
KMT-PFP camp, in response to calls from the public, hopes that all
constitutional amendment proposals "will be dealt with immediately."
</P>
<P>
On the issue of halving the number of legislative seats,
Legislative Yuan President Wang said a reasonable number should be
based on the "ecology and needs" of the legislature so that it will
run more smoothly and will be more representative of the will of the
people.
</P>
<P>
KMT Chairman Lien Chan said that he has always supported the
"halving of the legislature, " and the "single seat, two votes"
system, and that he is happy to see legislative reform.
</P>
<P>
But he said that the chances of the reforms passing before March
20 is slim, as there is not enough time.
</P>
<P>
PFP Chairman James Soong said that his party will be happy to see
a cut in the number of legislative seats, although he added that full
discussion on other complementary measures is also needed. He added
that if "one is constrained by pressure from populism and ideology,
then legislative goals will not be achieved."
</P>
<P>
"One should carefully consider how many seats are needed to allow
the legislature to function well," Soong said.
</P>
</TEXT>
