<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040311.0020" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
ROC SUPPORTS FORMATION OF PACIFIC UNION: MOFA
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  11 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Republic of China supports the
proposal to form a European Union-style Pacific Union, a Ministry of
Foreign Affairs official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Gary Song-huann Lin, director of the foreign ministry's East
Asian and Pacific affairs department, told a regular news conference
that both New Zealand and Australia have been advocating the
formation of a Pacific Union and that Australia has become
increasingly active in participating in South Pacific affairs.
</P>
<P>
If the proposed Pacific Union can truly be established, Lin said
it will contribute to regional stability and cooperation. The union
can also become a mechanism for solving disputes, he added.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Taiwan has five diplomatic allies -- the Solomon
Islands, the Marshall Islands, Palau, Nauru and Tuvalu -- in the
South Pacific and has representative offices in two other countries
in the region -- Fiji and Papua New Guinea -- Lin said Taiwan has
traditionally played an important role in the region's development.
</P>
<P>
So if the Pacific Union is formed, Lin said, the ROC will apply
for membership.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lin said the ROC's engagements with New Zealand and
Australia have increased significantly in recent years. Several
parliamentary groups from the two countries will travel to Taiwan in
the coming days to observe Taiwan's presidential election and its
first-ever referendum to be held simultaneously on March 20, Lin
said, adding that a delegation, headed by Craig Emerson, a member of
the Australian House of Representatives, will visit Taiwan March
14-20 to look into Taiwan democratic development.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a foreign wire service report that Bangladesh has
recalled its ambassador to Beijing, Lin said the foreign ministry is
still checking whether the recall is for routine home consultations
or whether the recall has anything to do with the opening of a Taiwan
representative office in that country.
</P>
<P>
"We have sent a message to the Bangladesh government asking about
the reasons behind the recall of its Beijing envoy. As Thursday is an
Islamic holiday in Bangladesh, we have yet to receive a response, "
Lin said, adding that the foreign ministry will closely watch for any
developments.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh maintains formal diplomatic ties with mainland China.
It reached an agreement with Taiwan earlier this year on the exchange
of representative offices. The ROC representative office in the
Bangladesh capital of Dhaka was inaugurated March 1. Lin said, the
representative office now operates normally and smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Lin further said the ROC has shipped a batch of rice to the
Dominican Republic to help flood victims there. According to Lin, the
ROC's diplomatic ally in the Caribbean was hit by serious floods last
November, resulting in huge financial losses and a food shortage.
</P>
<P>
"We hope our rice donation will help relieve food shortages in
the Dominican Republic and further cement our bilateral
relationship," Lin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040311.0021" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION CALLS FOR RESTRAINT IF ACCOSTED DURING MARCH 13 RALLIES
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,   March  11  (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The opposition "pan-blue alliance"
released a set of provisions Thursday for people taking part in an
islandwide demonstration against President Chen Shui-bian and his
administration to avoid clashes if participants at the rallies are
provoked.
</P>
<P>
The "pan-blue alliance" of Kuomintang (KMT) Chairman Lien Chan,
who is running for president, and his running mate, People First
Party (PFP) Chairman James Soong, has called for a number of rallies
for March 13, the last Saturday before the March 20 presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
Ma Ying-jeou, the mayor of Taipei and one of the top campaign
aides for the "pan-blue alliance" announced at a news conference the
set of guidelines, which were grouped in an apparent parody of the
"four noes plus one, " that the president included in his 2000
inaugural speech. These included not holding a referendum on the
nation's status quo concerning independence or unification with
mainland China.
</P>
<P>
Ma explained that the "four noes" of the "pan-blue alliance"
refer to "no welcome for those who mudsling or otherwise call
participants at the rallies communists; no response to those who try
to provoke marchers; no clashes with those who try to frame the
participants, and no retort to abusive language." Ma asked that all
participants remain calm, rational and avoid any conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The final "no" is "no litter should be left behind after the
rallies, only the footsteps of the marchers," Ma said.
</P>
<P>
He urged all participants to follow the spirit of Gandhi by
expressing their dissatisfaction with the present government in a
"loving, peaceful and non-violent manner."
</P>
<P>
Ma said that the main theme of the March 13 rallies is a "vote
for change, " and he welcomed everyone who is unsatisfied with the
ruling Democratic Progressive Party to take part in a peaceful way,
but he hoped that no one would create a disturbance during the
rallies.
</P>
<P>
Ma said that anyone who is bullied or verbally abused should not
take matters into their own hands and instead let the police or those
tasked with maintaining order and security handle the situation. If,
for example, someone raises the national flag of the People's
Republic of China and shouts, "Hail to [Beijing President] Hu Jintao"
to try to frame the "pan-blue alliance" supporters, marchers should
not be angry or feel the need for retribution -- just flash the "V
for victory" sign, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
Ma said that changing the president is the means to an end,
namely, "saving Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
In any democratic society, Ma continued, presidential elections
are a time for review of the performance of the president during his
term, and the incumbent should face the review by the people in a
humble way.
</P>
<P>
Both Ma and other top campaign officials, including Legislative
Yuan Speaker Wang Jin-pyng, KMT official Ting Shou-chung and
spokesman Tsai Cheng-yuan donned red headbands emblazoned with the
word "change" at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
Each of them also carried paper fans with the word "change, "
printed on them and wore pins saying, "got 20, " meaning that the
wearer will secure 20 other people to vote for the "pan-blue
alliance" candidates. They also flashed the "V" sign and repeatedly
shouted, "Change the president to save Taiwan, " in Mandarin,
Taiwanese and Hakkanese.
</P>
<P>
They urged all "pan-blue alliance" supporters to come out wearing
blue (the color of the KMT) or orange (that of the PFP) , and bring
plastic baton noise-makers, horns, trumpets, whistles, and even pots
and pans to bang together at the rallies.
</P>
<P>
Ma encouraged those who intend to participate in Saturday's
rallies to use alternate mean of transportation since traffic
controls will be in force. He even suggested people walk to the
venues if possible. Although no official pre-march figures are
available, Ma said he was confident that one million people would
show up to back the Lien-Soong ticket.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of the ruling Democratic Progressive Party mobilized
more than one million people to form a 500-kilometer, "hand-in-hand"
human chain along the length of Taiwan in a rally on Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
Ma said that starting from 1 p.m. Saturday, supporters will
converge on 145 staging points in 25 cities and counties. They will
then march to a designated place, for example, in Taipei to the
intersection of Ketagalan Boulevard and Park Road near the
Presidential Office.
</P>
<P>
Lien, Soong, Wang and Ma will take the stage at around 3:15 p.m.
to prepare to face the Presidential Office and shout, "Change the
president to save Taiwan" at 3:20 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
