<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040311.0023" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
NAVY TAKES DELIVERY OF EIGHTH PERRY-CLASS MISSILE FRIGATE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Kaohsiung,  March  11 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ROC Navy took delivery of a new
Perry-class missile frigate from the Kaohsiung-based China
Shipbuilding Corp. (CSBC) Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Annette Lu presided over the delivery ceremony
held at the CSBC's Kaohsiung shipyard in southern Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
In the ceremony, CSBC Chairman Hsu Chiang handed over a
scaled-down replica of the new frigate, christened the "Tien Tan,"
to ROC Navy Commander-in-Chief Admiral Miao Yung-ching to symbolize
the delivery. Naval officers then hoisted the ROC national flag on
the ship and decorated it with the ROC Navy's emblem to mark the
commissioning of the frigate into service.
</P>
<P>
The new warship is named after Tien Tan, a general during the
Warring States period (475-221 B.C.) in China who recovered his
fatherland from invaders.
</P>
<P>
The "Tien Tan" is the eighth and last Perry-class frigate that
the state-owned shipbuilding company had been commissioned to build
for the navy under a naval fleet modernization program launched in
the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the delivery ceremony, Lu said the smooth completion
of the Perry-class frigate construction program marks a remarkable
achievement in the pursuit of self-reliance and self-sufficiency in
national defense.
</P>
<P>
"I'm convinced that the addition of the 'Tien Tan' frigate to
the naval fleet will beef up the navy's defense capabilities to
ensure stability and security in the Taiwan Strait," Lu said.
</P>
<P>
CSBC Chairman Hsu Chiang said the CSBC signed a contract with the
navy in August 2000 for the construction of the "Tien Tan" frigate
and that construction had proceeded smoothly since it began in
February 2001.
</P>
<P>
The 3,800-ton Perry-class frigate is armed with many
sophisticated weapons, including an advanced radar system, torpedoes,
rockets, deep-water bombs, and locally built "Hsiungfeng" II anti-ship
missiles. It can also be equipped with two anti-submarine
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Seven CSBS-built Perry-class frigates have long been commissioned
into service. With three-dimensional combat capabilities, the
Perry-class frigates have formed the backbone of the nation's
second-generation naval fleet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040311.0024" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION MINISTER ADDRESSES SCHOOLING FOR TAIWAN CHILDREN IN CHINA
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 11 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ministry of Education will encourage
the opening of more schools for Taiwan businessmen's children in
mainland China, or having them study on Kinmen Island opposite Fujian
province, according to Minister of Education Huang Jong-tsun.
</P>
<P>
Huang made the remarks after having paid a visit to Kinmen
Wednesday, where he inspected the situation regarding mainland-based
Taiwan businessmen's children going to school there. Huang was
accompanied by ranking ministry officials and various lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
According to the education minister, his ministry is supportive
of the establishment of more schools for Taiwan businessmen's
children in mainland China. Otherwise they can consider receiving
education on Taiwan's outlying Kinmen Island, which lies closer to
the mainland's Fujian province.
</P>
<P>
Huang made the proposal given the fact that only about 10 percent
of Taiwan businessmen's school-age children based in the mainland's
southeastern coastal regions are able to enroll in local elementary
and junior schools set up especially for them.
</P>
<P>
Kinmen County Education Bureau Chief Lu Chih-hui made a briefing
on the occasion, reporting that a total of 42 children of Taiwan
businessmen from Xiamen, Quanzhou and Zhangzhou in Fujian province
are studying in Kinmen now -- 10 at elementary schools, 16 at junior
high schools and eight each at senior high schools and vocational
schools.
</P>
<P>
Lu said capacities at all levels of Kinmen's schools are more
than sufficient to accept more Taiwan businessmen's children from
mainland China.
</P>
<P>
Kinmen County has in recent years earmarked more than NT$10
million (US$300,000) in building and refurbishing student residences,
Lu noted, adding that primary schools and junior high schools in
Kinmen can take at least 2,000 people and 1,000 people, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Lu stressed that Taiwan businessmen's children studying in Kinmen
will be given the same privilege as local students, ranging from free
insurance, books, transport and education fees to subsidized housing.
</P>
<P>
Lawmaker Cheng Jhen-long of the Taiwan Solidarity Union said only
1,500 out of about 15,000 Taiwanese children in the Dongguan and
Shanghai areas are accepted by the special schools for Taiwan
businessmen's children there, with the rest of them attending
international or local schools.
</P>
<P>
Cheng suggested that the government should pay greater heed to
assist Taiwan businessmen with operations in the mainland in opening
more schools for their children or encouraging Taiwanese children to
receive an education on Kinmen, a location which is particularly good
for those from the Fujian and Shanghai areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
