<HEADLINE>
CABINET TO RESIGN AS ESTABLISHED PRACTICE AFTER ELECTION: YU
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 11 (CNA)
(By P.C. Tang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Premier Yu Shyi-kun said Thursday that he
and his Cabinet will respect the nation's established constitutional
procedures by presenting their resignations after the March 20
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The premier made the comments in an interview on a political talk
show broadcast by a local television channel of the Eastern
Multimedia Group.
</P>
<P>
Although the March 20 election day is quickly approaching, Yu
said that he would only take leave to help in the campaign affairs of
his party's candidate after he has been able to take care of his
administrative work.
</P>
<P>
On the Cabinet resignation issue, Yu said that according to
established procedures, the premier and other members of the
Executive Yuan must present their resignations within a set period of
time after a presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that he is a "team player, " Yu said that he will
respect his team's views, and that it is up to the team to decide his
political future after the election.
</P>
<P>
He said that he attaches great importance to the presidential
election and that he hasn't had any time to think about affairs after
election day.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether President Chen Shui-bian has promised to let him
continue serving in his post if he is re-elected for a second term,
Yu said he is not in a position to discuss the matter, adding that he
has to respect the president's authority and decision on the matter.
</P>
<P>
On President Chen's recent comments that he might consider
selecting a woman to be premier if he is re-elected, Yu said the
comments represent the fact that the president attaches great
importance to women's participation in running the country.
</P>
<P>
Yu said that he agrees with the president's views on the issue,
but added that the president's comments by no means indicate that a
woman will be appointed premier after May 20, the inauguration day of
the newly-elected president.
</P>
</TEXT>
