<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040312.0005" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
RALLIES FOR PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES DOMINATE LAST WEEKEND BEFORE VOTE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 12 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Both contenders for the presidency are
scrambling their supporters to come out on the last weekend before
the vote on March 20 with rallies islandwide.
</P>
<P>
The Kuomintang and People First Party, which fielded a joint
ticket of Lien Chan and James Soong in the race, have called for
their supporters to take to the streets wherever they are on 3:20
p.m. Saturday and yell, "Go pan- blue, elect Lien-Soong" and "Change
the president to save Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
People who are not able to attend organized rallies have been
urged to blow their car horns, bang on kitchen utensils or make noise
however they can to show their solidarity.
</P>
<P>
Lien will lead his followers in a march in downtown Taipei and
give a speech in the square in front of the Presidential Office.
</P>
<P>
Notable among Lien's followers in the march will be former
Premier Sun Yun-hsuan, although he has been confined to a wheelchair
since suffering a stroke, and well-known Taiwanese opera actress Sun
Chui-feng.
</P>
<P>
To accommodate the march, several streets in Taipei City will be
closed to traffic on Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Soong will lead a similar march in Taichung City, while Lien's and
Soong's campaign manager, Legislative Yuan Speaker Wang Jin-pyng will
preside over another march in Kaohsiung City.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Lien and Soong predicted that more than one
million supporters will take part in the rallies in all 25 counties
and cities around the island to show their dissatisfaction with the
administration of President Chen Shui-bian.
</P>
<P>
So many want to take part, the spokesman claimed, that organizers
in different places have hired almost all of the tour buses on the
island and have even enlisted help from truck drivers to help ferry
them to the 100-odd gathering places.
</P>
<P>
The islandwide rallies will receive heavy media coverage. The
Kuomintang-run China Television Company will cooperate with 11 TV
companies to provide live broadcasts of the activities. There will be
25 satellite news relay vehicles, four helicopters and more than 500
technicians and reporters covering the event from every corner of the
island, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ruling Democratic Progressive Party has lined up
four huge campaign rallies for the final weekend before election day
for its presidential candidate, incumbent President Chen, with one in
its stronghold of Kaohsiung on Saturday, and another three in
Taichung, Ilan and Hualien on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Kaohsiung rally will bring together Chen, his running mate,
Vice President Annette Lu, Chen's wife and former President Lee
Teng-hui.
</P>
<P>
Each of them will give traditional campaign speeches and urge
their followers to flash a thumbs-up sign to show their support for
Chen and, who have been designated with the No. 1 for voting
purposes.
</P>
<P>
DPP organizers predict the Kaohsiung rally will bring together
around 500,000 supporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040312.0006" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
WORLD TAIWANESE ORGANIZATIONS TO HOLD CONVENTION IN KAOHSIUNG
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 12 (CNA)
(By Huang Kwang-chun)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The World Taiwanese Congress (WTC) and the
World Federation of Taiwanese Associations (WFTA) will jointly hold
their annual conventions in Kaohsiung, southern Taiwan, March 13-14,
a convener of the gathering said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kuo Chung-kuo, the WFTA's president, said that nearly 800
representatives from around the world will participate in the two-day
meeting which is designated to support President Chen Shui-bian's
re-election bid and the referendum he has called to be held alongside
the March 20 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
He encouraged the people of Taiwan to vote in the referendum to
show the world their desire for cross-Taiwan Strait peace and their
feeling about the mainland Chinese missile threat.
</P>
<P>
The main topic of the meeting will be "A new country with a new
constitution," he noted.
</P>
