<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040312.0008" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG, MALAYSIA REACH AIR SERVICES DEAL
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Hong  Kong,  March  12 (CNA)
(By Stanley Cheung)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong signed an open-capacity
arrangement on air services with Malaysia Friday after two days of
negotiations in Kuala Lumpur, according to a government official.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Secretary for Economic Development and Labour Wilson Fung
said the deal provides an open structure for both airlines to operate
as many passenger and cargo services between Hong Kong and anywhere
in Malaysia as they wish, without any limitation on routing, type of
service or aircraft.
</P>
<P>
It is the first of its kind signed by Hong Kong with an Asian
partner, Fung noted.
</P>
<P>
"The new open-capacity structure accords full flexibility for
airlines of the two sides to plan ahead and expand their services in
response to market demand," he said.
</P>
<P>
"With a view to expanding further our bilateral aviation
relationship, we have reached agreement with the Malaysian government
to enable the airlines of Malaysia to operate all cargo services
beyond Hong Kong to the United States," Fung explained.
</P>
<P>
"The new services will enhance competition in this long-haul
market. This is in the best interests of Hong Kong's shipping
community and reflects the government's determination to support the
development of Hong Kong's logistics industry. In return, airlines of
Hong Kong get very flexible and valuable fifth-freedom rights to
operate beyond Malaysia," Fung added.
</P>
<P>
He encouraged Hong Kong and Malaysian airlines to make use of the
liberal structure to introduce new services between the two places,
and beyond to other destinations.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian airlines have also been invited to use Hong Kong as
their hub for trans-Pacific all-cargo services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040312.0009" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN-BASED BANKS POST LOWERED OVERDUE LOAN RATES FOR DECEMBER
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  12 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan-based banks posted an average
overdue loan rate of 4.33 percent for December last year, a level
better than the target set by the Ministry of Finance, according to a
quarterly report issued Friday by Taiwan's Central Bank of China
(CBC).
</P>
<P>
The top five domestic banks with the lowest overdue loan rates
are Cathay United Bank (0.82 percent), East Sun Bank (1.18 percent),
First Commercial Bank (1.46 percent) , Taishin International Bank
(1.59 percent) and Chinatrust Commercial Bank (1.65 percent), the CBC
report shows.
</P>
<P>
On the other side, 12 banks, such as Chung Shing Bank and Medium
Business Bank of Kaohsiung District, still failed to surpass the
government-set level, the CBC report shows. Chung Shing Bank recorded
the highest level of 59.03 percent, followed by Medium Business Bank
of Hualien District with 23.99 percent, Pan Asia Bank with 22.63
percent and ChinFon Commercial Bank with 19.21 percent.
</P>
<P>
Among them, seven major public banks posted a lowered average
overdue loan of 4.31 percent for February this year, an improvement
as compared to the January's average level of 4.35 percent, the
December's 4.37 percent and the November's 4.76 percent.
</P>
<P>
The drop is an indication that the seven major domestic banks --
Bank of Taiwan, Land Bank of Taiwan, Taiwan Cooperative Bank, Chang
Hwa Bank, Hua Nan Bank, First Commercial Bank and Medium Business
Bank of Taiwan -- have improved their business in writing off bad
loans and in the control of releasing loans due to a better business
conditions in many sectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040312.0010" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN AIMING TO INCREASE OUTPUT OF ELECTRIC  VEHICLES THIS YEAR
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 12 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The annual four-day Taipei International
Cycle Show at the Taipei World Trade Center showcased electric
vehicles Friday, with an official saying that Taiwan will up its
production of some kinds of the environmentally friendly vehicles by
10 percent to 20 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The official from the Industrial Development Bureau under the
Ministry of Economic Affairs said that with societies across the
globe seeing the proportion of the elderly rising, the need for more
low-speed electric vehicles will gradually increase. These electric
wheelchairs and other vehicles are also needed by the handicapped, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's output of these electric vehicles will increase to
400,000 units this year, compared with 300,000 units last year.
Taiwan expects to outpace South Korea in global market share in 2004,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Electric scooters were first introduced in Taiwan in 1998 and
roughly 23,000 of them have been sold, but because of high prices,
the cancellation of subsidized purchase plans, difficult maintenance
and being inconvenient to charge, sales have been slow.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers are now turning their attention to light electric
vehicles that have a cruising range of only about 30 kilometers on a
single charge, compared with 50 kilometers to 60 kilometers for
electric scooters. The official said that the current thinking is to
target potential users who would only drive the vehicles around town.
</P>
<P>
These vehicles retail for around NT$20,000 (US$600) and Taiwan
will produce 100,000 of them this year, an increase of 10,000 units
from the previous year, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Although the global market for electric vehicles is at present
not very large, the official said that Taiwan should be able to carve
out a niche in the global market for them since it has a great deal
of experience in producing scooters and has much skill it its
mechanical industrial sector.
(Eric Liu)
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040312.0011" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
SEVERAL LAWMAKERS URGE PATIENCE IN CONSTITUTIONAL REFORM
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 12 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hours after various political factions in
the legislature agreed to amend the ROC Constitution before the March
20 presidential election to reduce by half the number of legislators
in the Legislative Yuan, several opposition lawmakers said Friday
that they had second thoughts on acting with so little time for
consideration.
</P>
<P>
Kuomintang legislators Chen Shei-saint and Shyu
Jong-shyong, and People First Party Legislator Hsu Yuan-kuo
said at a news conference that they support the reform of the
legislature but worry that if it is done in haste, more problems will
be created than are solved.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that is unfortunate that the first time the Legislative
Yuan has the chance to initiate a constitutional amendment, it wants
to rush through the process. If the amendment is adopted without
first being carefully considered and evaluated, the legislature would
be even more irresponsible than the National Assembly which used to
be in charge of amending the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
He said the Constitution is the fundamental legal framework of
the country, and as such should be revised only after much thought
and deliberation rather than by rushing an amendment through the
legislature when the public is absorbed in the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Shyu Jong-shyong, a four-term lawmaker, criticized the ruling
Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) lawmakers who have demanded that
the amendment be passed before the presidential election, saying that
they were simply "fooling around."
</P>
<P>
He said the ruling party is eager to make the legislative reform
a feather in its cap in the lead-up to the presidential election, and
thereby prevent many lawmakers from airing their different views. The
current problems with the legislature lie not in the number of its
seats, but in the quality of it members, he said.
</P>
<P>
Reducing the number of lawmakers and switching the election
system from multiple members from one district to one member per
constituency won't address the current problem, Shyu said.
</P>
<P>
Lawmaker Hsu Yuan-kuo, who has a doctorate in jurisprudence, said
halving the legislature will only prompt chaos instead of preventing
it.
</P>
<P>
In a legislature with only 113 seats, as proposed by the ruling
party, each of the 12 standing committees will consist of no more
than 10 members and four of five members teaming together would be
enough to control the whole committee, which would not be in the best
interest of the country, Hsu Yuan-kuo said.
</P>
<P>
Chen said he is seeking support from his colleagues to bring a
halt to the headlong rush to amend the Constitution and to leave the
issue until after the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Legislator Chen Chin-teh is the only ruling DPP member who
opposed an agreement entered by various political factions to act on
the proposal to reduce the number of seats before the presidential
election. He told a news conference that all proposals aimed at
revising the Constitution should be enacted together.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
