<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040312.0018" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
CABINET DEFENDS CEC DECISION TO COUNT MISCAST BALLOTS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  12 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cabinet spokesman Lin Chia-lung said
Friday that the Central Election Commission's (CEC's) decision to
count miscast ballots in the March 20 presidential election and
referendum is legal and reasonable.
</P>
<P>
Lin was responding to opposition criticism that the CEC's
decision to count ballots cast in the wrong boxes in the presidential
election and referendum is "illegal and absurd."
</P>
<P>
According to the Referendum Act, anybody who casts articles other
than referendum ballots into the boxes will be liable to a fine of
between NT$5,000 and NT$50,000.
</P>
<P>
The CEC announced Thursday that election administrators should
prevent voters from mistakenly casting presidential ballots into
referendum ballot boxes. If necessary, such voters should be brought
to justice and could be given a maximum two-year prison term in line
with the law.
</P>
<P>
The CEC also decided that presidential ballots that are miscast
into referendum ballot boxes due to the negligence of polling station
workers will still be counted as valid.
</P>
<P>
Lin hailed the CEC decision, saying the decision complies with
the democratic principle of respecting and protecting people's voting
rights.
</P>
<P>
"In a democratic system, we must respect opinions expressed by
citizens through ballots. Therefore, every ballot is precious and
sacred. We should not lightly invalidate a ballot simply because of
certain minor technical issues, such as a ballot being cast into the
wrong box," Lin said.
</P>
<P>
The opposition "pan-blue alliance" of the Kuomintang (KMT) and
the People First Party (PFP) has questioned the legality and
constitutionality of the nation's first-ever referendum to be held
alongside the election.
</P>
<P>
Claiming that the legality and constitutionality of President
Chen Shui-bian's decision to hold the referendum are undisputable,
Lin said it is very common in democratic countries around the world
for a referendum to be held simultaneously with a general election.
</P>
<P>
"Local voters are also no strangers to casting ballots for
different elections at the same time. In 1998, Taipei voters elected
the city mayor as well as city councilors and legislators of their
constituencies simultaneously at same polling stations.
</P>
<P>
At that time, ballots cast into the wrong boxes were counted as
valid, " Lin recalled, adding that he could not understand why
opposition politicians would question the CEC's decision on the
validity of miscast ballots.
</P>
<P>
However, the KMT and PFP legislative caucuses called a joint news
conference Friday evening urging the CEC to have second thoughts on
its decision.
</P>
<P>
The opposition caucuses said CEC commissioners should meet again
next Monday to review and "correct" its decision to avoid controversy
and speed up the vote-counting procedure on election day.
</P>
<P>
"Since the CEC acknowledges that the act of casting a
presidential ballot into a referendum box is illegal, how can a
miscast ballot be counted as valid? " PFP Legislator Feng Ting-kuo
asked.
</P>
<P>
PFP Legislator Diane Lee said that if the CEC fails to correct
its contradictory decision, the "pan-blue alliance" will mobilize its
supporters to stage a protest in front of the CEC.
</P>
<P>
CEC Chairman Huang Shih-cheng said Thursday that while it is
unlikely that ballots for the presidential election will be cast in
the boxes provided for the referendum ballots, or vise versa, any
such vote will still be counted.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Huang said, the outcome of the presidential election
will have to be announced twice. The first announcement will be made
when all ballots in the boxes for presidential election are tallied
and the second will be made when the boxes for referendum ballots are
counted, in case any presidential votes are found to have been cast
in the referendum boxes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040312.0019" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
NEW EVIDENCE FOUND OVER CAL JET CRASH
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 12 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China Airlines (CAL) will be fined by the
government, as fresh evidence indicating that the carrier was to
blame for a crash off Penghu County in May 2002 has been found, a
spokesman for the Aviation Safety Council (ASC) under the Executive
Yuan reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Aeronautics Administration (CAA) under the Ministry of
Transportation and Communications is planning to issue a fine of
NT$1.8 million (about US$54,000) to the carrier over the crash, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The ASC official, however, pointed out that while the new
evidence might not necessarily be the key cause of the crash of
flight CI611, it will make the investigation into the fatal accident
more comprehensive. The results of the ASC probe are slated to be
released late this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the ASC official, the new evidence was discovered
during a CAA investigation into CAL's maintenance and repair record
of the crashed Boeing 747-200 jet, which shows that the carrier had
failed to conduct a preventive anti-rust operation in a timely manner
every four years.
</P>
<P>
The evidence clearly shows that CAL carried out the operation
some 13 months past the date the work should have been carried out,
he explained, pointing out that the carrier should have done the work
in November 1997 but did not do so until December the following year.
</P>
<P>
CAA officials added that CAL has already been punished three
times since last year alone for failing to carry out its maintenance
and repair operations on schedule. It was penalized twice last year
with fines of NT$600,000 and NT$900,000, respectively, and was issued
a third fine of NT$3 million early this year.
</P>
<P>
In the face of the carrier's repeated failings, the CAA will
demand a detailed explanation of CAL's maintenance and repair work on
its airplanes, the CAA officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Boeing 747-200 passenger plane crashed into the sea off
Penghu County May 25, 2002, en route for Hong Kong, killing all 225
people on board. An initial investigation showed that metal fatigue
might be the main cause of the accident, as the aircraft broke into
pieces in flight.
</P>
</TEXT>
