<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION  RESULT WILL BE LATER THAN PLANNED: CEC
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 12 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A formal announcement of the outcome of
the March 20 presidential election will be two hours later than
originally expected due to a two-stage vote-counting system, the head
of the Central Election Commission (CEC) predicted Friday.
</P>
<P>
CEC Chairman Huang Shih-cheng made the remarks when he fielded
questions in the Legislative Yuan about a CEC meeting the previous
day in which the commission decided that presidential election and
referendum ballots cast in the wrong boxes will be counted as valid.
</P>
<P>
Huang had said earlier that although it is unlikely that ballots
for the presidential election will be cast in the boxes provided for
the referendum ballots, or vice versa, any such votes will still be
counted.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the outcome of the presidential election will have
to be announced twice. An initial announcement will be made when all
ballots in the boxes for the presidential election have been tallied
and the actual result will be announced after the boxes for
referendum ballots have been counted, in case any presidential votes
are found to have been cast in the referendum boxes.
</P>
<P>
Huang said that the CEC's decision to make a two-stage
announcement of the tallies "should be a quite simple procedure" and
he dismissed the possibility of any controversy.
</P>
<P>
But he also said that if there are "other factors, " then he
cannot predict what will happen, although he stressed that the CEC
will take full responsibility.
</P>
