<P>
"I have expressed deep condolences from the Republic of China
government and people to the Spanish government and people in this
terrible hour of tragedy, and in the face of unspeakable evil, that
has brought about the deaths of so many innocent people, " Chien said
at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
The minister said he has directed the ROC representative office
in Madrid to convey his sympathy and condolences to his Spanish
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
Chien said the ROC government and people love peace, respect
human rights and firmly oppose any form of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Ten terrorist bombs exploded in three busy Madrid train stations
during the height of the Thursday morning rush hour, killing nearly
200 commuters and wounding more than 1,000 others in Spain's worst
terrorist attack ever.
</P>
<P>
Chien said he is very concerned about the safety of ROC
expatriates and travelers in Spain. "I have instructed our
representative office in Spain to strengthen protective measures and
offer all necessary security services for ROC expatriates and
tourists," he added.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he went on, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs has asked
domestic law enforcement authorities to step up security measures at
foreign embassies and representative offices in Taiwan and tighten
protection for their staff.
</P>
<P>
The rush-hour bombings struck three railway stations in the
Spanish capital, three days before the nation's elections. The
Spanish government initially blamed the Basque separatist group ETA,
but ETA-linked officials denied involvement. A statement e-mailed to
an Arabic newspaper later claimed that the international al-Qaida
terror network was responsible.
</P>
<P>
Messages of dismay and sympathy sent to the Spanish government
from capitals worldwide all condemned the attacks as a "ferocious,
senseless and barbaric" assault on Spanish democracy.
