</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The number of mainland Chinese citizens
who are eligible to vote in Taiwan totals about 16,000, a
high-ranking Mainland Affairs Council (MAC) official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Huang Chieh-cheng, a vice chairman of the Cabinet-level MAC, said
that of the 16,000-odd mainlanders, about 13,000 are spouses of
Taiwan citizens, while the remaining 3,000 are members of the
extended families of Taiwan citizens as a result of closer
people-to-people relations across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
Fielding questions at a regular MAC press conference, Huang was
asked whether the mainlanders who are eligible to cast presidential
ballots in Taiwan March 20 are also eligible to cast referendum votes
on the same day.
</P>
<P>
Huang answered that if mainland citizens are eligible to vote in
the election, it means they all have already obtained their Republic
of China IDs. As ROC ID card holders, they are eligible to cast
referendum votes just like every ROC citizen in Taiwan, he added.
</P>
<P>
Huang declined to speculate on the turn-out rate of the
Taiwan-residing mainlanders in the presidential election and
referendum.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the MAC has paid close attention to
developments in the ongoing second session of the 10th National
People's Congress (NPC) in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Although many NPC deputies have expressed differing opinions on
the so-called "Taiwan issue" and related affairs, the MAC considers
Beijing's policy on Taiwan to be basically unchanged, although the
rhetoric has eased in general, Huang said.
</P>
