<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATIVE REFORM BILL TO GO INTO 2ND, 3RD READING MARCH 19
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 12 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Legislative Yuan decided Friday after
consultations between the ruling and the opposition parties that a
draft constitutional revision bill concerning legislative reforms
will be put to second and third readings on the eve of the March 20
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
In response to calls from the public for a more efficient
legislature, a constitutional revision committee in the legislature
on Wednesday passed the first reading of the draft constitutional
revision bill on legislative reforms, one of nine constitutional
revision bills on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft constitutional revision bill, the number of
legislative seats will be cut to 113 seats from the current 225 in
2008 and the electoral system will be changed to a "single seat, two
votes" system, meaning that instead of the current multiple seat
system, there will be one vote for the individual candidate and one
vote for the party in each constituency. The legislative term will
also be lengthened to four years instead of three.
</P>
<P>
However, there are misgivings about whether a streamlined
legislature will ensure efficiency and there are also calls that the
legislature should hold public hearings to listen to views from all
quarters so as to make a comprehensive overhaul of the details
instead of rushing the bill through.
</P>
<P>
Still, the ruling Democratic Progressive Party and the opposition
parties agreed in consultations Friday that the bill will go to a
second and third reading March 19 to project a pro-reform image
before the neck-and-neck presidential election,
</P>
<P>
Tsai Huang-lang, DPP legislative whip, hailed the long-awaited
completion of the bill and said it will "live up to the expectations
of the people" and will be a great stride toward legislative reforms,
which will be a victory for the people.
</P>
<P>
DPP Legislator Lee Chun-yi also said that the "consultation
Friday was unexpectedly smooth and that the Legislative Yuan should
complete the final reading of the bill March 19."
</P>
<P>
Under the procedure for constitutional amendment, the legislature
will then ask the National Assembly, whose 300 members will be chosen
in proportion of the ratio of the various political parties, to
confirm the constitutional amendment bill in a specially convened
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, former DPP Chairman Lin Yi-hsiung was elated to learn
that the bill is very likely to clear the legislature before the
election.
</P>
<P>
Lin, who led a group of his supporters in a relay fast in front
of the Legislative Yuan to highlight the cause of halving the number
of legislative seats, thanked the legislature for its decision.
</P>
<P>
Lin said that the legislature "made a good decision" and he
expressed hope that the procedure in the Legislature can be completed
by next week, so that the public will feel that "there is hope for
reforms and that the nation can continue to progress" before March 20.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040312.0031" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN ELECTION PREVENTS QUICK E.U. REMOVAL OF ARMS EMBARGO ON CHINA
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Paris,  March 11 (CNA)
(By Y.S. Lo and P.C. Tang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Commission of the European Union feels
that as Taiwan's presidential election is approaching, the E.U.
cannot make a formal decision in its upcoming summit meeting to
remove an arms sales embargo on mainland China, an influential French
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The European Council, the E.U.'s highest decision-making body
that groups the heads of state and governments of the fifteen E.U.
countries, is scheduled to hold a summit meeting March 25-26 to
discuss whether the E.U. should remove its embargo on arms sales to
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
According to Le Monde newspaper, Beijing has urged European
countries and the E.U. to lift the embargo in place since Beijing's
1989 massacre of pro-democracy activists in Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper also said that the E.U. issued a code of conduct in
1998 to regulate its members' arms sales as well as high-tech
transfers to third countries, and that removing the embargo does not
mean that E.U. countries can easily export arms to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
However, there are no laws to stop such arms sales and those
E.U. countries that sell weapons to the mainland secretly cannot
be prevented from doing so, the newspaper cited French defense
experts as saying.
</P>
<P>
Although the upcoming European Council summit will touch on the
embargo issue, the newspaper said that "the E.U.'s executive body
estimates it is impossible that a formal decision will be taken on
the occasion due to the proximity of the presidential election and
referendum scheduled to be held in Taiwan March 20."
</P>
</TEXT>
