<HEADLINE>
KMT PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE PAYS TRIBUTE TO ROC FOUNDING FATHER
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 12 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Opposition Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan
paid tribute to the Republic of China's founding father, Dr. Sun
Yat-sen, Friday by laying flowers at the foot of Sun's statue at the
Sun Yat-sen Memorial Hall to mark the 79th anniversary of his
passing.
</P>
<P>
Lien, the "pan-blue alliance's" presidential candidate, said that
at a time when the 2004 presidential election is only seven days
away, all ROC citizens should remember the ideals and teachings of
the nation's founding father as well as his contributions to the
nation and its people.
</P>
<P>
Lien called for all the people of the Republic of China to use
their ballots in the March 20 presidential election to choose a head
of state who is able and willing to champion Dr. Sun's pivotal
nation-founding ideals of democracy, freedom and equality.
</P>
<P>
The former ROC vice president was accompanied by KMT Vice
Chairman Wu Po-hsiung and Lin Cheng-chih, who was once the top
official in charge of cultural affairs during the era of KMT rule.
</P>
<P>
After more than five decades of ruling in Taiwan, the KMT,
founded by Dr. Sun Yat-sen, lost power in the 2000 presidential
election to the Democratic Progressive Party's Chen Shui-bian.
</P>
<P>
March 12 is better known as Arbor Day. The ROC government
designated the day of Dr. Sun's passing as Arbor Day four years after
his death in 1925. Today, trees are planted each March 12 in
remembrance of Dr. Sun's encouragement of afforestation and his
contribution to the nation.
</P>
<P>
Also on Friday, President Chen Shui-bian led an official
delegation to the scenic left bank of Tamshui River in Pahli, Taipei
County to plant a sapling of the Formosa date palm to celebrate Arbor
Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040312.0035" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL HEADLINE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
