<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040312.0036" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT PLANTS FORMOSAN DATE PALM SAPLING TO MARK ARBOR DAY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 12 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian planted a sapling
of an indigenous palm tree on the scenic left bank of Tamshui River
in Pahli, Taipei County Friday to celebrate Arbor Day.
</P>
<P>
Chen was flanked by a group of pupils from Tahkan Elementary
School in Pahli while he planted the Formosan date palm. He told the
school children that the Formosan date palm is a tough species able
to endure harsh environmental conditions. He added that the tree is
much like the Taiwan people who he said have great tenacity in the
face of tough challenges.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the tree-planting ceremony organized by the Taiwan
Forestry Bureau to mark Arbor Day, Chen said the event was designed
not only to remember Dr. Sun Yat-sen, the Republic of China's
national founding father, but also to remind the people of the
importance of preserving the natural environment.
</P>
<P>
To signify its determination to protect Taiwan's natural
environment and make Taiwan a "green" silicon island, Chen said, the
government has made improving water conservation and afforestation
part of the "Challenge 2008 National Development Plan."
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Taipei County Magistrate Su Chen-chang,
whose "egg head" has been his trade mark, jokingly said to the school
children that as he is bald, he knows very well about cold and wind.
He said he wants the children to help conserve the environment so as
to prevent the planet "from becoming bald."
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Taiwan Forestry Bureau said the Formosan date
palm was chosen as the tree to be planted on this year's Arbor Day in
a bid to help beautify the coastline near Taipei County as coastal
areas are the most suitable places for planting the tree.
</P>
<P>
The Formosan date palm is one of the four "great wonders" in
Taiwan's botanical history as it has survived through thousands of
years of climatic harshness, including the last ice age, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Formosan date palm is not actually a species of date palm,
they said, pointing out that it is so called because its fruit, which
is blue when mature, tastes like date.
</P>
<P>
Similar tree-planting events were held in other cities and
counties around the country Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Republic of China government designated the day of Dr. Sun's
passing as Arbor Day four years after his death in 1925. Today, trees
are planted each March 12 in remembrance of Dr. Sun's encouragement
of afforestation and his contribution to the nation.
</P>
<P>
In 2003, the Cabinet designated the Feb. 4 to March 12 period as
"Arbor Month" for the first time. During the month, some 1.29 million
plants and seedlings were planted on 534 hectares of community
parkland and school campuses around the island.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
