<HEADLINE>
YU HOPES TO SEE LEGISLATIVE REFORM BEFORE MARCH 20 ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 12 (CNA)
(By P.C. Tang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Premier Yu Shyi-kun on Friday said that he
strongly hopes several bills concerning reform of the Legislative
Yuan will be passed into law before the March 20 presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
The premier made the comments while responding to media questions
at the Legislative Yuan, which is currently discussing whether to
send the constitutional draft amendment halving the number of
legislative seats through to its second reading.
</P>
<P>
The Legislature's constitutional reform committee came to an
agreement Wednesday that would reduce the number of legislative seats
from 225 to 113, as well as extend legislators' terms from three to
four years, and alter the rules on electing lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that the Taiwan people have long been critical of
the Legislative Yuan for its poor quality, efficiency, image and
performance, the premier said there is a general consensus among the
people for reform of the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
A majority of the lawmakers have agreed to push for the
legislative reform, Yu said, adding that passage of the reform bills
into law would help upgrade Taiwan's competitiveness.
</P>
</TEXT>
