<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040312.0039" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 12 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Friday, March 12, or the 22nd
day of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according to the
lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that have
occurred on this date in the past:

641A.D.: Chinese Princess Wen Cheng of the Tang dynasty goes to
Tibet to marry the Tibetan ruler.

1799: Austria declares war on France.

1832: Charles C. Boycott, English land agent in Ireland, is born.
After he refused to lower rents on his estates in Ireland, tenants
refused any further communication with him and his name was adopted
to describe this form of protest.

1881: Kemal Ataturk, originally Mustafa Kemal, Turkish national
leader and founder of modern Turkey, who served as president of the
Turkish Republic from 1923 to 1938, is born.

1913: Canberra is made the capital of Australia.

1925: Dr. Sun Yat-sen, who in 1940 would be posthumously declared
the founding father of the Republic of China for his life-long
contributions to the revolution, dies of liver cancer in Peking at
the age of 59.

1926: A foundation-stone-laying ceremony for the construction of
the Dr. Sun Yat-Sen Mausoleum is held in Nanking.

1938: Adolf Hitler's troops march into Austria and make the
country a German province after the resignation of Austrian Premier
Kurt von Schuschnigg.

1945: Anne Frank, German Jewish diarist who fled from Nazi
Germany to Amsterdam with her family in 1933 and kept a diary during
her years in hiding, dies of typhus in the German concentration camp
at Belsen at the age of 16.

1947: U.S. President Harry Truman tells Congress that the United
States must support countries fighting communism, a stance that
becomes known as the "Truman Doctrine."

1949: The Central Daily News publishes its first issue in Taipei.

1966: Gen. Suharto becomes acting president after the Indonesian
Congress stripped Sukarno of his authority.

1967: Svetlana Alliluyeva, daughter of Joseph Stalin, arrives in
Switzerland asking for political asylum.

1968: A ground-breaking ceremony is held in Taipei for the
construction of the National Dr. Sun Yat-Sen Memorial Hall.

1972: Britain and Communist China agree to exchange ambassadors,
22 years after London first recognized the Beijing regime.

1985: Yang Kuei, a noted Taiwanese writer during the Japanese
rule of Taiwan, dies of illness at the age of 80.

1989: Riot police battle demonstrators in Seoul demanding that
President Roh Tae Woo step down.

1990: The Parliament of the Republic of Lithuania declares
independence from the USSR, becoming the first Baltic republic to
break away from Soviet control.

1990: The Communist Party leadership in Outer Mongolia approves
opposition demands for sweeping political reforms.

1993: North Korea suddenly announces its withdrawal from the
nuclear non-proliferation treaty, intensifying the already tense
situation in Northeast Asia.

1996: Mainland China commences nine days of naval and air
military exercises in an area of the Taiwan Straits only 53
kilometers from Kinmen and 70 kilometers from the Penghu Islands.

1999: ROC President Lee Teng-hui echoes the pope's 1999 message
for the World Day of Peace, saying that true peace lies in respect
for human rights.

1999: The U.S. Senate and House of Representatives introduce a
resolution reaffirming U.S. commitment to Taiwan and expressing
concern over the mainland Chinese military threat to the island.

2000: Opposition Democratic Progressive Party presidential
candidate Chen Shui-bian says that if elected, he will not be opposed
to peace talks with mainland China.

2000: The Kinmen chapter of the Red Cross Society of the ROC is
formally established with the aim of promoting humanitarian
activities.

2001: The Ministry of Finance announces that the Bank of Taiwan,
the Land Bank of Taiwan and the Central Trust of China will merge
into a new bank.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "A man of character is one who is
sparing with his words. A good and wise man is without anxiety and
fear."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040313.0001" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN MUST STICK TO SOVEREIGNTY TO FACE GLOBALIZATION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Kaohsiung, March 13 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan must stick to its own indigenous
sovereignty in order to ride over the many challenges brought by
globalization, Vice President Annette Lu said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Lu made the remarks while giving a speech at the 2004 joint
annual conference of the World Taiwanese Congress and the World
Federation of Taiwanese Associations being held in this southern
Taiwan port city from Saturday to Sunday. Nearly 800 representatives
from around the world attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
In the face of mainland China's relentless efforts to gain turf
by competing against the United States in the Pacific region, Lu
encouraged the people of Taiwan to uphold their belief in democratic
values and principles and never surrender to the threat from Beijing.
"Taiwan must walk its own way and participate more actively in the
international community," she insisted.
</P>
<P>
Hailing the fact that the people of Taiwan have succeeded in
terminating authoritarian rule, implementing democracy and pushing
for transfer of power, Lu said that the Taiwan people still need to
accomplish the two above-mentioned tasks -- safeguarding Taiwan's
sovereignty and embracing globalization by displaying its strength as
an oceanic country.
</P>
<P>
At a time when Taiwan is at a historical crossroads, the country
should open up bravely to the world and pursue greater globalization
as a democratic member in the international community, the vice
president said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
