<HEADLINE>
PLAN TO INSTALL LED TRAFFIC LIGHTS ALMOST COMPLETE: MOEA
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 13 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A plan to replace incandescent lamps with
light-emitting diodes (LEDs) in certain traffic lights will be
completed in March, creating major energy savings, the Energy
Commission under the Ministry of Economic Affairs said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Once the plan has been fully implemented, 280,000 of the 646,000
incandescent lamps used in traffic lights around the country will
have been replaced, which will save 8,000 watts of electricity per
year and reduce dioxide emissions by 75,000 tons through the savings
on electricity, which is usually produced by burning coal.
</P>
<P>
The plan will bring the usage of LED's from 8 percent of the
country's traffic lights to 32 percent, creating major savings on
electricity charges for local governments, which are in charge of
maintaining traffic lights.
</P>
<P>
LEDs are safer and last longer than the incandescent lamps,
produce more stable light and cost less to maintain. The Energy
Council began the plan to replace some traffic lights in July last
year.
</P>
<P>
The remaining traffic lights will also be substituted with LEDs
in the future, Energy Council officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
