<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040313.0012" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
ELECTION CAMPAIGN ACTIVITIES HEATING UP ISLANDWIDE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 13 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan was embroiled in presidential
election campaign activities Saturday as the 2004 campaign entered
its last week and both contenders in the race went all-out to woo
voters.
</P>
<P>
The opposition "pan blue alliance" of the Kuomintang (KMT) and
People First Party (PFP), which is fielding a joint ticket, organized
huge rallies in 25 counties and cities around the island to boost
support for their candidates -- KMT Chairman Lien Chan for the
presidency and PFP Chairman James Soong for the vice presidency.
</P>
<P>
In Taipei, some 400,000 alliance followers gathered in different
places in the city and marched toward the square in front of the
Presidential Office.
</P>
<P>
At 3:20 p.m., the crowd blew whistles, banged on kitchen utensils
and made noise however they could to show their dissatisfaction with
President Chen Shui-bian and yell in chorus "Go pan-blue, elect
Lien-Soong" and "Change the president to save Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
The noise lasted for ten minutes, measured 82 decibels and was
greeted with four tickets for a combined fine of NT$33,000
(US$1,000) from local environmental officials who were monitoring the
noise throughout the rally.
</P>
<P>
Lien, who had just emerged from a televised presentation of his
campaign promises, gave a speech to the followers. He also lay down
to kiss the land to show his love for the country. Joining him on the
platform were former Premier Sun Yun-hsuan, well-known Taiwan opera
actress Sun Chui-feng and various others.
</P>
<P>
Although confined to a wheelchair after suffering a stroke, Sun
attended the rally the whole way and even stood up to speak to the
followers. In a faltering and unclear voice, he urged them to vote
for Lien.
</P>
<P>
In a humorous response to first lady Wu Shu-chen's jeer a few
days ago that the rallies would not attract more than "a few
kittens, " Lee Hsin, the deputy speaker of the Taipei city council,
appeared at the rally in a cat costume.
</P>
<P>
In a similar rally in Taichung, Soong vowed to struggle for this
country with his life. In order to show his love for the country, the
former Taiwan governor and his wife also lay down to kiss the ground
at the rally.
</P>
<P>
In Kaohsiung, Legislative Yuan President Wang Jin-pyng, who is
the campaign manager for Lien and Soong, led a similar rally that
brought together more than 500,000 supporters for Lien and Soong.
Many veterans in the rally were so emotional that they broke into
tears.
</P>
<P>
Not surprisingly, many people brought their pet cats along on the
march, thanks again to the first lady's ridicule.
</P>
<P>
Even in Tainan County, which is the hometowm of President Chen
Shui-bian and a bastion of the DPP, some 150,000 people attended a
rally to show their support for Lien and Soong.
</P>
<P>
In Chiayi, some 65 fishing boats gathered off the coast of Putai
to blow horns and let off firecrackers while they yelled "Lien Soong
go, go" on their civil band radios at an at-sea rally.
</P>
<P>
In the remote island county of Penghu, some 10,000 followers of
Lien and Soong gathered at Makung to show their support, a record
high turnout, according to its organizers.
</P>
<P>
In Miaoli, some 30,000 people attended a rally, prompting Miaoli
County Magistrate Fu Hsueh-peng to say that "with 30,000 together,
even the kittens will scare away a tiger."
</P>
<P>
In the frontline county of Lienchiang (Matsu), some 1,000 people
attended a rally, another record high, according to its organizers.
</P>
<P>
One of Lien's campaign workers claimed that the rallies attracted
more than 3 million people altogether.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the DPP also organized campaign activities around the
island. Chen's campaign offices in different places simultaneously
staged a skit in which actors swept the ground with brooms as a
symbol of cleaning up the "black gold" -- referring to corrupt
business tycoons who used to be closely associated with the preceding
KMT administration.
</P>
<P>
However, in Kaohsiung City, a march organized by the DPP to
highlight the importance of voting in the March 20 referendum,
Pingtung County Magistrate Su Chia-chuan and Kaohsiung County
Magistrate Yang Chiu-hsing were warned by police for giving speeches
to marchers without having obtained prior approval.
</P>
<P>
Later, a campaign rally was lined up in Kaohsiung attended by
President Chen, his running mate, Vice President Annette Lu, his wife
and former President Lee Teng-hui, all of whom gave speeches. It drew
some 500,000 followers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040313.0013" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIPEI CAR,  MOTORCYCLE NUMBERS RECORD HIGH IN JANUARY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 13 (CNA)
(By Eric Liu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The total number of vehicles registered in
Taipei City as of the end of January were up to a record high of
1,696,000, according to statistics released Saturday by the
Department of Budget, Accounting and Statistics under the Taipei city
government.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics, 267 cars and 379 motorcycles were
owned per 1,000 head of population. Chungshan, Sungshan and
Chungcheng districts had the most car owners, while Wanhua had the
least. Datong and Wanhua districts, however, had the highest number
of motorcycle owners, with Ta-an district having the fewest.
</P>
<P>
The figures represent an increase of 2.69 percent year-on-year.
Among them were around 700,000 cars and 900,000-odd motorcycles.
On average, each parking lot was used by 1.58 cars and by 4.29
motorbikes.
</P>
<P>
Taipei had 677,000 parking spots as of the end of January, with
444,000 allocated to cars and 232,000 allocated to motorcycles, an
increase of 11.92 percent year-on-year, according to the statistics.
</P>
<P>
Neihu district was listed as having sufficient parking spaces,
while Wanhua, Peitou, Shihlin, and Datong districts were listed as
suffering a parking shortage.
</P>
</TEXT>
