<HEADLINE>
ANTI-SARS PRODUCT IN MASS PRODUCTION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 13 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A product that researchers claim is
effective in fighting severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) has
been put into mass production, a Tamkang University professor
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Adam S.Y. Lee, head of the Department of Chemistry, said that at
present, a chemical compound that is 99 percent pure can be produced
in quantities of 10 kg per week that can be provided to manufacturers
who produce anti-SARS masks and protective garments.
</P>
<P>
Lee noted that the Ministry of Economic Affairs had originally
commissioned the National Taiwan University (NTU) to research the
anti-SARS product, which was jointly developed by the NTU and Tamkang
University last year and has been proved effective in fighting the
atypical pneumonia, which hit Taiwan hard between March and late June
last year.
</P>
<P>
He noted that NTU commissioned Tamkang University to mass produce
the compound and said related technology will be transferred to six
manufacturers, who will produce disinfecting spray, shampoo, hand
soap and other cleaning products.
</P>
<P>
The product can also be dissolved in water and sprayed onto
surgical masks and protective garments, he added.
</P>
<P>
The major component of the "NTU anti-SARS No.1" compound is
8-hydroxy octanoic acid, which kills the virus that causes SARS, Lee
said, adding that tests show that 45 seconds after spraying the
chemical compound, it will destroy the outer membrane of the virus,
leading to the death of the virus. The product is non-toxic to
humans if eaten inadvertently.
</P>
<P>
Lee said that N-95 surgical mask, which is widely believed to be
effective against SARS, loses its effectiveness when wet, but the
"NTU anti-SARS No.1" will be even more effective when wet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040313.0016" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PRESIDENT TO APPEAL FOR SUPPORT FOR MARCH 20 REFERENDUM
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 13 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Former President Lee Teng-hui will appeal
at a forum Sunday for Taiwanese to support the first-ever national
referendum in Taiwan March 20.
</P>
<P>
The forum titled "National Referendum: Taiwan Makes its Voice
Heard, " is being sponsored by the Taiwan Advocates, in which the
former president serves as chairman.
</P>
<P>
The participants will include 496 "elite" from all walks of life
who will voice opposition to "the 496 missiles deployed by mainland
China targeting Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
Lee and several scholars and experts will speak on the legality,
necessity and the urgency of the two questions to be put to the
referendum vote -- whether Taiwan's anti-missile capability should be
strengthened in the face of the missile threat from mainland China,
and whether Taiwan should talk with Beijing over establishing
a peace and stability framework of cross-strait interactions.
</P>
<P>
Amid the controversy about President Chen Shui-bian's plan to
hold the referendum in tandem with the presidential election, Taiwan
Advocates officials said the referendum will be the first time that
Taiwan people use their ballots to express the views and the will of
the people, which will be a milestone in Taiwan's history.
</P>
<P>
"All Taiwan people have the responsibility and obligation to come
forward to cast their votes irrespective of their ethnic group,
gender, age or party affiliation, especially while faced with the 496
missiles targeting Taiwan," the officials said.
</P>
<P>
"All Taiwan people should use their right and obligation to make
their voices heard to China and the world," they added.
</P>
<P>
The forum, which will have its main venue in Taipei, will be
linked live with eight other places in Kaohsiung City, Kaohsiung
County, Pingtung City, Tainan City, Chiayi City, Hsinchu City and
Taitung City via teleconference.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that through the hookup, the number of people
taking part in the forum will set a record for participants at a
single conference in Taiwan.
</P>
