<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS OPEN INVESTIGATION INTO 1,500 VOTE-BUYING COMPLAINTS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 13 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Prosecutors have opened investigations
into 1,579 complaints of vote-buying in the run-up to the
presidential election, which is almost four times more than the 432
investigations in the 2000 presidential election, according to
statistics released Saturday by the State Public Prosecutor General's
Office under the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
Although the number of investigations into vote-fixing complaints
has increased sharply, no one has been indicted thus far. Instead, 38
of the cases were closed due to a lack of evidence and two others
were ruled by prosecutors as "no indictment should be filed."
</P>
<P>
Most of the complaints concern allegations of the distribution of
free gifts, free dinner parties and free trips offered in return for
promises of support.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there have been 19 investigations into complaints
about violence in the election, two of which have ended with
indictments and one of which was thrown out due to lack of evidence.
</P>
