<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040313.0022" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
CEC URGED TO RECONSIDER  DECISION ON MISCAST BALLOTS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 13 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Legislative Yuan President Wang Jin-pyng
joined a chorus Saturday urging the Central Election Commission (CEC)
to reconsider its decision that presidential ballots cast in the
wrong boxes will be counted as valid votes.
</P>
<P>
One day after the ruling Democratic Progressive Party caucus at
the Legislative Yuan asked the CEC to reverse its decision about
miscast votes, the parliament speaker said the CEC seems to be
contradicting itself by considering miscasting illegal, yet in the
same breath counting these misplaced ballots as valid.
</P>
<P>
The CEC decided Thursday to announce the outcome of the
presidential election in two steps. The first announcement will be
made when the boxes intended for the presidential election have been
counted, but the final results will not be announced until the boxes
for referendum ballots have been tallied and ballots for the election
placed in those boxes picked out and added to the tally of the
election.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the two-step announcement will be troublesome because
the longer the wait before the final results are announced, the more
anxious the public will become, and it might even lead to riots if
the winner in the first announcement loses in the second
announcement.
</P>
<P>
Even the Executive Yuan, which insisted that any misplaced
ballots be counted backed down Friday after security officials
expressed concern that the longer the interval between the first
announcement and the second announcement, the more difficult it will
be to maintain order.
</P>
<P>
Premier Yu Shyi-kun said he will respect the CEC's decision.
</P>
<P>
The CEC is expected to meet again Monday to address the DPP
Legislative Caucus concerns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040313.0023" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 13 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Saturday, March 13, or the 23th
day of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according to the
lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that have
occurred on this date in the past:

1733: Dr. Joseph Priestley, the British chemist noted for his
work on the isolation of gases and his discovery of oxygen in 1774,
is born.

1781: William Herschel, a German-born British organist and
amateur stargazer, discovers the planet Georgium Sidus, later renamed
Uranus. Sir Herschel later became astronomer to George III and
catalogued more than 800 double stars and 2,500 nebulae.

1855: Percival Lowell, the American astronomer whose detection of
irregularities in the orbit of Uranus led to the discovery of Pluto,
is born. The astronomer also founded the Lowell Observatory in
Arizona, where his studies of Mars led him to believe that the planet
was inhabited.

1881: Alexander II, the Tsar of Russia who emancipated the serfs
in 1861, is killed by bombs thrown at him by extremists in St.
Petersburg on the very day he had finally agreed to implement
democratic reforms.

1900: Giorgos Seferiadis, Greek poet and diplomat, is born. He
won the 1963 Nobel Prize for literature.

1901: Benjamin Harrison, the 23rd U.S. president during whose
administration the first Pan American Conference took place, dies at
the age of 68.

1930: Pluto, the planet farthest from the sun, is discovered.

1942: British bombers stage a saturation raid on the German city
of Cologne.

1946: Republic of China government forces enter Shenyang (Mukden)
following the evacuation of Soviet troops.

1959: Some 300,000 Tibetans revolt against the Communist Chinese
regime.

1961: Pablo Picasso, Spanish artist and one of the most prolific
and influential artists of the 20th century, marries his 37-year-old
model, Jacqueline Rocque, in Nice, France at the age of 79.

1967: Peasant rioting is reported in mainland China.

1967: Indira Gandhi is sworn in as the first woman prime minister
of India.

1969: The Executive Yuan of the ROC decides to construct an
international airport in Taoyuan County by enlarging an existing air
force base.

1972: Britain closes its consulate general in Taipei after
agreeing to exchange ambassadors with the regime in Beijing.

1974: The Charles de Gaulle Airport in Paris is opened.

1978: Moluccan terrorists hold 72 people hostage in government
buildings in Essen, Holland, demanding the release of comrades in
Dutch jails. The hostages were rescued by the police the next day.

1979: The European Monetary System is officially inaugurated.

1990: The parliament of the Soviet Union votes to end the
political monopoly of the Soviet Communist Party after 72 years, to
allow for private ownership of factories and for a strong presidency.

1992: A strong earthquake rocks eastern Turkey, killing some
4,000 people.

1992: Mauritius, an island located in the Indian Ocean, becomes a
republic, dropping its links with the British crown 24 years after
proclaiming its independence.

1998: President Kim Dae Jung grants amnesty to some five million
South Korean prisoners, including political prisoners and those
convicted on drunk driving charges.

2000: Taipei Mayor Ma Ying-jeou presents the keys to the city to
his Panamanian counterpart, Juan Carlos Navarro.

2000: Academia Sinica President Yuan T. Lee says that he will
resign in order to accept Democratic Progressive Party presidential
candidate Chen Shui-bian's invitation to head his national advisory
group.

2001: Opposition People First Party Chairman James Soong says
that he is extremely disappointed by what he described as the
Democratic Progressive Party-ruled government's "fast and rampant
corruption."

Confucius' lesson of the day: "A man who can resist the
long-continued attempts of others to insinuate prejudice into him, or
one who cannot be influenced by a sudden appeal to his own personal
safety -- such a man may be considered a man of perspicuity. Indeed,
a man who can resist such an influence, or such an appeal, must
really be a superior man."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040314.0001" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN TO SEEK RESUMPTION OF FOWL EXPORTS THROUGH WTO MECHANISM
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Geneva,  March 13 (CNA)
(By Neil Lu and P.C. Tang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan will use its power as a member of
the World Trade Organization (WTO) to call for counties that have
disallowed the import of fowl from Taiwan to rescind the ban, an
unnamed source said in Geneva Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Many countries have adopted measures to ban fowl imports from
Canada and the United States due to last December's outbreaks of
avian flu in these two countries. Taiwan also on the no-import list
despite the fact that Taiwan has only witnessed a few cases of
low-risk pathogenic H5N1 bird flu virus infection among its fowl.
</P>
<P>
Health experts have said that according to standards of both the
WTO and the World Animal Health Organization (OIE) , Taiwan's fowl
exports should not be affected by outbreaks of H5N2 avian flu virus
in other countries, adding that banning the importation of Taiwan's
fowl is unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting scheduled to be held by Taiwan's permanent mission
to the WTO March 15, senior officials from Taiwan's health and
agriculture authorities are expected to brief delegates from nine WTO
members -- Japan, Hong Kong, South Korea, Saudi Arabia, Singapore,
the Philippines, Indonesia, Thailand and Malaysia -- on the efforts
that the island has made in its fight against bird flu and to seek
their support for removal of the ban on Taiwan's fowl exports.
</P>
<P>
The officials will also emphasize during the gathering that
Taiwan has always been transparent in its efforts of disease
prevention and honest in informing the WHO and OIE of its situations
regarding epidemics, the source said.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that the WTO's Committee on Sanitary and
Phytosanitary Measures will hold a two-day meeting March 17-18, the
source said that by using the WTO multilateral mechanism, Taiwan will
take this opportunity to directly urge those countries that have
banned the island's fowl imports to remove the restriction.
</P>
<P>
An official from Taiwan's trade mission in Geneva said that the
government will do its utmost to protect Taiwan farmers and related
sectors although he does not know whether the March 15 meeting will
immediately help Taiwan resume its fowl exports or not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040314.0002" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT CHEN VOWS TO PUSH FOR NEW CONSTITUTION IF RE-ELECTED
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Kaohsiung,  March 14 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian said Sunday
that if he is re-elected, he will push for a new constitution to
better substantiate the fact that Taiwan is a genuine democracy and
that the people are the real leaders of the country when it comes to
enacting the nation's fundamental laws.
</P>
<P>
Calling the existing Republic of China Constitution "ambiguous
both on national identification and governmental structure, " Chen
said it is absolutely imperative that a new constitution be enacted
for Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
He added that if he is re-elected, he will see to it that the new
constitution is affirmed by the people of Taiwan in another
referendum held in 2006, paving the way for the implementation of the
new constitution beginning in 2008.
</P>
<P>
Chen made the remarks during his keynote speech to the joint
meeting of the World Taiwanese Congress (WTC) and the World
Federation of Taiwanese Associations (WFTA), which opened in Taiwan's
southern port city of Kaohsiung Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Chen said he is encouraged to see that Taiwan's first-ever
nationwide referendum will allow the people to voice their feelings
about mainland China's missile threat and whether to seek a framework
to build better cross-Taiwan Strait interactions to ensure peace.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's historic referendum, to be held on the March 20
presidential election day, is the best gift that he has given the
people of Taiwan this year, the president said.
</P>
<P>
Chen offered his heartfelt appreciation to the nearly 1,000 WTC
and WFTA representatives who have traveled from around the world to
Kaohsiung to take part in the annual meeting, and he thanked them for
their support of himself and his vice president, Annette Lu.
</P>
<P>
In a teleconferenced WTC-WFTA meeting in 2002, Chen recalled, he
said that Taiwan and mainland China are "countries on either side of
the Taiwan Strait, " based on the fact that Taiwan is a sovereign
state and is not a part of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
Chen said he advocated the "one side, one country" concept to
firmly express his opposition to Beijing's "one-China" policy and the
"one country, two systems" model that mainland China used to take
over Hong Kong and Macau several years ago.
</P>
<P>
"Any move that is aimed at changing Taiwan's status quo should be
first approved by the 23 million people of Taiwan via a referendum, "
Chen argued.
</P>
<P>
Chen told his audience that the government decided to push for
Taiwan's first-ever nationwide referendum after serious
considerations on its importance and necessity.
</P>
<P>
Defying Beijing's suppression, he said, the government is
determined in carrying out the referendum, adding that, "The harder
Beijing's pressure, the firmer is our determination."
</P>
<P>
Chen said that participation in a referendum is a basic human
right and a demonstration of populist values, adding that the
government is advocating the upcoming referendum in the belief that
the people are in charge and that the government should trust the
people.
</P>
<P>
Noting that 165 countries in the world have held 1,523
referendums to allow their people to express their feelings on major
issues, Chen asked why there has not been a single referendum yet in
Taiwan, a sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
Facing the PRC's mounting military threat, including 496
ballistic missiles targeting Taiwan and Beijing's refusal to renounce
the use of force to solve cross-strait disputes, Taiwan should have
the right to free itself from terror and voice its disdain of
mainland China's missiles and other forms of intimidation, Chen
stressed.
</P>
<P>
If he is re-elected, Chen went on, he will also be instrumental
in safeguarding Taiwan's economic sovereignty in the international
community and facilitate Taiwan's participation in global activities,
including membership in the World Health Organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040314.0003" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
OVERSEAS VOTES COULD BE CRUCIAL IN PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION OUTCOME
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  14 (CNA)
(By P.C. Tang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Overseas Chinese eligible to vote in
Taiwan's March 20 presidential election could be crucial in tipping
the scale in favor of one candidate given the closeness of the race,
several politicians said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to Taipei County Magistrate Su Tseng-chang, who is also
the secretary-general of the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP)
campaign headquarters, the winner of the election could be decided by
as little as 3 percentage points and, therefore, votes from abroad
could be key.
</P>
<P>
Sun Kauo-hwa, an overseas Chinese-elected legislator from the
opposition Kuomintang (KMT) , also said that for overseas supporters
of both sides, the upcoming election could be seen as a battle to
defend the Republic of China or to establish a new nation of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics released by the Overseas Chinese Affairs
Commission show that 9,020 qualified persons, who are expected to
return from abroad, have registered to vote in the upcoming election.
</P>
<P>
In the 2000 presidential election, only 2,800 eligible overseas
Chinese registered to vote.
</P>
<P>
Many leaders from both political camps - the "pan-blue alliance"
of Lien Chan of the KMT and James Soong of the People First Party,
and incumbent President Chen Shui-bian -- have visited overseas
Chinese and Taiwanese communities in various countries to encourage
those who are qualified to return to Taiwan to vote.
</P>
<P>
Claiming that nearly 20,000 overseas Chinese and Taiwanese will
eventually come back to support the "pan-blue alliance, " Sun said
that at least 10,000 of them will attend a rally March 17 at the Sun
Yat-sen Memorial Hall in Taipei.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, DPP Legislator Chang Shiow-jen claimed that about
50,000 overseas Chinese and Taiwanese will support President Chen and
Vice President Annette Lu in their quest for re-election. She added
that members of the World Taiwanese Association are expected to join
a two-day activity held in Kaohsiung March 13-14 to express their
support for the DPP candidates.
</P>
<P>
A DPP official responsible for overseas affairs estimated that at
least 25,000 supporters of President Chen from abroad will return to
vote.
</P>
<P>
Because of the diametrically opposed ideologies of the two
candidates, and given the possible differing consequences of either
winning, Sun said that it is likely that more people will return to
Taiwan to vote than in the past.
</P>
</TEXT>
