<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040314.0010" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
CROSS-STRAIT TIES BECOME FOCUS OF REFERENDUM DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 14 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cross-Taiwan Strait relations became the
focus of the final round of 10 referendum debates Sunday, which
pitted the nation's top mainland policy planner against a
sharp-tongued independent lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
In the 70-minute live TV debate on whether Taiwan should
negotiate a viable mechanism with Beijing for peaceful interaction,
Mainland Affairs Council Chairwoman Tsai Ing-wen said cross-strait
relations are dynamic and need a viable mechanism for long-term
engagements to forge trust and avoid misunderstanding and
misjudgment.
</P>
<P>
"What we want to negotiate is an agreement on the
establishment of a viable interactive mechanism to handle dynamic
cross-strait relations, not to negotiate an ultimate solution to our
political dispute," Tsai explained.
</P>
<P>
In her view, Tsai said, cross-strait issue is not an issue
regarding independence or unification. "It's an issue regarding the
definition of relationship between two sovereign entities," she
explained.
</P>
<P>
Under mainland China's pressure, Tsai said Taiwan has spent much
more time than other countries on enacting a referendum law. "Now
that we have a referendum act to allowing for the holding of our
first-ever nationwide referendum, we should treasure it."
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that a referendum result favoring dialogue would
bolster Taiwan's position in any talks with Beijing, since it would
show that the Taipei government is backed by the public.
</P>
<P>
"History has told us that the smaller party in negotiations needs
the support of all the people to turn things to their advantage,"
Tsai said. "With people's support, the Chinese Communists would have
no opportunity to force us to unify and our government will have more
confidence in negotiations," she added.
</P>
<P>
However, Legislator Sisy Chen, who is also a flamboyant TV
political talk-show host, argued against the unprecedented
referendum.
</P>
<P>
Sisy Chen claimed that President Chen Shui-bian broke the law when
he called for the referendum, to be held March 20 alongside the
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
She argued that the president can only legally call such a
referendum when the island's sovereignty faces an imminent threat
from a foreign force. She said there is no immediate danger from
mainland China that makes Saturday's vote necessary.
</P>
<P>
Sisy Chen also disagreed with President Chen's view that the
referendum would help encourage Beijing to begin negotiations
with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
"If the two sides can just sip tea and chat, then they would
have held hundreds of rounds of talks already," said Sisy Chen, who
was once the spokeswoman for the president's Democratic
Progressive Party, but has become one of its sharpest critics.
</P>
<P>
She said that before talks can happen, Taiwan must find a way to
meet Beijing's demand that Taiwan accept its "one China" policy.
The president has refused to agree to this.
</P>
<P>
In her view, Sisy Chen said cross-strait issues are too
complicated to be resolved through a referendum. "Cross-strait
dispute will continue raging no matter whether we cast or not
cast our ballots in this referendum," she claimed, adding that
she hopes local voters will not take part in this referendum.
The referendum will ask voters two questions whether Taiwan needs
to beef up its anti-missile defenses if China refuses to remove
hundreds of missiles pointing at the island and whether Taiwan
should seek talks with Beijing to set up a "peace and stability
framework."
</P>
<P>
The Tsai-Chen debate was the final round of a series of 10
such events required by the newly passed Referendum Act.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040314.0011" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
MISCAST BALLOTS NOT TO BE COUNTED: CEC
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 14 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After many twists and turns, the Central
Election Commission (CEC) finally decided Sunday that miscast ballots
in the March 20 presidential election and referendum will be
considered invalid.
</P>
<P>
CEC Chairman Huang Shih-cheng made the announcement after all
CEC commissioners discussed the validity issue for three hours at an
extraordinary session.
</P>
<P>
"We have come to a conclusion that presidential election ballots
cast into the boxes provided for the referendum will not be counted
and vice versa," Huang said, adding that the decision was made in
line with the "expectations of major domestic political parties and
mainstream public opinion."
</P>
<P>
Huang's announcement marked the CEC's yet another policy
about-face in handling the upcoming presidential election and
referendum.
</P>
<P>
Just last Thursday, Huang said miscast election and referendum
ballots should be counted as valid. As a result, he said, the outcome
of the presidential election would have to be announced twice. The
first announcement would be made when all ballots in the boxes for
presidential election were tallied and the second would be made when
the boxes for referendum ballots were counted, in case any
presidential votes were found to have been cast in the referendum
boxes.
</P>
<P>
The decision came under fire from the opposition camp on the
ground that since the act of mistakenly casting presidential election
ballots into the referendum ballot boxes is illegal, such miscast
ballots should not be regarded as valid.
</P>
<P>
Under strong pressure, the CEC called a provisional meeting
Sunday to review its previous decision. After a heated debate
among CEC commissioners, the CEC finally decided to invalidate all
miscast ballots to avoid any controversy.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet spokesman Lin Chia-lung said the Cabinet respects the
CEC's final decision and hopes that the commission will not to make
any change again.
</P>
<P>
"Now that the CEC has made a decision, all election
administrators will abide by all CEC rules to ensure a smooth
proceeding of the presidential election and our first-ever
nationwide referendum," Lin said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the opposition camp to give the CEC more freedom in
handling election- and referendum-related administrative affairs.
</P>
<P>
Besides ridiculing the upcoming referendum as "illegal and
absurd," the opposition camp has also claimed that the CEC might
rig the election results or that the outcome might cause a
post-election rioting.
</P>
<P>
"Such ill-motivated allegations have undermined election
workers' morale and reputation. We hope opponents can stop their
boycott against the referendum now that the CEC has responded to
their opinion regarding vote counting," Lin said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, legislative caucuses of all major political parties
hailed the CEC's latest decision, saying that the new decision will
help speed up vote counting on the election day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040314.0012" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
REFERENDUM DEBATE PITS LAWMAKER AGAINST MEDIA PERSONALITY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 14 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The final round of debates on the upcoming
referendum on whether Taiwan should beef up its anti-missile muscle
in the face of Beijing's intensified military threat was held Sunday,
with a ruling party lawmaker facing off against a prominent media
figure.
</P>
<P>
In the 70-minute televised debate, Legislator Kuo Cheng-liang of
the ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) defended President Chen
Shui-bian's decision to hold Taiwan's first-ever nationwide
referendum alongside the March 20 presidential election, while UFO
Network Broadcasting Co. Chairman Jaw Shau-kong questioned the
legality and constitutionality of the referendum.
</P>
<P>
Kuo said mainland China began to deploy missiles against Taiwan
back in 1995, long before Taiwan's first-ever transition of power
between different political parties in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Worse still, Kuo said Beijing has become ever-more inflexible in
its attitude toward Taiwan. "In the past, Beijing said it would
attack Taiwan if the island declared independence. But now, it has
changed its stance, saying that if Taiwan indefinitely drags its feet
on unification, it would use force to have Taiwan come to terms."
</P>
<P>
Against this backdrop, Kuo said, the United States has come up
with a report warning that if Taiwan fails to upgrade its missile
defense system, the military balance in the Taiwan Strait will tilt
in favor of mainland China by 2006.
</P>
<P>
"Should that be the case, mainland China would force Taiwan to
negotiate unification under its terms. In the face of this situation,
we cannot sit idle," Kuo argued.
</P>
<P>
Claiming that President Chen's decision to hold Taiwan's
first-ever nationwide referendum will allow local people to show the
world their aversion to mainland China's missile threat and their
determination to safeguard national security, Kuo said if the
referendum fails due to a boycott from the opposition camp, it would
mark a severe blow to the people of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, Kuo said, the international community
doesn't care about the opposition camp's questioning of the legality
and necessity of the upcoming referendum.
</P>
<P>
"What the world society cares about is the results of the
referendum, " Kuo said, adding that if the referendum fails, it will
deal a serious blow to Taiwan's international image and affect
relations with the United States and mainland China.
</P>
<P>
"If the 'strengthening missile defense' question is voted down,
the international community will look down upon us, the United States
will question our commitment to defend our own national security, and
mainland China will become even more hawkish toward us," Kuo claimed.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that the referendum will help local people better
understand the importance of reinforcing Taiwan's defense
capabilities, Kuo urged local voters to cast ballots in the
referendum to have their voice heard in the international community.
</P>
<P>
However, Jaw, a former lawmaker who also once served as
environmental chief, said the upcoming referendum was a joke and a
ploy to boost President Chen's re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
Jaw said the opposition camp has never opposed procurement of
anti-missile batteries. "Such an issue doesn't need a referendum. We
should respect professionalism in dealing with defense issues.
Whether we should buy more anti-missile batteries should be left to
the Ministry of National Defense to decide."
</P>
<P>
He further said holding a referendum alone can never help
strengthen Taiwan's national defense. "The most important thing at
the moment is to revitalize our economy. If we enjoy an economic
boom, we'll have more budget to renovate our arsenal. Our defense
budget has declined steadily in the past few years mainly
because of the DPP administration's inexperience and
incompetence in managing our economy," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
Jaw also blamed the DPP administration for its pro-independence
stance, claiming that the DPP administration's emphasis on Taiwan's
national identity has strained relations with mainland China and
confused the nation's military service members. "Our troops have
become very confused about our nation's cause," he argued.
</P>
<P>
Before ending his debate, Jaw urged voters to boycott what he
called the "illegal" March 20 referendum.
</P>
<P>
According to Taiwan's Referendum Act, a nationwide referendum
will be considered valid only if more than half of eligible voters
vote in the referendum.
</P>
<P>
Estimates indicate that at least 8.2 million voters must turn out
to vote to make the upcoming referendum valid. Observers say the
target will be difficult given that the opposition parties have
traditionally enjoyed an edge in Taiwan's divided political map.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040314.0013" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS FROM RIVAL CAMPS SAY MISCAST BALLOTS SHOULD BE INVALID
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 14 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Several legislators from both the ruling
"pan-green" camp and the opposition "pan-blue alliance" expressed the
hope Sunday that presidential ballots cast in boxes designated for
referendum votes will be considered invalid.
</P>
<P>
More legislators joined a chorus Sunday urging the Central
Election Commission (CEC) to make its final decision on miscast votes
as quickly as possible given that the presidential election and that
of the referendum is less than a week way. The two votes will be held
Saturday, March 20.
</P>
<P>
The CEC's most recent ruling was to allow presidential ballots
cast incorrectly in referendum ballot boxes to be counted as valid,
although technically, according to the Referendum Law, anything put
into referendum ballot boxes except authorized ballots for the
referendum should be thrown out.
</P>
<P>
Legislative Yuan President Wang Jin-pyng said Saturday that the
CEC seems to be contradicting itself by considering miscasting
illegal, yet in the same breath counting the misplaced ballots as
valid.
</P>
<P>
The CEC decided Thursday to announce the outcome of the
presidential election in two steps. The first announcement will be
made when the boxes intended for the presidential election have been
counted, but the final results will not be announced until stray
ballots that were erroneously put in referendum boxes have been added
to the total.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the two-step announcement could spell trouble since the
longer the public has to wait for the final results, the more anxious
they will become. This, he said, could even lead to rioting if the
winner in the first announcement turns out to be the loser in the
second announcement.
</P>
<P>
Even the Executive Yuan, which insisted that any misplaced
ballots be counted, backed down Friday after security officials
expressed concerns that the interval between the first announcement
and the second announcement, could have an adverse effect on civil
order.
</P>
<P>
In view of the twists and turns over the past several days on the
issue of miscast votes, opposition People First Party (PFP)
Legislator Hsu Yuan-kuo, a PFP deputy whip at the Legislative Yuan,
said the CEC decision to considering miscasting illegal but counting
these misplaced ballots as valid is illogical and self-contradictory.
</P>
<P>
Such a decision benefits nothing and nobody except causing
greater suspicion for voters, Hsu added.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Kuomintang Legislator Cho Po-yuan said that according
to the Referendum Law, anything aside referendum ballots that are put
into the referendum ballot boxes is illegal and the voter could be
fined. It is ridiculous that illegal ballots could be counted as
valid votes, Cho added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Legislator Chiang Chao-yi from the ruling DPP advised
his party Sunday to respect the CEC's new decision if it changes its
previous decision and announces finally that miscast ballots are
invalid.
</P>
<P>
Chiang said that considering miscast ballots invalid will not
only contribute to reducing the opposition camp's bombardment, it
will also contribute to lowering the risks that might occur in
postponed announcements of the outcome of the presidential election
and referendum questions.
</P>
<P>
Wu Nai-jen, the campaign manager for President Chen Shui-bian,
said what ever the CEC decision is, it should be releases quickly to
"prevent the elections from being undermined by trivial technical
problems."
</P>
<P>
Wu blamed the opposition "pan-blue alliance" for constantly
interfering with electoral affairs, thus making it difficult for the
CEC to make wise and clear decisions.
</P>
<P>
The CEC met again Sunday to address concerns surrounding the
miscast ballot issue. It is expected to make an announcement later in
the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040314.0014" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
RECONCILIATION WILL ENABLE GREAT DEVELOPMENT FOR TAIWAN: SOONG
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 14 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Reconciliation" will be the keynote of
the opposition "pan-blue alliance" in its final campaign efforts to
win the 2004 presidential election, which is six days away, the
alliace's vice presidential candidate said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
James Soong, chairman of the opposition People First Party and
running mate of opposition Kuomintang (KMT) Chairman Lien Chan, said
the "pan-blue alliance" will borrow the essence of "reconciliation"
as a tool to push for "great development" and "great reforms" in
Taiwan if the Lien-Soong ticket is elected.
</P>
<P>
It is the ultimate belief of the "pan-blue alliance" that only
striving to revive the domestic economy and seeking cross-Taiwan
Strait peace will the people of Taiwan be benefited, Soong said.
</P>
<P>
"If the economy continues to be bogged down, Taiwan will have no
future, and if there is no peace in the Taiwan Strait, the island's
economy will be doomed," Soong added.
</P>
<P>
Soong said he and Lien were touched by the overwhelming support
shown to them by alliance supporters around the country Saturday by
joining huge rallies in 25 counties and cities to support the notion
of "changing the president to save Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
Soong said he still believes that President Chen Shui-bian had a
golden opportunity to lead the country to a much better situation
after he was newly inaugurated as president back in 2000, when many
supported the president's promise to institute reforms.
</P>
<P>
To the people's chagrin, Soong said, President Chen has
disappointed the voters first by failing to deliver on his reform
promises and flex the government's administrative muscle over the
past several years, and then by causing nationwide confusion by
pushing for a referendum alongside the presidential election and
failing to give satisfactory explanations to doubts about the
abilities of some of Chen's administration officials and the first
lady's alleged massive trading in the stock market in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Chen's failure in various areas over the past four years has
become an edge for the Lien-Soong ticket, Soong said, adding that
huge numbers of alliance supporters who covet political stability for
Taiwan and peace across the Taiwan Strait will turn out to vote for
Lien and Soong giving them an overwhelming victory.
</P>
