<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040314.0016" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 14 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Sunday, March 14, or the 24th
day of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according to
the lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that have
occurred on this date in the past:

1492: Queen Isabella of Castile orders the 150,000 Jews in Spain
to accept Christian baptism or face immediate expulsion.

1793: Eli Whitney, American inventor and manufacturer, patents
his cotton gin, revolutionizing the cotton industry. He also
established the first factory to assemble muskets with
interchangeable parts, marking the advent of modern mass production.

1820: Victor Emmanuel II, the first king of a united Italy, is
born.

1879: Albert Einstein, the German-born American theoretical
physicist who won a 1921 Nobel Prize for his explanation of the
photoelectric effect, is born. His special and general theories of
relativity revolutionized modern thought on the nature of space and
time and formed a theoretical basis for the exploitation of atomic
energy.

1883: Karl Marx, German philosopher, economist and revolutionary
who, with the support of Friedrich Engels, wrote "the Communist
Manifesto" and "Das Kapital," dies in London at the age of 65.

1900: President McKinley puts the United States on the Gold
Standard.

1917: The Republic of China severs diplomatic relations with
Germany after the U.S. government severed its ties with Germany in
February 1917 and pressed China to do the same.

1932: The League of Nations' Lytton Commission arrives in China
to investigate the Shenyang (Mukden) Incident.

1932: George Eastman, the American inventor and industrialist who
invented a dry-plate process of photographic film development, as
well as flexible film, the Kodak camera and a process for color
photography, commits suicide at the age of 78.

1934: A train explosion in El Salvador claims 200 lives and
injures some 1,000 people.

1947: The newly independent Republic of the Philippines leases
its military bases to the United States for 99 years under a military
cooperation agreement.

1953: The butterfly orchid produced in Taiwan wins first prize in
a contest at the international flower exhibition held in California.

1953: Nikita Krushchev becomes first secretary of the Soviet
Communist Party, replacing Georgi Malenkov.

1954: The ROC Ministry of the Interior formally names the Atayal,
Saisiyat, Bunun, Tsou, Paiwan, Rukai, Puyuma, Ami and Yami as the
nine major indigenous tribes of Taiwan Province.

1962: Foreign Minister Shen Chang-huan declares that the ROC does
not recognize Japan's so-called "residual sovereignty" over the
Ryukyu Islands.

1964: Dallas nightclub owner Jack Ruby is found guilty of killing
Lee Harvey Oswald, the presumed murderer of U.S. President John F.
Kennedy.

1979: A Trident aircraft crashes into a factory outside Beijing,
mainland China, killing more than 200 people.

1987: More than 12 people are killed in the Philippines in an
escalating communist insurgency.

1988: Warships of mainland China and Vietnam exchange fire near
the Nansha (Spratly) Islands.

1991: The Executive Yuan passes the Guidelines for National
Unification, which become the highest directives governing the ROC's
mainland policy. The long-term goal of the guidelines is to establish
a democratic, free and equitably prosperous China.

1996: A committee in the U.S. Congress approves a resolution
urging the United States to defend Taiwan. But Clinton administration
officials say they have received assurances from Beijing that it has
no plans to invade.

1996: Wang Luo-pin, noted mainland Chinese folk-song composer,
dies of illness in Urumqi, capital of Xinjiang Province, at the age
of 83.

2000: In an open statement, Soong Mayling, the widow of late
President Chiang Kai-shek, endorses the ruling Kuomintang's
presidential candidate Lien Chan.

2001: Honduran President Carlos Flores decorates ROC Defense
Minister Wu Shih-wen in recognition of his contributions to the
promotion of friendship and military cooperation between the two
countries.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "Without the confidence of the
people in their rulers, there can be no government."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
