<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN-JAPAN COOPERATION SHOULD BE INCREASED UNDER WTO FRAMEWORK
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 15 (CNA)
(By Eric Liu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bilateral trade and economic cooperation
between Taiwan and Japan should be increased under the framework of
the World Trade Organization (WTO) , a government official said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar on Taiwan-Japan economic cooperation and
trade, Shen Chien-i, director of multilateral trade affairs under the
Bureau of Foreign Trade (BOFT) , said that the WTO offers a platform
for normal economic exchanges between Taiwan and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The two countries should increase official exchanges in the
economic field under the WTO framework to offset the losses caused by
the absence of diplomatic ties between them, Shen suggested.
</P>
<P>
Japan is Taiwan's second-largest trade partner and its largest
source of imports, while Taiwan is Japan's fourth-largest trade
partner, he noted.
</P>
<P>
However, he went on, the two countries lack channels for official
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's economic and trade environment is more friendly and
transparent after it admitted to the WTO in 2002, Shen said, adding
that it is time for Japan's trade sector to capitalize on this.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was co-sponsored Monday by the BOFT under the
Ministry of Economic Affairs, the Taipei office of Japan's
Interchange Association and the Association of East Asian Relations,
and was aimed at closer communication and cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
