<HEADLINE>
NUMBER OF STUDENT SUBSIDIES FOR OVERSEAS STUDIES TO BE INCREASED
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 15 (CNA)
(By Huang Kwang-chun)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The government will increase the number of
subsidies for students and researchers pursuing advanced studies
overseas from the current 235 to 1,000 per year by 2008, Cabinet
officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to a resolution adopted by the board for recruitment
and cultivation of talented technological individuals under the
Executive Yuan, the officials said, the number of student subsidies
for study abroad toward a doctorate will be increased from 85 to 610
a year by 2008, while the number of doctoral research subsidies for
research abroad will be increased from 120 to 310 per year and the
number of subsidies for post-doctorate research abroad will be
increased from 30 to 80.
</P>
<P>
The number of Taiwan students enrolled in prestigious
universities in the United States for advanced studies has decreased
in the last 10 years in contrast with increasing numbers of students
studying in the U.S. from mainland China, South Korea, India and
Singapore, they noted.
</P>
<P>
If this trend continues, the officials added, Taiwan's
competitiveness in technological development will be weakened in the
long-run.
</P>
<P>
The government will offer more incentives to attract students to
pursue advanced studies abroad, including increases in government
subsidies, as a means of cultivating talent, they went on.
</P>
<P>
Under the new program, they said, the government will put an
additional NT$450 million (US$13.4 million) per year in the budget
for technological development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
