<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040315.0009" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
EXPERT SEES FUTURE IN ASIAN-EUROPEAN BIOTECHNOLOGY COOPERATION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 15 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two-way cooperation between Asian and
European biotech companies will create a mutually beneficial
relationship for both sides, Industrial Technology Research Institute
(ITRI) President Johnsee Lee said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Lee, who also serves as chairman of the Taiwan Bio Industry
Organization, made the forecast at a seminar in which he gave a
keynote speech on the advantages of Asia's biotechnological
development and introduced investment and business opportunities and
strategies in the domestic industry to scores of foreign specialists
from around the world.
</P>
<P>
The ITRI chief had just returned to Taiwan from Europe, where he
was invited to take part in the 2004 annual meeting of the BioSquare
held in Basel, Switzerland from March 10-12 in which more than 1,500
representatives participated.
</P>
<P>
Hailing the performance of the European biotech industry as the
most eye-catching in the world, Lee revealed that the ITRI -- one of
Taiwan's leading research organizations -- is promoting cooperation
with research institutes based in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's participation in this year's BioSquare annual conference
-- a unique platform where the managers of biotechnology companies
can meet with key research and business development executives from
the pharmaceutical, nutritional, agricultural, food and finance
industries -- has allowed European businesses to gain an
understanding of Taiwan's industry, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are about 1,100 biotech companies in Europe,
most of which are promising small- and medium-sized businesses, Lee
said, adding that the formation of joint ventures between companies
on the two sides will help forge a "win-win" situation.
</P>
<P>
According to Lee, European biotech companies are particularly
interested in creating cooperative ventures with Taiwan-based firms
specializing in food, agriculture and Chinese herbs.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that the production value of the global
biotechnology grew by 46 percent in 2003 from the previous year's
level, Lee predicted that business prospects for two-way partnership
between Taiwanese and European companies are bright, as both sides
have the potential and enjoy a strong competitive edge to develop the
industry.
</P>
<P>
Lee said he also met with TNO President Hans de Wit during his
trip to Europe for discussions on studies related to Chinese herbs
and opto-electronic displays. He added that de Wit showed a keen
interest in setting up a long-term partnership with the ITRI and to
travel to Taiwan to take part in a series of activities to be
launched by the organizers of a "Taiwan Biotech Month" planned for
July.
</P>
<P>
TNO is one of the top and largest research and technology
organizations in Europe, whose prime mission is to apply scientific
knowledge to businesses and government to strengthen their innovative
capacity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
