<HEADLINE>
DPP URGES SUPPORTERS NOT TO HARASS CONTROVERSIAL BUDDHIST TEMPLE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  15 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The legislative caucus of the ruling
Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) urged party members and supporters
Monday not to harass a controversial Buddhist temple in Nantou
County's Puli township in central Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Tsai Huang-lang, the DPP's legislative whip, made the appeal
after the Chung Tai Temple announced its decision earlier in the day
to close its doors to the public for a month as its leader's
endorsement of the opposition presidential candidate and his stance
against Taiwan's first-ever nationwide referendum to be held
alongside the March 20 presidential poll has sparked protests.
</P>
<P>
Scores of supporters of President Chen Shui-bian gathered at
Chung Tai on Sunday to protest Master Wei Chueh's endorsement last
Thursday of opposition Kuomintang (KMT) Chairman Lien Chan in the
upcoming election and his encouragement to his followers to refuse to
cast ballots in the referendum. Wei Chueh is one of Taiwan's top Zen
masters and has hundreds of thousands of followers.
</P>
<P>
Tsai urged DPP supporters to respect Wei Chueh's freedom of
speech and to stage no further protests at the temple.
</P>
<P>
"We should regard Wei Chueh's expression of his opinions as part
of his freedom of speech," Tsai said. "We respect his decision. We do
not want to see our supporters demonstrate against the temple any
more, as such actions only hurt the DPP's image."
</P>
<P>
The Zen master's endorsement of the opposition presidential
challenger and his anti-referendum stance has sparked a heated debate
about whether religion should be mixed with politics. A popular
Buddhist nun -- Dharma Master Shih Chao Huei -- criticized Wei Chueh
for getting involved in the election and accused him of failing to
abide by the law in reporting the temple's financial status.
</P>
<P>
Buddhism is Taiwan's most popular religion, with more than 9,860
clergy and 5.48 million followers, according to government
statistics.
</P>
