<HEADLINE>
FLIGHTS ADDED TO BRING TAIWAN BUSINESSMEN BACK FOR ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 15 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a bid to tackle the large number of
Taiwan businessmen wishing to return from mainland China to vote in
the March 20 presidential election, airlines flying between Taiwan,
Hong Kong and Macau have decided to add flights to meet the demand,
spokesmen for the various aviation companies said Monday.
</P>
<P>
With only five days left before polling day, various airlines
have made the decision to cope with the extra passengers, they said.
</P>
<P>
China Airlines (CAL) will add three flights on its Hong
Kong-Taipei route March 19, while EVA Airways Corp. will add four and
five flights to its Hong Kong-Taipei and Macau-Taipei flights,
respectively, on the same day. CAL and EVA Airways are Taiwan's two
largest carriers.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Taipei-based Trans Asia Airways has decided to
resume its previous level of five flights per day on its Taipei-Macau
route, up from the present three-flights-daily service in the run-up
to the election.
</P>
<P>
UNI Airways. Corp. -- an affiliate of EVA Airways that offers 14
flights per day from the offshore island of Kinmen to Taipei,
Taichung, Tainan, Chiayi and Kaohsiung -- announced that flights will
be added on these routes to help Taiwan businessmen return via the
"mini links" -- direct transport and trade services maintained
between the Kinmen and Matsu islands and the ports of Xiamen and
Fuzhou in mainland China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hong Kong-based Dragon Airlines will add one flight to
its regular daily flight service between Hong Kong and Taipei on
March 17, 18 and 19.
</P>
<P>
It has been estimated that up to 120,000 Taiwan businessmen
operating on the mainland will return to Taiwan to cast their ballots
in the presidential poll.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
