ALTERNATIVE SERVICE CONSCRIPTS DOING WELL OVERSEAS: FOREIGN MINISTER
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 15 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Taiwan conscripts serving alternative
military service overseas are performing well and have helped win
great respect and recognition in the international community,
Minister of Foreign Affairs Eugene Chien said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chien made the remarks during a meeting at the Foreign Ministry
with 15 conscripts who recently returned home after having completed
their alternative military service of more than one year abroad
serving mainly as assistants to Taiwan's agricultural, technical and
medical care missions dispatched by the Republic of China government
to friendly countries.
</P>
<P>
In addition to exchanging opinions and viewpoints on working
overseas, Chien also thanked them for their hard work and efforts in
their host countries and lauded their outstanding performances for
having gained a thumbs-up from local people, governments and ROC
outposts there.
</P>
<P>
"This encouraging result will push more young Taiwan men with
tertiary education to join the alternative military service program,
which in turn will win more international friendship and recognition
for the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chen Hen-tai, an alternative military conscript who served as an
aide in a medical mission based in Malawi, said that he learned about
very different lifestyles and values while performing his service in
a foreign country. "That will be a very valuable and treasured
experience in our lives because we have learned tolerance and love, "
he added.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan started to promote the alternative service program in
2001, and a total of 112 conscripts have been sent to serve in more
than 20 countries in Africa, Central and South America, the Caribbean
and the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040315.0020" type="story" >
