<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040315.0022" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL SEMINAR ON ISLAM OPENS IN TAIPEI
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 15 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Local Muslims have contributed to Taiwan's
cultural diversity, Minister of Foreign Affairs Eugene Chien said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening of an international seminar on Islam,
Chien said Muslims have enjoyed exactly the same rights and
obligations as other Taiwan citizens and that many outstanding Muslim
nationals have contributed to Taiwan's development in various fields
over the years.
</P>
<P>
"Muslims have been an integral part of Taiwan's diverse culture,"
Chien said, adding that communications and understanding are the most
effective way to promote ethnic and religious harmony and avoid
misunderstandings, suspicion and conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Islam seminar was co-sponsored by the World Muslim League
(WML) and National Chengchi University in suburban Taipei. The World
Muslim League, headquartered in Mecca, Saudi Arabia, was founded in
1962 to promote Islam, humanitarian aid and cooperation among Islamic
countries and organizations. It is one of the most influential
non-governmental organizations in the Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that the WML has organized an
international seminar on Islam in Taiwan. Chien said he is glad to
see many Islamic experts from around the world travel to Taipei to
attend the two-day seminar.
</P>
<P>
Chien said the history of Islam in Taiwan dates to the mid-17th
century when a group of Muslims immigrated to Taiwan from the Chinese
mainland together with Koxinga or Cheng Cheng-kung (1624-1662), the
leader of an anti-Manchu resistance movement after the fall of the
Ming dynasty in mainland China who ousted the Dutch from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning, Chien said, Muslims were concentrated in
Tamsui, Tainan, Lukang, Yunlin and Ilan. At present, Taiwan has about
50,000 Muslim citizens.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Chien said, about 50,000 Muslims from Islamic
countries are working in Taiwan. Taiwan now has six mosques that
sponsor many Islamic religious activities and festivities each year,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan Muslims organize a delegation to embark on an annual
pilgrimage to Mecca and serve as Taiwan's goodwill ambassadors to the
Islamic world, he said. In the past two years, President Chen
Shui-bian has met with the delegation members upon their return to
express his support for Islamic cultural development.
</P>
<P>
President Chen, who is busy with his re-election campaign, issued
a congratulatory message on the opening of the Islam seminar, which
was read at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
In his written message, Chen said Taiwan upholds religious
freedom and cultural diversity. In the past four years, Chen said,
his administration has stepped up efforts to help local people better
understand Islamic culture and to promote exchanges among different
religions.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the same occasion, WML Secretary-General Dr. Abdullah
Al-Turki said many people have misunderstood Islam due to terrorism
advocated by some Islamic extremists. In fact, he said, Islam, like
other major religions, advocates peace.
</P>
<P>
"Peace is consistently our ultimate goal. We firmly oppose
terrorism. The World Muslim League has been striving to preach the
true spirit of Islam and promote exchanges with other religious
groups to enhance mutual understanding," said Al-Turki.
</P>
<P>
During the opening ceremony, Chien decorated Al-Turki
with the Order of Brilliant Star with Grand Cordon in recognition of
his contribution to the promotion of cultural exchanges on behalf of
the ROC government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
