<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040315.0024" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PASSENGERS ALLOWED TO CARRY UP TO 6,000 RENMINBI IN AND OUT OF TAIWAN
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Kaohsiung,  March 15 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Passengers entering or leaving Taiwan
are now allowed to carry mainland Chinese currency of up to 6,000
renminbi with them, the Kaohsiung Customs authorities said Monday.
</P>
<P>
At current rates, 6,000 renminbi is about NT$24,300 or US$725.
</P>
<P>
The customs officials said that passengers, particularly inbound
passengers, presumably most of them Taiwan citizens returning from
trips to mainland China, are now allowed to carry renminbi with them
as part of the government's efforts to increase convenience for
people amid the rapid rise in cross-strait exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance (MOF) adopted the new policy at the end
of 2003 in compliance with a Statute Governing the Relations Between
the People of the Taiwan Area and the Mainland Area amendment that
was passed by the Legislative Yuan last November.
</P>
<P>
Before last December, mainland Chinese currency was not allowed
to be brought into Taiwan by anyone.
</P>
<P>
MOF officials said that the limit of 6,000 renminbi was decided
upon after the MOF took into consideration Taiwan's overall economic
development as well as the practices adopted by other countries.
</P>
<P>
The exact amount could be increased once Taiwan and mainland
China sign a bilateral currency clearance pact, MOF officials said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the maximum amount in foreign currency that people are
allowed to carry with them into or out of Taiwan is US$10,000.
Inbound and outbound passengers are also allowed to carry Taiwan
currency of up to NT$60,000 with them, according to the country's
laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040315.0025" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
600-PLUS FOREIGN JOURNALISTS CONVERGE ON TAIWAN TO COVER ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 15 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More than 600 foreign journalists from
200-odd media organizations have arrived in Taiwan to cover the March
20 presidential election as well as Taiwan's first-ever nationwide
referendum scheduled for the same day, the Government Information
Office (GIO) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In addition, scholars and researchers from 22 foreign academic
groups and think tanks are also expected to arrive to observe and
collect first-hand information about the presidential election and
referendum, GIO officials said.
</P>
<P>
GIO officials said the arrival of such a large number of foreign
newspeople and scholars indicates that the international community is
paying much attention to the upcoming presidential election -- a
close race -- and the landmark referendum, which symbolizes the
progress of Taiwan's democratization.
</P>
<P>
Among the foreign media organizations, 53 have come from six
countries in North and Latin America, 59 from 14 countries in Europe
and 102 from 17 countries and areas in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
In Taiwan's first-ever nationwide referendum to be held March 20,
the Taiwan voters will be asked two questions. First, whether they
agree that the government should acquire more advanced weapons to
strengthen its anti-missile defenses if mainland China refuses to
remove its ballistic missiles targeting Taiwan. Second, whether they
would agree that the government should negotiate with mainland China
on establishing a "peace and stability" framework in order to build
consensus and for the welfare of people on both sides of the Taiwan
Strait.
</P>
