<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040315.0027" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE, INTERIOR MINISTRIES RESPECT CEC DECISION ON MISCAST BALLOTS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  15 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Officials from both the Ministry of
Justice and the Ministry of the Interior said Monday that the
ministries respect the latest decision that the Central Election
Commission (CEC) has made on the controversial issue of miscast
ballots.
</P>
<P>
The Legislative Yuan invited officials from the CEC, the Ministry
of Justice and the Ministry of the Interior to report on validity
issue after the CEC finally decided Sunday, less than a week before
the presidential election and Taiwan's first-ever referendum slated
for March 20, that miscast ballots will be counted invalid.
</P>
<P>
Vice Minister of the Interior Chien Tai-lang said that the CEC's
decision that presidential ballots cast in boxes designated for
referendum votes will not be counted and vice versa will help
alleviate doubts and worries of the electorate and contribute to
facilitate a smooth election day March 20.
</P>
<P>
After many twists and turns, the CEC finally decided Sunday that
miscast ballots in the March 20 presidential election and referendum
will be considered invalid.
</P>
<P>
CEC Chairman Huang Shih-cheng made the announcement after all CEC
commissioners discussed the validity issue for three hours at an
extraordinary session.
</P>
<P>
"We have come to the conclusion that presidential election
ballots cast into the boxes provided for the referendum will not be
counted and vice versa, " Huang said, adding that the decision was
made in line with the "expectations of major political parties and
mainstream public opinion."
</P>
<P>
Huang's announcement marked yet another policy change for the CEC
in one week in handling the upcoming presidential election and
referendum.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, Huang said miscast election and referendum ballots
should be counted as valid. As a result, he said, the outcome of the
presidential election would have to be announced twice. The first
announcement would be made when all ballots in the boxes for
presidential election were tallied and the second would be made when
the boxes for referendum ballots were counted, in case any
presidential votes were found to have been cast in the referendum
boxes.
</P>
<P>
The decision came under fire from the opposition camp on the
grounds that since the act of mistakenly casting presidential
election ballots into the referendum ballot boxes is illegal, such
miscast ballots should not be regarded as valid.
</P>
<P>
Under strong pressure, the CEC called a provisional meeting
Sunday to review its previous decision. After a heated debate among
CEC commissioners, the CEC finally decided to invalidate all miscast
ballots to avoid any controversy.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet spokesman Lin Chia-lung said Sunday that the Cabinet
respects the CEC's decision and hopes that the commission will not
make any more changes.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) Legislator
Tsai Huang-lang, a DPP party whip at the Legislative Yuan, said that
the CEC made its latest decision with half a heart Sunday under huge
pressure from the opposition "pan-blue alliance, " which has warned
that prolonged time for vote counting and result announcements might
cause post-election rioting.
</P>
<P>
Tsai urged the "pan-blue alliance" not to incite trouble and
create confusion by continuing to look for faults in electoral
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Legislative caucuses of all major political parties hailed the
CEC's latest decision Sunday, saying that the new decision will help
speed up vote counting on election day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040315.0028" type="story" >
