<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040315.0034" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 15 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Monday, March 15, or the 25th
day of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according to the
lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that have
occurred on this date in the past:

44 B.C.: Julius Caesar, Roman general, statesman and historian,
who invaded Britain, crushed the army of his political enemy Pompey,
pursued other enemies to Egypt, where he installed Cleopatra as
queen, is stabbed by Marcus Brutus while attending a meeting of the
Senate in Pompey's theater. He dies at the age of 56.

1521: Ferdinand Magellan, the Portuguese navigator who sailed
across the Pacific Ocean, which he named, discovers the Philippines,
where he is killed by native warriors. One of his ships returned to
Spain in 1522, thereby completing the first circumnavigation of the
globe.

1767: Andrew Jackson, the seventh U.S. president who as a general
in the War of 1812 defeated the British at New Orleans and as
president opposed the Bank of America and increased the president's
powers, is born.

1776: The Congress of the United States decides to ignore the
authority of the British Crown.

1874: France establishes a protectorate over Annam (now Vietnam),
which breaks off its vassalage to China's Qing imperial court.
Controversies with Russia in the northwest and with England and
France in the southwest jeopardized the stability of the Qing
dynasty. In the latter half of the 19th century, China lost its
suzerainty rights over Indo-China and large areas of the northwest.

1943: Japanese warplanes raid Darwin, in northern Australia.

1954: An archaeological team formally begins excavations on
Yuanshan in Taipei.

1960: Syngman Rhee is elected president of South Korea for a
fourth consecutive term.

1964: The U.S. basketball team the Harlem Globetrotters visit
Taipei to show off their skills.

1969: Border fighting breaks out between Communist Chinese and
Soviet forces.

1970: The Osaka Expo is opened.

1973: The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of China
issues a statement condemning the Japanese government for allowing
Communist China to occupy the ROC embassy in Japan.

1973: Yu Chun-hsien and Chou Po-lien are elected president and
vice president, respectively, of the ROC Control Yuan.

1974: The West German government abolishes the speed limit for
cars on its freeways, better known as autobahns.

1975: Greek shipping tycoon Aristotle Onassis, who in 1968
married Jacqueline Kennedy, widow of U.S. President John F. Kennedy,
dies in Paris at the age of 69.

1976: More than 600 government and civic leaders gather for a
breakfast meeting with Premier Chiang Ching-kuo.

1976: Gen. Ro Jae Hyun, chairman of the South Korean Joint Chiefs
of Staff, arrives in Taipei for a four-day visit.

1980: A tour bus accident near Lishan in central Taiwan kills 17
and injures 15 recent graduates of National Taiwan Normal University.

1990: Mikhail Sergeyevich Gorbachev is sworn in as president of
the Soviet Union.

1991: The ROC Central Bank raises the ceiling on the annual
amount of capital inflow per individual to US$3 million.

1996: President Lee Teng-hui tells Beijing to stop "nagging" the
ROC with its war games. Communist China responds by announcing more
exercises, this time much closer to Taiwan.

2000: The ROC Ministry of Foreign Affairs says that it cannot
accept a unilateral Philippine decision to immediately suspend direct
flight services between the two countries.

2000: The ROC Ministry of National Defense reiterates its firm
stance of maintaining administrative neutrality with just three days
to go before the presidential election.

2001: President Blaise Compaore of Burkina Faso arrives in Taipei
for a six-day state visit to the ROC at the invitation of President
Chen Shui-bian.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "Make conscientiousness and
sincerity your first principles. Act up to what is right. In that
way, you will raise your moral sentiment."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040316.0001" type="multi" >
