<HEADLINE>
NTUA LAUNCHES BLOOD DONATION DRIVE TO SAVE PROFESSOR
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 16 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
National Taiwan University of Arts (NTUA)
launched a blood donation drive Tuesday in a bid to save the life of
Prof. Hsieh Chang-fu, who is now in critical condition as a result of
fulminant hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
Hsia Hsueh-li, an associate professor at NTUA's Institute of
Applied Arts Studies, said all healthy people with blood type A are
welcome to donate blood at National Taiwan University Hospital (NTUH)
where Prof. Hsieh is awaiting liver transplant surgery, which will
require a large amount of type-A blood.
</P>
<P>
People with other blood types are also welcome to donate blood at
NTUH to help other patients in dire need of blood, Hsia noted.
</P>
<P>
Hsieh, 55, an energetic tennis player and a popular professor at
the university, suffered fulminant hepatic failure earlier this
month. NTUH doctors said that a liver transplant would be the only
option to save Hsieh's life. The fatality rate among fulminant
hepatitis patients is 80 percent to 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
As of noon Tuesday, five of Hsieh's relatives were undergoing
tests to see whether they are suitable candidates to donate part of
their liver to save Hsieh's life.
</P>
<P>
Hsieh's oldest son, who works in the United States, has flown
back to Taipei to be with his father, while his second son, who
currently studies in mainland China, is expected to fly back later
Tuesday. China Airlines arranged a seat for him after he himself was
unable to book one due to the lack of availability in the run-up to
the March 20 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
At the NTUA campus, students have hung yellow ribbons and paper
cranes on trees to cheer up Hsieh, while his students at the NTUA
Institute of Applied Arts Studies have set up a Web site with the
words "Go, go, go! Boss Hsieh!" on the homepage.
</P>
<P>
The owner of a cafe on the NTUA campus claimed Monday that he
will donate part of the income of his restaurant to help out with
Professor Hsieh's medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
Fulminant hepatitis, according to NTUH doctors, is an acute
disease apt to hit males in their young to prime years, probably
because of the fact that their immune systems are at their strongest
during that period.
</P>
<P>
Patients of chronic hepatitis B are also liable to be hit with
fulminant hepatitis under certain conditions, such as by smoking or
drinking excessively or by overdosing on fever or pain-killer
medicines that contain such things as acetaminophen, the NTUH doctors
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
