politicians of the opposition Kuomintang and the PFP and whether
Soong agreed to any conditions offered by him when accepting the
donation, Huang refused to answer.
</P>
<P>
In response, Soong, who is the running mate of KMT Chairman Lien
Chan in the March 20 presidential election, described Huang's claims
as "nonsense," saying that he is not familiar with Huang and does not
want to get involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
In an open letter to local media March 8, Huang also claimed that
Lien accepted NT$100 million from him as a political donation in
1998. The KMT filed a libel suit against him the next day.
</P>
<P>
Describing Huang's accusations as false, lawyer Lin Fu-hung
commissioned by the KMT said that the alleged NT$100 million
political donation was confirmed by the Taipei Prosecutor's Office
during its investigation into an investment project by Zanadau
Development Co. to be a rebate for Liu Tai-ying, former chairman of
the KMT Investment Commission.
</P>
<P>
