<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040316.0008" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
NO BAN ON  PRO, ANTI-REFERENDUM SIGNS AT EXIT POLLS: OFFICIALS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  16 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
People who go to the polls March 20
wearing badges, stickers, armbands or other accessories that show
their support or opposition to the referendum will not be stopped by
poll workers or police unless they constitute a disruption of the
referendum, according to a decision taken by the Executive Yuan
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The decision will allow opponents of the referendum to wear
stickers calling for a boycott of the referendum.
</P>
<P>
Talk show host Chao Sao-kang said during a televised referendum
debate Sunday that a ban on anti-referendum stickers would be an
infringement of the constitutional right of free expression and he
added that he will wear a sticker to the polls March 20 and challenge
police to arrest him.
</P>
<P>
Lin Chia-long, a spokesman for the Executive Yuan, said the
Executive Yuan's decision was reached with the purpose of carrying
out the first nationwide referendum peacefully and smoothly.
</P>
<P>
People who interrupt the polls by urging or luring others into or
out of casting their referendum votes within 30 meters of the polling
stations will be asked to stop before being told to stop and any
punishments will only be meted out after the referendum, Lin said.
</P>
<P>
However, Lin said that voters are prohibited from carrying any
presidential candidate's badges, stickers, campaign caps or other
accessories to within 30 meters of the polling stations, as laid out
in the Presidential Election and Recall Law.
</P>
<P>
Presidential election exit polls of the type a local television
station plans to conduct on election day for the first time, will not
be prohibited according to Central Election Commission Chairman
Huang Shih-cheng, as long as the polls are carried out more than 30
meters from the polling stations and as long as results are not
released until after 4 p.m. when the polling stations close.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Lin Chia-long cautioned that anyone who wants to
held exit polls should conduct them "carefully," as incorrect results
are very likely in such a close race, which could trigger chaos in
the country.
</P>
<P>
As a newly developed democracy, Lin said, Taiwan seems unprepared
for exit polls. Voters do not trust pollsters and might not tell them
their true voting patterns, which would undermine the accuracy of the
exit polls.
</P>
<P>
Citing an exit polls that showed an opposite result to the final
outcome of the 2000 U.S. presidential election, Lin warned that a
similar mistake in Taiwan could prompt unpredictable reactions from
the supporters of the losing candidate.
</P>
<P>
"The government won't interfere with any mass media decision to
do an exit poll, but anyone who wants to do it should do it in a
responsible way," Lin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
