(By Wu Hsien-kuang &amp; Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
One more member of the Canadian Parliament
called on the Canadian government Monday to take concrete action to
support Taiwan's entry into the World Health Organization (WHO) as an
observer.
</P>
<P>
During a parliamentary interpellation session, Stephane Bergeron
of the Quebec Party, urged the Ottawa authorities to support Taiwan's
WHO bid in line with a proposal adopted by the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Bergeron noted that the Parliament passed a proposal in favor of
Taiwan's participation in the WHO as an observer about one year ago
when the island urgently needed the world health body's assistance
because of the outbreaks of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS).
</P>
<P>
One year later, the island faced a rising threat from the H5N2
avian flu virus, Bergeron pointed out. "Why is our government still
reluctant to assist Taiwan in obtaining WHO observer status or push
for an amendment to the WHO organic statutes to facilitate its
accession?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
