<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040316.0021" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY APOLOGIZES FOR NEGLIGENCE IN STOCK TRADING REPORTS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 16 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
First lady Wu Shu-chen apologized Tuesday
for failing to report five stock trading deals to the watchdog
Control Yuan's public functionaries assets report department between
2000 and 2003.
</P>
<P>
Presidential Office Secretary-General Chiou I-jen offered the
apology on behalf of the first lady at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
"Wu has asked me to convey her deep apology to the general public
over her negligence in her assets reports, " Chiou said, adding that
Wu's accountant had already reported the omitted stock trading deals
to the Control Yuan earlier in the day and has paid the fines due in
accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
According to the newly revised public functionaries assets report
regulations, any single stock trading deal worth over NT$10 million
should be reported to the Control Yuan, the nation's highest watchdog
body.
</P>
<P>
Chiou said the omitted stock trading deals were found recently
while the accountant was handling the first family's assets trust
affairs.
</P>
<P>
During the period from President Chen Shui-bian's inauguration in
May 2000 until the end of last year, Chiou said, five of Wu's stock
trading deals were not reported, including two deals worth between
NT$22 million and NT$27 million, as well as three deals worth between
NT$12 million and NT$13 million.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing was special in those deals. The omission mainly
resulted from negligence. The first lady did not purposely hide
information about those five deals," Chiou claimed.
</P>
<P>
Wu, who has been confined to a wheelchair since being run over by
a truck in 1985, reportedly took up stock trading as a "hobby, " but
it has become a hot presidential campaign topic in recent months.
</P>
<P>
In a televised debate Feb. 21, the opposition presidential
candidate, Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan, brought up the issue. In
response, Chen said even though his wife has not committed any
wrongdoing or insider trading in her investments, he agreed that her
actions were "inappropriate" in consideration of her capacity as the
first lady. He said his wife will not conduct any stock trading deals
prior to the March 20 presidential election and also made a public
pledge that he will put his family assets into "blind trust" after
the presidential poll.
</P>
<P>
To honor his promise, Chiou said, Chen asked the accountant to
begin preparations for putting his family assets into trust and it
was in this process that Wu's omitted stock trading deals were
spotted, Chiou explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
