</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  16 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With the expected opening of domestic
airports to privately owned planes, a Brazilian aircraft manufacturer
will come to Taiwan to show its products.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturer, which specializes in the production of small
jet passenger planes, will visit Taiwan Wednesday. Domestic air
carrier Trans Asia Airways will be in charge of ground operations,
while Trans Asia Airways Chairman Fan Chi-chiang will also test fly
the plane.
</P>
<P>
The small jet passenger plane can accommodate 70 people and can
cater to special needs. The plane carries a price tag of around
US$20 million, but the actual selling price could be cheaper.
</P>
<P>
Under current civil aeronautics regulations, individuals can own
aircraft, but since there is no hangar facilities for them at
Taiwan's airports, plane owners here must park their aircraft outside
of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Aeronautics Administration (CAA) said that it considers
the regulations out of date and is revising them.
</P>
<P>
In addition, domestic airline traffic has continued to drop.
After the inauguration of Taiwan's first high-speed rail linking
Kaohsiung and Taipei in 2005, this traffic is expected to shrink
further, and there will be more space for private planes to park, CAA
officials said.
