<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040316.0042" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 16 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Monday, March 16, or the 16th
day of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according to the
lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that have
occurred on this date in the past:

1527: Babar, a Muslim ruler from central Asia who established the
Mogul Empire in 1526, defeats the Hindu Confederacy at Kanwanha.
Babar later conquered India.

1751: James Madison, the fourth president of the United States,
who supported ratification of the Constitution, is born. He was the
first and only president to exercise his rank as commander-in-chief
in an actual battle.

1787: Georg Simon Ohm, German physicist noted for his
contributions to mathematics, acoustics and the measurement of
electrical resistance, is born.

1802: The U.S. Military Academy at West Point, New York, is
established.

1815: William of Orange is made King of the United Netherlands
and crowned William I.

1900: Sir Arthur Evans, British archaeologist, unearths at
Knossos, on the Greek island of Crete, remnants of a Bronze Age
civilization that he named Minoan, after the legendary King Minos.

1906: Japan nationalizes its railways.

1914: Madame Caillaux, wife of the French finance minister,
shoots dead the editor of the newspaper Le Figaro to protect her
husband against libel.

1925: An earthquake rocks Kunming, Dali in Yunnan Province,
killing more than 4,000 people and damaging numerous houses.

1926: Robert Hutchings Goddard launches the first successful
liquid-fueled rocket which he developed at Auburn, Massachusetts.

1926: Jerry Lewis, American film star famous for his zany roles
and partnership with singer-actor Dean Martin, is born.

1935: German Chancellor Adolph Hitler renounces the terms of the
Treaty of Versailles that ended World War I and induces conscription
in preparation for armed aggression.

1937: Joseph Austen Chamberlain, British politician who helped
establish the Locarno Pact and won the 1925 Nobel Peace Prize, dies
at the age of 74.

1945: U.S. forces recapture the Pacific island of Iwo Jima during
World War II after meeting strong Japanese resistance.

1955: The U.S. State Department makes public all documents
related to the Yalta Secret Agreement, which was concluded by the
three allied leaders, Winston Churchill, Franklin D. Roosevelt and
Joseph Stalin, at a secret meeting in the Black Sea resort of Yalta
on Feb. 11, 1945. The three agreed, among other things, that the USSR
would enter the war against Japan on condition that its former rights
in China plundered by Japan in 1904 would be restored.

1968: U.S. troops kill more than 100 civilians during an
operation in the South Vietnamese village of My Lai.

1973: British monarch Queen Elizabeth II opens the new London
Bridge.

1974: John K. Tabor, U.S. under-secretary of commerce, arrives to
participate in the dedication of the Taipei U.S. Trade Center.

1976: The Asian indoor handball Olympic qualifying tournament
opens in Taipei with teams from South Korea, Japan and the ROC taking
part.

1977: A delegation of government officials headed by Economic
Vice Minister Chang Kwang-shih leaves for Riyadh to attend a
Sino-Saudi Arabian meeting on economic and technical cooperation.

1979: The Joint Commission on Rural Reconstruction is reorganized
and renamed as the Council for Agricultural Planning and Development.

1985: The Tsukuba Expo is opened.

2000: Chen Chin-hsing, formerly Taiwan's most-wanted fugitive, is
ordered to pay NT$171.3 million (US$5.19 million) in damages to
well-known TV entertainer Pai Ping-ping for kidnapping and murdering
Pai's daughter Pai Hsiao-yen.

2000: Two aging destroyers, the Tangyang and Laiyang, are
decommissioned at a military port near Kaohsiung Harbor in southern
Taiwan after more than 25 years of service in the ROC Navy.

2001: New Party Legislator Elmer Feng files a lawsuit against
presidential advisor Chin Mai-ling (Alice King) for committing
"improper" deeds that he said "endangers the internal security of
Taiwan."

Confucius' lesson of the day: "You wish to live and hate to die.
But while clinging to life, you yet hanker after those things which
can only shorten life: that is a great delusion in life."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040317.0001" type="story" >
