<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN NTV NEWS CREW TO COVER TAIWAN ELECTION, DAILY LIFE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Moscow,  March  17 (CNA)
(By Chang Hung-kuang and Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A news crew from Russia's most watched
television channel, Russian NTV, is scheduled to arrive in Taipei
Wednesday to cover Taiwan's March 20 presidential election and
referendum.
</P>
<P>
The four-member crew, to be led by prime time news anchor Anton
Khrekov, is expected to cover campaign activities in Taiwan's three
major cities -- Taipei, Kaohsiung and Taichung -- in the run-up to
election day.
</P>
<P>
The Russian journalists are also expected to interview President
Chen Shui-bian and his running mate, Vice President Annette Lu, on
Chen's campaign strategies in the tight two-way race, as well as
interview the opposition "pan-blue alliance" ticket of Kuomintang
Chairman Lien Chan and People First Party Chairman James Soong.
</P>
<P>
During their week-long stay, the Russian NTV reporters and
cameramen will also take time to cover the daily life of local Taiwan
people, several cross-Taiwan Strait families, and a number of Russian
expatriates residing in Taiwan, as well as tourist attractions around
the island.
</P>
<P>
The crew has decided to introduce Taiwan's tea plantations and
tea culture, hot springs, and horticulture -- which are areas that
the Russian people are most interested in concerning tourism in
Taiwan, according to Russian NTV management.
</P>
<P>
Khrekov, 29, who holds a master's degree from Moscow State
University's Institute of Asian and African Studies, speaks fluent
Chinese and English. With eloquence and talent in TV news reporting,
Khrekov has climbed the ladder of success quickly over the past three
years.
</P>
<P>
Russian NTV, established in St. Petersburg in 1993, is the first
privately-run TV station in Russia. Currently one of the three major
TV companies in that country, Russian NTV boasts some 117 million
regular viewers around Russia, or about 83 percent of the entire
population.
</P>
</TEXT>
