<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040317.0011" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
BAN ON DIRECT CROSS-STRAIT SHIPPING REMAINS IN PLACE: KEELUNG PORT
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 17 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The central government has not lifted its
ban on direct shipping between Taiwan and mainland China, and owners
of the vessels, including those of foreign nationalities, who break
the rule will be punished with fines in accordance with the law, a
spokesman for the Keelung Harbor Bureau said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman made the remarks after local media outlets reported
that a Panamanian-flagged cruise ship -- the Seven Seas Voyager --
departed for Shanghai Tuesday afternoon directly from Keelung Harbor
in northern Taiwan after having received permission from the bureau.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman pointed out that the bureau did not give its
approval to the vessel and made it clear that it will issue a fine to
its owner. He added that violators can be penalized with a fine
ranging from NT$3 million to up to NT$15 million (about US$450,000)
in accordance with the Statute Governing the Relations Between the
People of the Taiwan Area and the Mainland Area.
</P>
<P>
The bureau will look into the report and the ship's owner will be
punished if it is proven to be true, he said, adding that the bureau
has asked the ship's agent in Taiwan to inform the captain of the
situation and possible fine if he cannot provide documents issued by
port authorities in a third country or area to show that the ship
really stopped there en route to Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Direct trade, transport and postal links across the Taiwan Strait
are banned in the absence of formal contacts between Taiwan and
mainland China. The two sides of the strait split in 1949 following
a civil war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040317.0012" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
MAC CHIEF EMPHASIZES LEGITIMACY OF PLANNED REFERENDUM
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 17 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mainland Affairs Council (MAC) Chairwoman
Tsai Ing-wen laid emphasis Wednesday on the legitimacy and
indispensability of Taiwan's first nationwide referendum to be held
in conjunction with the March 20 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Referendums are indispensable in the process of democratic
development and cross-Taiwan Strait relations promotion, Tsai said
while delivering a speech on the planned referendum and perspectives
for national development at the ruling Democratic Progressive Party
(DPP) headquarters.
</P>
<P>
In response to the opposition camp's query as to why the DPP
government has linked the referendum to the March 20 presidential
election, Tsai said if it had not been linked to the election, the
ruling and opposition parties would haven't weathered all the
difficulties to pass the Referendum Law and the people of Taiwan
would stand no chance of being able to vote in the referendum.
</P>
<P>
Claiming that people have the right to express their viewpoints
on issues concerning national development and cross-strait relations,
Tsai said that in the process of the deepening of Taiwan's democracy,
several of Taiwan's allies have expressed their concern over whether
the referendum will have an adverse impact on the stability across
the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
However, the top planner of Taiwan's policies toward mainland
China added that the international community's inquietude was
dissipated after President Chen Shui-bian made public the two
questions to be on the referendum.
</P>
<P>
The questions are whether Taiwan should increase its anti-missile
defenses if mainland China refuses to remove the missiles it has
aimed at Taiwan, and whether the government should negotiate with
Beijing for the establishment of an interaction mechanism for peace
across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that the March 20 referendum will help forge a national
consensus on the promotion of national development and cross-strait
relations, Tsai said that if the majority of eligible voters cast a
"yes" vote in the referendum, the Beijing leadership will dare not
look down on the island.
</P>
<P>
Tsai further said that the planned referendum is aimed at
pursuing peace across the Taiwan Strait. "The international community
will understand our stance as long as we explain the referendum
purpose to our allies with patience," she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
