<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN PROVINCE CHAIRMAN CRITICIZES PROSECUTOR FOR INDICTING HIM
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 17 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan Provincial Governor Lin Kuang-hua
criticized a prosecutor in Hsinchu Wednesday who indicted him a
couple of days ago for breaching the Public Officials Election and
Recall Law saying that the move was politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
With three days to go before the presidential election, Lin said
at a news conference that the prosecutor indicted him with the
intention to tarnish President Chen Shui-bian's administration, of
which the provincial governor is a senior official.
</P>
<P>
President Chen, who is also the chairman of the ruling Democratic
Progressive Party (DPP) , is engaging in a close race against
Kuomintang (KMT) Chairman Lien Chan.
</P>
<P>
"Although this indictment doesn't mean I am guilty, it is still a
heavy blow to my image," Lin said.
</P>
<P>
The indictment arose from the 2001 election when Lin was running
on a DPP ticket for a second term as magistrate of Hsinchu County. He
accused his rival in the race, Cheng Yung-chin from the KMT, of vote-
buying.
</P>
<P>
The indictment came after a three-year investigation.
Prosecutors determined that Lin had made groundless accusations against
Cheng to hurt his chances of winning the election.
</P>
<P>
Lin claimed that Cheng, who did go on to win the 2001 election,
made similar accusations against him in the lead-up to the election
but the prosecutor in charge of the investigation didn't bother to
look into them, not to mention indict Cheng. This casts into
question the fairness of the prosecutor's investigation, Lin
contended.
</P>
<P>
Although losing the race for county chief, Lin was named
provincial chairman in 2003 and doubles as a senior adviser to the
president.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cheng said Wednesday he was pleased that it was Lin
who was indicted and not him although each of them accused the other
of violating the Public Officials Election and Recall Law.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed as ridiculous Lin's claims that the prosecutor was
biased for political reasons, saying that since his KMT is the
opposition party now, how could it be the one pulling strings to get
an indictment against Lin?
</P>
</TEXT>
