BRAZILIAN AIRCRAFT MAKER TO TAP CROSS-STRAIT DIRECT FLIGHT MARKET
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,   March  17  (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Brazilian commercial jetliner
manufacturer displayed a new model of small passenger aircraft in
Taiwan Wednesday in the hopes of cashing in on the much-anticipated
opening of direct air links across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
EMBRAER, a listed aircraft manufacturer, displayed its EMB-170
model passenger jet in Taipei.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian firm's Asia-Pacific marketing director said he
believes direct cross-strait flight services will open in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
"Our EMB-170 plane, which can accommodate 70 passengers, is very
suitable for cross-strait flights. We believe that the opening of
direct cross-strait air links will bring us new business
opportunities," he said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
The plane will also be displayed in mainland China later this
month, he added.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's TransAsia Airways offered ground services for the
Brazilian aircraft during the promotion tour of the island. An
airline spokesman said that at the moment, medium and small passenger
planes used in Taiwan are propeller-powered.
</P>
<P>
"The EMB-70 jet can fly faster than prop-powered planes. Once
direct cross-strait air links are opened, we'll consider purchase
this type of plane," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, EMBRAER reportedly also set its target on local
business tycoons as Taiwan's civil aviation authorities will revise
regulations to allow domestic airports to accommodate privately owned
planes.
</P>
<P>
Under current civil aeronautics regulations, individuals can own
aircraft, but since there is no hangar facilities for them at
Taiwan's airports, plane owners here must park their aircraft outside
of the country. Once domestic airports are open to private use, more
rich people are expected to buy small planes, airline sources said.
</P>
<P>
EMBRAER, founded in 1969, specializes in manufacturing small jet
passenger planes and military trainers.
</P>
