<HEADLINE>
QUANTITY OF GARBAGE COLLECTED IN TAIPEI FALLS YEAR ON YEAR
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 17 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The new kitchen leftover recycling program
and paying for garbage by volume in Taipei City has reduced the
amount of trash collected from January to February by 13.58 percent
compared to last year, according to the Department of Budget,
Accounting and Statistics under the Taipei City Government.
</P>
<P>
The department statistics showed that ever since the new kitchen
leftover recycling program was put into practice at the end of last
year, kitchen waste collected has amounted to around 6,100 metric
tons, resulting in a significant decrease of general garbage
collected. The general garbage volume, on average, was up to around
1,500 metric tons per day, a decrease of 13.58 percent year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
The total garbage collected in 2003 was more than 0.74 million
metric tons, a decrease of 17.16 percent from a year earlier, the
statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics, Taipei garbage volume from January
to February, on average, was 1,514 metric tons per day, a decrease of
13.58 percent, compared to 1,752 metric tons per day in the same
months a year earlier. Taipei City residents, on average, generated
around 0.58 kilograms per day, a decrease of 12.12 percent
year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
Taipei garbage fees were originally imposed along with water
rates, but since the new pay-by-bag garbage fee was put in place in
2000 along with recycling programs, Taipei garbage volume has
declined year by year, based on the statistics.
</P>
<P>
By (Eric Liu)
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040317.0016" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN EXPECTED TO BECOME MEMBER OF INTERNATIONAL TUNA ORGANIZATION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,   March  17  (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan is expected to join the
Inter-American Tropical Tuna Commission (IATTC) as a "fishing entity"
later this year, the Executive Yuan said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Executive Yuan officials made the remarks after the Cabinet
approved documents concerning joining the commission and will send
them to the Legislative Yuan for confirmation.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that this was another diplomatic achievement
for the nation since Taiwan took part in the Convention on the
Conservation and Management of Highly Migratory Fish Stocks in the
Western and Central Pacific in September 2000.
</P>
<P>
The officials noted that the IATTC is an international fishery
organization to conserve and manage tuna in the east Pacific, and
which currently has 14 members, including the United States, Japan,
France and countries from Central and Southern America.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan joined the IATTC as an observer in 1973, and in 1998
attended its meeting to revise the Antigua Convention in Guatemala,
and the signing of the convention paper in November 2003.
</P>
<P>
After becoming an IATTC member, Taiwan, through the Antigua
Convention, will be able to take part in the policy-making of fishing
regulations, fish haul quotas and annual budget appropriations under
the framework of the IATTC, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
This will protect Taiwan's fishing rights in the east Pacific,
and contribute to its duty of conservation as a major fishing
country, which the officials said will help upgrade the nation's
image.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
