</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 17 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The National Police Administration (NPA)
will do everything possible to uphold social order in the run-up to
the March 20 presidential election under four principles: neutrality,
administration of public affairs based upon relevant laws, overall
mobilization, and strict collection of evidence, NPA Director-General
Chang Szu-liang said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chang made the remarks while delivering a report to the Judiciary
Committee under the Legislative Yuan on various measures aimed at
preventing vote-buying and violence as well as maintaining social
order and public security before and after the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Since Oct. 3 last year, the NPA has sponsored six seminars on
vote-buying investigation and violence prevention in order to upgrade
law enforcement personnel's skills in carrying out their missions,
Chang said in his report.
</P>
<P>
In the face of the far-reaching presidential election, local
police authorities have collected and submitted bribery-related
information to prosecutors for references, Chang said, adding that if
deemed necessary, local prosecutors will command police officers and
investigators to strictly crack down on violence or vote-buying
cases.
</P>
<P>
To demonstrate the government's determination to thwart corrupt
"black gold" politics, Chang pointed out that the NPA has worked out
a set of measures for local police authorities to effectively crack
down on vote-buying and safeguard social order during election of the
11th president and vice president as well as the holding of the
first-ever nationwide referendum in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Chang further said that a strong police presence will be deployed
around various important facilities, such as the Presidential Office,
and campaign headquarters and electoral affairs offices to deal with
possible protests or riots after the announcement of election
results.
