<HEADLINE>
FORMER TAIWAN COMFORT WOMEN DEMONSTRATE AT JIA OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 17 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Four former Taiwan comfort women staged a
protest at the de facto Japanese embassy in Taipei Wednesday to push
the Japanese government to apologize for forcing them into
prostitution during World War II.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration at the Japanese Interchange Association (JIA) ,
which represents Japanese interests in Taiwan in the absence of
formal diplomatic ties, was part of an worldwide campaign to demand
an apology and compensation from Japan for its wartime atrocities.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese forced more than 200,000 Asian women to serve as sex
slaves, euphemistically called comfort women, for their soldiers
between 1938 and 1945, including at least 1,200 from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, a group of former South Korean comfort women,
students and human rights activists have staged a sit-in at the
Japanese embassy in Seoul every Wednesday noon. This Wednesday marked
the 600th sit-in of its kind. They invited former comfort women in
Taiwan and the Philippines to stage similar protests. Japanese human
rights activists also demonstrated in Tokyo and Osaka in support of
former Asian comfort women's cause.
</P>
<P>
The four elderly former Taiwan comfort women were accompanied by
senior executives from the Taipei Women's Rescue Foundation (TWRF) ,
including lawyer Wang Ching-feng, in the protest at the JIA office in
Taipei. Several Japanese youths studying in Taiwan also lent their
support by joining the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
They issued a joint appeal, demanding that the Japanese
government offer them a formal apology, financial compensation and
make public all comfort women-related archives.
</P>
<P>
The joint appeal also urged all Asian countries to correctly
recount the comfort women history in their school textbooks as part
of their human rights and peace value education in order to prevent a
recurrence of similar tragedies.
</P>
<P>
The appeal further suggested that Asian countries set up special
museums to preserve historical documents, data and illustrations
regarding the comfort women system adopted by the Japanese wartime
government.
</P>
<P>
In July 1999, nine former Taiwan comfort women filed an appeal
with the Tokyo District Court, demanding a public apology and
financial compensation from the Japanese government. The Tokyo
District Court rejected the appeal in 2002. Two of the plaintiffs
have since died. The Tokyo High Court upheld the district court's
ruling in February this year.
</P>
<P>
A Japanese lawyer has appealed on behalf of the seven surviving
Taiwanese women to the Japanese Supreme Court against the Tokyo High
Court's recent ruling. All of the seven former comfort women are in
their 80s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040317.0020" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
LIEN HIT WITH NT$300,000 FINE FOR FAILING TO REPORT PROPERTY IN U.S.
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 17 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Opposition presidential candidate Lien
Chan failed to report his ownership of a house in the United States
during his term as vice president and will be fined at least
NT$300,000 (US$9,036), an official of the watchdog Control Yuan said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Hsieh Yu-nan, director of the Control Yuan's department in charge
of assets-reporting by public functionaries, said that Lien, chairman
of the opposition Kuomintang, had not reported a house in Cambridge,
Massachusetts, under the name of his wife, Lien Fang-yu, throughout
the time he was vice president from 1996 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
Lien did report the house when he registered with the Central
Election Commission (CEC) recently to run for president, which showed
that Lien had not included the property in his earlier filing.
</P>
<P>
Hsieh noted that several legislators have contended that Lien's
failure to declare the house, a company in the United States and a
foundation in the name of Lien's father makes the case that Lien is
concealing family assets.
</P>
<P>
He said his department will make an overall review of the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
Noting that there is substantial evidence to support the
ownership of the house in Massachusetts, Hsieh said the department
will suggest a fine of NT$300,000, but will wait until the
investigation into other cases is finished to make a final
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
On the alleged withholding of information of a U.S. company,
Hsieh said the department will have to collect more information on
this.
</P>
<P>
The department will ask the Ministry of Foreign Affairs within
two days to track down the assets of Lien in the United States via
its overseas representative offices, he said.
</P>
<P>
If more information can back up the claims of the legislators
that Lien has deliberately withheld assets or tried to evade taxes,
then the department will urge the integrity commission under the
Control Yuan and tax bureaus to further investigate the cases, Hsieh
said.
</P>
<P>
Between January and March, several legislators from the ruling
Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) , including Wang Shu-hui, Lan
Mei-chin, Chiang Chao-yi, Yeh Yi-chin, Lai Ching-teh and Chiu
Chuan-chin reported to the Control Yuan about Lien's house in
Massachusetts, pointing out the discrepancy between Lien's report as
vice president and as presidential candidate to prove that Lien had
not declared his assets honestly.
</P>
<P>
DPP legislators Duan Yi-kang and Lee Wen-chung made the
allegations about Lien's company in the United States to the Control
Yuan Tuesday, and criticized the nation's top watchdog body for
dragging its feet in investigating the reported cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
