<HEADLINE>
EX-PRESIDENT TRIES TO CLAIM MONEY PUT IN ESCROW BY JAMES SOONG
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  17 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An attorney for former President Lee
Teng-hui filed a motion with the Taipei District Court Wednesday to
have funds deposited with the court in escrow by People First Party
Chairman James Soong returned to Lee as stipulated by court
documents.
</P>
<P>
Lawyer Chuang Po-lin said Lee retained him a couple of days ago
and asked him to obtain some NT$300 million (US$8.98 million) that was
put into the court's custody by Soong in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Chuang quoted Lee as saying that the money is part of the KMT's
illegally gained assets and should be returned to the people. Chuang
did not elaborate on how Lee intended to do this.
</P>
<P>
The money stems from a case in 2000 when Soong was engaged in a
five-way race for the presidency. The KMT charged Soong with
embezzling some NT$300 million from party coffers when he served as
KMT secretary-general between 1989 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
Proclaiming his innocence, Soong offered to return the funds, but
the KMT, under the leadership of Lee, refused to take it out of fear
it would temper Soong's guilt. Soong put the money in the custody of
the court instead.
</P>
<P>
According to court documents, the money was to be released into
the guardianship of Lee, who was then chairman of the KMT, for party
use.
</P>
<P>
A prosecutor cleared Soong of the charges in a ruling in 2001
after the presidential election in which Chen Shui-bian won. Lien
Chan, who succeeded Lee as KMT chairman, decided not to pursue the
case and eventually formed an alliance with Soong in the 2004
presidential election. Lien is running for president with Soong as
his vice president.
</P>
<P>
The court turned down the KMT's request for the funds since Lee
was listed in the court's official documents as the recipient of the
money.
</P>
<P>
Ironically, Lee has became a staunch supporter of President Chen
in the 2004 presidential election and has gone out of his way to
campaign for Chen's re-election. He criticized the Lien-Soong ticket
as a convenient marriage between two cunning politicians who will do
anything to grab power.
</P>
</TEXT>
