<HEADLINE>
COA LISTS MAJOR AGRICULTURAL PRODUCE EXPORTS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  17 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Council of Agriculture (COA) has
listed four agricultural products -- phalaenopsis (butterfly orchid),
oolung tea, tilapia and mangoes -- as the major agricultural produce
exports.
</P>
<P>
Lin Chia-jung, a specialist of the COA's Department of
International Affairs, noted that Taiwan exports more than 8 million
phalaenopsis every year, worth around US$20 million, mainly to Japan,
the United States and mainland China, making it the world's number
one phalaenopsis exporter and giving the country a major position in
the global floral market.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's oolung tea is world famous, Lin went on, adding that the
world produces around 100,000 tons of oolung tea every year, 20
percent of which comes from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's oolung tea is high quality and production planning is
managed well, giving it a strong competitive edge. The tea is
exported mainly to Japan, Southeast Asia and mainland China.
</P>
<P>
Lin noted that with the supply of white-fleshed sea fish -- which
is most-favored by world consumers -- gradually depleting, tilapia,
which has a fine texture, has the potential to replace sea fish.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan exports 47,000 tons of tilapia every year, making it a
major global exporter. Most of the fish goes to the United States,
Saudi Arabia, Canada, Britain and Kuwait, Lin said.
</P>
<P>
Mangoes, the second-largest fruit export in Taiwan after bananas,
mainly go to Hong Kong, Singapore and Japan. Taiwan mangoes, which
boast excellent quality and fresh preservation technology during
quarantine and delivery, is highly competitive, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040317.0026" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
NO MORE CONSTITUTIONAL REVISION BILLS PASSED BY LEGISLATIVE COMMITTEE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 17 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Members of the Committee of Constitutional
Amendment under the Legislative Yuan met Wednesday to review a
package of proposals concerning constitutional reform, including
abolishing the National Assembly, but failed to pass any of the
motions.
</P>
<P>
It was the second weekly meeting held by the committee to review
nine proposals on the agenda after it passed the first reading of
three draft constitutional revision bills on legislative reforms last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Based upon the draft amendments, the current 225 seats in the
legislature will be cut to 113 starting from 2008, the current
electoral system will be changed to a "single seat, two votes" system
-- meaning one vote for an individual candidate and another vote for
a political party in each constituency -- and legislators' terms will
be extended to four years from the current three years.
</P>
<P>
According to Legislator Liao Feng-teh, secretary-general of the
opposition Kuomintang's legislative caucus, the legislature is
scheduled to deal with the three draft bills on legislative reforms
this Friday in response to the public's repeated calls for upgrading
the legislature's efficiency and quality.
</P>
<P>
As the legislative caucus of the Alliance of Independent
Legislators insists that the draft constitutional revision bills be
referred once again to joint negotiations, Liao pushed for the ruling
Democratic Progressive Party's legislative caucus to coordinate
independent lawmakers' stance so that the legislature can pass the
second and third readings of the draft amendments.
</P>
<P>
Chen Chien-ming, chief convener of the opposition Taiwan
Solidarity Union's legislative caucus, said that the public look
forward to the passage of the proposals on halving the number of
legislative seats and extending legislators' terms. He also voiced
the hope that the Legislative Yuan will give priority to dealing with
the draft legislative reform bills.
</P>
<P>
For his part, DPP Legislator Lin Chung-cheng said that all
lawmakers must transcend party lines and take into consideration
national interests while dealing with constitutional reform issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040317.0027" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT TO DISSUADE TV STATION FROM EXIT POLL RESULT
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 17 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Although there is no law prohibiting the
conducting and unveiling of exit poll results, the Cabinet will
dissuade a local television from doing so for "moral reasons, " a
government spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Lin Chia-lung, a spokesman of the Executive Yuan, made the
remarks after local TV station TVBS said it intended to conduct exit
polls during Saturday's presidential election, although it also said
that it will not publish the results if a majority of the voters
refuse to divulge their ballot choices.
</P>
<P>
Saying that "the media has social responsibility, " Lin added
that media outlets know the situation of Taiwan's social development
and should avoid being the cause of possible clashes and disturbances
during elections.
</P>
<P>
"Taiwan has not conducted nationwide or credible exit polls
before, " Lin said, claiming that the matter involves "law and
regulations, credibility and social responsibility."
</P>
<P>
"It will be perfectly all right if the exit polls are conducted
for academic research, but at a time when the presidential election
is running neck and neck, great disturbance could erupt if things are
not handled properly," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lin said interviewers at the exit polls should stay more than 30
meters from the polling stations. Should disputes or disturbances
erupt, this will create headaches for local police, who will have to
determine if there are violations of election regulations.
</P>
<P>
Exit polls could also interfere with the election, Lin claimed,
adding that TVBS said that it will unveil the results at 4: 01 p.m.
one minute after the polling stations close, although those who are
already in the stations and have received their ballots will be
allowed to complete the voting procedure.
</P>
<P>
This, he said, could trigger disputes.
</P>
<P>
Another thing that needs to be addressed is that if the
television station unveils its result at noon, or spreads rumors to
imply a certain candidate will win the election, the emotions of the
public could be whipped up, Lin cautioned.
</P>
<P>
He said that exit polls also involve a credibility issue, saying
that this is the reason why no academic research bodies have dared to
unveil exit poll results immediately after elections in the past.
</P>
<P>
He said that although Taiwan's electronic media have improved the
credibility of its polls, they are still a far cry from accurately
predicting the result of elections.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that if the results released at 4:01 p.m and
the official election results released at around 7:30 p.m are
significantly different, then it will be a shock to society and the
safety of media staff could be threatened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
