<HEADLINE>
MANUAL VOTE-COUNTING WILL BE LAST RESORT: CEC
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 17 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Manual counting of ballots in Saturday's
election and referendum will be a last resort in the event that
computer systems at polling stations fail, Central Election
Commission (CEC) Chairman Huang Shih-cheng said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Fielding questions at the Legislative Yuan Committee of Interior
Affairs, Huang said that basically, all polling stations around the
country will use computers to count ballots and file reports of
election results to the CEC on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Huang said recent concerns that computers might crash as a result
of overload caused by counting both presidential ballots and
referendum votes have been alleviated now that the computers have
been tested with vote-counting simulations.
</P>
<P>
Over the past several days, Huang had announced that
vote-counting would all be done manually in anticipation that
computers would be unable to handle both presidential ballots and
referendum votes on the same day, and that polling stations around
the country would report the election results by fax or telephone.
</P>
<P>
Huang also said that on Saturday, after the presidential election
and referendum voting is wrapped up, all polling stations will also
send result reports to the campaign headquarters of both the ruling
"pan-green camp" and the opposition "pan-blue alliance" via computer,
in addition to reporting via computer to the CEC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040317.0031" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PREMIER URGES VOTERS TO CAST REFERENDUM VOTES
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 17 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Premier Yu Shyi-kun urged Taiwan voters
Wednesday to cast their referendum votes on the March 20 presidential
election day.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, Yu said the 16 million-strong Taiwan
electorate should exercise their democratic rights by casting their
votes in the country's first nationwide referendum.
</P>
<P>
The referendum will be a landmark, unprecedented democratic
practice allowing the people to make direct decisions on public
policies that will be decisive to Taiwan's future, according to Yu.
</P>
<P>
Yu said a great majority of the people of Taiwan attach great
expectations to the referendum, in the belief that it is poised to
take Taiwan a further step toward becoming a more fully functioning
government of the people and by the people.
</P>
<P>
The referendum will also mark a huge step forward in Taiwan's
democratic evolution, Yu added.
</P>
<P>
Voters will be asked two questions Saturday on whether they agree
that the government should acquire more advanced weapons to
strengthen its anti-missile defenses if mainland China refuses to
remove its ballistic missiles targeting Taiwan and on whether they
would agree that the government should negotiate with mainland China
on establishing a "peace and stability" framework in order to build
consensus and for the welfare of people on both sides of the Taiwan
Strait.
</P>
<P>
Allowing the electorate to make right and clear decisions in the
referendum will let the leadership on the opposite side of the Taiwan
Strait know what the Taiwan people need and what they are thinking
about, Yu said.
</P>
<P>
The referendum will also send messages to Beijing that military
intimidation is not conducive to long-lasting development of
cross-strait relations and is not in the interests of the people on
either side, Yu added.
</P>
<P>
He admitted, however, that some people disagree with the
government's stance on the referendum and have decided to boycott it.
Accusing those people of "boycotting the referendum simply for the
sake of boycotting, " Yu claimed that their action not only makes
Taiwan a laughing-stock in the international community, but also
causes the international community to doubt the will and
determination of the people in seeking genuine democracy and opposing
the mainland's hegemony toward Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
