TV ANCHOR IN 2002 LONDON TRAIN CRASH TO RETURN TO TAIWAN FOR VISIT
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Beijing,  March 17 (CNA)
(By H.Y. Chou and Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Taiwan TV personality whose condition
has improved steadily during more than a year of treatment in a
Beijing hospital after suffering a serious injury in a train crash in
London two years ago took a one-month leave from the hospital
Wednesday to head home.
</P>
<P>
Liu Hai-roh, who was a news anchorwoman for Hong Kong-based
Phoenix Television Co., was accompanied by her parents and younger
brother on her flight to Hong Kong Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Liu said she is "very happy and excited" to be heading home.
During her two-week stay in Hong Kong, she plans to meet with friends
and co-workers from the Phoenix Television Co.
</P>
<P>
She will also visit a Hong Kong hospital to undergo a more
detailed physical checkup.
</P>
<P>
She said that she has already contacted friends in Taiwan, hoping
to meet them when she heads back there in late March or early April.
</P>
<P>
Liu's mother said her daughter's biggest wish is to visit the
families of her friends Wu Chia-ching, a television journalist, and
Lin Chia-hsin, a former TV journalist, and pay her respects at the
graves of the two.
</P>
<P>
The trio of Liu, Wu, and Lin were on the ill-fated train that
crashed north of London May 10, 2002. The accident, which was caused
by faulty points, killed seven passengers, including Wu and Lin, and
injured more than 40 others.
</P>
<P>
Liu was pronounced brain-dead after being sent to Royal Free
Hospital in London. She was later transferred to Beijing for
lengthy treatment.
</P>
<P>
Her doctors at the Beijing hospital decided to grant her a
one-month leave, saying they were satisfied with her condition. She
received a physical checkup and physiological counselling before the
trip back home.
</P>
</TEXT>
