<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040317.0039" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 17 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Wednesday, March 17, or the 27th
day of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according to the
lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that have
occurred on this date in the past:

1190: Some 500 Jews are massacred in York, England.

1766: Britain's Parliament votes to repeal the controversial
Stamp Act, a hated colonial tax that fueled a climate of rebellion in
the American colonies.

1776: The British are forced by American revolutionaries under
George Washington to evacuate Boston.

1853: Christian Johann Doppler, the Austrian physicist and
mathematician who first enunciated the principle known as the Doppler
Effect, which has an important influence on radar, navigation and
astronomy, dies at the age of 50.

1886: Vincent van Gogh, the 33-year-old Dutch post-impressionist
painter who had been studying at an art gallery in Antwerp, comes to
Paris to further his training. His works were to include "The Potato
Eaters" and "Starry Night," but his long struggle with depression was
to end in suicide at the age of only 37.

1888: Britain sets up a protectorate over Sarawak on Borneo.

1906: A strong earthquake rocks the area between Chiayi and
Toulio, killing more than 1,100, injuring nearly 2,000 and destroying
some 6,700 houses.

1939: British Prime Minister Neville Chamberlain accuses Adolf
Hitler of breaking his word after German forces cross the Czech
frontier.

1942: American Gen. Douglas MacAthur arrives in Australia and
sets up headquarters in Melbourne.

1946: Tai Li, director of the Investigation and Statistics Bureau
under the National Military Council, is killed when a plane flying
from Tsingtao to Nanking crashes. He was 50.

1959: Skate, a U.S. submarine, surfaces at the North Pole after
completing a historic voyage under ice to reach its destination.

1959: People in Tibet launch a major uprising against mainland
Chinese rule as the Dalai Lama flees Lasha in disguise.

1963: Mount Agung on the Indonesian island of Bali erupts,
killing more than 11,000 people.

1969: Golda Meir, a 70-year-old grandmother, takes office as
Israel's first female prime minister.

1973: More than six million eligible voters go to the polls in
Taiwan to elect county and city councilors, mayors and township
chiefs for terms of four years.

1973: Yu Chin-hsien and Chou Po-lien are sworn in as president
and vice president of the Control Yuan.

1973: Henry Kearns, president of the Export-Import Bank of the
United States, signs loan agreements with the Taiwan Railway
Administration and the Taiwan Fertilizer Corporation.

1974: Dr. Harrison S. Brown, vice president of the international
Council of Scientific Union and foreign secretary of the U.S. Academy
of Science, arrives in Taipei for a five-day visit.

1974: Leo G. de Grijs, senior vice president of the Continental
Bankof Chicago, arrived in Taipei for a four-day visit.

1974: The U.S. Trade Center is opened in Taipei. Premier Chiang
Ching-kuo attended the opening ceremony at which U.S. Undersecretary
of Commerce John Tabor presided.

1975: Chu Fu-sung, ambassador to the Republic of Korea, presents
his credentials to President Park Chung Hee.

1975: Maj. Gen. Carl W. Hoffman, commander of the U.S. Third
Marine Amphibious Force, arrives in Taipei for a three-day visit.

1976: Y. S. Sun, minister of economic affairs, tells the Taipei
American Chamber of Commerce that foreign investment is still welcome
in Taiwan.

1978: The tanker Amoco Cardiz runs aground off the coast of
Brittany, France, and then splits in two, releasing its massive cargo
of crude oil.

1990: Thousands of university students stage a sit-down protest
at Chiang Kai-shek Memorial Hall to express opposition to the
National Assembly's attempt to expand its authority.

1997: Madame Chiang Kai-shek celebrates her 100th birthday.

1998: Zhu Rongji is elected mainland China's premier with a
mandate to overhaul ailing banks and crumbling state industries.

2000: Lee Ching-hua, head of the New Party's national election
and development committee, announces that he is quitting his post as
convenor of the party and withdrawing his party membership in support
of independent presidential candidate James Soong.

2001: The World Taiwanese Congress, an umbrella organization of
60-odd pro-Taiwan indpendence groups that was founded in December
2000, opens its first annual meeting in Taipei.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "While sitting in court (as chief
justice), in deciding upon the suits that come before me, I am no
better than other men. But what I always try to do is to make even
the suits unnecessary."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040318.0001" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
ELECTION WORKERS TO BE GRANTED TWO DAYS OF LEAVE: CEC
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 18 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Central Election Commission (CEC)
announced Thursday that all election affairs staff working this
weekend will be given two days of leave to be used anytime after the
election.
</P>
<P>
More than 16 million ROC citizens are eligible to vote in the
March 20 presidential election as well as to cast ballots in Taiwan's
first-ever nationwide referendum.
</P>
<P>
The election staff's workload is expected to be heavier than
usual as the nationwide referendum, on missile defense and relations
with mainland China, will be held simultaneously with the
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The CEC has thus decided to give staff working this weekend two
days of leave, a CEC official said, adding that this special
privilege is for this election only.
</P>
<P>
According to the last available poll results which were released
10 days ahead of election day, incumbent President Chen Shui-bian and
Vice President Annette Lu were running neck and neck with the
opposition "pan-blue alliance" ticket of Kuomintang Chairman Lien
Chan and People First Party Chairman James Soong.
</P>
<P>
In the referendum, voters will be asked two questions:
</P>
<P>
1. The people of Taiwan demand that the Taiwan Strait issue be
resolved through peaceful means. Should mainland China refuse to
withdraw the missiles it has targeted at Taiwan and to openly
renounce the use of force against us, do you agree that the
government should acquire more advanced anti-missile weapons to
strengthen Taiwan's self-defense capabilities?
</P>
<P>
2. Do you agree that our government should engage in negotiations
with mainland China on the establishment of a "peace and stability"
framework for cross-Taiwan Strait interactions in order to build
consensus and for the welfare of the peoples of both sides?
</P>
<P>
According to the Referendum Act passed last November, the
referendum will be rendered invalid if fewer than 50 percent of
eligible voters collect a referendum ballot. Taking a ballot, whether
it is then cast or not, is counted as participation in the
referendum. And the referendum is approved if more than 50 percent of
those who take part cast "yes" votes.
</P>
<P>
A total of 16,497,746 voters are eligible to vote in the
referendum. Results are expected by 10 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
