<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040318.0016" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT URGES FIRST-TIME VOTERS TO CAST BALLOTS IN REFERENDUM
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 17 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian urged Thursday
those who have reached the age of suffrage for the first time to cast
their ballots in the country's first-ever nationwide referendum to be
held alongside Saturday's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Chen, who is seeking re-election, made the appeal to the 1.04
million first-time voters, most of whom are college students.
</P>
<P>
"No matter which ticket you vote for in the presidential
election, please be sure to cast your ballots in the referendum on
missile defense and relations with mainland China, " Chen said at a
news conference.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the international community will be watching Taiwan's
referendum carefully, Chen said he hopes voters will take part in the
referendum to show the world their determination to safeguard their
homeland and make peace with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
According to the Referendum Act passed last November, the
president is authorized to call a "defensive referendum" when he
deems Taiwan's sovereignty to be under external threat.
</P>
<P>
Chen said the mainland's deployment of 496 missiles aimed at
Taiwan constitutes a national security threat and therefore decided
to hold a referendum to coincide with the presidential poll.
</P>
<P>
Opposition presidential contender Lien Chan, chairman of the
Kuomintang, who is running neck-and-neck with Chen, has claimed that
the referendum "illegal and meaningless" and the "pan-blue alliance"
of the KMT and the People First Party is airing advertisements urging
supporters not to vote in the referendum.
</P>
<P>
The referendum will ask voters two questions:
</P>
<P>
1. Should mainland China refuse to withdraw the missiles it has
targeted at Taiwan and openly renounce the use of force against
us, would you agree that the government should acquire more advanced
anti-missile weapons to strengthen Taiwan's self-defense
capabilities?
</P>
<P>
2. Would you agree that our government should engage in
negotiation with mainland China on the establishment of a
"peace and stability" framework for cross-strait interaction
in order to build consensus and for the welfare of the people
on both sides?
</P>
<P>
The referendum will be rendered void if fewer than 50 percent of
voters collect a referendum ballot. Picking up a paper ballot
constitutes taking part in the referendum. The referendum is
approved if more than 50 percent of those who take part cast "yes"
votes. A total of 16,497,746 voters are eligible to vote in the
referendum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040318.0017" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL DONATION BILL CLEARS LEGISLATURE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 18 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Political figures will not be allowed to
accept political donations during non-election periods and only those
who intend to run in an election will be able to do so, according to
a political donation bill passed by the Legislative Yuan Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, neither political parties, groups, nor election
aspirants can accept political donations without prior approval from
the government, and any approved donations must be paid into special
accounts in financial institutions or the Post Office.
</P>
<P>
The bill also stipulates that there is no ceiling on the total
amount of political donations and that in terms of the period in
which donations can be accepted, a president can accept political
donations one year before his term expires, legislators can accept
donations up to 10 months before their term expires, and elected
mayors, city councilors, magistrates and county councilors can accept
donations up to eight months before their term expires.
</P>
<P>
An individual can donate a maximum of NT$300,000 (US$8,982) ,
while civic groups can donate at most NT$2 million and businesses can
give no more than NT$3 million to the same political party or
political group.
</P>
<P>
The legislative caucuses of the ruling Democratic Progressive
Party and its ally, the Taiwan Solidarity Union, had proposed that
political parties should not be allowed to donate more than a quarter
of the maximum election campaign fees to an election aspirant.
</P>
<P>
When the proposal was put to the vote, however, it failed to
pass, with 105 against it compared with 91 in favor and one
abstention.
</P>
<P>
The bill was passed amid revelations by several figures,
including disgraced former Tuntex Group Chairman Chen You-hao, that
they have made political donations to various political figures,
which sparked debate about the practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
