</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Keelung,   March  18  (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
All 15 crew members aboard a
Panama-registered freighter that ran aground off the northern Taiwan
coast Thursday have been rescued, coast guard officials said later
that day.
</P>
<P>
According to the officials, the cargo ship was transporting 5,500
tons of gravel from mainland China's southeastern port city of Fuzhou
to the Japanese island of Okinawa when it ran aground off Yehliu in
northern Taipei County at around 2:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
Three coast guard patrol ships braved rough seas and high winds
to reach the stricken vessel as soon as the Keelung coast guard
office received a distress call from the grounded freighter
identified as the "Shuntong."
</P>
<P>
All of the crew are mainland Chinese citizens. Tan Dehzhou, the
freighter's captain, said he and his colleagues are all very grateful
for the Taiwan coast guard rescue. Tan said the freighter ran aground
mainly because of a mechanical failure. If the weather conditions
improve, he went on, the vessel is not expected to sink or leak oil
for the time being. "I have informed the shipping firm, which will
handle the case," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Keelung coast guard office said it has assigned patrol ships
to monitor whether there is any oil leakage from the ill-fated
vessel. "We have also prepared contingency measures to prevent any
oil leakage and pollution of nearby waters," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040318.0023" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
DPP LEGISLATOR COMES FORWARD TO SPEAK ON POLITICAL DONATIONS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 18 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Legislator Shen Fu-hsiung of the ruling
Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) on Thursday broke his silence
regarding his alleged role in the political donation case that
prompted the first lady to file a libel suit against a fugitive
tycoon.
</P>
<P>
Shen fell short of saying outright that he was the one who had
accompanied disgraced former Tuntex chairman Chen You-hao on a visit
in 1994 to the wife of Chen Shui-bian to present her with a donation
to help with the mayoral campaign of her husband.
</P>
<P>
With only two days to go before the March 20 presidential
election, Shen said that the focus of the presidential campaign
blurred because of the attention being paid to an event that happened
10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
He appealed for a return to normal, saying that both the ruling
and opposition presidential candidates should stage a "high-class"
election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Shen made the remarks in a news conference called at the
Legislative Yuan in response to the tycoon-turned-fugitive's
statement in a Sunday news conference held in Los Angeles where Chen
You-hao said that the "DPP heavyweight" he had mentioned earlier was
Shen. Chen You-hao said he and Shen visited Chen Shui-bian's wife
twice at her home and presented her with NT$3 million (US$89,820).
</P>
<P>
Although first lady Wu Shu-chen had denied Chen You-hao's
allegations, Shen said, "My memory of the matter differs from that of
the first lady."
</P>
<P>
Shen had refused to comment on the matter after Chen You-hao's
statement in spite of rumors that his silence was a tacit admission
of his complicity.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the question as to whether he went to the first lady's
home or not, Shen said that there were "four possibilities."
</P>
<P>
The first one is that he did in fact visit the first lady, Shen
said, but remained ambiguous by adding, "This is the reasonable
answer that most people would give, although the three other
possibilities cannot be ruled out."
</P>
<P>
The second scenario is that he didn't go, but he thought he did.
The third is that he didn't go, but is deliberately trying to frame
the first lady - a very unlikely scenario, and the fourth is that he
is sick and suffered from delusions.
</P>
<P>
Shen said that the most likely scenario is that he did go, and if
he must testify in court, he will go willingly.
</P>
<P>
On the part of the first lady, Shen said the problem is that Wu
simply has no memory of the event. The first lady has already filed a
libel suit at the Taipei Prosecutors' Office over the matter.
</P>
<P>
Shen said that regarding the first lady, there are three other
possibilities, one being that Wu has totally forgotten the incident
and would, therefore, pass a polygraph test. The second is that she
maliciously concealed the fact that the visit was made, which is very
unlikely, and the third is that Wu had indeed forgotten but now
remembers but is choosing not to recall the incident out of good
intentions. This last case is something that an average person would
be able to come out and admit, but being the wife of the head of
state, this may be difficult to do, he said.
</P>
<P>
Shen refused to comment on any of the three possibilities.
</P>
<P>
Shen said that the Tuntex Group was one of the top-10
conglomerates a decade ago, and Chen You-hao's donation was made "out
of respect for the individual, " and the recipient was full of
gratitude. Shen said he was "an innocent bystander, " and can't
understand how the whole thing has turned so vicious during the
presidential election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Shen said that his original intention had been to say nothing
about the matter until after the March 20 election, but given the way
the situation had "disappointed" him, he decided to come forward.
</P>
<P>
He said that if he had not come forward, the situation would be
further blown out of proportion with a media circus surrounding him
as if he were running for president.
</P>
<P>
Shen said that he and Chen You-hao are not good friends and are
not in regular contact and that neither Chen You-hao nor anyone else
have "any evidence of illegal dealings" by him, although Chen You-hao
did make " generous political donations" to him during elections.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the reactions of various political parties were mixed
after Shen's news conference.
</P>
<P>
Chiou I-jen, re-election campaign manager for President Chen
Shui-bian, said that the DPP will respect the differences in memory
of Shen and the first lady. As the case is now in court, Wu is
willing to take "a scientific approach" on the different memory
issue.
</P>
<P>
DPP Legislator Hung Chi-chang said that an event that took place
a decade ago should not become the focus of the presidential campaign
today. His legislative colleague, Tsai Huang-lang, said that Shen had
given the voters a lesson on how to return to real issues in the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan Solidarity Union (TSU), an ally of the DPP, said that
Shen's explanation should have a positive effect on the DPP's
election campaign since it will show the difference between the DPP
and the opposition Kuomintang, as the DPP will face the facts.
</P>
<P>
TSU Secretary-General Lin Chi-chia said that Shen's words echoed
those of Lee Yuan-tseh, the president of Academia Sinica and the
nation's only Nobel laureate, who said that the DPP, although lacking
in experience in ruling the country, nevertheless has more momentum
to move forward than the opposition Kuomintang (KMT).
</P>
<P>
The KMT said that it had no comment on Shen's statement, saying
that the KMT and its ally, the People First Party, will not interfere
with the matter between President Chen, Legislator Shen and Chen
You-hao.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
