<HEADLINE>
2004 TAIPEI INTERNATIONAL PLASTICS AND RUBBER INDUSTRY SHOW OPENS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 18 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 2004 Taipei International Plastics and
Rubber Industry Show opened Thursday at the Taiwan World Trade
Center.
</P>
<P>
A total of 344 companies from around the world are showing their
products at 1,818 booths during the four-day event, said a spokesman
for the Taiwan External Trade Development Council (TAITRA), which is
jointly sponsoring the fair with the Taiwan Association of Machinery
Industry.
</P>
<P>
Well-known world-class companies, such as Toshiba, Matsui and Shi
Plastics from Japan and those from the France, Italy, the United
States and South Korea, are also participating in the show.
</P>
<P>
The biennial show, the largest of its kind in Asia, provides good
access for buyers of plastics and rubber processing machinery,
engineering components and auxiliary components in the plastics and
rubber machinery trade.
</P>
<P>
According to the TAITRA official, the domestic industry is an
important export business for the country. Following the developments
over the past 30 years, the industry's exports last year set a new
high of US$768 million, he said, adding that its export value will
continue to grow this year out of keen demand from foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
Demand from Mainland China, India, Turkey, Brazil and South
American countries for Taiwan-made plastics and rubber machinery is
particularly strong because of their good quality and reasonable
prices, he noted.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of the show, the TAITRA will also sponsor three
seminars to provide the latest trade information about the markets in
Brazil, Turkey, India and Pakistan to businesses wishing to break
into these markets.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, foreign-based professional magazines, including
Plastics &amp; Rubber Asia from Britain, Injection Molding Magazine from
the United States and Plastics Info World from Japan, have sent
reporters to cover the show, the spokesman added.
</P>
</TEXT>
