<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN POPULAR AMONG OVERSEAS FILIPINO WORKERS: ROC ENVOY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Manila,  March 18 (CNA)
(By Emerson Lin and Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan is a popular choice among the many
Filipino workers wishing to work overseas, due to a handsome salary,
geographic proximity, political stability and a democratic
environment, according to the Republic of China Representative to the
Philippines Wu Shin-hsing.
</P>
<P>
Wu made the remarks in a recent program recorded on the OFW Hour,
a program produced by the RPN TV station, during an interview in
which Wu spoke about the lives of Filipino workers in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Citing ROC government statistics, Wu said there were a total of
81,895 Filipino workers in Taiwan as of the end of January, with 34
percent of them serving as caregivers, 63 percent working in the
manufacturing sector and the remaining 3 percent employed as maids
and construction workers.
</P>
<P>
Some 71 percent of the Filipino workers in Taiwan, or 58,192
people, are women, and the laborers from the Philippines form the
second-largest group of foreign workers in Taiwan only after the
103,000 Thai workers, he further pointed out.
</P>
<P>
When asked why many returning Philippine workers would like to
work in Taiwan again, Wu said it was because of the good pay, the
closeness of the two countries, the political stability, and Taiwan's
democracy and legal protection.
</P>
<P>
However, Wu pointed out that the ROC government might adjust the
number of foreign workers imported to Taiwan depending on its
economic situation. Alien workers will be allowed mainly in to
Taiwan's manufacturing, construction, and fishery sectors, or to
serve as domestic maids and caregivers in the coming few years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040318.0030" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TSU HAILS PASSAGE OF POLITICAL CONTRIBUTIONS ACT
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 18 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Taiwan Solidarity Union (TSU) hailed
the passage of the much-anticipated Political Contributions Act
Thursday, saying the legislation marks a step forward in the
establishment of clean politics.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the passage of the new act as it is long overdue, "
said TSU legislative whip Chen Chien-ming.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Chen said he feels regret that the act fails to
regulate political party assets due to a deliberate dodge and boycott
by the opposition "pan-blue alliance" of the Kuomintang (KMT) and the
People First Party (PFP).
</P>
<P>
Chen claimed that the KMT's huge party assets have hindered fair
competition among domestic political parties. To remedy this
deficiency, he said, the TSU, a pro-Taiwan ally of the ruling
Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) will push for the early passage of
other "sunshine bills, " including the political party bill and the
legislative lobby bill.
</P>
<P>
Chen said the political party bill must prohibit all local
parties from operating profit-making businesses to ensure
fair inter-party competition. He also urged the KMT to return all of
its ill-gotten assets to the national coffers to substantiate its vow
to push for clean politics.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ruling DPP legislative caucus said it is
regrettable that the newly passed Political Contributions Act fails
to restrict political parties from donating funds to those who intend
to run for public office.
</P>
<P>
"While we are happy to see that our long-term efforts to push
this legislation has finally borne fruit, we feel regret that the act
fails to impose a ceiling on political parties' financial
contributions to individual candidates, " said DPP Legislator Chao
Yung-ching.
</P>
<P>
Claiming that the KMT, one of the world's wealthiest parties, has
traditionally granted huge funds to its candidates, Chao said the
absence of a ceiling on donations from political parties has created
a loophole in the new act.
</P>
<P>
"This sunshine law fails to shed light on political party funds.
I'm worried that this may lead to grave consequences," Chao said.
</P>
<P>
During the second reading of the bill at Thursday's legislative
session, the DPP proposed to add a clause to the bill stipulating
that political party contributions should not exceed 25 percent of
individual candidates' total campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
The proposal failed to clear the legislative floor due to the
opposition of the "pan-blue alliance" which controls a majority in
the Legislative Yuan.
</P>
<P>
KMT legislative whip Liao Feng-teh said the DPP-proposed
restriction violated the principle of party politics. "It's
unreasonable to restrict political parties from donating funds to
individual candidates," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
PFP Legislator Lee Yung-ping echoed Liao's views, saying that
restrictions on political parties' donations to individual candidates
will encourage hopefuls to forge ties with business groups. "Such
practices could lead to favoritism and corrupt deals," Lee claimed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Liao said the KMT will put all of its profit-making
businesses into a "blind trust" in the near future.
</P>
<P>
To show its commitment to establishing clean politics, Liao said
the KMT had thrown support behind a DPP-proposed amendment to the
Political Contributions Act which bans political party-owned
enterprises from donating funds to political parties, political
groups and individual candidates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
