<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040318.0035" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 18 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Thursday, March 18, or the
28th day of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according
to the lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that
have occurred on this date in the past:

1455: Fra Angelico, also known as Giovanni da Fiesole, an Italian
Dominican friar and religious painter of the Florentine school, dies
at the age of 55.

1662: The first public bus service is inaugurated in Paris,
France.

1745: Robert Walpole, English politician who as first Lord of the
Treasury and Chancellor of the Exchequer led the Whig administration.
Walpole is regarded as Britain's first prime minister, although the
office was not officially recognized until 1905, dies at the age of
69.

1858: Rudolf Diesel, German engineer and pioneer of the modern
car engine, is born.

1869: Neville Chamberlain: British politician and prime minister
from 1937 to 1940 who advocated a policy of appeasement toward the
fascist regimes of Europe, is born.

1890: Otto von Bismarck, the Germany chancellor who governed
Prussia and later Germany with a policy of "blood and iron" since
1862, is dismissed from his post by Kaiser Wilhelm II.

1922: India's Mahatma Gandhi is sentenced to six years in jail
for his civil disobedience campaign.

1926: Guard units under the orders of Tuan Chi-jui, provisional
chief executive of the Peking-based government, open fire at citizens
and students who went to Tien An Men to make a petition, killing 47
and injuring 160. The incident becomes known as "March 18 Tragedy".
Tuan resigned on April 9, 1926.

1932: Chiang Kai-shek becomes chairman of the National Military
Council and concurrently chief of the general staff.

1936: F. W. de Klerk, South African president who initiated the
reforms which led to the end of apartheid and co-winner of 1993 Nobel
Peace Prize, is born.

1940: Adolf Hitler and Benito Mussolini meet at the Brenner Pass
in the Alps, agreeing that Italy would eventually join the war.

1949: The United States and Western European countries establish
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).

1962: Chi Ju-shan, a great master of Peking opera, dies of a
heart attack in Taipei at the age of 86.

1965: Soviet cosmonaut Aleksei Leonov becomes the first man to
float in space as he leaves his orbiting spacecraft and dances and
somersaults in orbit hundreds of miles above the earth, secured only
by a slender lifeline.

1967: Soviet Union expels two Beijing diplomats from Moscow,
charging them with anti-Soviet activity.

1969: American President Richard Nixon orders a secret bombing
campaign of Cambodia.

1970: Prince Norodom Sihanouk is deposed as chief of state of
Cambodia while on a visit to Moscow.

1990: East German holds its first democratic elections, paving
the way for the unification of Germany.

1996: The Chinese mainland begins eight days of war games
involving ground, air, and naval forces in seas 85 kilometers
northwest of Taiwan proper.

1997: Former chairman of the US Joint Chiefs of Staff General
Colin L. Powell visits the ROC.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "Be patient in maturing your plans
and then carry them out with conscientiousness."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040319.0001" type="multi" >
