<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL HEADLINE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Manila, March 19 (CNA)
(By Emerson T. Lim)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Manila Bulletin: Erap
allowed to visit mother.
The Sandiganbayan Special Division granted yesterday
afternoon former President Joseph Estrada a 36-hour
special pass to visit his 98-year-old ailing mother,
Dona Mary Ejercito, who is now confined at San Juan
Medical Center.

The Philippine Daily Inquirer: Estrada speaks at
Poe rally.
DETENTION at an Army camp is not stopping deposed
President Joseph Estrada from campaigning on behalf
for his friend Fernando Poe Jr. As 15,000 people
swarmed to a rally for Poe in Iligan City, a live
interview with Estrada over a radio station was piped
in over the public address system. In it, he endorsed
the actor and political novice known by his initials
FPJ.

The Philippine Star: Buried alive.
NASIPIT, Agusan del Norte -- Up to thirty people
were buried alive under broken slabs of concrete and
steel while three others were killed after a huge
wood-drying kiln they were salvaging steel bars from
collapsed on them the other day.

The Manila Times: GMA warns of 'dark ages'
THE poll campaign heated up on Thursday with the two
leading presidential candidates -- President Arroyo and
the movie actor Fernando Poe Jr. -- trading barbs not
heard before.
