<HEADLINE>
PREMIER URGES PUBLIC TO REMAIN CALM AFTER SHOOTING INCIDENT
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 19 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Premier Yu Shyi-kun urged all local
citizens Friday to calm down and support the government after
President Chen Shui-bian and Vice President Annette Lu were shot
while on the campaign trail in southern Taiwan ahead of Saturday's
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Yu made the appeal after presiding over a meeting of the National
Security Council on behalf of President Chen.
</P>
<P>
While campaigning in the southern city of Tainan in the
afternoon, Chen was grazed in the stomach and Lu was hit in the right
knee.
</P>
<P>
"Their injuries were not life threatening," Yu said, adding that
local people need not be panicked. "President Chen still can
direct national affairs and the administration is operating
normally."
</P>
<P>
Yu said the Central Election Commission has announced that the
presidential election and the nation's first-ever referendum will be
held Saturday as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
The premier further said the national security mechanism has been
activated to maintain law and order and social stability in the wake
of the unprecedented shooting incident. The MInistry of Foreign
Affairs has also briefed foreign envoys stationed in Taiwan on the
incident.
</P>
<P>
This marked the first time that an ROC president has been shot.
Yu said he feels deep regret over the incident. He said the National
Police Administration under the Ministry of the Interior has formed a
special task force to investigate the case.
</P>
<P>
"We'll do every possible effort to bring to justice all those who
were involved in the shooting incident," Yu said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Legislative Yuan President Wang Jin-pyng, who
concurrently serves as the campaign manager of the opposition
"pan-blue alliance's" presidential candidate Kuomintang Chairman Lien
Chan, said he believes the people of Taiwan will be able to weather
through this crisis smoothly.
</P>
<P>
As to whether the incident will have any impact on the
presidential poll, Wang said it remains unclear. He would not go
into details.
</P>
<P>
Former President Lee Teng-hui, who has been campaigning hard for
President Chen's re-election bid, was reportedly in tears after
hearing of the shooting incident. Taiwan Solidarity Union
President Huang Chu-wen quoted Lee as having called on local people
to remain calm and rational at this moment.
</P>
<P>
About five hours after the shooting, the president left the
hospital to return to Taipei.
</P>
<P>
Chen and Lu were riding in a red convertible four-wheel-drive
vehicle and waving to crowds lining the streets in Tainan when
shots were fired into their motorcade. People were setting off
celebratory fireworks as he drove by and early media reports said he
was injured by firecrackers.
</P>
<P>
Doctors showed pictures of an 11-centimeter-long wound just under
Chen's navel. Chan Chi-hsien, head of Chi Mei Hospital in Tainan where
Chen was treated, said there was no injury to internal organs.
</P>
<P>
The bullet grazed the vice president's right knee, leaving a
wound about two centimeters, he said, adding that the bullet caused
no bone fractures and it wasn't found.
</P>
</TEXT>
