<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATURE DOWNSIZING PROPOSAL TO BE SUBJECT TO FURTHER DISCUSSION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  19 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Legislative Yuan failed to pass a
constitutional amendment bill to halve the number of legislative
seats from 2008 Friday as scheduled, due to an opposition from
independent lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
The legislature was originally scheduled to complete second and
third readings of the much-anticipated constitutional amendment bill
at its last plenary session ahead of Saturday's presidential election
to pave the way for legislative downsizing.
</P>
<P>
However, an alliance of independent lawmakers came up with a
motion demanding that the constitutional amendment bill be further
discussed to mend what it calls some deficiencies in the draft bill.
</P>
<P>
According to the legislature's operational rules, a bill should
be referred to negotiations among the various parties if any of the
political factions in the legislature request such a move. If
consensus is still elusive after four months of negotiation, a bill
could be put to the vote anyway.
</P>
<P>
In response to the independent lawmakers' request, Legislative
Yuan President Wang Jin-pyng then announced that the constitutional
amendment bill should be subject to further inter-party consultations
before a second reading can be held. He also ordered the two largest
parties in the legislature -- the ruling Democratic Progressive Party
(DPP) and the opposition Kuomintang (KMT) -- to jointly organize a
consultative session on the bill within four months.
</P>
<P>
The DPP legislative caucus blamed the opposition "pan-blue
alliance" of the KMT and the People First Party (PFP) for the failure
to pass the constitutional amendment bill before the presidential
poll. The "pan-blue alliance" controls a majority in the 225-seat
legislature.
</P>
<P>
"We feel regret that the 'pan-blue alliance' failed to honor its
promise to pass the constitutional amendment bill regarding
legislative seats reduction before the presidential poll as the first
step toward legislative reform, " said DPP legislative whip Tsai
Huang-lang.
</P>
<P>
According to the constitutional amendment bill that passed the
first reading last week, the number of legislative seats will be cut
to 113 from the current 225 from the seventh-term legislature to be
elected in 2008, and the legislative tenure will be extended to four
years from the current three years. According to the bill, there
should be at least 34 women legislators and the number of at-large
legislators should be set at 34.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
