JAPAN URGED TO MAKE TAIWAN STRATEGIC PARTNER
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Tokyo,  March 19 (CNA)
(By Perry Hsieh and Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Japan should give deeper thought to its
relations with mainland China and should make Taiwan an important
strategic partner of Japan, a world renowned Japanese sociologist has
said.
</P>
<P>
Mineo Nakajima, former president of the Tokyo University of
Foreign Studies, was quoted by the Sankei Shimbun newspaper Friday as
saying that although the People's Republic of China has continued to
adhere to its "one China" policy, the PRC has not ruled Taiwan for a
single day.
</P>
<P>
Nakajima, also a famed political commentator in Japan, said
during a speech Thursday that Japan and Taiwan are virtually "one
body of esprit de corps " and that if Taiwan were annexed by the
mainland, it would definitely result in major damage to Japan's
interests.
</P>
<P>
Saying that the mainland is not a "trustworthy" opponent,
Nakajima said Beijing's increase of its defense budget by a whopping
11 percent is worrisome.
</P>
<P>
He called for the Japanese government, as well as the Japanese
private sector, not to be fooled by the mainland's "false impression
of success, " including its scheduled hosting of the Olympic Games in
2008 and the mammoth Three Gorges dam on the Yangze River.
</P>
<P>
He added that the mainland's freewheeling economy has now
encountered a bottleneck and that the country will face an economic
bubble sooner or later.
</P>
</TEXT>
