</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 19 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The National Police Administration (NPA)
inaugurated Friday a cyber national united law enforcement command
headquarters, which is designed to allow the NPA authorities to be in
full control of public order islandwide before, during and after
Saturday's presidential election and referendum.
</P>
<P>
NPA Director-General Chang Si-liang presided over a meeting at
the NPA headquarters Friday on nationwide law enforcement
preparedness during the crucial election days, and on the possible
impact on the country's law and order caused by the election and
referendum.
</P>
<P>
Chang talked via teleconference with authorities from police
headquarters scattered throughout Pingtung, Kaohsiung, Yunlin, Chiayi
counties and Kaohsiung City in Taiwan proper, as well as the outlying
counties of Kinmen and Lienchiang to gain a better understanding of
the public order situation in those areas on the eve of the election.
</P>
<P>
He instructed police authorities around the nation to prepare
themselves for any contingencies in the event of scuffles or
post-election riots.
</P>
<P>
Chang said the cyber national united law enforcement command
headquarters will oversee public order nationwide in real time in
three areas: public security, transportation and communications and
supervisory.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, officers from the NPA's public security division said
that in light of reports that international terrorists have included
Taiwan as a target, the NPA has heightened surveillance nationwide,
particularly in public places where people tend to converge.
</P>
<P>
Stepped-up surveillance attention will also be paid at public
transportation systems, infrastructure systems, airports and
seaports, NPA officials said.
</P>
