<HEADLINE>
PREMIER TO COORDINATE WITH  TV STATION OVER EXIT POLLS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 19 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Premier Yu Shyi-kun said Friday that the
government will do everything possible to coordinate with a local
television station that had earlier said it will conduct exit polls
on Saturday's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a radio interview, Yu said that although there is no
law prohibiting the conducting of exit polls, the Executive Yuan is
worried about the possibility of "incidents" erupting between the
unveiling of exit polls and the formal announcement of the election
results.
</P>
<P>
Yu said that exit polls have never been conducted in Taiwan
before and that there is no law prohibiting them. The problem, he
went on, is that this is a bitterly contested election and the
government has to take a lot factors into consideration.
</P>
<P>
The premier said that an earlier decision by the Central Election
Commission (CEC) to count as valid any presidential ballots miscast
in the referendum ballot boxes and vice versa has triggered concern
that incidents could erupt between the opening of the ballots and the
formal announcement of the election results.
</P>
<P>
The CEC later reversed its decision to allow an earlier
announcement of the presidential result.
</P>
<P>
The premier said that if the cable television station unveils its
exit poll right after the polling stations close at 4 p.m Saturday,
then there will be still two to three hours before the formal
announcement of the election result, and the administration is
worried that there could be disturbances during this period.
</P>
</TEXT>
