<HEADLINE>
ESTABLISHING NATIONAL IDENTITY  HISTORIC MISSION: PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Hong Kong,  March 19 (CNA)
(By Stanley Cheung and Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian said Friday
that his "historic mission and obligation" as the nation's leader is
to establish the identity of Taiwan as a national leader.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with CNN aired Friday morning, Chen said he is
happy that support for a separate Taiwanese identify has increased
over the years.
</P>
<P>
On relations with mainland China, Chen said that Taiwan has to
establish its national identity, including the independence of its
economy, which he said is very important.
</P>
<P>
If Taiwan loses its national identity, it will reach a dead end
and there will be no future cross-strait relations and no respect for
the will and choice of the 23 million people of Taiwan, he said.
</P>
<P>
The president said that the status quo of Taiwan is a historic
evolution and that his past statements on the country's status have
simply been telling the facts without changing them.
</P>
<P>
More specifically, he said, Taiwan's relationship with China is a
"state to state" one.
</P>
<P>
On concern by the United States over Saturday's referendum -- the
first nationwide referendum in Taiwan -- Chen said that Taiwan has
continued to watch the views of the U.S. government and the feelings
of the U.S. people while promoting democracy.
</P>
<P>
He said that relations between Taiwan and the United States are
definitely one of democratic allies and added that Taiwan will not
become a liability of the United States but an asset.
</P>
