</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040319.0036" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
SNUB TO REFERENDUM WOULD HURT CONSENSUS-BUILDING: MAC
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 19 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A snub to Taiwan's first-ever nationwide
referendum to be held alongside Saturday's presidential election will
hinder the establishment of a consensus-building system in Taiwan, a
Mainland Affairs Council (MAC) official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular news conference, MAC Vice Chairman Chen
Ming-tong said that if the historic referendum is rendered void
because more than 50 percent of eligible voters refuse to take part,
it will hurt Taiwan's consensus-building through referendum.
</P>
<P>
Worse still, Chen said, the result could cause a setback in the
development of cross-Taiwan Strait relations.
</P>
<P>
"Mainland China will interpret the invalid referendum as evidence
of the Taiwan people's lack of consensus on national defense and on
the development of cross-strait ties, " Chen explained, adding that
the scenario will give room for Beijing to drive a wedge between the
Taiwan people.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chen went on, a null referendum will give the
international community the impression that the people of Taiwan are
divided. "Should that be the case, foreign friends' support for our
cause may decrease," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the Referendum Act passed last November, the
president is authorized to call a "defensive referendum" when he
deems Taiwan's sovereignty to be under external threat.
</P>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian said after the passage of the Referendum
Act that mainland China's deployment of 496 missiles aimed at Taiwan
constitutes a national security threat and therefore decided to hold
a referendum to coincide with the March 20 presidential poll.
</P>
<P>
Opposition presidential contender Lien Chan, chairman of the
Kuomintang, who is challenging Chen's re-election bid, has claimed
that the referendum is "illegal and meaningless" and the "pan-blue
alliance" of the KMT and the People First Party is airing
advertisements urging supporters not to vote in the referendum.
</P>
<P>
The referendum will ask voters two questions:
</P>
<P>
1. Should mainland China refuse to withdraw the missiles it has
targeted at Taiwan and openly renounce the use of force against
us, would you agree that the government should acquire more advanced
anti-missile weapons to strengthen Taiwan's self-defense
capabilities?
</P>
<P>
2. Would you agree that our government should engage in
negotiation with mainland China on the establishment of a
"peace and stability" framework for cross-strait interaction
in order to build consensus and for the welfare of the people
on both sides?
</P>
<P>
The referendum will be rendered null and void if fewer than 50
percent of voters collect a referendum ballot. Picking up a paper
ballot constitutes taking part in the referendum. The referendum is
approved if more than 50 percent of those who take part cast "yes"
votes.
</P>
<P>
During Friday's news conference, MAC Vice Chairman Chen was asked
if the referendum is valid, but more than half the voters cast "no"
votes, how the government will react.
</P>
<P>
Chen said since a negative reply is also a form of opinion,
such a referendum result will be "binding."
</P>
<P>
"The government will certainly respect the outcome," he claimed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
