<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040319.0045" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 19 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Friday, March 19, or the 29th
day of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according to the
lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that have
occurred on this date in the past:

721 B.C.: The Babylonians make the first-ever record of an
eclipse of the sun.

1711: War breaks out between Turkey and Russia.

1813: David Livingstone, the Scottish missionary and African
explorer who discovered the Zambezi River and Victoria Falls, is
born.

1834: Six farm workers from southern England are sentenced to
seven years' banishment to a penal colony in Australia for trying to
set up a rural trade union. The convicts are called the Tolpuddle
Martyrs after the name of their Dorset village.

1853: During the Taiping Rebellion in China, Taiping troops led
by their leader, Hung Hsiu-chuan, capture Nanking.

1858: Kang Yu-wei, the Chinese thinker who, together with Liang
Chi-chao, in 1898 initiated a reform movement that came to an
inglorious end after only 100 days and who later formed the China
Reform Association in exile in Canada, is born.

1920: The U.S. Senate votes against the United States joining the
League of Nations.

1929: Rabindranath Tagore -- the Indian poet who won the 1913
Nobel Prize in literature and who was known especially for his poetry
collection "Gitanjali," which is based on traditional Hindu themes --
arrives in Shanghai for a visit.

1930: Arthur Balfour, the British prime minister who promised
British support for a national homeland for Jews in Palestine
provided that the rights of existing communities would be
safeguarded, dies at the age of 82.

1932: The Sydney Harbor Bridge, the world's longest single-span
arched bridge, is opened in New South Wales, Australia. The bridge
has a 503-meter span, four rail tracks, a 17-meter wide road and two
footpaths.

1933: Benito Mussolini, Italian dictator, proposes a pact with
Britain, France and Germany.

1944: German troops cross the border into Hungary during World
War II.

1947: Republic of China government troops capture Yenan.

1950: Edgar Rice Burroughs, the American novelist who created
"Tarzan of the Apes" and sold more than 100 million copies of his 70
novels in 56 languages, dies at the age of 75.

1960: The third session of the first National Assembly decides to
set up a committee to study the exercise of initiatives and
referendums by the National Assembly.

1964: The Great St. Bernard Tunnel under the Alps between Italy
and Switzerland is formally opened to traffic.

1987: American TV evangelist Jim Bakker is forced to resign from
his "Praise the Lord" religious network in the southern United States
after confessing to a string of sexual adventures. In addition,
Bakker is placed under investigation for allegedly having pocketed
church funds donated by supporters.

1996: A discotheque fire kills more than 150 and injures 105
others in Manila in one of the worst fire-related disasters ever in
the Philippines.

1999: Taipei Mayor Ma Ying-jeou says that he is willing to push
for the formation of a ticket between Vice President Lien Chan and
former Taiwan Provincial Governor James Soong in Taiwan's 2000
presidential race.

2000: U.S. President Bill Clinton congratulates Chen Shui-bian on
his victory in the Republic of China's presidential election and
promises to maintain close unofficial ties with Taiwan under the
"one-China" policy, while again urging Taipei and Beijing to resolve
their differences peacefully through dialogue.

2000: Thousands of furious protesters, including members of the
Kuomintang, whose candidate lost in the previous day's presidential
election, surround the KMT headquarters to demand that President Lee
Teng-hui step down from his post as party chairman.

2001: ROC President Chen Shui-bian reaffirms his commitment to
adopting a new "middle-of-the-road" policy in dealing with relations
across the Taiwan Strait.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "A man who studies extensively the
arts and literature, and directs his studies with judgment and taste,
is not likely to get into a wrong track."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040320.0001" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CONGRESSMEN EXPRESS CONCERN TO PRESIDENT CHEN
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Washington,  March 19 (CNA)
(By Jay Chen and Huang Kwang-chun)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Four co-chairs of the United States
Congressional Taiwan Caucus sent jointly a message Friday to Republic
of China President Chen Shui-bian and Vice President Annette Lu,
expressing their concern on a failed assessination attempt of Chen
and Lu earlier that day.
</P>
<P>
Congressmen Sherrod Brown, Steve Chabot, Dana Rohrabacher and
Robert Wexler said in the message "We want to express our deepest
condolences and heartfelt concern following the tragic attempt on
your lives."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. lawmakers also condemned the violence of this attack and
expressed the hope that those individuals responsible for the assault
will be brought to the justice.
</P>
<P>
"While we are grateful to find your injuries are not
life-threatening, the violence of this attack remains fresh in our
minds, " they said, adding that "it is our hope that justice is
quickly brought to those individuals responsible for this despicable
attack."
</P>
<P>
Both Chen and Lu were injured Friday while campaigning in the
southern Taiwan city of Tainan. Their conditions were described as
stable after being treated at Chi Mei Medical Center in Tainan.
Chen's ability to govern was not impaired.
</P>
</TEXT>
