<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040320.0003" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 20 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Saturday, March 20, or the 30th
day of the second month of the Year of the Monkey according to the
lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that have
occurred on this date in the past:

1602: The Dutch East India Company receives a charter granting it
a monopoly on all trade between Holland and the lands lying between
the Cape of Good Hope and the Straits of Magellan.

1727: Sir Isaac Newton, the English mathematician and scientist
who invented differential calculus and formulated the theories of
universal gravitation, terrestrial mechanics and color, dies at the
age of 85.

1792: The French Legislative Assembly approves the use of the
guillotine as a means of capital punishment.

1815: French Emperor Napoleon Bonaparte returns to Paris as a
hero after putting behind him a dreary year of exile on the
Mediterranean island of Elba.

1896: The Ching court's first modern post office begins
operations, turning a new leaf in the history of China's postal
service. The ROC Ministry of Transportation and Communications in
1947 formally fixed March 20 as Postal Service Day.

1913: Soong Chiau-jen, acting chairman of the ROC's Kuomintang
(Nationalist Party), is gunned down by assassins and severely injured
at the northern railway station in Shanghai. He died two days later
at the age of 33.

1934: Radar is first demonstrated in Kiel Harbor, Germany, by Dr.
Rudolph Kuenhold.

1949: The S.S. Chungking, a cruiser which had earlier defected to
Communist China from the Republic of China, is sunk by ROC Air Force
warplanes off Hulu Peninsula in Liaoning Province.

1959: Tibetans stage a large-scale armed revolt in their capital
of Lhasa against the Chinese communists.

1965: A car accident on Yangmingshan in suburban Taipei kills 29
people and injures 71 others, most of them fourth-grade students and
their teachers from Yoong-An Primary School in Hsinwoo Village,
Taoyuan County.

1974: Princess Anne, the daughter of Britain's Queen Elizabeth
II, escapes unhurt after an armed man tries to kidnap her in The
Mall, London.

1976: A newly invented Chinese character computer, the "Fu Hsi
4674 Chinese Character Data Procession System," goes on display.

1990: Imelda Marcos, wife of Ferdinand Marcos, ex-president of
the Philippines, stands trial in New York for fraud.

1990: The Republic of Namibia gains independence after 75 years
of military occupation by South Africa.

1994: Mikhail Sergeyevich Gorbachev, former president of the
Soviet Union, accompanied by his wife, arrives in Taipei for a visit.

1995: A nerve gas attack in a Tokyo subway station by the
Japanese Aum Shinri Kyo religious cult kills 10 and injures more than
5,500.

1995: Sheu Yuan-dong replaces Liang Kuo-shu as governor of the
ROC's Central Bank of China.

1996: The British government acknowledges that mad cow disease
could probably be transmitted to humans.

1997: The ROC Council of Agriculture under the Executive Yuan
confirms that an epidemic of foot-and-mouth disease among the
nation's pigs has caused economic losses of more than NT$100 billion.

1999: U.S. Rep. Tom Campbell (R-Calif.) introduces a concurrent
resolution in the House of Representatives seeking to express the
feeling that all Chinese people, including those in Taiwan, deserve
to be represented in international institutions.

2000: Soong Mayling, better known as Madame Chiang Kai-shek,
marks her 103 birthday at her residence in Manhattan, New York.

2001: Taipei Mayor Ma Ying-jeou, who is currently on a four-day
visit to Singapore, meets with senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew to
exchange views on relations between Taiwan and mainland China.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "A good and wise man encourages men
to develop the good qualities in their nature; whereas, a bad man and
a fool does the very opposite."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040320.0004" type="multi" >
