<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040320.0010" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
DPP CAMP URGES CALM AND HUMILITY AFTER VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  20 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The winning camp of President Chen
Shui-bian has called for its supporters to be humble and embrace
those with different ideals after Chen won by a narrow margin in the
hotly contested presidential election Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Central Election Commission announced that President Chen won
50.12 percent of the valid ballots, or 6,471,970 votes, while his
challenger, Lien Chan, won 49.88 percent, or 6,442,452 votes.
</P>
<P>
Officials from Chen's campaign headquarters urged the president's
supporters to be calm and humble and "once again embrace your
brethren with different ideals" on this night of victory.
</P>
<P>
Lin Chia-lung, spokesman for the Executive Yuan, urged the
supporters to embrace the victory with peace and extend their hands
in warm greetings to supporters of the opposition team.
</P>
<P>
Lee Ying-yuan, deputy secretary-general of the ruling Democratic
Progressive Party (DPP), said that Saturday night is a "crucial
moment of establishing bi-partisan" politics in Taiwan, and that
Taiwan will face a lot of difficulties ahead, and it will need
solidarity from all the people.
</P>
<P>
Both Lee, Council of Labor Affairs Chairman Chen Chu, Department
of Health Director-General Chen Chien-jen and Legislator Hsiao
Bi-khim urged a night of "love and people."
</P>
<P>
They urged all feuds stemming from the election to end starting
tomorrow, and asked that everyone on Taiwan learn to live in
"tolerance and forbearance" with one and another and those who have
different ideals.
</P>
<P>
They urged supporters to hold rose --s a symbol of love and peace
-- and not honk horns, stressing that Taiwan is an immigrant society,
and that Taiwan can transcend ethnic groups to forge ahead for a new
future for Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Lo Wen-chia, director of the DPP's youth affairs, expressed his
appreciation for youngsters, who have traditionally supported the
DPP.
</P>
<P>
Hsiao Bi-khim said that all Taiwan people are enjoying the fruits
of the difficult campaign, and expressed the hope that all Taiwan
people could shout "good morning Taiwan" tomorrow.
</P>
