</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Hong Kong tourist authorities are
launching drives to lure Taiwan tourists in an effort to entice more
visitors from Taiwan, which has long been one of the territory's
tourist sources.
</P>
<P>
Since the outbreaks of severe acute respiratory syndrome in the
first half of last year, the number of Taiwan tourists heading to
Hong Kong has dropped noticeably recently at a time when many Taiwan
people have put off their overseas trips out of a grave concerns over
the hotly contested presidential election on March 20.
</P>
<P>
According to a spokesman for the Hong Kong Tourism Board, Taiwan
people paid a total of 2.42 million visits to Hong Kong in 2002, but
the number dropped to about 1.85 million in 2003. He added that the
bureau hopes to attract at least 2.4 million visitors from Taiwan for
Hong Kong this year.
</P>
<P>
Mainland China now is Hong Kong's largest source of tourists,
with more than one million visitors coming each month, he noted.
</P>
<P>
It means that some 200,000 Taiwan people traveled to mainland
China's special administrative region per month in the past, but
statistics show that because of this year's presidential race in
Taiwan, the number dropped to some 140,000 in January this year.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to forge a romantic image for Hong Kong, the bureau
also sponsored an online activity inviting the public to choice the
top 10 spots most popular in the territory during the period from
Dec. 30 last year to Jan. 30, which attracted a total of 17,697
people to take part, including a large number of participants from
Taiwan, the spokesman said.
