<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATORS URGED TO SOLVE ASSASSINATION ATTEMPT CASE AGAINST CHEN
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  20 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Premier Yu Shyi-kun has directed the
special investigative task force investigating Friday's assassination
attempt against President Chen Shui-bian and Vice President Annette
Lu to solve the case as soon as possible, Cabinet spokesman Lin
Chia-lung said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
President Chen and Vice President Lu were both shot and wounded
while their motorcade was driving through the southern Taiwan city of
Tainan Friday afternoon. Chen was hit in the abdomen, while Lu was
grazed in the knee, but their injuries weren't life threatening.
</P>
<P>
Despite the shooting incident, the nation's third direct
presidential election and first-ever referendum were held Saturday as
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Lin said Yu was satisfied with the smooth proceeding of the
election and referendum. "The premier has ordered the investigative
task force to solve the riddles surrounding Friday's shooting case as
soon as possible to stem speculation and allay public misgivings, "
Lin said.
</P>
<P>
Law enforcement authorities have ruled out involvement by
mainland China in the assassination attempt, with Tainan prosecutor
Wang Sen-jung telling a news conference held early Saturday that the
shooting "is purely a criminal case"
</P>
<P>
Police haven't announced the arrest of any suspects. However,
there was no early evidence that the shooting involved a conspiracy
or mainland China.
</P>
<P>
Wang said police found two bullets that seemed to match the two
shells found by passersby in the street close to the alleged scene of
the attack.
</P>
<P>
At first, investigators said they only found the bullet that
grazed the president's stomach and ended up in the lining of his
jacket. "It was only after the president had returned to Taipei that
we searched his vehicle and found the other bullet on the floor, "
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
A criminal investigator said judging from the characteristics of
the bullets and the shells, they could belong together, but he added
that further testing is needed before a definitive conclusion can be
reached.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the same occasion, Criminal Investigation Bureau
Director Hou You-yi said it was still too early to say much about the
trajectory of the bullets.
</P>
<P>
"The direction of the bullet (which hit Chen) was from right to
left, but we need more testing to determine the exact trajectory of
the bullets," Hou said.
</P>
</TEXT>
