<HEADLINE>
TOP POLITICAL FIGURES HEAD TO POLLS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 20 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian, surrounded by
security guards armed with automatic weapons, cast his ballots in the
presidential poll and the landmark referendum Saturday, a day after
he was shot in the abdomen in an assassination attempt on the
campaign trail in the southern city of Tainan.
</P>
<P>
Chen, wearing a cream-colored jacket, pink tie and dark trousers,
walked slowly as he waved to crowds of cheering supporters before he
entered a polling station in a school in an eastern Taipei district.
</P>
<P>
The president was accompanied by his wheelchair-bound wife as
well as their son and daughter while arriving at the polling station.
</P>
<P>
In a brief speech delivered after casting his ballots, Chen
expressed his heartfelt gratitude for the concern shown by all his
fellow compatriots as well as foreign government officials and
friends.
</P>
<P>
Chen further said he feels lucky to have survived the
assassination attempt so that he could vote in the nation's
first-ever referendum, which he described as an important step in
deepening Taiwan's young democracy and showing the world Taiwan's
determination to safeguard its security and make peace with mainland
China.
</P>
<P>
Both Chen and Vice President Annette Lu were shot Friday
afternoon while leading a motorcade in Tainan to canvass support for
their re-election bid on the eve of the election. While Chen's
abdomen was grazed by a bullet, Lu sustained minor injuries to her
right knee.
</P>
<P>
Lu returned to her hometown in Taoyuan County, some 40 kilometers
south of Taipei, at around noon to vote in the presidential poll and
the referendum.
</P>
<P>
The vice president was in good spirits and all smiles when she
appeared at the polling station to cast her ballots. Lu said she was
glad to see the election and the referendum proceed smoothly as
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the shooting incident, all of our compatriots have
remained calm and rational, " Lu said, adding that "violence cannot
obstruct our determination to pursue democracy."
</P>
<P>
A day after surviving the assassination attempt, Chen and Lu of
the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) are battling for re-election
against their sole challengers -- the "pan-blue alliance" ticket of
Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan and People First Party Chairman James
Soong.
</P>
<P>
Lien, accompanied by his wife, two sons and daughter, went to the
polling station near his home in Taipei's bustling Chunghsiao East
Road shopping district at 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
Lien said he had come early to vote in the presidential poll with
a view to encouraging his supporters not to be swayed by Friday's
shooting incident.
</P>
<P>
"We should not let a simple violent event change our minds and
change our destiny, " Lien told reporters after casting his ballot.
His remarks were seen by many as an attempt to dampen the possible
"sympathy vote" effect for the Chen-Lu ticket caused by the
assassination attempt.
</P>
<P>
Lien and his family members didn't pick up referendum ballots as
the "pan-blue alliance" has held the position that the President
Chen-initiated referendum on missile defense and relations with
mainland China is "illegal and unconstitutional."
</P>
<P>
Lien's running mate, James Soong, also cast his ballot in the
presidential poll at a polling station in Taipei County's Linko
township early in the morning. He was accompanied by his wife and
their daughter. They also didn't vote in the referendum.
</P>
<P>
Former President Lee Teng-hui cast his ballots in both the
presidential election and the referendum. Lee, who had campaigned for
President Chen's re-election bid, said he felt regret over Friday's
shooting incident.
</P>
<P>
"Taiwan has come a long way in its pursuit of freedom and
democracy. There shouldn't be any more violence or tragedies, " he
urged.
</P>
<P>
Premier Yu Shyi-kun returned to Taipei after casting his ballots
in his hometown in the northeastern county of Ilan. Yu said he has
directed the national defense, foreign affairs, interior, and justice
ministers as well as other relevant department heads to stay in their
offices after casting their ballots.
</P>
<P>
"All relevant government agencies should work out response
measures to cope with any possible disputes or conflicts in the wake
of Friday's incident and in the voting and vote-counting process," Yu
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
