<HEADLINE>
VOTERS HEAD TO POLLS FOR PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION, REFERENDUM
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 20 (CNA)
(By Huang Kwang-chun)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Voters are heading to the polls normally
around Taiwan Saturday to cast their ballots in the presidential
election and the accompanying referendum, despite of a failed
assessination attempt of President Chen Shui-bian a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
The polls are open from 8 a.m. through 4 p.m., with vote counting
to begin immediately after the polls close.
</P>
<P>
President Chen and Vice President Annette Lu of the ruling
Democratic Progressive Party are seeking reelection in a bitter
contest against the sole challenging ticket formed by opposition
Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan and People First Party Chairman James
Soong in the election.
</P>
<P>
Alongside the presidential election, the electorate also cast
ballots in Taiwan's first nationwide referendum on two questions:
Should the government buy new anti-missile systems to counter the
growing mainland Chinese missile threat and should the government
open talks with Beijing to establish a framework for the cross-Taiwan
Strait peace.
