<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040321.0001" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 21 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Sunday, March 21, or the first
day of the leap second month of the Year of the Monkey according
to the lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that
have occurred on this date in the past:

1685: Johann Sebastian Bach, German composer and organist who is
considered to be among the greatest composers in history, is born.

1804: A new civil code, the Code Napoleon, comes into force in
France.

1829: An earthquake rocks Spain, killing some 6,000 people.

1908: French aviator Henri Farman flies over Paris with the first
air passenger.

1927: The Northward Expeditionary Forces led by Commander in
Chief Chiang Kai-shek take the city of Shanghai.

1939: Wang Ching-wei, who fled from Chungking to Hanoi, Vietnam,
escapes an assassination attempt in his residence in the early
morning, but his secretary, Tseng Chung-min, dies of a gunshot wound.
Wang later established a puppet regime in Nanking on March 29, 1940.

1940: Dr. Sun Yat-sen is posthumously declared the Founding
Father of the Republic of China for his life-long contributions to
the revolution. The decision was made at a meeting of the Kuomintang
Central Standing Committee.

1950: President Chiang Kai-shek appoints Chiang Ching-kuo chief
of the General Headquarters, Political Warfare Department under the
Ministry of National Defense.

1953: Nikita Khrushchev is appointed first secretary of the
Soviet Communist Party, succeeding Georgi Malenkov who becomes Soviet
premier.

1966: The National Assembly elects President Chiang Kai-shek to a
fourth term as president of the Republic of China.

1972: President Chiang Kai-shek is reelected to a fifth six-year
term.

1973: An Asian small- and medium-size enterprise league is
inaugurated in Taipei.

1975: Kao Cheng is named minister and charge d'affaires of the
Chinese Embassy in Tonga.

1975: Dr. Albert M.J. Parisis, deputy speaker of the Belgian
House of Representatives, arrives in Taipei for a week-long visit.

1975: Republic of China officials stationed in Phnom Penh return
to Taipei.

1977: Prime Minister Indira Gandhi resigns after losing her seat
in India's parliamentary elections.

1978: Premier Chiang Ching-kuo is elected by the National
Assembly as president for the sixth constitutional presidential term
of the Republic of China.

1984: President Chiang Ching-kuo is reelected for a second
six-year term.

1989: Beijing's leaders announce new controls and taxes on
private business, rural factories and free-market farming.

1990: Lee Teng-hui wins 641 votes out of the 668 votes in the
National Assembly and is elected as the eighth president of the
Republic of China.

1993: Republic of Nauru President Bernard Dowiyogo visits Taipei.

1996: India successfully launches its domestically produced
one-ton class satellite into orbit.

1998: King Norodom Sihanouk of Cambodia grants a royal pardon to
his son, Norodom Ranariddh.

2000: U.S. Reform Party presidential candidate Patrick Buchanan
praises the people of Taiwan for their courage in defying Beijing's
bullying tactics and threats by electing opposition politician Chen
Shui-bian as the ROC's next president.

2001: Opposition People First Party Chairman James Soong urges
the government to adopt a cautious attitude towards U.S. arms sales
to Taiwan.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "In your government, why should you
think it necessary to depend upon capital punishment? Wish for
honesty, and the people will be honest. The moral power of rulers is
as the wind, and that of the people is as the grass. Whithersoever
the wind blows, the grass is sure to bend."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040321.0002" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
BALLOTS MORE POWERFUL THAN BULLETS: VICE PRESIDENT LU
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 20 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Vice President Annette Lu said Saturday
the smooth conclusion of the presidential election has proved that
ballots are more powerful than bullets.
</P>
<P>
Lu made the remarks after the opposition "pan-blue alliance"
ticket of Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan and People First Party James
Soong refused to concede defeat and claimed that the election was
unfair.
</P>
<P>
"What's fair? What's unfair? " she said in a speech delivered
after the Central Election Commission announced the re-election of
President Chen Shui-bian and Vice President Lu.
</P>
<P>
"This is a democratic country. Unless there is evidence, they
must should not doubt the validity of the election, or democracy
might be destroyed, " she told cheering supporters outside the ruling
Democratic Progressive Party's (DPP) campaign headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Friday's shooting of her and President Chen on the
campaign trail in the southern city of Tainan, Lu said the incident
was a "battle between bullets and ballots." Lu sustained minor
injuries to her right knee in the shooting while Chen was grazed in
his abdomen. Lien claimed that the shooting of the president and vice
president on the eve of the presidential poll was suspicious and that
its influence on the vote should be investigated.
</P>
<P>
Lu said Lien's allegations were unfounded. "Since the incident is
still being investigated, we should refrain from speculation, " Lu
said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Taiwan has come a long way in its pursuit of freedom
and democracy, Lu said all local people should respect Taiwan's
hard-won democratic system.
</P>
<P>
After winning a second four-year term, Lu said she will work with
President Chen and other DPP members in promoting social, economic,
judicial and political reforms as well as pursuing international
justice.
</P>
<P>
Lu, who holds a master's degree in law from the University of
Illinois, was a women's rights campaigner before joining mainstream
party politics. She received a 12-year prison term in 1980 for
helping organize Taiwan's first unauthorized mass demonstration by
the opposition in the previous year. When she was released in 1985,
she continued to campaign for better human rights and democracy under
Kuomintang rule.
</P>
<P>
In 1986 she joined other leading opposition members in forming the then
illegal Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), now the ruling party. She was also
behind the drive in 1993 pushing for Taiwan's re-entry to the United Nations,
which was dropped in favor of mainland China in 1971.
</P>
<P>
Lu was a member of parliament in 1993-96 and was serving as the highest
elected official for Taoyuan county when the DPP's Chen Shui-bian asked her to
be his running mate for the 2000 presidential race. The DPP's
surprise victory made her the highest-ranking woman in the
government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
