<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040321.0005" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN STOCK, FOREX MARKETS WILL OPEN MONDAY AS USUAL
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  21 (CNA)
(By Huang Kwang-chun)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan's stock and foreign exchange
markets will open Monday as usual, Vice Premier Lin Hsin-i said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Lin, who doubles as chairman of the Council for Economic Planning
and Development (CEPD) , made the announcement after chairing an
interministrial meeting with the participation of Secretary-General
of the Executive Yuan Liu Shih-fang, Minister without Portfolio Hu
Sheng-cheng, Minister of Finance Lin Chuan, Minister of Economic
Affairs Lin Yi-fu, Governor of Central Bank of China Perng Fai-nan,
Director-General of the Directorate General of Budget, Accounting and
Statistics Liu San-chi and CEPD Vice Chairwoman Ho Mei-yueh.
</P>
<P>
The meeting adopted three resolutions for stabilizing stock and
foreign exchange markets and heightening domestic investment, Lin
said.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's economy has been recovering since the second half of
last year with an economic growth rate of 4.18 percent for the third
quarter and 5.17 percent for the fourth quarter, Lin said, adding
that the country's imports and exports also expanded by 32.6 percent
and 26 percent in the first two months of this year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Lin called on the public, particularly investors, to be confident
in the national economic prospectives, citing estimate by foreign
research institutions which shows Taiwan's gross domestic product
will increase by an annual rate up to six percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The vice premier also instructed relevant government agencies to
concretely fulfill the resolutions and to make communications with
leading domestic and foreign business groups for further
consolidating their confidence in Taiwan's economy.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance Lin Chuan said that the government will
respect the market mechanism on stock exchanges when the bourse
reopens Monday.
</P>
<P>
Referring to whether the government will use the national
stabilization fund to maintain market stability in the wake of
Saturday's election, Lin said that will depend on whether there are
irrational factors involved in the market.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank of China Governor Perng Fai-nan also said if events
surrounding the presidential election spark high volatility in the
forex market, the central bank will step in to stabilize the
situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
