results in a democratic society, regardless of how slim the margin
between winner and loser.
</P>
<P>
Any disputes over the election should be settled by judicial
means and the public should return to normal life immediately after
the election, he said.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's election results show that a majority of Taiwan's
people are willing to give President Chen Shui-bian four more years
to carry out his policies and that they wish to enjoy stability.
</P>
<P>
The country's economy has been recovering since the second half
of last year, Huang noted, adding that this fact shows that the
policies of Chen's administration have borne fruit.
</P>
<P>
Huang called on the public to appreciate the hard-earned economic
recovery, which he said can only be maintained with social stability.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Gary Wang, president of the General Chamber of
Commerce of the Republic of China, said the public should wait for a
judicial ruling with regard to Lien's appeal for an annulment of the
election in a cool and rational manner.
</P>
<P>
The business sector wishes for a stable environment, Wang went
on, adding that Taiwan's economic foundation cannot afford to be
shaken if the country wants to continue to advance.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of angry supporters of the Lien-Soong ticket have
staged a protest at their campaign headquarters and in front of the
Presidential Office since Chen won Saturday's election by a narrow
margin. They are demanding that the election be annulled.
</P>
<P>
Protests also erupted in other major cities around Taiwan after
Chen's victory by less than 30,000 votes.
</P>
