<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040321.0014" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
KMT CHAIRMAN CALLS FOR IMMEDIATE EXAMINATION OF BALLOTS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 21 (CNA)
(By P.C. Tang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Opposition Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan
called Sunday for the relevant government agencies to conduct an
immediate, open and fair recount of the presidential election
ballots, to "prove his claim" that the election was unfair.
</P>
<P>
Lien, who narrowly lost the election to the incumbent President
Chen Shui-bian of the Democratic Progress Party, made the appeal in a
rally held in front of the Presidential Office.
</P>
<P>
The KMT chairman said that he will be unable to explain to the
next generations, as well as to the nation, Taiwan's history and
democratic system if he keeps silent in the face of "an unfair
election that could destroy the country."
</P>
<P>
He also urged the people of Taiwan to stand up for themselves.
</P>
<P>
Saying that his appeal is very simple, Lien claimed that the
election was unfair and that the results should be declared invalid.
</P>
<P>
Lien also said the government should investigate last Friday's
shooting that wounded Chen and Vice President Annette Lu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040321.0015" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS LEADERS CALL ON PUBLIC TO FACE ELECTION RESULTS RATIONALLY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 21 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two religious leaders called on the public
Sunday to face the March 20 presidential election results rationally
after a group of "pan-blue alliance" supporters converged in front of
the Presidential Office to protest against what they claim is an
"unfair" election.
</P>
<P>
Master Cheng Yen, founder of the Buddhist Compassionate Tzu Chi
Relief Foundation, said during a meeting with Tzu Chi volunteers that
all candidates and their supporters should respect the results,
irrespective of who is victorious.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the people have exercised their rights and
obligations in the election, Cheng Yen voiced the hope that all
compatriots will love and respect each other.
</P>
<P>
"We all should pray for our nation with a mind of tranquility.
Only when our society is stable and harmonious will the people's
welfare be improved, " added the leader of the country's largest
charity organization.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zen Master Sheng Yen, founder of the Taiwan Buddhist
group Dharma Drum Mountain (DDM) Social Welfare and Charity
Foundation, said that no matter who has won the election, the public
should keep calm and accept the fact with a joyful mind.
</P>
<P>
The Buddhist leader said those who are concerned with Taiwan's
society should deal with the election results rationally and he added
that the democratic spirit lies in respecting every voter's choice.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of angry supporters of the opposition "pan-blue
alliance" ticket of Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan and People First
Party Chairman James Soong staged a protest in front of the
Presidential Office after President Chen Shiu-bian won by a narrow
margin. They demanded that the election be annulled.
</P>
<P>
Protests also erupted in other major cities after Chen's victory
by less than 30,000 votes in Saturday's poll.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040321.0016" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIPEI MAYOR HOPES OPPOSITION PROTESTS END BY NIGHTFALL
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 21 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei Mayor Ma Ying-jeou called Sunday
for demonstrators to be cool and rational and to exercise
self-control in protests against what they called Saturday's "unfair"
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Ma, a vice chairman of the opposition Kuomintang and a campaign
manager for the "pan-blue alliance" presidential ticket of Lien Chan
and James Soong, urged alliance supporters to end their sit-in in
front of the Presidential Office before the end of the day, as
stipulated in their protest application.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of "pan-blue alliance" supporters had continued to
converge at the Presidential Office for a sit-in that began Saturday
night after the Central Election Commission (CEC) announced that
incumbent President Chen Shui-bian had succeeded in his re-election
bid by winning 6,471,970 votes, only 0.228 percent, or less than
30,000 votes, more than those garnered by the "pan-blue alliance"
ticket of Lien and Soong.
</P>
<P>
Ma told the protestors that the CEC and the Taiwan High Court
have responded to the protesters' appeal to have all ballot boxes
nationwide frozen and have all presidential ballots recounted.
</P>
<P>
In his capacity as Taipei mayor, Ma said it is his keen
expectations that the protestors will conclude the sit-in by 10 p.m.
as scheduled so that the city can return to normal by Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040321.0017" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION VICTORY ESTABLISHES TAIWAN IDENTITY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 21 (CNA)
(By P.C. Tang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The reason for President Chen Shui-bian's
re-election Saturday is that he has always stuck to his Taiwan
identity ideology, Presidential Office Secretary-General Chiou I-jen
claimed late Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Chiou, who is also executive secretary-general of the "pan-green
camp" campaign headquarters for the election, made the remarks in
response to questions from the media.
</P>
<P>
Chen and Annette Lu, the incumbent vice president, claimed
victory over opposition Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan and his running
mate, People First Party Chairman James Soong, by a razor-thin
margin.
</P>
<P>
Chiou added that Lien and the "pan-blue alliance, " on the
contrary, sometimes followed the president's direction and sometimes
did not.
</P>
<P>
A true Taiwan identity has been established through the election
and any political party's development in the future should accept the
values of this ideology, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040321.0018" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT RULES FREEZE OF ELECTION BALLOTS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 21 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Taiwan High Court ruled Sunday morning
that all presidential election ballots being held by the election
authorities in 25 cities and counties nationwide should be frozen
until controversy over the election results has been cleared up.
</P>
<P>
The court announced that all presidential ballots, including
blank, valid and annulled ballots, as well as name-lists of voters
and electoral workers should also be frozen and sealed to be used as
evidence in a lawsuit filed by the opposition "pan-blue alliance"
presidential ticket.
</P>
<P>
Having refused to accept Saturday's election results, the
opposition "pan-blue alliance" presidential ticket of Kuomintang
Chairman Lien Chan and People First Party Chairman James Soong filed
a motion with the court to demand an annulment of the election
results and a recount of the votes.
</P>
<P>
The Lien-Soong ticket lost to incumbent President Chen Shui-bian
and Vice President Annette Lu by a razor-thin margin of 0.228
percent, or 6,442,452 votes to 6,471,970 votes.
</P>
<P>
As of Sunday noon, district court judges in Taipei, Taoyuan,
Keelung, Taichung, Changhua, Chiayi, Penghu and Kinmen had proceeded
to their local election commissions to oversee the ballot-freezing
process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040321.0019" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
AIT REQUESTS MEETING WITH PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Washington,  March 20 (CNA)
(By W.C. Lin, K.Y. Liu and P.C. Tang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan's top official in the United
States said Saturday that Washington's top liaison official in Taiwan
has asked to meet with the candidates of two rival camps of
Saturday's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Chen Chien-jen, the island's representative to the United States,
said that James Kelly, U.S. assistant secretary responsible for East
Asia and Pacific Affairs, told him Saturday that Douglas Paal,
director of the American Institute in Taiwan (AIT), had contacted the
two camps in the election to express his hope that he can meet with
their presidential and vice presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
The State Department issued a statement after the election in
which it not only congratulates the people of Taiwan for conducting a
democratic election but also expresses confidence that both sides
will use the established legal mechanism to resolve any questions
about the election results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
