<HEADLINE>
LIEN, SOONG LEAD SUPPORTERS IN PROTEST AT PRESIDENTIAL OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 21 (CNA)
(By P.C. Tang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Opposition Kuomintang (KMT) Chairman Lien
Chan and his running mate in the presidential election, People First
Party Chairman James Soong, continued to lead their supporters Sunday
in a protest in front of the Presidential Office against what they
called an "unfair election."
</P>
<P>
The "pan-blue alliance" leaders had also joined in an overnight
sit-in with their supporters at their campaign headquarters Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
Lien and Soong lost the election by a razor-thin margin to
incumbent President Chen Shui-bian and Vice President Annette Lu of
the ruling Democratic Progressive Party.
</P>
<P>
Ma Ying-jeou, Taipei mayor and general secretary of the "pan-blue
alliance" campaign headquarters, did not say whether he would join
the supporters to go to the Presidential Office when Lien and Soong
decided to lead supporters on a march to the Presidential Office to
protest the results.
</P>
<P>
KMT Secretary-General Lin Feng-cheng filed a lawsuit with the
Taiwan Hight Court late Saturday, demanding that the court annul the
election result and recount the votes.
</P>
