<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040321.0022" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT ORDERS OPENNESS, TRANSPARENCY IN ELECTION CONTROVERSY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 21 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian has instructed
the administration to handle the opposition's protests over
Saturday's presidential election results in an open and transparent
manner, Premier Yu Shyi-kun said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Yu quoted Chen as saying that the dissatisfaction of the
opponents' supporters over his victory by a slim margin Saturday is
fully understandable.
</P>
<P>
Chen and Vice President Annette Lu won their re-election bid by
garnering 6,471,970 votes, beating the opposition "pan-blue alliance"
ticket of Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan and his running mate, People
First Party Chairman James Soong, by a razor-thin margin of 0.228
percent.
</P>
<P>
Chen was also quoted by Yu as instructing that the Executive Yuan
should deal with all ensuing controversies speedily and that the
government should fully trust any decisions that the courts make
concerning a vote recount and other electoral affairs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yu issued directives to the National Police
Administration and other law enforcement agencies islandwide to take a
"soft" approach to handling protests.
</P>
<P>
Yu stressed that the government respects the opposition's
decision to seek the election's annulment via legal process, but
considers that illegal gatherings of protesters should not continue
uncontrolled.
</P>
<P>
Yu said he is fully aware that it had been a long night after
Saturday's presidential election, with sporadic strife staged by
angry voters islandwide, including a man who rammed his car into the
District Prosecutors' Office in Kaohsiung, southern Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Refusing to accept the election results, Lien declared Saturday
night that he would file a lawsuit to seek the election's annulment
and demanded that all ballots now held by polling authorities in 25
cities and counties nationwide be recounted.
</P>
<P>
"Pan-blue alliance" supporters continued a sit-in in front of the
Presidential Office that began Saturday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040321.0023" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
ELECTION  DISPUTE SHOULD BE RESOLVED THROUGH JUSTICE: PREMIER
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  Marcy 21 (CNA)
(By P.C. Tang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Premier Yu Shyi-kun called Sunday for the
opposition "pan-blue alliance" leaders and their supporters to trust
and respect the decision of the justices in dealing with their
dispute over the presidential election results.
</P>
<P>
The premier made the appeal while responding to a demand
by pan-blue supporters at a press conference that the Executive Yuan
should give them "an answer" with regard to the election results.
</P>
<P>
Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan and his running mate, People FIrst
Party Chairman James Soong immediately filed a lawsuit with the
Taiwan High Court to demand an annulment of the election results and
a recount of the ballots after they lost by a razor-thin margin to
the incumbent President Chen Shui-bian and Vice President Annette Lu
of the Democratic Progressive Party.
</P>
<P>
They also led their supporters in a protest over what they
consider an "unfair election" in front of the Presidential Office
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that the pan-blue supporters "are aiming at a wrong
target and use the wrong method" in seeking a resolution of the
dispute, Yu said that the issue has been passed on to the judicial
institutions and that the pan-blue supporters must trust their
decision.
</P>
<P>
The government respects the right of the pan-blue alliance to
resolve the election dispute through the established legal mechanism,
the premier said, adding however that the alliance should not
continue its "illegal gathering" in front of the Presidential Office.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that the High Court has already decided to seize all
the ballot boxes, the premier said that the alliance's supporters
should stop worrying.
</P>
<P>
Concerning the question of an increasing number of spoiled
ballots in the election, the premier explained that activists had
appealed to the voters during the campaign to spoil their ballots,
while the passage of a law last year to strictly define vote validity
could also be a reason for the spoiled ballots.
</P>
<P>
Yu said the pan blue disappointment should be balanced by their
perception of democracy and added that it is pointless to tarnish
Taiwan's international image because of an election.
</P>
<P>
The premier also said that he respects Lien and expressed hope
that he will lead his supporters in the right direction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
