<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040321.0029" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
LIEN, SOONG LEAD SUPPORTERS PROTEST IN FRONT OF PRESIDENTIAL OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  21 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan and his
running mate in the presidential election, James Soong, led their
supporters to march to the presidential office early Sunday after
staging an overnight sit-in at their campaign headquarters to protest
what they called the unfair election in which they lost to incumbent
President Chen Shui-bian by a razor-thin margin.
</P>
<P>
Lin Chung-hsiung, the secretary-general of James Soong's People
First Party, said Lien and Soong wants to stage a sit-in front of the
presidential office until their request to have the votes recounted
was granted.
</P>
<P>
Lien has filed a motion with the Taiwan High Court late Saturday
asking for a recount of the ballots in the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan High Court has referred the motion to 21 district courts
around the island asking them to dicide for themselves whether to
seize the ballots boxes in the districts within their jurisdiction
for a recount.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, their supporters have encircled several courts in
central and southern Taiwan since Saturday night urging the court to
grant their request and shouting noisily "recount the votes, recount
the votes".
</P>
<P>
Separately clashes between these protesters and police were
reported in Kaohsiung and Taichung when protesters there tried to
broke into the buildings of court.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Kaohsiung calmed down early Sunday after the
court decided to seize the vote boxes in the greater Kaohsiung area
in preparation from a recount.
</P>
<P>
A similar decision was taken by Chiayi District Court.
</P>
<P>
Minister of the Interior Yu Cheng-hsien called Lien and Soong to
help calm down their supporters at a press conference early Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040321.0030" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN SOLIDARITY UNION CALLS FOR HUMBLE GOVERNMENT
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 20 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan Solidarity Union (TSU) Chairman
Huang Chu-wen appealed for ethnic harmony and a humble government
Saturday in the wake of the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Hailing President Chen Shui-bian's re-election success as
evidence of Taiwan's democratization and providing a stabilization
force to Taiwan's politics, Huang also urged Beijing authorities to
rethink their saber- rattling policies toward Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Chen's re-election represents the fact that the awareness of
Taiwan's identity is growing fast among the people in Taiwan and
mainland China should rethink its strategy in its dealings with
Taiwan, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
According to the leader of the TSU, a political ally of the
ruling Democratic Progressive Party, the United States will also have
to rethink Taiwan's role as one of its strategic partners.
</P>
<P>
Chen and his running mate, Vice President Annette Lu, won over
the ticket formed by opposition Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan and
People First Party Chairman James Soong by a very slim margin. Chen
received 6,471,970 votes, or 50.11 percent of the total, while Lien
gained 6,442,452 votes.
</P>
</TEXT>
