</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 22 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The central government will help Taipei
City to calm protesters and render whatever support the city needs to
defuse the opposition's ongoing rally in the wake of Saturday's
presidential election, Executive Yuan spokesman Lin Chia-lung said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Lin said at a news conference that Premier Yu Shyi-kun fully
understands the awkward situation that Taipei Mayor Ma Ying-jeou is
facing now being top administrative official in Taiwan's capital city
while being a campaign manager for the opposition "pan-blue alliance"
presidential ticket of Lien Chan and James Soong, who lost to
President Chen Shui-bian and Vice President Annette Lu by a
razor-thin margin of 0.228 percent, or 6,442,452 votes to 6,471,970
votes.
</P>
<P>
Having refused to accept the election results, "pan-blue
alliance" supporters continued their sit-in Monday in front of the
Presidential Office that began Saturday night. They filed a lawsuit
with the Taiwan High Court to seek an annulment of the presidential
election and to have all presidential ballots nationwide recounted.
</P>
<P>
The protesters are demonstrating on the grounds that the
circumstances surrounding the unexplained assassination attempt
against Chen and Lu on the eve of the election have yet to be
understood clearly and that the number of ballots certified invalid
was unusually high.
</P>
<P>
Lin said that the central government is in full support of the
Taipei City Government in solving problems related to the aftermath
of the election, particularly the disruption of social order around
the Presidential Office and the concerns of the average citizen as to
how far the protesters will go to take matters into their own hands.
</P>
<P>
He also called for the protesters to go home so that the mayor
does not have to face such a difficult situation.
</P>
<P>
Lin said while it is right to show magnanimity to one's opponent
and sympathy with the losing side, it is wrong to take an irrational
attitude and act on disputes, which, he said, should be solved
through legal processes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, commenting on the continuing demonstration that the
"pan-blue alliance" supporters have staged in front of the
Presidential Office, the legislative caucus of the ruling Democratic
Progressive Party said that the election is over and they should go
home and face the new reality.
</P>
<P>
DPP legislative party whip Tsai Huang-lang said that President
Chen's opponents, "pan-blue alliance" leaders Lien and Soong, should
face the results now that the election is over and demonstrate their
democratic magnanimity.
</P>
<P>
Lien and Soong should respect the law and follow judicial rules
to serve as an example of democratization for their supporters,
instead of manipulating pluralism and public opinion, Tsai said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Legislative Yuan President Wang Jin-pyng and Taipei
Mayor Ma, both head officials of the opposition "pan-blue alliance"
campaign headquarters, should step forward to persuade alliance
supporters to go home and wait for judicial decisions on any
disputes.
</P>
</TEXT>
