<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040322.0027" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TRANSPORTATION MINISTRY TO BEGIN WORK ON DIRECT LINKS DETAILS SHORTLY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  22  (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ministry of Transportation and
Communications (MOTC) will soon begin to work on the technical details
pertaining to direct cross-Taiwan Strait links based on the timetable
that President Chen Shui-bian announced last year, a ranking MOTC
official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Lin Chih-ming, director of the MOTC Department of Navigation and
Aviation, said that with President Chen's victory in his re-election
bid, the issue of direct transportation links across the Taiwan
Strait has now become one of the focuses of attention.
</P>
<P>
Lin said the MOTC will soon launch technical planning on
President Chen's "three-stage" timetable -- namely preparation,
negotiation and implementation -- on the opening of direct shipping
and air links across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
According to the president's timetable, Lin said, negotiations
are to kick off shortly after the presidential election, paving the
way for the implementation of direct cross-strait transportation
links by the end of 2004.
</P>
<P>
Lin said that the MOTC completed an overall assessment on
Taiwan's opening of direct transportation links based on the
"three-stage" timetable and submitted it to the Mainland Affairs
Council (MAC) for the council's reference last year. The MAC is the
top agency in charge of formulating Taiwan's mainland China policies.
</P>
<P>
Lin added that when policy makers give the green light, the MOTC
will have no problems in dealing with the technical matters
pertaining to direct cross-strait links.
</P>
</TEXT>
