<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 22 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Monday, March 22, or the second
day of the leap second month of the Year of the Monkey according
to the lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that
have occurred on this date in the past:

1832: Johann Wolfgang von Goethe -- German writer, scientist,
master of poetry, drama and the novel, and one of the greatest
thinkers of his age -- dies at the age of 82.

1916: Yuan Shih-kai, who declared himself emperor Dec. 12, 1915,
is forced to cancel his imperial reign after 83 days and calls
himself "president" again. He also appoints Hsu Shih-chang as
premier.

1917: The United States becomes the first country to recognize
the new provisional government in Russia after the collapse of the
monarchy.

1927: The first troops of the National Revolutionary Army, under
the leadership of Commander in Chief Chiang Kai-shek, enter Shanghai
during a military expedition northward to eradicate various feuding
warlords in central and northern China.

1935: The first television service is inaugurated in Berlin,
Germany.

1935: Persia changes its name to Iran.

1945: Jordan gains its independence.

1945: The Arab League is established in Cairo by seven Middle
Eastern countries in order to coordinate political action and
safeguard their sovereignty. The member countries are Egypt, Saudi
Arabia, Syria, Lebanon, Iraq, Jordan and Yemen.

1954: Chiang Kai-shek is re-elected president of the Republic of
China for a second six-year term.

1960: Chiang Kai-shek is reelected to a third term as president,
while Chen Cheng is reelected for a second term as vice president.

1966: The National Assembly elects Premier Yen Chia-kan as the
third vice president of the Republic of China.

1966: Relations between Beijing and Moscow deteriorate further
when the Communist Chinese refuse to attend the 23rd national
congress of the Soviet Communist Party.

1966: President Chiang Kai-shek signs into law and makes public
the "Temporary Provisions Effective During the Period of Communist
Rebellion" amended by the National Assembly on March 19, 1966.

1972: Vice President C.K. Yen is elected to a second six-year
term.

1973: President Chiang Kai-shek appoints Kiding Wang as the ROC
ambassador to the Central African Republic.

1974: Y.T. Wong, director of the Board of Foreign Trade under the
Ministry of Economic Affairs, leaves for Rio de Janeiro to negotiate
the purchase of soybeans.

1975: Tang Ching-hsuan, the new ROC ambassador to Honduras, and
Konsin C. Shah, ROC consular-general in New York, leave Taiwan to
take up their respective posts.

1976: A Sino-American seminar on biochemistry opens with 21
Chinese and American delegates, including U.S. Nobel laureate
Stanford Moore, attending.

1983: Pu Nai-fu, a noted mainland Chinese writer with the pen
name "Mr. Anonymous," arrives in Taipei from Hong Kong and issues a
statement against the Communist Chinese.

1984: Lee Teng-hui is elected by the National Assembly as the
seventh vice president of the Republic of China.

1990: Li Yuan-zu is elected vice president of the Republic of
China.

1992: The Democratic Party in Albania scores a landslide victory
in elections, ending Communist Party rule.

1997: Tibetan spiritual leader the Dalai Lama arrives in the
Republic of China for a six-day visit.

2000: President-elect Chen Shui-bian vows that he will do his
best to ensure Taiwan's stable political and economic order and to
set a good example for a peaceful power transition by cooperating
with all political forces.

2001: The 2001 Taiwan International Orchid Exhibition opens in
Taipei with more than 20,000 potted orchids of various kinds on
display.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "Now a man who is really a man of
distinction is one who stands upon his own integrity and loves what
is right: who forms a correct judgment of men by observing how they
look as well as by regarding what they say. Reflection makes him
humble in his estimate of himself as compared with other men. Such a
man, whether he be in public life or in private life, will be a
distinguished man."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040323.0001" type="story" >
