<HEADLINE>
DPP CAUCUS PROPOSES AMENDMENT TO FACILITATE VOTE RECOUNT
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  23 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The legislative caucus of the ruling
Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) put forward a proposal at the
Legislative Yuan Tuesday aimed at legitimizing a recounting of the
votes in Saturday's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The DPP legislative caucus proposed an amendment to the President
and Vice President Election and Recall Law to allow losers of an
election to request a vote recount if the margin of the loss is less
than 1 percent of the total ballots cast.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of the opposition "pan-blue alliance" ticket of
Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan and People First Party Chairman James
Soong have continued their sit-in in front of the presidential palace
that began Saturday night, claiming the March 20 election was
"unfair" and demanding a recount.
</P>
<P>
The Lien-Soong ticket lost to incumbent President Chen Shui-bian
and Vice President Annette Lu by a razor-thin margin of just under
30,000 votes, or 0.228 percent of the total votes counted.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to clear up the opposition's doubts and seek an
early settlement to the election dispute, which has disrupted social
order and plunged the Taipei stock market, the DPP caucus has put
forward the proposal and has called for an extra voting session
Tuesday for speedy passage of the amendment, DPP legislative party
whip Tsai Huang-lang said.
</P>
<P>
"It is hoped that the proposed amendment can go through the three
readings at the Legislative Yuan before nightfall Tuesday so that it
can be formally passed into law and implemented by Thursday, " Tsai
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, opposition "pan-blue alliance" legislators voiced
doubts about the feasibility of the DPP's timetable, saying it is
impossible for the amendment to be passed into law within two days
given the existing legislative structure and voting process.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the demonstrators cannot wait any longer, Liao
Feng-teh, a Kuomintang legislative party whip, demanded that the
Central Election Commission (CEC) immediately convene a members
meeting to pass a motion, with the consent of at least half of the
CEC members, asking for an administrative recount of Saturday's votes
without delay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040323.0003" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN AND G-10 GROUP MEMBERS TO HOLD TALKS WITH MAJOR WTO MEMBERS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Geneva, March 22 (CNA)
(By Neil Lu and P.C. Tang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan will join other members of the G-10
Group in holding a series of meetings beginning Tuesday with major
World Trade Organization (WTO) members and groups as the agricultural
talks of the Doha Round Trade talks resumed Monday.
</P>
<P>
The G-10 Group, made up of Taiwan, Bulgaria, Israel, Iceland,
Japan, Mauritius, Norway, Switzerland, South Korea and Liechtenstein,
is aimed at protecting and advancing the agricultural interests of
its members.
</P>
<P>
A well-placed source in Geneva revealed Monday that members of
the G-10 Group will hold various consultation meetings with the
United States, the European Union, the G-20 Group nations as well as
with other agricultural product exporting nations and the "Special
Products Union" to consolidate their common positions in the
agricultural negotiations of the Doha Round Trade talks.
</P>
<P>
The G-20 Group consists of 20 developed nations, while the
"Special Products Union" is an organization of 42 developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Fifth WTO Ministerial Conference held in Caucun, Mexico
last September marked a setback mainly because of the differences
among WTO members over issues regarding agricultural talks.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that Yen Ching-chang, permanent representative of
Taiwan's mission to the WTO, will head officials from the Council of
Agriculture and his mission to participate in the upcoming meetings.
</P>
</TEXT>
