<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT GETS CONGRATULATORY MESSAGES FROM ABROAD: MOFA
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 23 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MOFA)
said Tuesday it has received messages from many foreign governments
and prominent political figures congratulating President Chen
Shui-bian on his re-election Saturday, despite the controversy over
the election results and demonstrations by opposition supporters.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular news conference, MOFA spokesman Richard
Shih said that as of Monday evening, governments and individual
political figures from 22 countries had sent congratulatory messages.
</P>
<P>
Those countries included Panama, Paraguay, the Dominican
Republic, Grenada, Chad, Senegal, Swaziland, The Gambia, the Solomon
Islands, Palau, the Marshall Islands, Japan, South Korea, Bangladesh,
Britain, Italy, the Netherlands, Sao Tome and Principe, Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait, Kiribati and Commonwealth of Dominica.
</P>
<P>
Shih said more congratulatory messages are expected to arrive in
the coming days.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Shih said, Foreign Affairs Minister Eugene Chien
briefed foreign ambassadors and representatives stationed in Taipei
on the election results.
</P>
<P>
Chen won with just 50.1 percent of the vote, compared to 49.9
percent for his sole challenger, opposition Kuomintang Chairman Lien
Chan -- a margin of just 29,518 ballots.
</P>
<P>
Lien and his running mate -- People First Party Chairman James
Soong -- immediately mobilized some of their supporters to stage a
sit-in in front of the Presidential Office to protest what they are
describing as an "unfair" election.
</P>
<P>
At Lien's request, the Taiwan High Court ordered all ballot boxes
sealed Sunday. Lien has demanded an immediate vote recount, claiming
that Chen "unfairly" received sympathy votes after being injured in a
mysterious election-eve shooting and that the number of invalid
ballots was, in his opinion, "unusually high."
</P>
<P>
After Monday's background briefing for foreign envoys, Chien
quoted Douglas Paal, director of the Taipei Office of the American
Institute in Taiwan (AIT) , as having said that the United States is
adopting a hands-off attitude toward the dispute over the election
result.
</P>
<P>
According to an AIT press statement released later that day, Paal
told Chen during a meeting last Sunday that the U.S.
position over the election dispute is that it is strictly an internal
affair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040323.0006" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL STABILIZATION FUND NOT USED TO SUPPORT STOCK MARKET
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 23 (CNA)
(By Eric Liu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Premier Yu Shyi-kun said Tuesday that the
National Stabilization Fund has not been used to maintain a stable
stock market in the wake of Saturday's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Even though the Taiwan bourse closed low Tuesday, Yu said, it did
not lose significant ground, so it was not deemed necessary for the
government to step in with the National Stabilization Fund.
</P>
<P>
Board members of the National Stabilization Fund discussed the
timing of using the fund to prop up the stock market, which has taken
abattering in the two trading days since the election, but decided no
action was needed. However, Chen Shuh, vice minister of finance who
doubles as executive secretary of the fund, is authorized to use the
fund to boost the market if need be.
</P>
<P>
Share prices ended the day lower on the Taiwan Stock Exchange
(TAIEX) Tuesday, with the weighted index, the market's key barometer,
losing 187.03 points to close at 6,172.89 with a total of 10.15
billion shares changing hands on a market turnover of NT$249.14
billion (US$7.44 billion), a sharp increase from the previous trading
session, which saw 220 million stocks traded on a market turnover of
NT$47.03 billion (US$1.40 billion).
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors' selling, however, outnumbered buying in the
trading session by NT$19.46 billion (US$580 million) , the
third-highest single day selling on record. Because of the political
turmoil following the election and ensuing controversy, foreign
investors, joined by investment trust companies and securities
brokers, have tended to play the part of onlookers for the time
being.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
