<HEADLINE>
AIT ANNOUNCES NEW APPOINTMENT SYSTEM FOR NON-IMMIGRANT VISAS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 23 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The American Institute in Taiwan (AIT)
announced Tuesday that a new appointment system for applicants for
non-immigrant visas to the United States will go into effect
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The AIT, which represents U.S. interests in Taiwan in the absence
of formal diplomatic ties, said the new system will apply to tourist,
business and student visa applicants.
</P>
<P>
Keith Powell, an AIT section chief in charge of consular affairs,
told a news conference that the new system is already in use in most
large U.S. visa-issuing facilities throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
The system will replace the AIT's existing caller-pay telephone
appointment system, Powell said, adding that the new system will
allow each applicant to set a specific time for a visa application
interview and will provide help to applicants in completing the
application forms.
</P>
<P>
From Wednesday, Powell said, all non-immigrant visa applicants
must go to the Atos Origin Application Processing Center (APC) -- the
AIT's new service provider -- to make an appointment for a visa
interview at AIT.
</P>
<P>
Powell said AIT will be able to handle more visa applicants more
quickly, thus reducing the waiting period for the interview and the
time needed to process a visa.
</P>
<P>
Both the visa application fee of NT$3,400, payable to Taiwan Post
Office account number 19189005, and the service charge of NT$240,
payable to Taiwan Post Office account number 19832104, must be paid
before submitting the visa application to the APC.
</P>
<P>
Applicants must bring a valid passport and receipts to the APC,
Powell said, adding that after accepting the application for
pre-processing, the APC will give each applicant a personal
identification number so that he or she can make an interview
appointment at AIT.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Powell said, the AIT is scheduled to start to collect
fingerprints and photos of visa applicants from Taiwan from September
in line with regulations unveiled by the U.S. Homeland Security
Department early this year. The AIT will not collect additional
charges for the fingerprints and photos, Powell said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040323.0008" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
VALUE OF EXPORT ORDERS FOR FEBRUARY SETS 17-YEAR HIGH GROWTH RATE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 23 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The value of foreign orders placed with
Taiwan companies in February totaled US$15.04 billion, representing
an annual growth rate of 34.68 percent -- a record single-month high
in 17 years, a spokesman for the Statistics Department under the
Ministry of Economic Affairs (MOEA) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The increase rate -- worth about US$3.87 billion -- was a result
of rising prices for stable commodities such as steel and oil in the
international market and an improved economic situation in Asian and
European countries in contrast to the lower levels posted in February
last year, which was also the time of last year's Chinese new year
holiday period, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The value of the foreign orders received last month by Taiwan
semiconductor manufacturers rose by US$1.17 billion, an annual growth
rate of 56.36 percent, while orders for information technology and
telecommunications goods increased by US$430 million in value
year-on-year, representing an annual growth rate of 17.73 percent.
</P>
<P>
Foreign orders for locally manufactured metal and precision
machinery products rose by US$380 million in value each, reflecting
an increase rate of 35.06 percent and 118.24 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Hong Kong, Japan and countries in Europe were
the prime buyers for Taiwan-made products, with local electronics
products being the most popular item, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chang Yaw-tzong, director-general of the MOEA's
Statistics Department, said that short-term non-economic factors will
only have a minimal impact on the country's overall economic
situation.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's export business will only be slightly affected as long
as political strife at home is settled quickly, Chang noted, adding
that the prospects for the domestic economy remain bright.
</P>
<P>
Chang was referring to the mass protest being held in Taipei over
the results of Saturday's presidential poll. Supporters of the
"pan-blue alliance" presidential candidate -- opposition Kuomintang
Chairman Lien Chan -- lost the race by less than 30,000 votes to
President Chen Shui-bian, who won a second term in office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040323.0009" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT RESENTS VOTE-RIGGING CHARGES AGAINST HIM
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 23 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian said Tuesday that
vote-rigging charges against him are a grave insult to his integrity.
</P>
<P>
"They called me a vote-rigging president. This is the biggest
humiliation to my character," Chen said in a raspier-than-usual voice
while meeting with the heads of the nation's five branches of
government at the Presidential Office.
</P>
<P>
In his first public appearance since claiming victory in the most
closely fought presidential election in Taiwan's history last
weekend, Chen said he favors a full recount of the ballots but that
the process must follow the principle of "rule of law."
</P>
<P>
The opposition "pan-blue alliance" presidential ticket of
Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan and People First Party Chairman James
Soong have alleged that Saturday's election was marred by
irregularities, but has so far presented little evidence to back
their claim.
</P>
<P>
Chen said he wants a quick recount to address all doubts. "I
won't object to a speedy, transparent and full-scale recount to help
us find the truth," Chen said, adding that he will accept the outcome
of the recount. "I'll accept it 100 percent, absolutely accept it, "
he said.
</P>
<P>
Lien's biggest complaint about the vote is that what he claims is
an "unusually high" number of ballots -- more than 330,000, or 10
times Chen's margin of victory -- were ruled invalid.
</P>
<P>
Chen said the high number might have been due to stricter
regulations that were used for the first time in accordance with a
revision to the President and Vice President Election and Recall Law
passed last October.
</P>
<P>
The rules required voters to register their candidate preferences
by putting a chop mark squarely inside a box above the candidate's
photo on the ballot. Ballots with stamps that crossed the boundary
lines were deemed invalid.
</P>
<P>
At Lien's demand, the Taiwan High Court seized and sealed all
ballot boxes Sunday and appointed three judges to study the case.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, only prosecutors and judges are eligible to
examine the ballots, a legal procedure that could take six months to
complete.
</P>
<P>
However, Chen said he does not oppose resolving the case through
political means. He suggested that the ruling and opposition parties
negotiate mutually acceptable terms and appoint credible judges to
recount the ballots. Another option would be to revise the law to
allow for people other than judges and prosecutors to examine the
ballots, he added.
</P>
<P>
"In any event, the government will resolve the dispute in line
with the principles of listening to the opposition camp's opinions,
understanding the feelings of the defeated contender and his
supporters, following the guidelines of rule of law and promoting
domestic unity and harmony," Chen explained.
</P>
<P>
The officials present at Tuesday's meeting included Vice
President Annette Lu, Premier Yu Shyi-kun, Legislative Yuan President
Wang Jin-pyng, Judicial Yuan President Weng Yueh-sheng, Control Yuan
President Fredrick Chien and Examination Yuan President Yao Chia-wen.
</P>
<P>
Looking a little under the weather, Chen further said it is
regrettable that some people have accused him of faking the
election-eve assassination attempt against him to win sympathy votes.
</P>
<P>
"Some people have asked if the shooting was real or faked. I
could understand such doubts because the campaign was so heated, "
Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The Presidential Office has released photos of the wound and of
his physicians treating the injury. Lien has demanded that an
independent task force made up of both foreign and local experts be
set up to investigate the shooting. Police have yet to identify
suspects or other important leads.
</P>
<P>
Chen was lightly wounded when an unidentified assailant fired at
least two shots at himself and Vice President Annette Lu while they
were driving past large crowds of supporters in an open-top jeep in
the southern city of Tainan last Friday. The shooting grazed Chen's
abdomen and hit Lu's right knee.
</P>
<P>
Noting that he and Lu were more eager than anyone else to get to
the bottom of the incident, Chen said he would welcome independent
third-party participation in an inquiry into the shooting incident.
</P>
<P>
"We are the ones who were shot. We are more eager than anyone
else to find out the truth," Chen added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
