<HEADLINE>
EXECUTIVE YUAN HOPES TO RECOUNT BALLOTS WEEKEND AFTER NEXT
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 23 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Executive Yuan hopes that a recount of
the ballots from Saturday's presidential election will be conducted
the weekend after next, an official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Executive Yuan Secretary-General Liu Shih-fang said that the
Executive Yuan has invited the Ministry of the Interior and the
Central Election Commission (CEC) to discuss the recounting
procedure.
</P>
<P>
She said that the Executive Yuan hopes that the Legislative Yuan
passes the third reading of a draft revising the President and Vice
President Election and Recall Law Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the opposition "pan-blue alliance" of the
Kuomintang and People First Party must retract the lawsuit they filed
after Saturday's presidential election to nullify the election and
its outcome to begin the recounting process, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
On the timing of the recount, Liu said that this would be up to
the Central Election Commission to decide, although the Executive
Yuan hopes to complete it the weekend after next. Presidential
candidates or their designated representatives and prosecutors will
be invited to witness the recounting process, she said.
</P>
<P>
She said that it should be possible to complete the recounting in
one day at a cost of about NT$300 million to NT$500 million
(US$9.09 million to US$15.15 million).
</P>
<P>
Recounting the votes by this weekend would be rushing things, she
said, adding that the weekend after next might be an ideal time,
although the decision remains with the CEC.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, she said that the application to recount the ballots
will not affect the scheduled publication by the CEC of the results
of the election on March 26.
</P>
<P>
"If the recount proves that Lien won, then the CEC will still be
able to retract its earlier publication," she said.
</P>
<P>
The CEC is scheduled to convene a meeting March 26 during which
its members will review the presidential election outcome and publish
the names of those elected.
