<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATIVE SPEAKER WILL MEDIATE TALKS ON REVISING ELECTION LAW
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 23 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Legislative Yuan President Wang Jin-pyng
said Tuesday he will mediate negotiations the same evening between
lawmakers of various political factions to explore the possibility of
revising the law to recount of votes in the controversial
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Although it would be quicker for the Central Election Committee
(CEC) to order a recount of the votes in the just-concluded
presidential election, the legal framework for such an order is weak,
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Revising the current law might be somewhat time consuming but in
the end would be more practical. The aim is to revise the law to call
for recounts in cases where the difference between votes for the
winner and runner-up in the presidential election is very small.
</P>
<P>
In Wang's view, if different parties agree to revise the law in
the negotiations Tuesday evening, the Legislative Yuan may enact it
in a legislative session on Thursday, which will open the door for a
recount of the votes.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after a skirmish between lawmakers of the
ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) and the opposition
Kuomintang (KMT) earlier in the day over whether the ongoing dispute
between the DPP and the alliance of the KMT and the People First
Party (PFP) should be settled through revising the President and Vice
President Election and Recall Law.
</P>
<P>
KMT Legislator Liao Feng-teh, who is the chairman of the Rules
Committee of the Legislative Yuan, turned down the request of a group
of DPP lawmakers on the committee to put onto the agenda a proposal
to revise the law to provide for a recount of votes when the
difference between the winner and the loser in the presidential
election is less than 1 percent of the total votes.
</P>
<P>
Insisting that it was the CEC that should order a recount, Liao
refused to discuss the DPP lawmakers' idea and ordered a recess of
the meeting, which irritated the DPP lawmakers. One of them chased
after him and stopped him from leaving the meeting room and a
skirmish ensued.
</P>
<P>
The dispute arises from the March 20 presidential election in
which the KMT's candidate, Lien Chan, and his running make, PFP
Chairman James Soong, lost by 0.228 percent.
</P>
<P>
Claiming that the election was unfair, the two have led their
supporters to protest in front of the Presidential Office where they
have been since Sunday morning, asking for a recount of the votes.
</P>
