TAIWAN HOPES TO LURE FOREIGN TOURISTS FOLLOWING PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 23 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Tourism Bureau under the Ministry of
Transportation and Communications has asked its overseas stations to
try to attract foreign visitors to Taiwan now that the emotional
presidential election has ended, a spokesman for the bureau said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman made the remarks after being notified by its
missions stationed in Japan that many Japanese tourists have put off
their travel plans to Taiwan in view of the present situation in
Taiwan -- mainly the mass protest being held in Taipei over the
results of Saturday's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Japan has long been Taiwan's No. 1 source of foreign tourists.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that the bureau has demanded its overseas outposts
to clarify and give an explanation of the current situation in Taiwan
to local travel agencies in their host countries, especially those in
Japan, the spokesman said that the bureau's outposts abroad have made
it clear that foreign travelers should visit Taiwan without fear,
because Taiwan is a country ruled by law and order.
</P>
<P>
The outbreaks of the potentially deadly severe acute respiratory
syndrome in the first half of last year in Taiwan and a spread of an
avian flu in Japan and other Asian nations have largely affected the
travel willingness of Japanese people, the spokesman said, noting
that the number of Japanese tourists to Taiwan has dropped by over 30
percent since the beginning of this year until now as compared to the
previous year's level.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the number of people from Hong Kong and Macau
visiting Taiwan rose by 3 percent in January over the year-earlier
level, but the February number plunged by 34 percent year-on-year.
Hong Kong and Macau generate the second-largest number of tourists
for Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian won his re-election by a very slim
margin of less than 30,000 votes over his challenger -- major
opposition Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan, prompting the latter to
question the fairness of the election. A group of Lien's supporters
have gathered in the square in front of the Presidential Office since
late Saturday to demand a recount.
