<HEADLINE>
NEUTRALITY FIRST IN INVESTIGATING SHOOTING OF PRESIDENT: PROSECUTOR
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 23 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A prosecutor general in Tainan, southern
Taiwan, stressed Tuesday that judicial neutrality will take
precedence over political party affiliation in investigating the
shooting of President Chen Shui-bian and Vice President Annette Lu
last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Liu Wei-chung said that there are four prosecutors investigating
the shooting, and he has no need to expand the task force.
</P>
<P>
Liu was responding to reports that the task force is excluding
other prosecutors from taking part in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
Both the president and the vice president were injured in the
attack when they were canvassing in Tainan Friday afternoon, the
shooting might have played a role in the bitterly contested
presidential election, in which Chen won by a razor-thin margin
against his challenger, Chairman Lien Chan of the Kuomintang.
</P>
<P>
Lien has raised questions about the shooting, demanding that an
independent task force be formed by local and foreign experts to
investigate the case.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that he would like to see other district prosecutors
providing information and other creative ideas to track down the
possible shooter or shooters, but that they would not be directly
involved with the hands-on, day-to-day work of the four
investigators.
</P>
<P>
Police have so far made no arrests and have not announced any
suspects or leads. They did find two bullets, and have said that
possible suspects include gamblers who illegally wagered a lot of
money on the election outcome.
</P>
<P>
"Four prosecutors are enough, " Liu said, adding that the role of
the prosecutors is to command police forces in their investigations
and more prosecutors would not be helpful.
</P>
<P>
On questions about the party affiliations of the prosecutors and
whether a balanced proportion between the two rival camps should be
maintained, Liu pointed to the judicial neutrality of the
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
He said that "judicial neutrality will supersede that of party
affiliation, " and that "it is not necessary to add more prosecutors
to the case and I will not do so."
</P>
</TEXT>
