<HEADLINE>
TAIPEI MAYOR MA YING-JEOU WELCOMES AMENDMENT TO FACILITATE RECOUNT
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 23 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei Mayor Ma Ying-jeou welcomed the
ruling Democratic Progressive Party's (DPP) move Tuesday to push for
an amendment to the President and Vice President Election and Recall
Law aimed at legalizing a recounting of the votes in Saturday's
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Ma said an early passage of the amendment -- put forward by the
DPP legislative caucus Tuesday at the Legislative Yuan -- will be
conducive to a quick and rational end to the demonstration which has
been going on in front of the Presidential Office by supporters of
the "pan-blue alliance" presidential ticket of Lien Chan and James
Soong since the evening of the election on March 20.
</P>
<P>
The Lien-Soong ticket lost to incumbent President Chen Shui-bian
and Vice President Annette Lu by a razor-thin margin of just under
30,000 votes, or 0.228 percent of the total votes counted. Some
"pan-blue alliance" supporters are protesting the March 20 election
as being "unfair" and are demanding a recount.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to remove any doubts by the opposition and to seek
an early settlement to the election dispute, which has disrupted
social order and caused a nosedive in the Taipei stock market, the
DPP caucus put forward the proposal and has called for an extra
voting session Tuesday for a speedy passage of the amendment, DPP
legislative party whip Tsai Huang-lang said.
</P>
<P>
"It is hoped that the proposed amendment can go through the three
readings at the Legislative Yuan before nightfall Tuesday so that it
can be formally passed into law and implemented by Thursday, " Tsai
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, opposition "pan-blue alliance" legislators voiced
doubts about the feasibility of the DPP's timetable, saying it is
impossible for the amendment to be passed into law within two days
given the existing legislative structure and voting process.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the demonstrators cannot wait any longer, Liao
Feng-teh, a Kuomintang legislative party whip, demanded that the
Central Election Commission (CEC) immediately convene a meeting to
pass a motion, with the consent of at least half of the CEC members,
asking for an administrative recount of Saturday's votes without
delay.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mayor Ma called for the central government to take
charge of efforts to deal with the demonstration rally in front of
the Presidential Office.
</P>
<P>
Ma said the demonstration is an issue of high political
sensitivity and is taking place in an area near the Presidential
Office. The Taipei City Government is unable to meet the protesters'
demands, he added.
</P>
<P>
Simply by asking the demonstrators to disperse and stop
disrupting the nearby hospital and schools has not had any effect, Ma
said, adding that it would be better if the central government took
over the matter.
</P>
<P>
The Taipei City Government will continue maintaining traffic
control and keeping the environment clean in the area surrounding the
Presidential Office once the central government takes over efforts to
appease the protesters, Ma added.
</P>
</TEXT>
