</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 23 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The protests in front of the Presidential
Office in downtown Taipei in the post-election turmoil since last
weekend may have claimed their first victim.
</P>
<P>
A 79-year-old woman in Hualien, eastern Taiwan, who has been
continuously watching the marathon protests carried live by several
television stations since the end of the presidential election,
collapsed at home in the early morning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
She was rushed to the hospital, but doctors were unable to
resuscitate her.
</P>
<P>
Family members said that she was very concerned with the
"pan-blue alliance" protesters, who are demanding a recount of all
the ballots in the election, and had been glued to the television
over the past two days.
</P>
<P>
She might have been in a sustained, agitated mood watching the
protests, which triggered a heart attack, they said.
</P>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian won re-election by a slim margin of
fewer than 30,000 votes Saturday against his challenger, Lien Chan,
who later said that the election was "unfair" and called for a
recount of the ballots.
</P>
