<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT SAYS VOTE-RIGGING CHARGE AN INSULT, FAVORS FULL RECOUNT
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 23 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian said Tuesday that
vote-rigging charges against him were a grave insult to his
integrity.
</P>
<P>
"They called A-bian a vote-rigging president. This is the biggest
insult to my integrity, " Chen said while meeting with the heads of
the nation's five branches of government at the Presidential Office.
A-bian is Chen's nickname.
</P>
<P>
In his first public appearance since claiming victory in the most
closely fought presidential election in Taiwan's history last
weekend, Chen also said he favors a full recount of the ballots but
that the process must follow the law.
</P>
<P>
"I won't object to a full-scale recount to help us find the
truth," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The opposition "pan-blue alliance" presidential ticket of
Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan and People First Party Chairman James
Soong alleged that Saturday's election was marred by irregularities,
but the alliance has so far presented little evidence.
</P>
<P>
President Chen also expressed his deep regret over allegations
that he faked an election-eve assassination attempt to win sympathy
votes.
</P>
<P>
"It is extremely regrettable that some people claim that I had
faked the shooting incident on the final day of the campaign to boost
my re-election bid," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
He was lightly wounded when an unidentified assailant fired at
least two shots at the president and Vice President Annette Lu while
they were driving past large crowds of supporters in an open-top jeep
in the southern city of Tainan last Friday. The shooting grazed
Chen's abdomen and hit Lu's right knee.
</P>
<P>
Chen said he would welcome independent third-party participation
in an investigation into the shooting incident after the opposition
"pan-blue alliance" demanded an external inquiry.
</P>
<P>
Chen said he and Vice President Lu were more eager than anyone to
get to the bottom of the incident. "We are the ones who were shot. We
are more eager than anyone else to find out the truth."
</P>
