<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040323.0033" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PERCENTAGE OF DISMISSED LOCAL WORKERS LINKED TO HIRING FOREIGNERS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 23 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
If the percentage of domestic workers laid
off or fired reaches a certain level, their employers will not be
allowed to apply to employ foreign laborers, the Council of Labor
Affairs (CLA) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
To protect local workers, CLA officials said that they will
examine the employment records for the past two years of companies
seeking approval to hire foreign workers to see whether they have
exceeded the percentage limits.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that for employers of over 200 workers, if
they lay off or fire 16 percent of their workforce, they will be
prohibited from hiring foreign workers. For employers of between 20
and 199 workers, 37 percent is the cutoff. For those employing fewer
than 19 workers, the limit is 76 percent.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the CLA's Employment and Vocational Training
Administration said that since the legal dismissal of domestic
workers is not directly related to the hiring of foreign workers,
they have formulated a more relaxed system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040323.0034" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATIVE HEAD SUGGESTS PRESIDENT ISSUE DECREE FOR RECOUNT
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 23 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Legislative Yuan President Wang Jin-pyng
suggested Tuesday that President Chen Shui-bian issue an emergency
decree to facilitate an immediate vote recount to clear up any doubts
surrounding Chen's victory in Saturday's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Wang suggested that President Chen issue the decree also to
facilitate the establishment of an ad hoc committee to conduct an
open and objective investigation into the unexplained assassination
attempt against Chen and Vice President Annette Lu on the eve of the
election. The sympathy generated by the incident is widely believed
to have given the Chen-Lu ticket a decisive boost in the election.
</P>
<P>
Wang said an emergency decree by the president is the best,
quickest and most efficient way of solving the election dispute,
which has disrupted social order and caused a nosedive in the Taipei
stock market.
</P>
<P>
The Legislative Yuan head made the suggestion during a meeting of
the presidents of the Executive, Legislative, Judicial, Examination
and Control Yuans called by President Chen. The meeting was the first
of its kind held in the wake of the election.
</P>
<P>
Wang, a campaign manager for the opposition "pan-blue alliance"
presidential ticket of Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan and People First
Party Chairman James Soong, said he made the suggestion to President
Chen in his capacity as the head of the Legislative Yuan -- a neutral
and independent position.
</P>
<P>
"Pan-blue alliance" supporters continued their sit-in in front of
the presidential palace that began Saturday night, claiming the March
20 election was "unfair" and demanding an open and immediate vote
recount.
</P>
<P>
The Lien-Soong ticket lost to incumbent President Chen Shui-bian
and Vice President Annette Lu by a razor-thin margin of just under
30,000 votes, or 0.228 percent of the total votes counted.
</P>
</TEXT>
