<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040323.0035" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 23 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Tuesday, March 23, or the
third day of the leap second month of the Year of the Monkey
according to the lunar calendar. Following is a list of important
events that have occurred on this date in the past:

1775: Patrick Henry, U.S. statesman, makes a plea for American
freedom from Britain, declaring: "Give me liberty or give me death."

1910: The British government removes its consulate in Anping,
southern Taiwan.

1912: Wernher von Braun, a German-born rocket expert who designed
the V1 and V2 rockets and later worked for NASA, is born.

1913: Fire engulfs the Taipei Post Office.

1916: Yuan Shih-kai, who declared himself Hung Hsien emperor on
Dec. 12, 1915, gives up his throne.

1918: Lithuania proclaims its independence.

1919: A group of disillusioned former socialists and Italian war
veterans, led by Benito Mussolini, form the Fascist Party (Fasci di
Combattimento) in Milan.

1935: The Soviet Union sells its interest in the Chinese Eastern
Railway to Japan.

1942: The U.S. government begins moving Japanese-Americans from
their homes on the U.S. West Coast to inland detention camps.

1956: Pakistan becomes an Islamic republic, with Maj. Gen.
Iskander Mirza as its first provisional president.

1959: Communist Chinese troops capture Lhasa, capital of Tibet,
and engage in large-scale suppression of rebelling Tibetans.

1962: Sixteen Communist Chinese MiG jet fighters fly over the
Republic of China-controlled island of Kinmen, with one of them being
shot and partly damaged by anti-aircraft fire.

1962: The Savannah, the world's first nuclear merchant ship, is
launched in New Jersey.

1973: Gen. Yin Chun, commander in chief of the Taiwan Garrison
Command, leaves for Manila for a four-day visit.

1974: A ceremony to honor the 2,346th anniversary of the birth of
Mencius is held in Taipei.

1983: U.S. President Ronald Reagan dubs the Soviet Union "an evil
empire" and proposes a "Star Wars" defense system.

1992: The first-ever meeting between Taiwan's Straits Exchange
Foundation and the mainland's Association for Relations Across the
Taiwan Strait convenes in Peking to discuss issues related to
document verification and indirect registered postal services.

1994: The Legislative Yuan increases the annual quota of
permanent residency permits for mainland spouses of ROC citizens from
300 to 600.

1995: The Regulations Governing the Management and Compensation
for Victims of the Feb. 28, 1947 Incident are passed by the
Legislative Yuan. The regulations provide for the establishment of a
foundation to manage relevant affairs and for the designation of Feb.
28 as a day of national commemoration.

1995: A two-day convention of secretary-generals of the Olympic
Council of Asian member nations opens in Kaohsiung. Following
international practice, the convention hoists the flags of all OCA
members -- including the five-star flag of mainland China.

1996: Four pairs of candidates compete in the first-ever direct
election of the ROC president and vice president. Lee Teng-hui and
his running mate Lien Chan win with 54 percent of the vote. At the
same time, 334 members of the Third National Assembly are also
elected.

1998: Russia's President Boris Yeltsin fires his prime minister
and the entire Cabinet.

2000: Newly appointed Republic of Sao Tome &amp; Principe Ambassador
to the ROC Ovidio Manuel Barb Osa Pequeno presents a copy of his
credentials to Foreign Minister Chen Chien-jen.

2000: ROC President-elect Chen Shui-bian meets with Defense
Minister Tang Fei and the chief of the General Staff, Tang Yao-ming.

2001: Premier Chang Chun-hsiung admits that his administration
thus far is a failure, only to recant the statement later and dismiss
its as a slip of the tongue.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "Make it a rule to work for
something before you accept anything as your own: that is, perhaps,
the best way to elevate the moral sentiment. Make it a habit to
assail your own vices and failings before you assail the vices and
failings of others: that is, perhaps, the best way to discover the
secret vices of your innermost mind."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
