<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040324.0010" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
NEARLY 64 PERCENT STILL CAUGHT UP IN ELECTION: POLL
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 24 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nearly 64 percent of respondents to an
Internet poll said that they are still emotionally involved in the
aftermath of last Saturday's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The online human resource company 1111.com.tw and Taiwan
Adventist Hospital jointly conducted the survey Tuesday, with over
2,000 effective questionnaires collected.
</P>
<P>
Wu Chun-ying, a spokesman of the online company, said that 53
percent of those responding to the Internet poll said they watched TV
all day Saturday, and nearly 30 percent said that they couldn't
accept the outcome of the election, which saw President Chen
Shui-bian win another four-year term by a slim margin of 0.228
percent, or fewer than 30,000 votes, against his challenger, Lien
Chan of the Kuomintang.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-seven percent also said that they couldn't sleep and were
anxious, showing signs of what has been termed "post-election
syndrome."
</P>
<P>
Lee Ming-ping, superintendent of the Taipei City Psychiatric
Center, said that there is no such disease as "post-election
syndrome, " in the medical sense; instead, it is viewed as something
that causes pressure, which could in turn exacerbate the conditions
of patients or trigger emotional disturbances.
</P>
<P>
Over 40 percent said that they continue to watch events unfold on
TV.
</P>
<P>
Lien filed a lawsuit right after the election to have it
nullified, claiming it was "unfair, " pointing particularly to the
shooting of President Chen and Vice President Annette Lu on the eve
of the vote, which the "pan-blue alliance" claims won enough sympathy
votes to hand the incumbent president victory. Supporters of the
"pan-blue alliance" continued their fourth day of protests in front
of the Presidential Office in downtown Taipei.
</P>
<P>
Wu pointed out that this shows that Taiwan voters are easily
affected by elections, and that this election has made a great impact
on the atmosphere of the workplace.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that one interesting result of elections of this sort is
that they bring families together, since people are required to vote
where they have housing registration, usually their hometowns.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 20 percent said that they had a "rare" family reunion
because of the election, the poll showed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040324.0011" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
ROC VICTIMS OF A-BOMBS IN JAPAN ELIGIBLE FOR JAPANESE  STIPENDS: MOFA
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 24 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Republic of China citizens who suffered
injuries from atomic explosions in Japan during World War II are
eligible to apply for living subsidies from the Japanese government,
the Ministry of Foreign Affairs said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to amendments to Japan's atomic explosions aid law
passed by the Japanese Ministry of Health, Welfare and Labor in
February 2003, victims of atomic explosions in the two Japanese
cities of Hiroshima and Nagasaki in 1945 who now live outside Japan
can also apply with the Japanese government for a monthly living
subsidy of 34,030 Japanese yen (US$318).
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministry officials said this new Japanese regulation is
applicable to ROC citizens.
</P>
<P>
"The foreign ministry has asked the Ministry of the Interior and
the Department of Health inform local people of this new regulation
and to urge local victims to file applications with Japanese
authorities as soon as possible," said a foreign ministry official.
</P>
<P>
He said local victims should mail application forms plus
diagnosis certificates and other related documents to the Nagasaki
City Government. Once the Japanese authorities approve the travel
schedule, the applicants can travel to Japan for physical checkups.
The Japanese government will pay for travel and other relevant
expenses.
</P>
<P>
The official further said only the victims themselves are
eligible to apply for the Japanese living subsidies. The next of kin
of those who have died of atomic explosion injuries are not eligible
to apply for the subsidy.
</P>
<P>
It's not clear how many Taiwan people were injured by atomic
bombs dropped by American forces in Hiroshima and Nagasaki in August
1945.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
