<HEADLINE>
KMT DISMISSES REPORTS ABOUT DISBANDING PROTESTERS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 24 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A spokesman for the opposition Kuomintang
(KMT) denied reports Wednesday that the party will disband the
protesters occupying the square in front of the Presidential Office
after a planned demonstration this Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Tsai Cheng-yuan made the remarks after KMT Chairman Lien Chan,
who lost by a razor-thin margin to President Chen Shui-bian, who won
another four-year term, in the March 20 presidential election,
presided over the regular weekly KMT Central Standing Committee
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Lien instructed related party organizations to plan for the March
27 "fight for justice and save democracy" rally on Ketagalan
Boulevard in front of the Presidential Office.
</P>
<P>
Lien said that he has been deeply touched by the sight of
thousands of protestors, many of them rotating in shifts, bracing
against days of chilly and damp weather to protest what they claim
was an "unfair" election.
</P>
<P>
The protestors demanded a quick recount of the ballots after Lien
lost by a 0.22 percent margin, or fewer than 30,000 votes, and a full
explanation of what they claim are "suspicious circumstances"
surrounding the shooting of President Chen Shui-bian and Vice
President Annette Lu on the eve of the election, which they believe
gave Chen sympathy votes and victory in the hotly contested election.
</P>
<P>
The crowd has refused to disperse and instead has continued a
generally orderly protest to keep up pressure, even though the
government has already agreed to a recount and has urged the leaders
of the "pan-blue alliance" of the KMT and the People First Party --
Lien and his running mate, PFP Chairman James Soong -- to take
responsibility for persuading them to leave the usually bustling
thoroughfare.
</P>
<P>
As the "pan-blue alliance" is now planning to stage another rally
March 27, reports have said that the KMT would disband the crowd
after the rally, but Tsai said that "this is not true " and added
that for "strategic reasons," the party will keep its options open.
</P>
<P>
Several KMT legislators also expressed their views about the
March 27 rally, with legislators and Central Standing Committee
members Hung Hsiu-chu and Huang Chao-shun saying that they are
willing to stage a sit-in fast.
</P>
<P>
Other KMT Central Standing Committee members said that the whole
party should be mobilized for the rally, while others suggested that
an islandwide journey should be embarked upon to appeal to the
grassroots.
</P>
<P>
KMT Vice Chairman and Taipei Mayor Ma Ying-jeou said that the
appeal should be expanded to solicit the support of the public views
in the days leading up to the rally, according to Tsai.
</P>
<P>
After March 27, a series of activities should be held around the
island, with KMT officials facing the people to explore the
ramifications of the election, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
Local support groups of the "pan-blue alliance" should also form
committees to become a force in opposing the "unfair" election, Ma
added.
</P>
<P>
In related developments, Ho Ching-he, speaker of the Chiayi
county council, called for civil servants of the KMT to donate one
month's worth of their salaries to buy fruit for the protesters in
Taipei as a gesture of support.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a 25-year-old man surnamed Kuo was arrested when he
moved toward Taipei Mayor Ma in a suspicious manner when Ma was
cheering on the protesters Wednesday afternoon. He was discovered to
be carrying a toy gun, although he claimed that he was at the scene
because of his admiration for Ma.
</P>
