<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN TEAM INSPECTS PALACE MUSEUM BRANCH CONSTRUCTION SITE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Chiayi,  Taiwan,  March 24 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A team of senior executives from
Canada's Lord Cultural Resources Planning and Management Inc. made an
inspection tour Wednesday of the planned construction site in Chiayi
County for the southern Taiwan branch of the National Palace Museum.
</P>
<P>
Lord has won the bid to come up with a blueprint for the National
Palace Museum's Chiayi branch and Wednesday's visit marked the first
time that Lord has sent staff to inspect the planned construction
site in southern Taiwan's Taipao City.
</P>
<P>
Chuck Sutyla, Lord's project director and leader of the Canadian
team, said he is impressed by the site's convenient location and the
rich tourist resources in the vicinity.
</P>
<P>
Lord has assisted in constructing museums in Saudi Arabia,
Singapore, the Philippines and Chicago. This is the first time the
company has been involved in building a cultural facility in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The National Palace Museum in suburban Taipei is one of the
world's most famous museums, with a huge collection of ancient
Chinese art treasures and antiquities.
</P>
<P>
The museum's southern Taiwan branch is scheduled for inauguration
in 2008. The construction site is near the Taipao station of the
Taiwan high-speed railway, which is scheduled for completion late
next year and will be a major gateway for the new museum.
</P>
<P>
The construction site is close to many tourist attractions in the
Yunlin-Chiayi-Tainan region, including the Alishan scenic area, the
Yunlin coastal scenic area and the Peikang Matsu Temple.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Palace Museum's plan, its southern
branch will focus on displaying Asian art objects and on promoting
cultural development in the southern part of the island. The new
museum is also expected to help boost tourist and economic
development in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
