<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040324.0018" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT VOWS TO HEAL RIFT IN SOCIETY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 24 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian said Wednesday he
will do whatever he can to "heal the rift" in local society in the
wake of his narrow re-election victory.
</P>
<P>
Chen made the pledge while meeting with 11 key opinion leaders at
the Presidential Office to seek their advice about how to resolve the
post-election dispute and how to increase social harmony and unity.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, he also said he is willing to meet with the
opposition "pan-blue alliance" presidential and vice presidential
candidates -- Kuomintang (KMT) Chairman Lien Chan and People First
Party (PFP) Chairman James Soong.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Chen expressed hope that the two opposition leaders
will ask their supporters still demonstrating in front of the
Presidential Office to disperse so that both sides can have a more
"calm, rational and objective" dialogue environment.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Lien-Soong supporters have been protesting outside
the Presidential Office following Chen's re-election last Saturday.
The Lien-Soong camp has alleged that Saturday's election was marred
by irregularities, but has so far presented little evidence to back
their claim.
</P>
<P>
Chen noted that the demonstrators have endured hardships,
including chilly drizzle, over the past four days. "I hope the
opposition leaders can persuade their supporters to go home as soon
as possible so that calmness can resume in our society," he added.
</P>
<P>
But the president said he has no intention of making an end to
the demonstration a premise for a meeting with Lien and Soong. In
fact, he said, he has always been willing to meet with the two
opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting need not be held inside the Presidential Office. I'm
willing to visit them at a place of their convenience. In addition to
discussing matters related to the election, I also hope to seek their
counsel about a broad range of national affairs and policy issues, "
Chen said.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to calm an increasingly divided public, Chen said
the 23 million Taiwan people share a common destiny. "All of us are
masters of this island, regardless of their ethnic origin."
</P>
<P>
During his second term, Chen went on, he will listen to
"different, diverse voices, " particularly opinions from the
opposition camp.
</P>
<P>
"The coming four years mark a new hope. My last election battle
is over. I no longer have 're-election' pressure and I'll work
selflessly for our homeland," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the election-eve assassination attempt against him,
Chen said his brush with death has had an impact on his view of life.
"I'll dedicate myself to service. I'll push for Taiwan's economic
growth and reform in various aspects. I'm the president of the 23
million Taiwan people, not just the president of the 647 million
people who voted for me," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The 11 opinion leaders included Red Cross Society President C.V.
Chen; China Times Group General Manager Huang Chao-sung; noted
writers Bo Yang and Huang Chun-ming; Clean Election Promotion
Association President Tsai Sung-lin; former Taipei Society President
Chu Hai-yuan; Public Television Service Chairman Wu Feng-shan; and
National Policy Adviser Hsiao Hsin-huang.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of the meeting, Chen said last Saturday's
presidential vote exposed some of the more serious divisions among
the 23 million people of the country.
</P>
<P>
"How can we unify Taiwan and heal the rifts among the various
ethnic groups?" Chen asked. "I'd like to have your valuable views and
opinions as guidelines for my next four years in office."
</P>
<P>
Before the election, Chen said he had assured Academia Sinica
President Lee Yuan-tseh, who is also the only Taiwan-born Nobel
laureate, that he will continue carrying out various reform programs
in his second term and give priority to "healing the ethnic rifts."
</P>
<P>
Many of those who are protesting outside the Presidential Office
are what are termed "mainlanders" -- people whose families fled to
Taiwan from mainland China when the communists took over the mainland
in 1949. This group, which comprises only about 15 percent of the
population, have traditionally supported the KMT, whose leader, Lien
Chan, lost Saturday's vote by a slim margin of 0.2 percent, or 29,518
ballots.
</P>
<P>
The core supporters of Chen's Democratic Progressive Party
describe themselves as "native Taiwanese" -- people whose ancestors
migrated to Taiwan from the mainland centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
During the election, the KMT frequently accused Chen of inflaming
the social divisions. The party said Chen unfairly suggested that
Lien was in cahoots with Beijing and would sell out Taiwan if
elected.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has never ruled Taiwan, but claims that the island
belongs to the mainland and must unify eventually or face war.
Beijing despises Chen because he refuses to endorse unification.
</P>
<P>
Chen has argued that his campaign was not divisive. While meeting
with the 11 opinion leaders, Chen said his campaign to strengthen
Taiwan's national identity should not be narrowly interpreted as a
drive to de-sinicization. He further said that in a democratic
country like Taiwan, political parties should compete for voter
support but should refrain from "zero-sum" political wrangling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040324.0019" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
CENTRAL GOVERNMENT URGED TO SAVE GUGGENHEIM MUSEUM PLAN
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taichung,  March  24  (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cultural and literary circles in
Taichung, central Taiwan urged the central government Wednesday to
retain a plan to build a satellite Guggenheim Museum in Taichung
before it's too late.
</P>
<P>
Since it is crucial that a decision is reached before the end of
March on whether the museum will be set up in Taichung City, members
of Taichung's cultural and literary circles called for help from the
Executive Yuan.
</P>
<P>
Taichung Mayor Jason Hu said in early February that the dateline
for signing an agreement with the Guggenheim has passed and that if
the city cannot ink the agreement soon by obtaining the trust and the
support of the Guggenheim Museum and overcoming technical problems,
the plan might have to be aborted altogether.
</P>
<P>
It will be pitiful if the plan is aborted, as the museum's
designer -- Iraqi-English architect Zaha Hadid -- has recently been
awarded the 2004 Pritzker Architecture Prize, the world's top
architectural honor, said Huang Chao-hu, a spokesman for the
Guggenheim Museum Promotion Group in Taichung.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the Taichung Guggenheim, Hadid also designed such
structures as the free-flowing Guggenheim Museum in Bilbao, Spain;
the Rosenthal Center for Contemporary Art in Cincinnati; a tram
station in Strasbourg, France; and a contemporary arts center in
Rome.
</P>
<P>
The first woman to win the Pritzker Architecture Prize, Hadid has
become known for her futuristic masterpieces featuring floating
spaces, geometric patterns and ribbons of concrete.
</P>
<P>
Huang and his group made three emergency calls Wednesday to the
Taichung city government and the central government. They urged Hu
not to give up his strenuous efforts to save the Taichung Guggenheim
plan.
</P>
<P>
If the central government will not allocate NT$5 billion (US$150
million) to support the plan it should take over the matter and in
turn finance the building of a national Taiwan Guggenheim Fine Arts
Museum anywhere in the country, they said.
</P>
<P>
In the event that the Guggenheim plan fails altogether, the
Taichung city council should use the funds that were originally
allocated for building the museum to construct a Taichung City
Contemporary Fine Arts Museum, they suggested.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hu said later in the day that he has not given up on
the plan and urged the Executive Yuan to make a decision quickly to
foot the NT$5 billion bill and related taxes to facilitate the
realization of the program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040324.0020" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
FEWER TAIWAN PASSENGERS USING MACAU AIRPORT
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Macau,  March 24 (CNA)
(By  Adam Lee and Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The number of passengers from Taiwan who
used Macau airport last year dropped by 33 percent, reflecting the
largest plunge in traveler numbers on all routes around the world to
the former Portuguese colony's airport since it began operations,
according to statistics released by the Macau authorities.
</P>
<P>
According to the tallies, a total of 2.9 million passengers used
the airport in 2003, a drop of about 30 percent compared to the 2002
level.
</P>
<P>
During this year's Chinese new year holiday season in late
January -- which traditionally is a peak travel season for Chinese
people around the world -- Taiwan people paid only about 169,000
visits to Macau, a 1 percent reduction from the number posted in
January of last year, when the annual lunar new year fell in
February.
</P>
<P>
Sources from Macau's aviation industry attributed the decline in
Taiwan passenger numbers using Macau -- a key transfer stop for
Taiwan people heading to or flying from mainland China -- to the
opening last year of an indirect Shanghai-Taipei route via Okinawa.
The source claimed that at least 10 percent of travelers are now
opting for routes other than Macau when they fly between Taiwan and
the mainland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
