<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040324.0026" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
DOH TO SPEND US$87.87 BILLION ON TUBERCULOSIS PROJECT
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  24 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In view of the fact that new cases of
tuberculosis continue to rise unabated each year in Taiwan, the
Department of Health (DOH) is preparing to spend NT$2.9 billion
(US$87.87 million) over the next five years on the diagnosis and cure
of sufferers of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Su Yi-jen, director-general of DOH"s Center for Disease Control,
said that among the new cases reported each year, 22 percent are not
tuberculosis but lung cancer cases that have been mis-diagnosed as
tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
This shows that in addition to X-ray examinations, a positive
sputum smear test is required to confirm a tuberculosis infection.
</P>
<P>
Chang Shan-chun, director of infectious diseases of the National
Taiwan University Hospital (NTUH), said that for a first-time patient
of tuberculosis, the typical symptoms of fever, coughing and weight
loss may not be apparent and even a sputum smear may not be
sufficient for a positive diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
Yang Su-piao, a former NTUH superintendent, said that the quality
and quantity of examiners for sputum smear tests are insufficient,
noting that sputum smear culture tests are very time-consuming and
that a single examiner can only conduct 30 tests a day at most.
</P>
<P>
Responding to their views, Su said that the DOH's five-year
project aims to raise the cure rate of tuberculosis to 87 percent and
lower the mortality rate to less than four out of every 100,000 cases
by 2008.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
