<HEADLINE>
CROSS-STRAIT PHONE CALLS GROWING RAPIDLY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 24 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Despite the fact that relations across
the Taiwan Strait have been in a prolonged state of limbo, the number
of cross-strait telephone calls has grown rapidly over the past eight
years, the Ministry of Transportation and Communications (MOTC) said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to MOTC tallies, the number of cross-strait phone calls
has grown at an average annual rate of 24 percent over the past eight
years.
</P>
<P>
The statistics showed that 435.64 million phone calls were made
across the Taiwan Strait in 2003, up 13.7 percent from the
year-earlier level. Among them, 185.78 million calls, or 42.7
percent, originated from mainland China, marking an increase of 9.7
percent over the previous year's figure. The number of
Taiwan-originating phone calls amounted to 249.86 million, up 16.8
percent over the 2002 level.
</P>
<P>
In terms of time, cross-strait telephone calls reached 1.51
billion minutes in 2003, marking a 22.6-percent increase over the
year-earlier level.
</P>
</TEXT>
