<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 24 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Wednesday, March 24, or the
fourth day of the leap second month of the Year of the Monkey
according to the lunar calendar. Following is a list of important
events that have occurred on this date in the past:

1401: Tamerlane, or Tamburlaine, the Mongolian ruler who led his
hordes from their capital of Samarkand in central Asia to overrun
vast areas of Persia, Turkey, Russia and India, conquers Damascus.

1603: Elizabeth I, Queen of England and Ireland who succeeded the
Catholic Mary I and reestablished Protestantism in England, dies at
the age of 70. Her reign was marked by the execution of Mary Queen of
Scots, the defeat of the Spanish Armada, and domestic prosperity and
literary achievement.

1783: Spain recognizes the independence of the United States.

1882: Robert Koch, the German bacteriologist who discovered the
cholera bacillus and the bacterial cause of anthrax, announces the
isolation of tuberculosis germs. He later won a 1905 Nobel Prize for
developing tuberculin.

1839: Ching Dynasty Commissioner Lin Tse-hsu closes down 13
guilds in Kwangtung after foreign merchants such as Lancelot Dent
refused to yield all the opium stored on Lingting Island. The foreign
merchants finally gave in and handed over 22,830 chests of opium to
Lin who, to the dismay of the drug dealers, promptly burned them.

1911: Denmark abolishes capital punishment.

1921: The first Women's Olympic Games are held in Monte Carlo,
Monaco.

1927: The Chinese communists seize Nanking.

1938: British Prime Minister Neville Chamberlain admits that he
will not oppose German Chancellor Adolf Hitler's annexation of
Czechoslovakia, in the interests of avoiding war between Britain and
Germany.

1951: American General Douglas MacArthur issues a statement
advocating that Allied forces fighting in Korea should push the war
to the Chinese mainland.

1954: Chen Cheng is elected by the National Assembly as the vice
president of the Republic of China for a six-year term.

1959: More than 10,000 monks in Lhasa join the Tibetan revolt
against the communists when new fighting erupts between the two
sides.

1974: Henry Kerns, former chairman and president of the U.S.
Export-Import Bank, arrives in Taipei for a week-long visit.

1975: Vice Adm. George P. Steele, commander of the U.S. 7th
Fleet, arrives at Keelung aboard his flagship USS Oklahoma for a
three-day visit.

1976: Charles Sperck, president of U.S. National Semiconductor
Corp., arrives in Taipei on a business trip.

1976: Argentinian President Isabel Peron, third wife of former
President Juan Peron, is deposed by the army in a bloodless coup. She
was succeeded by Gen. Jorgi Videla.

1976: U.S. Chase Manhattan Bank and Continental Illinois National
Bank jointly loan US$15 million to Taiwan Fertilizer Corp.

1984: Taiwan's first liver transplant surgery is completed at
Chang Gung Memorial Hospital.

1988: The Government Information Office and the Ministry of
National Defense reiterate that the Republic of China has never
engaged in the development of nuclear weapons. This is confirmed by
the U.S. government.

1989: Stanley Pons of the University of Utah and Martin
Fleischmann of the University of Souththampton publish a paper in
which they claim to have unlocked the secret of cold nuclear fusion.

1994: The ROC Legislative Yuan increases the annual maximum
number of permanent residency permits for mainland spouses from 300
to 600.

1995: Beijing Premier Li Peng signs a declaration announcing a
five-day work week.

1998: The European Union declares 11 nations eligible to issue
the euro, the currency that will eventually replace their respective
national currencies.

2000: Republic of China President Lee Teng-hui, who concurrently
served as the Kuomintang's chairman, steps down from the party
chairmanship, formally putting an end to the "Era of Lee Teng-hui"
and the KMT's 54-year rule in Taiwan.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "If a man allows himself to lose
his temper and forget himself of a morning, in such a way as to
become careless for the safety of his own person and for the safety
of his parents and friends -- is that not a case of a great delusion
in life?"
</TEXT>
</DOC>
