<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040325.0008" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
NO CONSENSUS ON HOW TO REVISE PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION LAW
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 25 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
One day before the Legislative Yuan was
slated to discuss the revision of the President and Vice President
Election and Recall Law to pave the way for a recount of the votes in
the March 20 presidential election, consensus among the different
parties over how to do this seemed elusive Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Kuomintang (KMT), whose candidate in the race was
defeated by a slim margin, suggested a recount supervised by the
court as a way to sort out the dispute about whether President Chen
Shui-bian won the election.
</P>
<P>
KMT Legislator Lo Ming-tsai told a news conference at the
Legislative Yuan that a recount by the Central Election Commission
would be inappropriate, as the commission is the organization that
carried out the first controversial vote-count and therefore cannot
be expected to come up with an outcome contrary to its first count.
</P>
<P>
However, the legal process to get a court order for a recount
will take three to six months, which is too long for the problem
facing the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Lo said, his party came up with a recommendation for a
recount presided over by the court, which could appoint independent
people to tally the votes again.
</P>
<P>
Describing it as both a judicial and administrative recount, KMT
lawmaker Huang Teh-fu urged his Democratic Progressive Party
counterparts in the legislature to support the KMT's idea in Friday's
discussion and enact it into law as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Other KMT lawmakers also requested the insertion of a provision
into the current law providing for an independent inquiry into
incidents in which any candidates in the presidential race are killed
or injured.
</P>
<P>
If these incidents were found to be a campaign scheme, the
election would become null and void and a new one would have to be
organized, according to these KMT lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
DPP legislators refused to commit themselves to any course of
action, saying they would have to study the KMT's ideas during
Friday's discussion.
</P>
<P>
Tsai Huang-lang, secretary of the DPP Legislative Yuan caucus,
said his party would accept any proposals put forward by the KMT as
long as they are "reasonable."
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the KMT should cancel a planned March 27
protest and persuade its supporters, some of whom are staging a
protest in front of the Presidential Office, to disperse if a
revision is passed Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
