<HEADLINE>
SINGAPORE PORTS TO COMPLY WITH NEW IMO SECURITY MEASURES: MINISTER
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Singapore,  March 25 (CNA)
(By Sherman Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Singaporean Transport Minister Yeo
Cheow Tong said Wednesday that two of Singapore's three ports have
met the requirements regarding the International Maritime
Organization's (IMO's) new security measures.
</P>
<P>
Singapore, which is the world's busiest container port, has been
quick to implement the International Ship and Port Facility Security
Code drawn up by the IMO, he said
</P>
<P>
The deadline for ports to comply with the new IMO security
measures is July 1 this year. Singapore's third port will likely get
its certificate by next week.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to be one of the first countries in the world to be
fully compliant," Yeo said.
</P>
<P>
Among the IMO security measures is the requirement that all ships
above 500 tons be fitted with an automatic identification system.
Singapore is going even further by looking at coming out with a low
cost transponder system for smaller ships. The transponder can
automatically send signals that identify the vessel and its position.
</P>
