KINMEN MIGHT BECOME CROSS-STRAIT TRANSSHIPMENT PLATFORM
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Kinmen,  March 25 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two members of the Control Yuan called on
the government Thursday to improve the facilities at Kinmen's airport
and to expand its operations so that the outlying island can become a
transshipment platform for maritime and air transport services
between the two sides of the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
Chao Jung-yao and Lee Shen-yi, who traveled to Kinmen to inspect
the "mini-three links, " made the appeal after hearing a briefing
delivered by Kinmen county government officials on the county's
administrative affairs.
</P>
<P>
The "mini-three links" refers to direct trade, shipping and
postal links between the Republic of China-held outlying islands of
Kinmen and Matsu and mainland China's ports of Xiamen and Mawei in
Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
Chao said that there are still many obstacles to the opening of
direct links between the mainland and Taiwan-proper, so the
government should try to build Kinmen into a transshipment platform
in order to satisfy the public's demand for growing cross-strait
economic, trade and cultural exchanges.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the existing shipping links with the mainland,
Chao pointed out, the Kinmen airport should be upgraded to allow
cross-strait chartered flight services, which would make it a
transport hub for passengers traveling between Taiwan and the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
If the proposal can be put into practice, it will give a boost to
Kinmen's economic development, he added.
