<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040325.0013" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN URGED TO UPGRADE EXCHANGES WITH TAIWAN
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 25 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Japanese government, while seeking to
strengthen cooperation with mainland China, should also review its
relations with the Republic of China on Taiwan and upgrade bilateral
exchanges, a senior official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Hsu Shui-teh, president of the Association for East-Asian
Relations (AEAR), made the appeal in a speech delivered at a seminar
on East Asia and mainland China affairs. The AEAR is a quasi-official
body authorized by the ROC government to handle relations with Japan
in the absence of diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
Hsu, who once served as the ROC representative to Japan, said he
hopes the two countries will have more high-level exchanges to boost
cooperation in cultural, academic, economic, technological and
regional security affairs.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Taiwan has evolved from an authoritarian rule to
one of the most vibrant democracies in Asia, Hsu said, the Japanese
government should raise the levels of its officials to be allowed to
visit Taiwan and should also grant visas to top ROC leaders for
visits to Japan.
</P>
<P>
For fears of offending Beijing, Japan has refrained from
high-level engagements with Taiwan. Since Japan switched diplomatic
recognition to Beijing in 1972, only low- or middle-ranking Japanese
official have been allowed to visit Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Hsu said this situation should be changed. "We hope Japanese
authorities will ease restrictions on engagements with Taiwan
to pave the way for closer bilateral cooperation in promoting
regional prosperity, security and stability."
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Hsu said, Taiwan and Japan should sign a free
trade agreement to facilitate further growth in bilateral trade,
investment and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In view of mainland China's rise as an economic and military
power, Hsu said Taiwan and Japan should also forge a viable mechanism
for dialogue and cooperation in security and defense affairs.
</P>
<P>
Hsu further urged Japan to support Taiwan's bid to join
non-political functional international organizations, such as the
World Health Organization (WHO), so that Taiwan can contribute more
to the international society.
</P>
<P>
"Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Yasuo Fukuda once expressed
support for Taiwan's participation in the WHO as an observer. We hope
the Japanese government can do more to help Taiwan realize this
goal," Hsu said.
</P>
<P>
The two-day seminar is being organized by the Institute of
International Relations of National Chengchi University. The
seminar brings together more than 100 scholars and experts, including
20 Japanese delegates, to discuss the latest developments in mainland
China and their possible impact on the general East Asian
situation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session, Takao Fujii, a Japanese
lawmaker, echoed Hsu's views, saying that Taiwan and Japan should
seek a common defense strategy for mutual benefits.
</P>
<P>
Fujii, who is also a leading figure of a pro-Taiwan group in the
lower house of the Japanese Diet (or parliament), said that in
the geopolitical sense, Taiwan and Japan have traditionally enjoyed a
very close relationship.
</P>
<P>
For instance, he said, the people of Taiwan and Japan make more
than 1.5 million visits to each other's country every year and Japan
enjoys a trade surplus of US$20 billion with Taiwan every year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Fujii said, Japan relies heavily on safe passage
through the Taiwan Strait, which is the lifeline of Japan's economy
at sea. "Against this backdrop, cross-strait political stability is
the best security for Japan," he said, adding that Taiwan and
Japan should jointly seek a strategy that will benefit both
countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040325.0014" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN TEXTILE INDUSTRY KEEN ON DESIGN, DIVERSIFICATION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Hong Kong,  March  25 (CNA)
(By S.M. Chen and Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan's textile industry will be
dedicated to product design and manufacturing upgrading in order to
take maximum advantage of a global market free of quota restrictions
in 2005, Taiwan Textile Federation Secretary General Huang Wei-chi
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Giving a keynote speech about the latest trends in Taiwan's
textile industry at Hong Kong's "Interest of Asia" spring exhibition,
Huang said the industry has shifted from labor-intensive to
diversified business, ranging from up-stream man-made fibers to
down-stream garment making.
</P>
<P>
According to Huang, Taiwan textile companies have transformed
themselves from original equipment makers to original design makers
capable of providing a comprehensive production line, coupled with
processing facilities in other countries, for customers from around
the world wishing to grab a larger market share.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that a majority of Taiwan fabric producers have
relocated to mainland China, with the rest moving out to Thailand,
Vietnam and countries in Central and South America.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that Taiwan-made products are today lauded as high-end
goods in the international market, he said many businesses are fully
aware of the fact that continued innovation and development in
quality, design, materials and function are their best weapons to
maintain an impressive presence in the world marketplace.
</P>
<P>
Output of Taiwan-made polyester totaled more than 1 million
metric tons last year, the highest level in the world, Huang added.
</P>
</TEXT>
