<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040325.0022" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
COA TO EXPAND  STRAY DOG STERILIZATION PROJECT
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 25 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Council of Agriculture (COA) announced
Thursday that it is expanding the stray dog sterilization project.
</P>
<P>
COA officials said that the COA is targeting the sterilization of
2,000 female dogs and 1,000 male dogs this year, hoping to stem their
reproduction.
</P>
<P>
Cutting the number of stray dogs has been a nagging headache for
the COA and local governments for years, the officials said, and the
COA began the sterilization project in 2003 on a trial basis, giving
operations to 528 male dogs and 982 female dogs.
</P>
<P>
"With the good results last year, the COA has decided to further
expand the project," they said.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that many volunteers in private animal
shelters have long taken care of stray dogs, but as theses shelters
often don't have enough funds and cannot afford to pay for the
sterilizations, the number of stray dogs has in fact continued to
increase, making it more difficult financially for the shelters.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that the COA will commission an association of
veterinarians to carry out the sterilization project, and that all
registered animal protection groups can apply for subsidies from the
association. More information is available at (02) 2339-0220.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040325.0023" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN, JAPAN URGED TO FIND COMMON STRATEGY FOR MUTUAL BENEFITS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 25 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan and Japan have a close relationship
and they must seek a common strategy that will benefit both
countries, a visiting Japanese parliamentarian said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Takao Fujii, who is also a key member of a pro-Taiwan
parliamentary group, made the remarks when he attended the 31st
Taiwan-Japan seminar on mainland China in Taipei.
</P>
<P>
The two-day seminar sponsored by the Institute of International
Relations of National Chengchi University is centered on " the
situation of the mainland and East Asia in 2004." More than 100
scholars and experts, including more than 20 Japanese delegates led by
Kunihiko Takano, president of the Association of Mainland Chinese
Affairs, attended the seminar.
</P>
<P>
Fujii said that the people of Taiwan and Japan make more than
1.5 million visits to each other's country every year and that Japan
enjoys a trade surplus of US$20 billion with Taiwan every year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Japan relies heavily on safe passage through the
Taiwan Strait, which is the lifeline of Japan's economy at sea, so
that cross-strait political stability is the best security for Japan.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the geopolitical sense, Japan and Taiwan have
very close relations, and they should jointly seek a strategy that
will benefit both countries. Japan should also work harder to help
Taiwan's bid to join international organizations.
</P>
<P>
He also said that when thinking about future Taiwan-Japan
relations, both sides should not pursue a quick result; rather, they
should consider the other side as an important neighbor and increase
bilateral understanding.
</P>
<P>
Fujii also said that mainland China has posted a high yearly
economic growth rate between 7 percent and 13 percent over the past
decade, and that businesses will naturally want to seek their future
on the mainland, which he said is an unstoppable trend.
</P>
<P>
But he said that mainland China has become unable to handle its
increased energy needs, and that Japanese businesses investing in the
mainland have to deal with power outages. Big cities in the mainland
also face the problem of not having a steady water supply, he said,
adding that if the mainland continues to develop at its current rate,
water and energy resources will be crucial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040325.0024" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
U.S. NOT INVOLVED IN POST-ELECTION DISPUTES: FOREIGN MINISTRY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 25 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The United States is not involved in the
post-election disputes in Taiwan, an official of the Ministry of
Foreign Affairs said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Victor J. Chin, director of the foreign ministry's Department of
North American Affairs, said that it is the long-standing stance of
the United States not to get involved in the internal affairs of
other countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department issued a statement Saturday
congratulating the conclusion of Taiwan's March 20 presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
"The United States congratulates the people of Taiwan for having
conducted a democratic election campaign and for having exercised
their democratic voting right in such large numbers, " the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
"We note that the Central Election Commission has declared that
the 'pan-greens' have won by a very narrow margin. We are aware that
the 'pan-blue alliance' has raised questions about the results.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that both sides and their supporters will
remain calm and that they will use the established legal mechanism to
resolve any questions about the election results," it said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Chin said that the United States has yet to issue an
official comment on the outcome of the referendum vote, which was
held alongside the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Both questions in the referendum -- whether to increase Taiwan's
anti-missile defense if Beijing does not withdraw the ballistic
missiles aimed at the island, and whether to establish a framework
for opening cross-strait talks -- failed to be declared valid because
less than half of the more than 16 million eligible voters took part
in the voting. Of those who did participate, over 90 percent answered
"yes" to both questions.
</P>
<P>
Chin said that election experts and academics from the United
States who observed the voting process said they were very much
impressed by the democratic election and are watching closely the
development of the post-election disputes.
</P>
</TEXT>
