<HEADLINE>
BILINGUAL HANDBOOKS FOR FOREIGN CAREGIVERS PUBLISHED
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 25 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei City Government's Bureau of Labor
Affairs is providing bilingual handbooks to help the more than 20,000
foreign caregivers in Taipei in taking care of seriously ill
patients.
</P>
<P>
Labor officials said that the "House Maid Care Handbook" is
available in three different versions -- Chinese-English,
Chinese-Vietnamese and Chinese-Indonesian.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 32,000 foreign laborers in Taipei, of which
nearly 80 percent are caregivers, the officials said. They noted
that although some of the foreign caregivers received training prior
to coming to Taiwan, most of them are not completely familiar with
care giving work.
</P>
<P>
The officials also noted that misunderstandings and quarrels
sometimes erupt because of communication problems resulting from
language barriers. The bureau therefore had invited Cheng Shin
Rehabilitation Medical Center and its volunteer team to provide
relevant information on how to provide basic care, such as extract
mucus, clean body, and train to defecate alone.
</P>
<P>
The center has published 5,000 Chinese-Indonesia handbooks, 2,500
Chinese-English handbooks and 2,500 Chinese-Indonesian handbooks.
</P>
<P>
Those interested in obtaining a copy of the handbook can go to
the Bureau of Foreign Affairs' consultation center for foreign
laborers located at No. 2, Lane 101, Sec. 2, Shinsheng North Road, or
call 2564-3157 or 2564-2546 for more information.
</P>
</TEXT>
