<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040325.0035" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 25 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Thursday, March 25, or the
fifth day of the leap second month of the Year of the Monkey
according to the lunar calendar. Following is a list of important
events that have occurred on this date in the past:

1306: Robert the Bruce, the eighth Earl of Carrick who defied
Edward I of England, is crowned King of Scotland at Scone, becoming
Robert I. He later won Scottish independence from England at the
battle of Bannockburn in 1314.

1799: At the Battle of Stockach, 60,000 Austrians led by Archduke
Charles defeat 40,000 French under Jourdan near Baden.

1807: Influenced by the philanthropic Member of Parliament
William Wilberforce, the British Parliament abolishes the slave
trade.

1815: Austria, Britain, Prussia and Russia form a new alliance
against Napoleon Bonaparte of France.

1867: Arturo Toscanini, the Italian conductor of the Metropolitan
Opera, the New York Philharmonic and many other orchestras worldwide,
is born. He refused to conduct in Italy or Germany when they were
ruled by the Fascists and the Nazis, respectively.

1936: Britain, France and the United States sign the London Naval
Convention.

1937: Chiang Ching-kuo of the Republic of China leaves Moscow for
home, ending a 12-year stay in the Soviet Union.

1941: Yugoslavia joins the Berlin-Rome-Tokyo Alliance, or Axis.

1950: ROC President Chiang Kai-shek issues a written order to
posthumously commend Lien Heng, a noted historian.

1957: Six European nations -- France, West Germany, Italy, the
Netherlands, Belgium and Luxembourg -- take a historic step toward
guaranteeing a future of peace and prosperity for their continent by
signing the treaties for the European Economic Community and Euratom.

1971: The Penghu Cross-Sea Bridge, which has a 2,160-meter span
between Paisha Island and Hsiyu in Taiwan's offshore county of
Penghu, is opened to traffic.

1973: The Chinese National Ethics and Science Education
Association is inaugurated in Taipei.

1974: The Second Museum Conference of the ASPAC Cultural and
Social Center opens in Taipei, with over 20 museum experts from six
nations participating.

1975: Saudi Arabia's King Faisal is murdered at the age of 70 by
his nephew Prince Faisal during a ceremony at the palace in Riyadh
celebrating the birthday of the Prophet Mohammed.

1986: Construction of Taipei's Feitsui Reservoir is completed in
the ROC.

1990: Hungary's first multiparty elections since 1949 are held,
with the Hungarian Democratic Forum -- a non-communist party --
winning a majority.

1993: Jiang Zemin becomes president of Communist China.

1994: Taiwan's Straits Exchange Foundation and the mainland's
Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Strait hold talks in
Beijing on fishery disputes and the repatriation of illegal
immigrants and hijackers.

1996: The United States, France and Britain sign the South
Pacific Nuclear-Free Zone Treaty.

1996: Due to concerns over the possible spread of mad cow
disease, officials from 15 European Union states agree to recommend a
ban on exports of British beef products.

1997: Australia's parliament votes to overturn the world's only
law allowing terminally ill patients to commit suicide with the help
of a doctor.

1999: The Republic of China and Costa Rica sign agreements to
boost bilateral economic and sports exchanges.

1999: The Ministry of Foreign Affairs informs 13 embassies in
Taipei that the ROC has increased measures to protect embassy
officials and staff members after death threats were received at the
embassies.

2001: The host Chinese Taipei team wins the title in the 21st
Asian Baseball Championship.

2001: President Chen Shui-bian presides over an official
welcoming ceremony for visiting Dominican President Hipolito Mejia in
northeastern Taiwan's Ilan County.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "The moral life of a man consists
of loving men. Understanding consists of understanding men. Uphold
the cause of the just, and put down every cause that is unjust in
such a way that the unjust will be made just."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040326.0001" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL  HEADLINE  NEWS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Tokyo, March 26 (CNA)
