</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040326.0002" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TOP SARS COORDINATOR PRESIDES LAUNCH OF URBANI BIOGRAPHY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Rome,  March 25 (CNA)
(By Tony Fang and Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The top coordinator in Taiwan's campaign
against severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) , Lee Ming-liang,
presided over Thursday a ceremony marking the launch of the
Italian-language biography of Carlo Urbani who was the first person
to identify the SARS virus.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Urbani, a World Health Organization communicable disease
expert, died of the flu-like atypical pneumonia in Bangkok on March
29, 2003. He was 47.
</P>
<P>
The Carlo Urbani biography, authored by Italian prize-winning
writer Lucia Bellaspiga, gives a detailed and human account of how
Urbani contributed his professional expertise to SARS identification
and treatment in Asia and how he fought against the deadly virus
during the crucial days prior to his death.
</P>
<P>
Lee, a former minister of Taiwan's Department of Health and
chairman of the Carlo Urbani Memorial Foundation established in
Taiwan last July in memory of the Italian doctor, said the
Chinese-version of the Urbani biography is expected to be published
in Taiwan shortly.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the biography debut ceremony held at Rome's Capital
Museum, Lee said that the book will provide great inspiration to the
younger generations around the world and that the Chinese-version
will let the vast population in the Chinese-speaking communities
learn about Dr. Urbani's spirits and teaching.
</P>
<P>
Lee also shared with the guests how and why the Carlo Urbani
memorial foundation was established in Taiwan. He said that Taiwan's
Executive Yuan decided in July 2003 to use the more than NT$330
million (US$9.56 million) in private donations it collected during
the SARS outbreak to set up a memorial foundation, with Lee serving
as its chairman.
</P>
<P>
During their first meeting, the directors of the foundation
decided that the funds would be used in prevention and relief efforts
against SARS and any other new communicable diseases, as well as in
conducting international exchanges, according to Lee.
</P>
<P>
To stress that Urbani's humanitarian spirit and medical treatment
know no borders, the foundation decided to publish Urbani's biography
in Chinese and English, as well as the biographies of those people in
Taiwan who displayed the same spirit and those who gave up their
lives in the fight against SARS.
</P>
<P>
Lee said that the foundation also decided to actively establish
contact with the Urbani Organization in Geneva, Switzerland, for
discussions on matters of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
On hand at the biography launching were a number of government
officials and leaders in the medical and literary circles in Italy,
including Mirko Tremaglia, minister of the World and Overseas Italian
Affairs, and Urbani's wife.
</P>
<P>
A written message from Rome's Mayor Walter Veltroni was read at
the launching ceremony. In the message, Veltroni offered his respects
to Urbani and sympathy to Urbani's family.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese-version of the Urbani biography, expected to be
published soon, was translated by Ku Kuei-ying, a leader in the
Chinese community in Italy, who has great attainments in both Italian
and Chinese languages.
</P>
<P>
SARS, the atypical flu believed to have originated in the
southern mainland Chinese province of Guangdong in late 2002, spread
to Taiwan in early 2003 and claimed the lives of 37 people before the
island was declared SARS-free in June last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040326.0003" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
SINGAPORE PORTS MEET NEW IMO REQUIREMENT FOR SECURITY MEASURES
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Singapore, March 25 (CNA)
(By Sherman Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Singapore Transport MinIster
Yeo Cheow Tong said two of Singapore's three ports have met
the International Maritime Organisation's (IMO) requirement
for new security measures.
</P>
<P>
Singapore has been quick to implement the International Ship
and Port Facility Security Code drawn up by the International
Maritime Organisation, he said The deadline for ports to
comply with the new IMO's security measures is July 1 this
year.
</P>
