The third port will likely get its certificate by next week.
Singapore is the world's busiest container port.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040326.0004" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
NEXT 20 YEARS TO BE FASCINATING FOR SINGAPORE: SENIOR MINISTER LEE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Singapore,  March 26 (CNA)
(By Sherman Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Singapore Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew
said he believes the next 20 years or so will be fascinating for
Singapore, given the changed outlook of the people and the
experiences they have undergone.
</P>
<P>
Important, too, will be developments and opportunities in an
economically more dominant mainland China -- something which
Singapore must also take advantage of, Lee said in an interview with
the BBC's East Asia Today current affairs program which was conducted
March 17 and broadcast Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Asked about what he thought lies ahead for Singapore, Lee said
that barring any unforeseen shocks such as terrorist acts, the
economy should grow by 3 percent to 5 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
As to developments on the social front in Singapore, he said he
believes "it's going to be a fascinating period because in the last
20 years, we've become so cosmopolitan in our outlook."
</P>
<P>
Singapore society used to be "very Asian Chinese-Confucianist, "
he said, adding that this has changed because of the use of English,
the exposure that television and the Internet have brought, and the
fact that Singaporeans travel extensively and interact with tourists
who visit Singapore.
</P>
<P>
On the topic of mainland China, Lee described the process of
change there as being "one of the world's greatest transformations."
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040326.0005" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TECHNICIAN WORKING FOR ROC MILITARY INDICTED FOR SELLING SECRETS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 26 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A technician working at the military-run
Chungshan Institute of Science and Technology was indicted Friday for
leaking military secrets to mainland China and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors said in their indictment that Huang Cheng-an offered
to sell the secret know-how about the country's home-made missiles to
mainland China and Egypt for US$7 million and US$66 million
respectively.
</P>
<P>
In order to convince his potential buyers, Huang has already
passed over some sensitive materials.
</P>
<P>
Huang's former wife, Chen Chu-chen, and another women, Lin Wei,
who were accused of serving as Huang's couriers to pass the secrets
or as brokers to seek potential mainland buyers, were also indicted
in the case.
</P>
