<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040326.0010" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
DR. HENRY LEE TO BE INVITED TO JOIN PROBE INTO ELECTION-EVE SHOOTING
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 26 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dr. Henry Lee, a world-renowned
Chinese-American forensic expert, will be invited to join an
independent forensic panel to probe into the election-eve shooting of
President Chen Shui-bian, the nation's top prosecutor said Friday.
</P>
<P>
State Public Prosecutor-General Lu Ren-fa said the proposed
independent panel under the State Public Prosecutor General's Office
(SPPGO) will assist the investigative task force formed by the
prosecution and police authorities in the southern city of Tainan in
solving the failed assassination attempt.
</P>
<P>
Lu stressed that the SPPGO forensic panel's work will not
conflict with the Criminal Investigation Bureau's (CIB's) forensic
examinations.
</P>
<P>
According to local media reports, Lee has agreed to travel to
Taiwan in April to assist in investigating the unsolved shooting
which slightly wounded President Chen and allegedly helped propel him
to the narrowest of election victories.
</P>
<P>
Lu said he has yet to get in touch with Lee. "But I think it
won't be a problem for Lee to come to Taiwan next week to join the
investigative work."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lu said Shih Tai-ping, a former director of the CIB's
forensic department, has agreed to join the SPPGO panel. Shih is
currently attending a meeting in the United States. "He has accepted
my invitation," he added.
</P>
<P>
Lu said the SPPGO will respect the two famous forensic experts'
opinions in deciding the roster of the special panel as well as its
investigative direction and operational guidelines. "Lee and Shih are
expected to map out work rules after discussions with the existing
investigative panel."
</P>
<P>
Lu said he hopes that the participation of the two experts will
help enhance the defeated presidential candidate's trust in the
government's determination to solve the case and stop the
post-election controversy.
</P>
<P>
The defeated electoral team of Kuomintang (KMT) Chairman Lien
Chan and People First Party (PFP) Chairman James Soong claimed that
the shooting unfairly swayed sympathy votes Chen's way. Their
supporters even claimed that the shooting was staged to boost Chen's
re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
Although the Lien-Soong team has provided little specific
evidence of wrongdoing in last Saturday's election, large crowds of
his supporters have rallied in front of the Presidential Office for
the past six days, at first demanding a recount and more recently an
entirely new election.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, CIB investigators said they are seeking a
bald man who was caught on a security camera as he ran from the
scene of last week's assassination attempt against President Chen.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was the first real lead since the shooting
last Friday in Tainan. Chen and Vice President Lu were driving
through the city on the last day of campaigning when the shooting
took palce.
</P>
<P>
The video footage, which is unclear, appears to show a bald man
in his 40s or 50s dressed in a yellow jacket and blue trousers
running down a nearby alley within minutes of the shooting, police
said.
</P>
<P>
"We find the fact that he was running away from the scene of the
crime suspicious," said Deputy CIB Director Wang Wen-chung.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the footage showed the man running away from the main
road where crowds had gathered to cheer the president's motorcade,
just three minutes after police believe the shooting took place.
</P>
<P>
It was given to police by the neighbourhood chief of that section
of Tainan on Wednesday, said Wang.
</P>
<P>
"We urge this man or anyone who saw him or may know him to
contact us and clear this up," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
Police say Chen and Lu, riding in an open-top jeep, were
each shot with one bullet believed to have been fired from the
same homemade gun.
</P>
<P>
Investigators are focusing their hunt for the would-be
assassin on underground factories that make homemade guns for
use by the Taiwan underworld by altering the firing mechanisms
of toy replicas.
</P>
</TEXT>
