<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040326.0016" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PREMIER CONDEMNS VIOLENCE AT CENTRAL ELECTION COMMISSION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 26 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Premier Yu Shyi-kun condemned the violence
at the Central Election Commission's (CEC) offices Friday, and urged
the leaders of the opposition "pan-blue alliance" to "rein themselves
in from the brink of a precipice."
</P>
<P>
The premier made the remarks after supporters of the "pan-blue
alliance, " who had gathered outside the Central Election Commission
(CEC) to try to prevent the CEC from formally announcing the
presidential and vice presidential winners from the March 20
election, clashed with police and stormed the building.
</P>
<P>
The CEC later officially confirmed the re-election of President
Chen Shui-bian and Vice President Annette Lu.
</P>
<P>
The premier was meeting with Taipei Mayor Ma Ying-jeou to learn
about the city's preparations for the March 27 mass rally called by
the "pan-blue alliance" comprised of the Kuomintang (KMT) and the
People First Party (PFP) and to discuss the situation regarding
information on the rally gathered by the Executive Yuan.
</P>
<P>
The alliance's planned 500,000-strong rally in front of the
Presidential Office is asking supporters to "let justice be done and
democracy be saved" to protest what it perceives as the "unfair
election" that saw President Chen win another four-year term by a
razor-thin margin of fewer than 30,000 votes against his rival, KMT
Chairman Lien Chan.
</P>
<P>
The premier said that after the violence at the CEC, the
government "finds it difficult to be optimistic about the mass rally
Saturday."
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet condemned the violence at the CEC, Yu said, adding
that, "Politicians who take the people to the streets should, based
on their consciences, take them away according to the law."
</P>
<P>
He urged Lien and PFP Chairman James Soong to "rein themselves in
before the brink of a precipice, " and "not to satisfy their own
selfish ends at the expense of social stability and the nation's
international image."
</P>
<P>
An official of the ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) also
condemned the use of violence at the CEC.
</P>
<P>
Lee Ying-yuan, DPP deputy secretary-general, said that according
to the law, after the March 20 election, the CEC is required to
officially announce the presidential and vice presidential winners
within seven days. Though it is only a formality, the CEC has to act
according to the law, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
He said that if the protestors have other views about the outcome
of the election, they can use legal means to voice their grievances
by filing suit.
</P>
<P>
"Regardless of whether we are talking about the ruling party or
an opposition political party, everyone has the chance to take the
helm of the nation; there will also be a winner and a loser in any
election, so it should not be taken so seriously," Lee added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the DPP has responded positively to "pan-blue
alliance" requests for a ballot recount and to participate in an ad
hoc committee to investigate the shooting of President Chen on the
eve of the election, which may have given Chen sympathy votes and
could have made the difference in his victory in the bitterly
contested election.
</P>
<P>
"There is no reason for the 'pan-blue alliance' to continue to
hurt Taiwan at the expense of the harmony of society, " Lee stressed.
</P>
<P>
Protesters started to gather outside the CEC building at noon to
protest against a CEC afternoon meeting where commission members
were reviewing the outcome of the election to formally announce the
presidential and vice presidential elects.
</P>
<P>
The angry protestors smashed the glass out of a bulletin board
and posted the words "suspension of the announcement of the elects
before the truth is known."
</P>
<P>
The protestors continued to shout "no announcement before the
recount of the ballots." PFP legislators Lee Chin-hua and Chiu Yi, as
well as a CEC member tried to communicate with them to no avail.
</P>
<P>
At around 4:30 p.m., several agitated protestors shouted "go" and
a large crowd tried to storm the first floor of the building where
the CEC was holding a meeting.
</P>
<P>
Sticks, rocks and eggs were thrown and the glass doors were
smashed despite a large number of police.
</P>
<P>
Several people were injured in the melee, and others were trying
to make another attempt to enter the building when the two
legislators and others managed to calm the crowd somewhat.
</P>
</TEXT>
