<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 26 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The opposition Kuomintang (KMT) and People
First Party (PFP) jointly put forth a plan at the Legislative Yuan
Friday aimed at revising the President and Vice President Election
and Recall Law.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, the two parties propose that presidential
candidates can ask the court to seize the ballots, lists of voters
and other election-related documents in case the margin between the
leader and the runner up in the race is less than 1 percent of the
ballots counted as valid. The request can be made before the Central
Election Commission (CEC) formally announces the winner.
</P>
<P>
The high court in the capital should re-examine in public the
ballots and documents within seven days of receiving the request and
should finish the recount of the ballots within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
The CEC should not announce the winner before the legal process
is complete and the CEC should withdraw its initial announcement of
the election outcome if it conflicts with the recount and should
announce the winner according to the court's recount.
</P>
<P>
Notable in the proposal is a request for the formation of an
investigation committee to look into the assassination attempt on
President Chen Shui-bian on the eve of the March 20 presidential
election. The two opposition parties suspect the assassination
attempt to be a political ploy designed to help Chen win the
election.
</P>
<P>
The investigation committee should come up with a report on the
incident within one month.
</P>
<P>
To prevent any future such incidents from influencing the results
of presidential elections, the two parties propose that a committee
under the Legislative Yuan be set up to look into any case taking
place within seven days before polling day in which any candidate is
killed or injured.
</P>
<P>
In such cases, the election can be put on hold and resumed only
one month after the investigation committee comes up with a report.
</P>
<P>
Police and armed forces who are on duty during the election
because of the higher alert the country is put on in such cases,
should be allowed to cast their votes after they come off duty,
according to the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Most important of all, the revision, if passed, should be applied
retroactively to the March 20 election, according to the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers of the ruling Democratic Progressive Party had yet to
respond to the proposal, but Minister of Justice Chen Ding-nan
immediately criticized the idea, pointing out that forming an
investigation committee under the legislature would constitute
interference in the power of the judiciary and would undermine the
administration's credibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040326.0021" type="story" >
