<HEADLINE>
MARCH CCI CONSPICUOUSLY DOWN DUE TO ELECTION DISPUTE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 26 (CNA)
(By Eric Liu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan's consumer confidence index (CCI)
for March stood at 79.52 points, a conspicuous drop of 4.18 points
from the February level, Chu Yun-peng, the head of the Research
Center for Taiwan Economic Development under the National Central
University reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chu said that the March figure, the lowest since last October,
was caused by the election-eve shooting of President Chen Shui-bian
and Vice President Annette Lu and post-election political
uncertainties. The survey, which was started before the election, Chu
continued, would have been even lower if it had been conducted after
the election.
</P>
<P>
Out of the six categories surveyed, four declined, with the
timing for buying stocks in the coming six months moving down the
most in scale to 66.1 points, down by 23.4 points from the previous
month. More than half of those polled said the next six months will
not be a good time for stock trading.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the points scored for the other three categories --
household economic situations, the timing for purchasing durable
goods, and the domestic employment market in the coming six months --
all dropped, with the score for the domestic employment market
registering the lowest figure among all six categories.
</P>
<P>
However, the score for domestic business conditions in the coming
six months rose from a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
Commodity prices in the coming six months also rose slightly by
0.5 point from February, signaling that public worry has not
deteriorated. Nevertheless, news of an oil price hike had not been
announced during the poll, Chu said, adding that the impact will be
reflected in next month's figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
