<HEADLINE>
U.S. HOUSE MAJORITY LEADER CONGRATULATES CHEN ON RE-ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  26 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
U.S. House Majority Leader Tom DeLay
(R-Texas) congratulated President Chen Shui-bian on his re-election
Friday, the Presidential Office said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
According to the press statement, DeLay, speaking by telephone,
first expressed concerns for the injury Chen sustained in a failed
election-eve assassination attempt. DeLay said he would pray for
Chen's quick recovery.
</P>
<P>
Chen was slightly wounded when an unidentified assailant fired at
least two shots at the president and Vice President Annette Lu while
they were driving past large crowds of supporters in an open-top jeep
in the southern city of Tainan last Friday. The shooting grazed
Chen's abdomen and Lu's right knee.
</P>
<P>
The Presidential Office press statement said DeLay also offered
his congratulations on Chen's re-election victory.
</P>
<P>
DeLay was quoted as having told Chen that his success in Taiwan's
most closely fought presidential election will receive full U.S.
recognition and support.
</P>
<P>
The influential U.S. congressman further said that Taiwan's
democratization and Chen's devotion to that bumpy process are
encouraging for American people and should be an inspiration to
mainland China and many other developing countries. DeLay assured
Chen that he and his congressional colleagues will offer full support
to Taiwan's cause.
</P>
<P>
DeLay said he hopes to organize a congressional delegation to
attend Chen's May 20 inauguration and he further said the U.S.
Congress will hold a series of activities in April to mark the 25th
anniversary of the enactment of the Taiwan Relations Act -- the U.S.
law that regulates relations with Taiwan in the absence of formal
diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
DeLay also said the U.S. House of Representatives will pass a
resolution in April to push the Bush administration to offer more
assistance to Taiwan's bid to join the World Health Organization
(WHO) . DeLay said he and his colleagues will also make sure the
international community understands that the United States supports
Taiwan's WHO bid.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Chen said Taiwan's accession to the WHO is not only
critical to the health and well-being of the 23 million Taiwan people
but will also symbolize an important step forward in relations across
the Taiwan Strait. Mainland China's opposition has been the biggest
obstacle to Taiwan's participation in the WHO and other major
international bodies.
</P>
<P>
Touching on Taiwan's post-election controversy, Chen told DeLay
that he has made a goodwill response to the demands of the rival
electoral team of Kuomintang (KMT) Chairman Lien Chan and People
First Party (PFP) Chairman James Soong for a vote recount.
</P>
<P>
"I support a quick, transparent and full-scale recount because I
never rigged the vote. In fact, the idea of vote-rigging never
occurred to me. Taiwan has come a long way to achieve democracy.
Vote-rigging is unlikely to work in our present electoral system, "
Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The president also dismissed opposition allegations that he
staged the election-eve shooting to win sympathy votes. Chen said he
is more eager than anyone else to get to the bottom of the matter and
that he supports an independent inquiry into the shooting.
</P>
<P>
Although the Lien-Soong team has provided little specific
evidence of wrongdoing in last Saturday's election, large crowds of
his supporters have rallied in front of the Presidential Office
for the past six days, at first demanding a recount and more
recently calling for an entirely new election.
</P>
</TEXT>
