<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040326.0027" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT MEETS ACADEMIA SINICA HEAD TO DISCUSS PEACE FRAMEWORK
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 26 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian met with Academia
Sinica President Lee Yuan-tseh Friday for a discussion on the
formation of an ad hoc group to push for the establishment of a
framework for peace and stability in cross-Taiwan Strait interaction.
</P>
<P>
Chen and Lee talked for about 90 minutes, mainly on the direction
of the soon-to-be-established ad hoc group and who will be appointed
as its members, according to Presidential Office spokesman Huang
Chih-fang.
</P>
<P>
Chen also appointed Lee as one of the two conveners of the
important ad hoc group, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
The president is expected to announce a line-up of the group as
soon as a second person has been appointed as the other convener,
Huang added.
</P>
<P>
Koo Cheng-fu, chairman of the quasi-official Straits Exchange
Foundation (SEF), who Chen has envisaged as the second convener, did
not take part in Friday's meeting for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
The head of the foundation established more than a decade ago to
handle cross-strait exchanges in the absence of formal contact
between the two sides of the Taiwan Strait, Ku, 87, has seldom made
public appearances in the recent year as a result of his advanced
age.
</P>
<P>
In his first news conference with members of the media from home
and abroad this year, Chen made clear Feb. 3 why he was promoting
what he referred to as the "peace referendum" that was held on the
March 20 presidential election day.
</P>
<P>
He called for a cross-strait agreement to serve as the basis for
future cooperation and the maintenance of peace and stability in the
Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
"Signing a cross-strait 'peace and stability' agreement will not
only cultivate and further enhance mutual trust and minimize
misjudgments, but will also help the two sides to face and understand
the basic elements and rules for peaceful coexistence, " Chen said at
that time.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides of the strait are now at a crucial juncture in terms
of their respective development. Taiwan is in the process of major
domestic reforms, while mainland China is focused on its economic
development. If we are able to seize the momentum, it will have great
impact on our development and future prospects. The key lies in
whether both sides can create a stable environment conducive for each
side to devote itself to its own development," he added.
</P>
<P>
On avoiding military conflict, the president also called for the
establishment of demilitarized zones, including the removal of combat
personnel, equipment and deployed missiles, to create a "buffer zone
in terms of time and space." He also appealed for a prohibition on
the use of military and economic blockades.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, Chen said, the two sides have been dispatching
appointed representatives to engage in negotiations. However, he
added, the negotiation process has been stalled by the mainland's
insistence on Taiwan's acceptance of Beijing's "one China" principle
and has used this to unilaterally obstruct negotiation channels,
thereby putting pressure on Taiwan to "give in."
</P>
<P>
"Through more than a decade of cross-strait exchanges, experience
shows that without direct contact and with the mainland's continued
refusal to negotiate, it is impossible to meet the requirements of
today's intensive exchanges," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
In the March 20 referendum, Taiwan voters were asked to vote on
two questions.
</P>
<P>
However, only 45.17 percent of eligible voters cast their ballots
in the first question in the referendum -- whether the country should
strengthen its anti-missile defense capability -- while 45.12 percent
voted on the second question -- whether the country should negotiate
a peace framework with the mainland China. Both failed to reach the
threshold of 50 percent required to be considered valid.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that Taiwan will nevertheless carry out the questions
in a positive way regardless of the outcome of the referendum.
</P>
</TEXT>
