<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN RAILWAY MULLS SHORT-DISTANCE TICKET FARE HIKE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 26 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Taiwan Railway Administration (TRA) is
considering whether to raise ticket fares for short-distance
passengers as part of its plans to help increase revenues.
</P>
<P>
The TRA, which faces losses of up to NT$10 billion (US$303.03
million) every year, is also considering the feasibility of adopting
flexible ticket rates for long-distance passengers.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan Railway Administrator Hsu Ta-wen said that the present
ticket pricing structure is unreasonable, pointing out that around
200,000 passengers travel between Panchiao in Taipei County and
Sungshan in Taipei City each day for a flat fare of just NT$18,
irrespective of the class of train.
</P>
<P>
Hsu said that a "reasonable" price between Panchiao and Sungshan
on the "Tzuchiang" express train class should be NT$36.
</P>
<P>
In terms of operational costs, ticket fares for short hops should
be relatively the most expensive, Hsu added.
</P>
<P>
He said that he will solicit the support of the Ministry of
Transportation and Communications to adjust the short-distance fare
according to the distance traveled, or else directly hike prices
across the board.
</P>
<P>
In addition, in view of the fact that the 345-km high-speed rail
link between Taipei and Kaohsiung will be inaugurated in October
2005, the TRA is considering ticket prices for passengers traveling
more than 200 kilometers between Monday and Thursday, in the hope
that cheaper prices will lure more passengers.
</P>
<P>
The TRA has estimated that both the volume of passenger and cargo
transportation will decrease this year.
</P>
<P>
The revenue from passenger transportation will be down by
NT$16.29 billion, down 12.38 percent from the previous year, mainly
because of the suspension of trains due to the construction of the
Nankang section of the high speed railway, it said.
</P>
<P>
The revenue from cargo transportation will also be down by about
NT$1.1 billion, a drop of around 10.72 percent in comparison to the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
The TRA has estimated that it will face overall losses of NT$10.7
billion this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
