<HEADLINE>
PRICES DOWN ON TAIPEI STOCK MARKET
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 26 (CNA)
(By Eric Liu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Share prices ended the day lower on the
Taiwan Stock Exchange (TAIEX) Friday, with the weighted index, the
market's key barometer, dropping 24.11 points to close at 6,132.62.
</P>
<P>
The bourse opened at 6,227.17 and fluctuated between 6,239.23 and
6,117.27 during trading.
</P>
<P>
A total of 4.61 billion shares changed hands on a market turnover
of NT$97.79 billion (US$2.92 billion) , a decrease from the previous
day's trading session which saw 5.67 billion stocks traded on a
market turnover of NT$119.28 billion (US$3.56 billion).
</P>
<P>
Only one of the eight major stock categories posted a gain, with
electrical shares moving up 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The other seven major categories posted losses, with construction
stocks moving down the most at 3.6 percent, followed by cement stocks
at 1.9 percent, foodstuff stocks at 1.4 percent, pulp and paper
issues at 1.3 percent, bank and insurance shares at 1.3 percent,
textile issues at 1.2 percent, and plastics and chemical shares at
0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Losers outnumbered gainers 663 to 182, with 132 stocks remaining
unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040326.0034" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN TAKES RIGHT PATH TO AVOID IRRELEVANCE IN DOHA TALKS: OFFICIAL
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Geneva,  March 25 (CNA)
(By Neil Lu and P.C. Tang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan could have become an isolated and
"irrelevant" member "without a voice" in the Doha Round agricultural
talks if it had not moved in the right direction, Taiwan's top trade
official in Geneva said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Yen Ching-chang, Taiwan's permanent representative to the World
Trade Organization (WTO), made the comments while analyzing Taiwan's
performance in the multilateral agricultural negotiations of the Doha
Round Trade Talks which resumed Monday.
</P>
<P>
Although Taiwan is a small country, its decision last year to
join the G-10 Group has strengthened its position and made it
impossible for other WTO members to ignore the island in the
agricultural talks, Yen said.
</P>
<P>
The G-10 Group, made up of Taiwan, Bulgaria, Israel, Iceland,
Japan, Mauritius, Norway, Switzerland, South Korea and Liechtenstein,
is aimed at protecting and advancing the agricultural interests of
its members.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that the efforts made by Taiwan's relevant
government agencies and its permanent mission to the WTO have helped
the island explain effectively its positions in the agricultural
talks, Yen said that Taiwan, as a key member of the G-10 Group, had
contact in the talks with leading agricultural countries and
organizations, including the United States, the European Union,
Canada and New Zealand, as well as members of the "Special Products
Union" and other agricultural product exporting nations.
</P>
<P>
According to Yen, Taiwan and other members of the G-10 Group have
also sought cooperation with the members of the "Special Products
Union" in the hopes of being able to get the maximum protection for
their special products.
</P>
<P>
He also said that in the so-called three pillars of the agricultural
talks, the tariff quota system and tariff cuts aimed at market opening,
are the issues that Taiwan is most concerned about.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural talks which began Tuesday are the first of their
kind to be held since the setback at the Fifth WTO Ministerial
Conference held in Cancun, Mexico last September. That conference
failed mainly because of the differences among WTO members over
issues regarding agricultural talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
