<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040326.0043" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 26 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Friday, March 26, or the sixth
day of the leap second month of the Year of the Monkey according
to the lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that
have occurred on this date in the past:

1827: German composer Ludwig van Beethoven, considered the
greatest composer of his day, dies in Vienna at the age of 57. His
music, which formed a transition from classical to romantic
composition, includes nine symphonies, five piano concertos, a violin
concerto, 32 piano sonatas, several other sonatas, two masses and an
opera.

1875: Syngman Rhee, South Korea's first president, is born. His
rule ended in 1960 when he was forced out of office and into exile.

1895: Japan occupies the Penghu Islands located in the Taiwan
Strait.

1902: Cecil John Rhodes, the British financier and colonizer who
became prime minister of Cape Colony in 1890, dies in Cape Town at
the age of 48. He amassed a huge fortune in the South African mining
boom of the 1870s and 1880s, eventually gaining control of 90 percent
of the world's diamond production.

1941: Ernest Miller Hemingway, the American writer who won the
1954 Nobel Prize in literature, interviews Gen. Yu Han-mou, commander
of the seventh war zone, in Chukiang, Kiangsi Province, during the
War of Resistance Against Japan.

1948: A total of 81 experts and scholars, including Wu Ta-you,
Chen Sheng-shen and Hu Shih, are elected as members of Academia
Sinica in the first elections held by the Republic of China's top
research institute.

1949: The Chinese communists announce that peace negotiations
with the Kuomintang will open in April in Beijing.

1953: American microbiologist Jonas Edward Salk announces the
development of the first effective dead-virus vaccine against polio.

1953: Burma files a complaint at the United Nations against the
ROC's support of guerrilla troops on the Sino-Burmese border.

1959: ROC President Chiang Kai-shek, in a special message to the
Tibetan people, pledges that "the government will assist the Tibetan
people in realizing their own aspirations in accordance with the
principle of self-determination."

1966: The Ministry of Foreign Affairs announces the ROC's
opposition to U.S. recognition of Outer Mongolia.

1971: Sheikh Mujibur Rahman declares that the former country of
East Pakistan is now the independent republic of Bangladesh.

1971: The ROC severs diplomatic relations with Kuwait.

1975: Lien Chan, the new ROC ambassador to El Salvador, leaves
Taipei to assume his post.

1976: Lin Yu-tang, one of the best-known Chinese writers in
English, dies of a heart attack in Hong Kong at the age of 80.

1976: Taiwan's Chinese Federation of Labor opens its first
national conference, with 118 delegates taking part.

1976: The ROC Executive Yuan nominates Chien Chun, deputy
director of the Central Bank of China, as director of the
International Monetary Fund.

1977: The ROC research vessel Hai Kung returns to Keelung after a
115-day exploratory expedition to Antarctica.

1979: In the presence of U.S. President Jimmy Carter, Prime
Minister Menachem Begin of Israel and President Anwar Sadat of Egypt
sign a peace treaty ending 30 years of war between the two nations.

1985: Wang Hsi-ling, Hu Yi-min and Chen Hu-men are indicted for
involvement in the murder of Liu Yu-liang, a noted writer with the
pen-name Chiang Nan.

1993: In an interview with CNN, President Lee Teng-hui stresses
the ROC's willingness to form a regional collective security system
with other Asia-Pacific countries.

1996: The IMF agrees to offer a loan of US$10.2 billion to Russia
over the next three years to help Russians transform their economy.

1999: Construction on Taiwan's first high-speed rail system kicks
off in the southern county of Kaohsiung.

1999: Visiting Costa Rican President Miguel Angel Rodriguez makes
history as he becomes the first incumbent foreign head of state to
deliver a speech at the Republic of China's Legislative Yuan since
its establishment at its current location.

2001: The Cross-Strait Common Market Foundation, initiated by
former Premier Vincent Siew and 20 others, is formally established.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "Be conscientious in what you say
to a friend. Lead him gently to what you would have him be; if you
cannot do that, stop. Do not quarrel with him only to get an insult."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040327.0001" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT VOWS TO BOOST RELATIONS WITH U.S., JAPAN IN COMING TERM
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 27 (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian vowed Saturday to
step up Taiwan's friendly relations with the United States and Japan
based upon the existing foundations during his coming four-year term,
according to a presidential aide.
</P>
<P>
Huang Chih-fang, director of the Department of Public Affairs
under the Presidential Office, made the remarks after the two
countries sent their separate congratulations to President Chen on
his re-election.
</P>
<P>
The president was quoted by Huang as saying that his
administration will also closely cooperate with the United States and
Japan to help boost stability, security and prosperity in the
Asia-Pacific area.
</P>
<P>
The White House congratulated Chen on his being re-elected after
the Central Election Commission officially proclaimed his victory in
the March 20 election Friday, but said in its statement that there
are pending legal challenges to the result of the election.
</P>
<P>
On President Chen's behalf, Huang extended his heartfelt
gratitude to the U.S. and Japan for their congratulatory messages,
and he said the Presidential Office approves of the White House's
remarks that all election-related disputes should be resolved through
Taiwan's existing legal mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
"We applaud the people of Taiwan for embracing established legal
mechanisms and rejecting extra-legal options to resolve their
differences," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Chen and his running mate -- Vice President Annette Lu -- beat
the opposition "pan-blue alliance" ticket of Kuomintang Chairman Lien
Chan and People First Party Chairman James Soong by a razor-thin
margin of just under 30,000 votes, or 0.228 percent.
</P>
<P>
After refusing to accept the election results, the "pan-blue
alliance" filed a lawsuit to seek the election's annulment and
demanded that a judicial recount of all ballots be conducted
immediately. That lawsuit was thrown out because it was incorrectly
filed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040327.0002" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE CONGRATULATES PRESIDENT CHEN ON  RE-ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Washington, March 26 (CNA)
(By Jorge Liu &amp; Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The White House congratulated Republic
of China President Chen Shui-bian on his being re-elected after
Taiwan's Central Election Commission officially proclaimed his
victory in the March 20 election Friday.
</P>
<P>
The statement issued by the Press Secretary at the White House
noted that there are pending legal challenges to the results of the
election. "We applaud the people of Taiwan for embracing established
legal mechanisms and rejecting extra-legal options to resolve their
differences," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The White House also reiterated its commitment to Taiwan as
provided in the Taiwan Relations Act, urging the country, as well as
Beijing, to pursue dialogue and refrain from unilateral steps that
would alter Taiwan's status.
</P>
<P>
As regard its own part, the White House promised to continue to
maintain close unofficial ties with the people on Taiwan in
accordance with its "one-China" policy, as embodied in the Taiwan
Relations Act and the three Joint Communiques between the United
States and the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
Following is the full text of the statement:
</P>
<P>
"We join the American people in congratulating the people of
Taiwan on the successful conclusion of their March 20 presidential
election. Taiwan's Central Election Commission on March 26 officially
proclaimed that Mr. Chen Shui-bian has won re-election, and we
congratulate Mr. Chen on his victory.
</P>
<P>
" We recognize that there are pending legal challenges to the
results of the March 20 election. We applaud the people of Taiwan for
embracing established legal mechanisms and rejecting extra-legal
options to resolve their differences. We reject calls for violence,
which threaten the very democratic principles to which we and the
people of Taiwan are committed.
</P>
<P>
"The maintenance of peace and stability in the Taiwan Strait and
the welfare of the people of Taiwan remain of profound importance to
the United States. To advance these goals, the United States will
fulfill its obligations under the Taiwan Relations Act. It falls to
Taiwan and Beijing to build the essential foundations for peace and
stability by pursuing dialogue through all available means and
refraining from unilateral steps that would alter Taiwan's status.
</P>
<P>
We will continue to maintain close unofficial ties with the
people on Taiwan through the American Institute in Taiwan in
accordance with our "one-China" policy, as embodied in the Taiwan
Relations Act and our three Joint Communiques with the People's
Republic of China.
</P>
</TEXT>
