<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040327.0011" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
DPP CALLS FOR SETTLEMENT OF ELECTION DISPUTES BY JUDICIAL MEANS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 27 (CNA)
(By Huang Kwang-chun)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ruling Democratic Progressive Party
(DPP) reiterated its appeal Saturday to settle disputes regarding the
March 20 presidential election through judicial channels.
</P>
<P>
DPP Secretary-General Chang Chun-hsiung made the appeal when he
commented on a mass protest staged by supporters of the opposition
"pan-blue alliance" formed by the Kuomintang (KMT) , People First
Party (PFP) and New Party in front of the Presidential Office.
</P>
<P>
Chang said that President Chen Shui-bian has agreed to revise the
President and Vice President Election and Recall Law to pave the way
for a vote recount and to accept experts recommended by the "pan-blue
alliance" to join the investigation into the shooting of President
Chen and Vice President Annette Lu on the eve of the election. Chang
said the moves were made out of goodwill by the president.
</P>
<P>
If the opposition camp or both KMT Chairman Lien Chan and PFP
Chairman James Soong themselves obtain any evidence of electoral
fraud or crimes, they should deliver them to the court, Chang said,
claiming that both President Chen and the ruling party are willing to
cooperate with the judicial authorities to investigate the alleged
cases and to accept the court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
The DPP does not want to see the opposition camp resorting to
unlawful moves or violence in its protests, which would jeopardize
the harmony and social order of the country, Chang noted, suggesting
that Lien and Soong should allow the demonstrations to end
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Both Chang and Legislator Tsai Huang-lang, DPP legislative caucus
whip, called on their party members and supporters to avoid the
vicinities of the demonstration site and refrain from provoking the
rival camp.
</P>
<P>
The "pan-blue alliance" supporters have staged the demonstration
since last Saturday shortly after the Central Election Commission
announced preliminary results of the election which gave President
Chen another four-year term by defeating Lien by a slim margin of
0.228 percent, or fewer than 30,000 votes out of the approximately 13
million ballots cast.
</P>
<P>
The "pan blue alliance" supporters described the election as
"unfair" and asked for a recount of the votes and demanded that an
independent investigation panel be established to look into the March
19 shooting which they believed gave Chen sympathy votes and victory
in the hotly contested race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040327.0012" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PAN-BLUE PROTEST DRAWS LARGE CROWD IN TAIPEI
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 27 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More than 320,000 people braved chilling
drizzle to gather in Taipei and protest what rally organizers claimed
was "unfairness" in the March 20 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,600 tour buses loaded with participants of the
protest began to converge on the capital from around the island
Saturday noon, and still more people from metropolitan Taipei joined
the protest organized by the opposition Kuomintang (KMT) and People
First Party (PFP).
</P>
<P>
A group of protesters, led by Penghu County Magistrate Lai
Feng-wei flew in from the outlying island county Saturday morning to
take part in the event.
</P>
<P>
The protestors, gathered at the square in front of the
Presidential Office, echoed the organizers' call, demanding the
administration of President Chen Shui-bian to clear away any doubts
surrounding the presidential election in which the joint KMT-PFP
ticket lost by a slim margin of 0.228 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the evening of the March 20 presidential election, Lien and
Soong led a group of their supporters to stage an overnight protest
in front of the Presidential Office, saying that the election was
"unfair." The protest had gone on for a week when the two parties
called in more supporters to stage what organizers said would be a
"huge protest unseen in the capital before."
</P>
<P>
Many KMT and PFP lawmakers took turns giving speeches during the
protest, urging Chen's administration to grant their requests for a
recount of the votes and an independent investigation into a shooting
incident the day before the election in which Chen and Vice President
Annette Lu were injured. The shooting sparked speculation that the
incident was the main reason for their victory and many wondered why
the government put the armed forces and police on a higher alert
after the incident, thereby stripping them of their right to vote.
Many in the armed forces are KMT and PFP supporters.
</P>
<P>
They also disputed criticism from the ruling party that most of
the protesters were mainlanders and their descendants, arguing that
the make-up of the crowd included people of different ethnic groups
in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
These politicians also took issue with assumptions that the
protesters came to the gathering carrying weapons, such as Molotov
cocktails, looking for a chance to resort to violence. Rather, they
said, the protesters are law-abiding people.
</P>
<P>
The protest put Taipei Mayor Ma Ying-jeou, who was a leading
campaigner for Lien and Soong, in a tight spot. As a rising political
star in the KMT-PFP alliance, he should stand shoulder to shoulder
with Lien and Soong in the protest to reinforce his status as their
successor, but as chief of City Hall, Ma is obliged to keep peace and
order around the city, not least of all around the Presidential
Office.
</P>
<P>
Ma has also been pressed by his ruling party critics to get tough
with the protestors.
</P>
<P>
Ma chose to do a delicate balancing act between the two forces.
Although he gave a pep talk to the protesters Saturday afternoon, he
did not appear together with Lien and Soong in the protest and was
careful not to offend the protesters by breaking up the gathering by
force. Instead, the soft-spoken mayor gently dissuaded the protesters
from violently venting their frustration with the re-election of
President Chen.
</P>
<P>
Since the time for the protest to end was 6 p.m, Ma said he had
approved another protest site applied for by the KMT at the Chiang
Kai-shek Memorial Hall from March 28 until April 3. He said he hoped
that the protestors would move to the memorial hall, which is a
little further from the Presidential Office. He said that their
presence there would be less disturbing to the residents of the city.
</P>
<P>
On a different note, politics makes strange bedfellows, as was
shown by the curious assortment of visitors to the protest, including
former DPP Chairman Hsu Hsin-liang, who staged a 66-hour hunger
strike to show his solidarity with the protesters, and independent
lawmaker Sisy Chen, who is a former DPP leader and an outspoken
critic of President Chen. As usual, Sisy Chen made a scathing
criticism of the president to the great pleasure of her audience.
</P>
<P>
Although the protest was peaceful in general, Taipei City
authorities summoned 4,600 police to maintain peace around the area,
with another 4,000 ready to join them if necessary, and another 3,000
in reserve.
</P>
<P>
After the 6 p.m. deadline, people were seen slowly leaving the
protest site, although it was not immediately clear if any of them
would remain beyond the deadline to end the protest at the
Presidential Office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040327.0013" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 27 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Saturday, March 27, or the
seventh day of the leap second month of the Year of the Monkey
according to the lunar calendar. Following is a list of important
events that have occurred on this date in the past:

1713: Spain agrees to cede Gibraltar and Minorca to Britain.

1794: The United States establishes its Navy.

1802: France and Britain sign the Peace of Amiens, creating a
short pause in the Napoleonic Wars.

1914: The first successful blood transfusion is performed in a
Brussels hospital.

1917: Cyrus Vance, American politician and secretary of state
from 1977 to 1980, is born.

1926: Construction of a railroad linking Taitung and Hualien in
eastern Taiwan is completed.

1933: Japan withdraws from the League of Nations after the
organization refuses to recognize "Manchukuo."

1945: Argentina declares war on Japan and Germany.

1953: The Republic of China Ministry of Education approves the
establishment of Tunghai University by a Christian organization.

1958: Nikita Kruschev ousts Soviet Prime Minister Marshal Nikolai
Bulganin in a Kremlin power struggle.

1968: Soviet astronaut Yuri Gagarin, the first man to orbit the
earth, dies in a plane crash near Moscow.

1969: The North Vietnamese delegate to the Paris peace talks
rejects South Vietnamese President Nguyen van Thieu's proposal for
direct and secret negotiations.

1973: Paul Cardinal Yupin leaves Taipei for the United States en
route to the Vatican to attend a meeting.

1974: Vice President C. K. Yen returns from a 20-day visit to
South America. He attended the inaugurations of President Carlos
Andres Perez of Venezuela and President Ernesto Geisel of Brazil.

1974: Retired Lt. Gen. James H. Doolittle of the U.S. Air Force,
who led the first American air raid over Tokyo, Osaka and Kobe during
World War II, arrives in Taipei for a six-day visit.

1976: Madame Yen Chia-kan awards Golden Phoenix Statues to the 10
outstanding young women (under 40) of 1975-76.

1976: Taipei Mayor Chang Feng-shu is decorated by Dr. Jose A.
Quezada Tajeda, administrative secretary of the Presidential Office
of the Dominican Republic.

1977: A KLM jetliner and a Pan Am jetliner collide on the runway
in Tenerife in the Canary Islands, claiming 575 lives.

1981: Urged by union leader Lech Walesa, millions of Polish
workers stage a general strike to protest police harassment of
activists belonging to the trade union Solidarity.

1989: The Central Bank of China of the ROC announces the
cancellation of limits on the daily fluctuation of the New Taiwan
dollar against the greenback, effective April 3.

1990: The eighth plenum of the ROC National Assembly passes a
motion to force members who failed to attend the plenary session to
retire by the end of July 1990.

1991: Chen Charng-ven, secretary-general of the Straits Exchange
Foundation, flies to the Chinese mainland to discuss the release of
three security policemen taken across the Strait by mainland
fishermen. The four would be returned to Taipei on April 3.

1992: The ROC and Bulgaria agree to establish direct air links
between Taipei and Sofia.

1994: The Eurofighter, a high-tech fighter jet developed under a
four-nation project, makes its successful maiden flight.

1995: The Cabinet-level Mainland Affairs Council of the ROC
adopts a regulation governing the participation of mainland Chinese
people in economic and trade activities in Taiwan.

2000: Minister of Transportation and Communications Lin
Feng-cheng assumes the post of secretary-general of the Kuomintang
Central Committee.

2000: ROC President Lee Teng-hui meets with Canadian Nobel
laureate Robert Mundell to exchange views on Asian financial
problems, Taiwan's economic development and global economic trends.

2001: John Chang, former secretary-general of the opposition
Kuomintang, registers to run for a seat in the Legislature in the
year-end elections.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "A man who can recite three hundred
pieces of poetry by heart, but who, when the conduct of the affairs
of a nation is entrusted to him, can do nothing; and who, when sent
on a public mission to a foreign country, has nothing to say for
himself -- although such a man has much learning, of what use is it?"
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040327.0014" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TRAFFIC SITUATION IN TAIPEI GOOD DESPITE MASS RALLY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 27 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The traffic situation in Taipei remained
good on Saturday despite the fact that a mass demonstration by the
opposition camp was held in the afternoon in front of the
Presidential Office, according to the city's traffic authorities.
</P>
<P>
Municipal traffic police officers said that the overall traffic
situation in the city was largely good, except for some areas
adjacent to the Presidential Office.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the number of the demonstrators, who
gathered around in the Presidential Office to protest what they
claimed was an "unfair and rigged" March 20 presidential election,
was about 320,000.
</P>
<P>
The opposition "pan-blue alliance" estimated a day earlier that
more than 3,000 tour buses carrying supporters from around the
country would flock to Taipei.
</P>
<P>
Main opposition Kuomintang (KMT) Chairman Lien Chan of the
"pan-blue alliance" formed by the KMT, the People First Party and the
New Party, lost the presidential election to incumbent President Chen
Shui-bian, who won a second term in office by a very small margin of
fewer than 30,000 ballots -- or 0.228 percent of the more than 13
million votes cast.
</P>
</TEXT>
