<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040327.0015" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER-MAKER OPTIMISTIC ABOUT CROSS-STRAIT RELATIONS AFTER ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  27 (CNA)
(By Eric Liu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Along with the continuous political
upheaval following the presidential election, Shih Chung-tang,
president of ASUSTeK, the world-renowned computer manufacturer based
in Taiwan, said Saturday he has high hopes for the opening of direct
cross-Taiwan Strait links -- trade, transportation and postal
services.
</P>
<P>
Shih, at an interview after the closing of the company's first
sports event held since ASUSTeK was set up 15 years ago, said that
both the "pan-blue alliance" and the "pan-green camp" should calm
down and settle the political issues in peace together to stabilize
the political and economic situation.
</P>
<P>
The direct cross-strait "three links" should be the economic core
after the presidential election, he continued, adding that President
Chen Shui-bian should treat mainland China-Taiwan issues using
perspective, and take global competition into consideration while
working on mainland China-related strategies. Taiwan would lose an
opportunity of upgrading its competitive edges in the long term if
proper strategies are not put in place, Shih said.
</P>
</TEXT>
