</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 27 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Law enforcers in Taipei have been asked to
keep watch for any violence during Saturday's protest demonstration
in the capital called by the opposition Kuomintang (KMT) and People
First Party (PFP), according a spokesman for the Executive Yuan.
</P>
<P>
Lin Chia-lung, a spokesman for the Executive Yuan, quoted Premier
Yu Shyi-kun as saying Saturday morning that law enforcers should
gather evidence of any violence in the protest and bring those
responsible to justice afterward.
</P>
<P>
Yu also asked prosecutors to look into the clash between
protestors and police at the Central Election Commission (CEC)
offices on Friday, when supporters of the KMT and PFP tried to storm
the CEC to prevent it from declaring President Chen Shui-bian as the
winner of the March 20 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Noting that some KMT and PFP lawmakers took part in the brawl
with police, the premier has asked law enforcers to call these
opposition lawmakers to account.
</P>
<P>
The premier, who said the previous day that his administration
has contingency plans to deal with 15 different scenarios at the
protest, also ordered the establishment of a panel to keep government
agencies as well as foreign journalists in the country informed of
the latest developments regarding the protest.
</P>
<P>
In a response to Beijing's warning on Friday that it won't sit on
its hands in case rioting erupts in Taiwan, the premier said the
government will spare no effort in preventing the protest from
developing into a riot and denying Beijing any excuse to interfere.
</P>
</TEXT>
