<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040328.0009" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
CHEN-LIEN-SOONG MEETING ON MONDAY REMAINS UNCERTAIN
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 28 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It remains uncertain whether a
much-anticipated meeting between President Chen Shui-bian and two
opposition leaders will take place on Monday, a Kuomintang (KMT)
official said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Ting Yuan-chao, a close aide to KMT Chairman Lien Chan, said
that as Lien has a busy schedule for Monday, he is not sure
whether Lien can meet with President Chen.
</P>
<P>
Chen told a news conference Saturday evening that he is willing
to meet with the defeated presidential electoral team of Lien
and People First Party (PFP) Chairman James Soong Monday without any
strings attached.
</P>
<P>
Ting said Lien and Soong had hoped to meet Chen since the
March 20 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
"President Chen first didn't make any response. And now he
abruptly agrees to meet with Lien and Soong unconditionally. It
requires further discussions to set the stage for the proposed
meeting," Ting said.
</P>
<P>
According to Ting, President Chen's chief of staff Chiou I-jen
should talk with KMT Secretary-General Lin Feng-cheng and PFP
Secretary-General Tsai Chung-hsiung to work out technical details for
the Chen-Lien-Soong meeting.
</P>
<P>
A Presidential Office source said earlier in the day that Chiou
already telephoned KMT and PFP secretaries-general for arranging the
proposed meeting.
</P>
<P>
"We are waiting for a response from the Lien-Soong camp so that
we can determine the exact time, venue and agenda for the planned
meeting," said one of Chiou's close aides.
</P>
<P>
The Lien-Soong ticket has contested the outcome of the March 20
election, in which Chen defeated Lien by a slim margin of 0.228
percent or 29,518 ballots out of more than 13 million cast. Lien and
Soong have mobilized their supporters to demonstrate non-stop at the
Presidential Office square for the past week.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday afternoon, about half a million of the Lien-Soong
supporters thronged the streets surrounding the Presidential Office,
demanding a "judicial" vote recount and an independent inquiry into a
failed election-eve assassination attempt against Chen that the
opposition camp claimed had unfairly swayed sympathy votes Chen's
way.
</P>
<P>
Hours later, Chen responded to the Lien-Soong camp requests at an
evening news conference, saying that as long as the "pan-blue
alliance" presidential contenders filed either an annulment or a
recount lawsuit, he would sign a letter of consent to allow for an
immediate and complete ballot recount regardless of whether evidence
of election fraud is provided.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not afraid of the recount, and it is my commitment to fully
accept the results of the recount whether or not they are in my
favor. I hope that KMT Chairman Lien and PFP Chairman Soong will be
able to do the same," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
He also retracted a previous request that Lien and Soong disperse
the demonstrators at Ketagalan Boulevard in front of the Presidential
Office before meeting with him.
</P>
<P>
"I hope to meet with the two pan-blue alliance leaders on Monday
unconditionally," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
He further said he will order law enforcement officers to clear
up Ketagalan Boulevard by Monday.
</P>
<P>
The "pan-blue alliance" rally at Ketagalan Boulevard ended at 6
p.m. Saturday, but some demonstrators refused to leave the site.
Outnumbered by police, some protesters left reluctantly but
calmly Sunday morning, while others struggled briefly. Some joined
another sit-in at the Chiang Kai Shek Memorial Hall complex nearby.
</P>
<P>
The end of the week-long demonstration outside the Presidential
Office is a relief for many Taiwan residents.
</P>
<P>
During Saturday's news conference, President Chen also refuted
opposition allegations that he staged the election-eve shooting
incident to boost his re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
Chen's voice quivered with rage when he described his humiliation
at suspicions that he staged the mysterious shooting.
</P>
<P>
"I have never staged this shooting incident and there is nothing
to hide. The investigation will be fair and transparent," Chen said.
"I do not want to bear this bad name any longer."
</P>
<P>
Chen vowed to step down at once if his rival could prove the
failed assassination in which a bullet gashed his abdomen had been
staged and challenged Lien to find the world's best sniper to
re-enact the shooting.
</P>
<P>
"If you can't do it or you are afraid of doing it, then shut up,"
he told Lien and Soong.
</P>
<P>
Chen and Vice President Annette Lu were both slightly wounded by
two bullets from a homemade gun as they campaigned in the southern
city of Tainan on the March 19 afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040328.0010" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
HEAD OF INTERNATIONAL BUDDHIST ASSOCIATION HONORED
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taichung,   central  Taiwan,   March  28  (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taichung County
Magistrate Huang Chung-sheng on Sunday bestowed an honorary county
resident certificate on Daisaku Ikeda, president of Soka Gakkai
International, a Buddhist association of more than 12 million members
in 187 countries and territories.
</P>
<P>
Huang said the honor is in recognition of Ikeda's long-term
contribution in promoting culture, educational exchanges and social
activities for the public welfare. Ikeda's son received the
certificate on his father's behalf.
</P>
<P>
The magistrate noted that Ikeda, a prolific writer, poet and
peace activist, has devoted his entire life to the promotion of
culture and education for the sake of world peace and that he has in
recent years focused on enhancing the bilateral friendship between
Taiwan and Japan.
</P>
<P>
He has already been presented with the highest medal by the
Ministry of the Interior as well as honorary Taipei City and
Kaohsiung City resident certificates, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Under the leadership of Ikeda, Taiwan members of the association
have devoted themselves to community concerns on the basis of "good
citizen and good national" ideals.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, the members have sponsored community friendship and
cultural activities around Taichung County, bringing culture and
vibrant dynamism into various communities.
</P>
<P>
Following the disastrous earthquake of Sep. 21, 1999, the members
sponsored art festivals in several villages and townships in hard-hit
Taichung County, and contributed actively to disaster relief and
after-math psychological counseling work. They also sponsored world
youth painting exhibitions and other major activities to enrich the
cultural life of the people of Taichung County.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040328.0011" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 28 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Sunday, March 28, or the eighth
day of the leap second month of the Year of the Monkey according to
the lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that have
occurred on this date in the past:

1483: Raphael, originally Raffaello Sanzio, great Italian
Renaissance painter, is born. His works, including frescoes and
portraits of religious subjects, exemplify the ideals of the High
Renaissance.

1844: Mexico breaks off relations with the United States over the
disputed territory of Texas.

1910: The first seaplane, designed by Frenchman Henri Fabre,
successfully takes off near the French port of Marseilles.

1911: Liang Chi-chao, who together with Kang Yu-wei initiated a
reform movement in China in 1898, arrives in Keelung from Kobe for a
two-week visit.

1920: Douglas Fairbanks and Mary Pickford, known to millions as
the King and Queen of Hollywood, get married while surrounded by
friends.

1930: Constantinople and Angora are renamed Istanbul and Ankara
respectively in Turkey.

1938: The Republic of China Ministry of Foreign Affairs issues a
statement denouncing the "Reform Government of China," a puppet
regime established by the Japanese in Nanking.

1939: Adolf Hitler renounces Germany's 1934 non-aggression pact
with Poland.

1939: Gen. Francisco Franco leads his army to take Madrid, ending
the three-year Spanish civil war.

1941: Britain's Royal Navy sinks seven Italian warships without
suffering any losses itself at the battle of Matapan, off the Greek
island of Crete.

1945: Nazi Germany mounts its last V2 rocket attack against
Britain.

1950: Nationalist troops retreat from Hsichang, in mainland
China's Hsikang Province, marking the total fall of mainland China to
communist forces.

1959: Mainland Chinese troops invade Tibet to quell an
anti-Communist Chinese rebellion, forcing the Dalai Lama, the
spiritual leader of Tibet, to flee into exile in India.

1969: Former U.S. President Dwight D. Eisenhower dies of heart
disease at the age of 79.

1969: Massive anti-Soviet demonstrations take place in Prague.

1969: Bishop Paul Yupin is appointed Cardinal.

1970: A disastrous magnitude 7.5 earthquake jolts western Turkey,
killing more than 2,000, injuring over 4,000, and leaving more than
90,000 homeless.

1973: Marlon Brando, American film actor, refuses to accept his
Oscar award for his role in "The Godfather" because of Hollywood's
abuses of the American Indians.

1979: In the United States, the Three Mile Island nuclear power
plant's reactor leaks radiation.

1985: Devan Nair resigns as president of Singapore on health
grounds.

1994: The ROC and the Central African Republic sign a joint
communique pledging further cooperation.

1996: After eight years of construction, the Mucha Line of the
Taipei Mass Rapid Transit System in Taiwan formally begins
operations.

1999: NATO aircraft widen their strikes against Yugoslavia,
targeting ground forces in Kosovo that are forcing tens of thousands
of ethnic Albanians from their homes.

2000: The ROC-Canada Biotechnology Development Fund is formally
established and is poised to become a prime mover behind a new round
of development of Taiwan's biotechnology industry.

2000: Taiwan decides to ban imports of live cloven-hoofed animals
and related products from Japan and South Korea after cattle in the
two countries were found to be infected with foot-and-mouth disease.

2001: Liberian President Charles Taylor and his wife arrive in
Taipei for a seven-day state visit.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "If a man is in order in his
personal conduct, he will be served even without taking the trouble
to give orders. But if a man is not in order in his personal conduct,
he may give orders, but his orders will not be obeyed."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040328.0012" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PINGTUNG FISHING VESSEL MISSING FOR 2 WEEKS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Pingtung,  southern  Taiwan,  March 28 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Pingtung fishing
vessel has been missing since it was last reported fishing near Bali,
Indonesia two weeks ago, a radio station of Tungkang Fishermen's
Association said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The radio station has asked nearby fishing vessels to help search
for the "Mantafeng 12" which was registered at Tungkang, Pingtung.
</P>
<P>
The family of Hung Kuo-fu, captain of the vessel, reported that
he has not been in contact with the family since March 14.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Hung, there are three other Taiwanese, two
Indonesian and one mainland Chinese crewmen aboard the fishing
vessel.
