</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040328.0013" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TIME NOT YET RIPE TO DISCUSS PAN-BLUE MERGER: KMT SPOKESMAN
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  28 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The time is not yet ripe for the three
political parties of the "pan-blue alliance" to merge, a spokesman of
the opposition Kuomintang (KMT) said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Alex Tsai was responding to questions about whether the KMT and
its splinter parties, namely the New Party and the People First Party
(PFP), will merge following KMT Chairman Lien Chan's remarks during a
mass rally the previous day that the three parties will cooperate
even more closely in the wake of the March 20 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Tsai said that "there has been consistent speculation to that
effect, but the timing is not yet ripe."
</P>
<P>
"The ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) has pulled out all
stops to try to disintegrate 'pan-blue alliance' cooperation, " Tsai
said, adding that he wanted to advise the DPP to direct its efforts
in the right places.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an ally of the ruling Democratic Progressive Party has
urged KMT Chairman Lien Chan to concede defeat and step down as the
party chairman.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Chen-lung, whip of the Taiwan Solidarity Union at the
Legislative Yuan, said that Lien, at the age of 68, is too old, and
that the KMT under his leadership has undergone several major
setbacks.
</P>
<P>
"Lien should pass the baton to others and let the grand old party
become Taiwanized, " Cheng said, adding that Legislative Yuan
President Wang Jin-pyng is the perfect candidate to take the helm of
the KMT.
</P>
<P>
Cheng said that the KMT should learn the will of the people to
move toward the direction of Taiwanization, adding that if Wang
serves as its chairman, the party can maintain its power to balance
that of the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
He also said that PFP Chairman James Soong has charisma and is
unlikely to step down from the chairmanship.
</P>
<P>
He said the KMT and the PFP will have to go their own ways in the
year-end legislative elections and that there is a possibility that
the PFP could replace the KMT as the second largest party in the
225-seat Legislature.
</P>
<P>
Lien teamed up with Soong in the March 20 presidential election,
but President Chen Shui-bian of the ruling Democratic Progressive
Party (DPP) won re-election by a razor-thin margin of 29,518 votes
out of a total of nearly 13 million valid ballots.
</P>
<P>
Lien has yet to concede defeat. He has raised questions about the
"fairness" of the election and demanded that there be an immediate
vote recount and that an ad hoc committee be established to
investigate the election-eve assassination attempt against President
Chen and Vice President Annette Lu which many believe decisively
influenced the outcome of the election by garnering sympathy votes
for Chen and Lu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040328.0014" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
DPP LEGISLATIVE CAUCUS DENIES TRYING TO LURE AWAY KMT LAWMAKERS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  28 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The legislative caucus of the ruling
Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) denied Sunday that it has stepped
up efforts to lure opposition Kuomintang (KMT) lawmakers to its camp
after President Chen Shui-bian's re-election.
</P>
<P>
Media reports quoted unidentified KMT legislators as saying that
the DPP legislative caucus is lobbying native Taiwanese KMT lawmakers
to join its ranks to facilitate passage of major bills proposed by
Chen's administration.
</P>
<P>
"The reports are not factual, " said DPP legislative whip Tsai
Huang-lang. "We have not taken such actions for the moment."
</P>
<P>
In his view, Tsai said, the best timing for the DPP to form a
"majority alliance" in the Legislative Yuan is after the legislative
elections scheduled for late this year.
</P>
<P>
For the time being, Tsai said, the DPP will focus on forging
cooperative ties with opposition parties on a case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
He said that before the year-end legislative elections, the DPP
legislative caucus hopes to cooperate with its opposition
counterparts in completing legislation of a number of important bills
to boost economic, political and financial reforms, including the
political party bill, the Executive Yuan restructuring bill, the
Judicial Yuan organization bill, and amendments to the statute
governing the Financial Reconstruction Fund.
</P>
<P>
As to the formation of a "majority alliance" with opposition
lawmakers, Tsai said, such a sensitive topic will not be addressed
until after the new Legislature is elected late this year.
</P>
<P>
Although the DPP is the largest party in the current Legislature,
it doesn't hold more than half of the seats. As a result, many
critical bills are pending approval of the Legislature, which is
controlled by the opposition "pan-blue alliance" of the KMT and the
People First Party.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, nearly all influential native Taiwanese KMT
lawmakers ruled out the possibility of an intraparty split before the
year-end legislative election.
</P>
<P>
Legislator Lee Chuang-chiao from Tainan County in southern Taiwan
said he feels the KMT should revise its basic policy line to win more
support from local residents after the bitterly contested
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the election outcome shows that Taiwan's separate
national identity has won more recognition among voters, Lee said
the KMT must adapt its party platform to this mainstream trend.
</P>
<P>
In the just-concluded presidential election, KMT Chairman Lien
Chan teamed up with People First Party (PFP) Chairman James Soong to
challenge President Chen's re-election bid. Chen won with a slim
margin of 29,518 votes, or 0.228 percent out of 13 million ballots
cast. Lien refused to concede defeate and will file a lawsuit
to annul the election Monday.
</P>
<P>
Lee said the KMT will address its party platform revision issue
after the election controversy is settled. As to whether the KMT will
merge with the PFP, he said, it's up to Lien and Soong to make
a decision on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Another KMT legislator, Lin Yi-shih, said incumbent native
Taiwanese KMT lawmakers are unlikely to "defect" to the DPP camp
before the year-end legislative election.
</P>
<P>
Lin, who is also a KMT Central Standing Committee member, said he
hope the KMT and the PFP will coordinate their nomination strategy
for the year-end legislative election in order to win as many seats
as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040328.0015" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
DEATH RATE FOR TUBERCULOSIS DROPS 60-FOLD IN 5 DECADES: DOH
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 28 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The death rate for tuberculosis dropped
60-fold in Taiwan over the past five decades thanks to the strenuous
efforts of the island's medical staff, a Department of Health (DOH)
official said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
DOH Deputy Minister Lee Lung-teng made the remarks at a meeting
in Taipei to mark world efforts in tuberculosis prevention.
</P>
<P>
Lee noted that the death rate in Taiwan used to be nearly 300 out
of every 100,000 persons five decades ago, but the ratio dropped to a
little more than 5 out of every 100,000 persons in 2001.
</P>
<P>
Lee, who has first-hand understanding of the disease because both
of his parents were tuberculosis patients, said that the formulation
and implementation of health policy requires wisdom from all sides
and adjustments with the passage of the time.
</P>
<P>
He cited the approach of the World Health Organization (WHO) in
ending the practice of concentrating tuberculosis patients in one
medical institution as an example.
</P>
<P>
Judging from his own experience, Lee said that it is not easy to
educate society on the importance of tuberculosis prevention and then
proceed to prevent the disease in a short time.
</P>
<P>
He said that based on the WHO standard of less than two deaths
out of every 100,000 persons, Taiwan still has a long way to go in
its fight against the disease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040328.0016" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE BAG TITLES AT 2004 TAIPEI ULTRAMARATHON
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 28 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Japanese runners Otaki Masayuki and Kimie
Noto won the men's and women's events of the 2004 Soochow University
International Ultramarathon Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Braving rains and chilly weather, a score of runners from around
the world, including Edit Berces from Hungary, the women's world
record holder with a distance of 250.108 kilometers, competed in the
fifth Soochow University International Ultramarathon that began
Saturday on its campus in suburban Taipei.
</P>
<P>
This ultramarathon is a race to see who can run the farthest in
24 hours.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese runners proved to be the best in this year's Taipei
race of endurance, with Masayuki winning the men's title with a
record distance of 271.75 kilometers, followed by his fellow
countryman Nobumi Iwamato with a distance of 247.26 kilometers, and
Kimie Noto garnering the women's title with a distance of 226.99
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Ryoichi Sekiya, who won the men's title last year, dropped out of
this year's race after 152 kilometers due to a pulled thigh muscle.
</P>
<P>
Edit Berces, who was last year's champion in the women's
category, failed to finish the 24-hour ultramarathon for unknown
reasons.
</P>
<P>
Chen Chin-tsai, the top runner from Taiwan, finished fourth in
the men's category with a distance of 220.03 kilometers, while Chang
Mei-lien finished sixth in the women's category with a distance of
190.06 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Masayuki, a physician and an amateur marathoner, said winning the
title was a surprise even to himself. He said his best hope had been
to finish second behind Sekiya, adding that after Sekiya dropped out
late Saturday night, he tried his utmost to "retain the championship
for Japan."
</P>
<P>
Masayuki said that he runs to work every morning to his hospital
office located 30 kilometers away from his home. He noted that he has
often promoted running to his patients as an effective way to improve
their health, adding however that he discourages his excessively
plump patients from running.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040328.0017" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
FIVE STATE-OWNED BANKS TO RECRUIT 446 NEW STAFF MEMBERS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 28 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Amid a domestic economic recovery, five
state-owned banks will recruit a total of 446 clerks this year,
financial sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The five banks -- Bank of Taiwan, Taiwan Cooperative Bank, Land
Bank of Taiwan, Central Trust of China, and the Export-Import Bank of
the Republic of China -- have commissioned the Taiwan Academy of
Banking and Finance (TABF) to handle a joint examination for
hopefuls, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
"This marks the first time in nearly a decade that the five
state-owned banks have held such a large-scale employee recruitment
drive, "a TABF executive said.
</P>
<P>
As of Saturday, about 30,000 hopefuls had registered for the
examination. The registration deadline is April 2. Hopefuls must be
aged under 28 years and have at least a senior high school diploma to
qualify.
</P>
<P>
Among the five banks, Land Bank and Taiwan Cooperative Bank
will each recruit 150 new clerks; Bank of Taiwan will recruit 120
clerks; Central Trust of China will recruit 25 clerks; while the
Export-Import Bank will only recruit one.
</P>
<P>
Except for the Export-Import Bank, the four other banks will all
be privatized soon. Taiwan Cooperative Bank will complete its
privatization process by the end of this year, while Bank of
Taiwan, Land Bank of Taiwan and Central Trust of China will be
privatized by the end of 2006. In order to retain their status as
civil servants, many staff members of these four banks have
transferred to other government agencies, thus leaving a number of
job positions vacant, banking sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
