<HEADLINE>
KENYAN, CHINESE RUNNERS WIN TOP SPOTS IN TAIPEI MARATHON
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  28 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jesse Maina Njuguna of Kenya and Hu
Xiuying from mainland China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region won
the men's and women's events, respectively, of the 2004 Taipei
International Express Marathon Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Njuguna, 31, finished with a time of 2: 18: 21 to successfully
defend his title in the men's 42.195-km marathon, the third of its
kind in Taiwan since 2002.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan runner, whose personal marathon best of 2: 12: 00 was
set in the 1999 Frankfurt Marathon, said he is satisfied with his
performance in the Taipei event. He defended the same title last year
with a time of 2: 21: 21. "It was too cold here in March 2003, " he
said, explaining his somewhat slower time.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Kosgei, also from Kenya, finished second in the men's
marathon with a time of 2: 19: 21. Kosgei said that he could have
beaten Njuguna if he had not developed stomach cramps from drinking
too much water during the final six kilometers of the race.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hu Xiuying won the women's race with a time of 2:41:19
for her third marathon title in just four marathons since switching
from being a professional 5,000-meter runner to a marathoner only
about one year ago.
</P>
<P>
Hu, who is scheduled to return to Inner Mongolia Monday, said
that she would be glad to represent Taiwan in international marathons
if given the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
Russia's Elena Bikulova, 39, winner of the 2003 Taipei
International Express Marathon women's event, finished second with a
time of 2:50:21.
</P>
<P>
The 2004 Taipei International Express also featured 5-km, 10-km
and 21-km running events held on the Wuku-Hsichih section of the Sun
Yat-sen Freeway near Taipei. Some 17,000 runners, including 1,000
marathoners, participated in the races.
</P>
