<TEXT>
<P>
Despite a 90-minute meeting Monday of the
top aides of President Chen Shui-bian, opposition Kuomintang (KMT)
Chairman Lien Chan and People First Party (PFP) Chairman James Soong,
no date was fixed for a meeting between the three.
</P>
<P>
Presidential Office Secretary-General Chiou I-jen said after
meeting KMT Secretary-General Lin Fong-cheng and PFP
Secretary-General Tsai Chung-hsiung that Chen agrees with Lien's and
Soong's demand for a recount, conducted by the judiciary system, of
the votes in the March 20 presidential election in which Lien, with
Soong as his running mate, was defeated by Chen by a slim margin.
</P>
<P>
Chiou said that Chen would also not take issue with the "pan-blue
alliance's demand for a panel formed under the Legislative Yuan to
investigate whether the government's decision to put the country's
armed forces and police on higher alert after Chen was shot on the
eve of polling day had deprived more military and police personnel of
their right to vote in the election than had previously been planned.
Lien and Soong believe those voters would have cast their ballots for
the "pan-blue alliance."
</P>
<P>
However, Chiou ruled out the possibility that Chen would agree
with the alliance's demand for an independent investigation by
presidential emergency decree into whether the shooting -- in which
Chen and his running mate, Vice President Annette Lu were slightly
injured -- was a political scheme designed to boost Chen's popularity
in the election.
</P>
<P>
Chiou did promise to convey to Chen the alliance's demand for a
special investigation team through a special act yet to be enacted,
if an emergency decree is out of the question.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Chen looks forward to meeting with Lien and
Soong, not only to exchange views with them on the disputes arising
from the election, but also on ways of improving unity among the
people, as well as on policy concerning mainland China and economic
affairs.
</P>
<P>
However, Tsai said Chen should first clear the questions
surrounding the election before seeking cooperation from the two
opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Lin claimed that the formation of a special investigation team
through a presidential emergency decree would be the best way to cut
the Gordian knot and that a special act would only be an alternative
choice or even a last resort.
</P>
<P>
Chiou said he was pleased with Monday's meeting, which he said
cleared up many speculations and rumors, even though no date was set
for a meeting of Chen, Lien and Soong.
</P>
<P>
Except for the last demand, Chiou said, the "pan-blue alliance"
can go ahead with its plan to pursue a recount through a court ruling
and set up a panel in the legislature to investigate the government's
response to Chen's shooting.
</P>
<P>
Lin and Tsai were not so optimistic, describing the outcome of
Monday's meeting as far from satisfactory and saying that unless the
president agrees with the formation of an independent investigation
team to look into the shooting, any meeting of the three leaders
would be meaningless.
</P>
<P>
They said they hope the president will respond to the demands in
a positive manner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
