<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040329.0016" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
COAST GUARD TO STEP UP PATROLS AS BLUEFIN TUNA FISHING SEASON BEGINS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Kaohsiung,  March 29 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Coast Guard Administration (CGA)
said Monday that it will step up patrols in the southern Taiwan
waters adjacent to the Philippines' 200-mile exclusive economic zone
as the bluefin tuna fishing season has begun.
</P>
<P>
Fishermen in the southern Pingtung area tend to focus on bluefin
tuna between March and June. For years, Taiwan fishing boats have
often been detained by Philippine authorities on the grounds that
they illegally intrude into the Philippines' economic zone.
</P>
<P>
The CGA called a meeting Monday to discuss measures to strengthen
the protection of Taiwan fishing boats operating in waters adjoining
Taiwan and the Philippines, where it was decided that the CGA will
send ships to patrol southern Taiwan waters twice a week between
March and June. During the off-season, the CGA usually patrols the
area twice per month.
</P>
<P>
A CGA official also urged crews of local fishing boats to produce
operation, navigation and communication logs, as well as charts and
all other legal documents, should they encounter Philippine coast
guard patrol ships.
</P>
<P>
Bluefin tuna, with its tender fatty flesh, has become a prized
delicacy in Taiwan in recent years and prime bluefin can fetch
NT$7,000 per kilogram. The "bluefin fever" in Taiwan has drawn the
attention of Philippine fishermen, who have also joined the chase for
the migratory fish, increasing the potential for conflict in the
overlapping area of the two countries' exclusive economic zones,
according to fishery sources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
