<HEADLINE>
NUMBER OF BAD CHECKS ISSUED DOWN IN FEBRUARY: CBC
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 29 (CNA)
(By Eric Liu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The number and value of bad checks in
February dropped from the January levels as a result of an active
stock market and rising market turnover, a spokesman for Taiwan's
Central Bank of China (CBC) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
More than 11.6 million checks with a total value of about
NT$2.179 trillion (US$65.04 billion) were drawn in February, 45,333
of which bounced, representing 0.39 percent of the total and a
combined value of about NT$9.7 billion -- a new low since 2000 --
according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The official attributed the decreases in the number and value of
bad checks to a continuing economic recovery at home, a booming stock
market and surging market turnover, all of which enabled enterprises
and individuals to monitor cash flow more efficiently.
</P>
