</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  29  (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Policial ripples from the March 20
presidential election continued to spread Monday, with lawmakers from
the two main opposition parties, the Kuomintang and the People First
Party, refusing en masse to attend a legislative session aimed at
discussing their demand for a revision of the President and Vice
President Election and Recall Law.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers from the ruling Democratic Progressive Party urged
Legislative Yuan President Wang Jin-pyng to persuade the KMT and PFP
lawmakers to raise themselves beyond the dispute over the
presidential election and attend to their jobs at the legislature.
</P>
<P>
Lee Chun-yi, the secretary of the DPP Caucus at the Legislative
Yuan, urged Wang -- who is a vice chairman of the KMT and the
presidential campaign manager of KMT Chairman Lien Chan -- to act as
a meditator between the two camps.
</P>
<P>
"Their absence from the legislature will neither help resolve the
presidential election dispute nor serve the national interests, " Lee
said.
</P>
<P>
The KMT and PFP lawmakers boycotted the legislative session in an
attempt to press the DPP into agreeing to their demand for a recount
of the votes in the March 20 election, in which President Chen
Shui-bian beat Lien by a wafer-thin margin.
</P>
<P>
Legislator Ker Chien-ming, DPP Convener at the Legislative Yuan,
also urged his KMT and PFP colleagues to stop spreading rumors and
speculation and allow the ripples from the presidential election to
settle.
</P>
<P>
He also urged Lien and his running-mate, PFP Chairman James
Soong, to put a planned meeting with Chen to good use by discussing
with him the issues of cooperation between the ruling and opposition
parties, finding ways to heal the rifts between different ethnic
groups after the election, economic development and constitutional
reform rather than simply airing their grievances against Chen.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the KMT-PFP "pan-blue alliance" has demanded that the
election be annulled by the judiciary, Ker urged Lien and Soong to
let justice run its course.
</P>
<P>
However their KMT colleague dismissed the DPP lawmakers, claiming
that they were trying to gloss over the dispute that it was an unfair
election.
</P>
<P>
Legislator Liao Feng-teh, secretary of the KMT Caucus at the
Legislative Yuan, said no talks with the DPP on cooperation in
legislative reforms are possible before the government gives in to
the "pan-blue alliance" demand for an immediate recount and a full
investigation into the shooting of President Chen one day before
polling day and the government's subsequent activation of the
national security mechanism.
</P>
<P>
He said his party was not pinning its hopes on the legislature to
revise the President and Vice President Election and Recall Law,
which would allow for a recount.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040329.0023" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
MOI TO CONSIDER RAISING REWARD FOR PRESIDENTIAL SHOOTING INFORMATION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 29 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Minister of the Interior Yu Cheng-hsien
said Monday that he might consider raising the reward for information
in the case of the shooting of President Chen Shui-bian one day prior
to the March 20 election to NT$100 million (US$3.02 million).
</P>
<P>
Yu made the remarks at an interior affairs committee meeting at
the Legislative Yuan. National Police Administrator Chang Su-liang
and Criminal Investigation Bureau (CIB) Commissioner Ho You-yi were
also on hand to give the first reports on the shooting since the
election, which saw Chen win re-election by a hair-thin margin of
29,518 votes out of 13 million votes cast against his rival Lien
Chan, the candidate of the "pan-blue alliance" of the Kuomintang
(KMT) and the People First Party (PFP).
</P>
<P>
Several KMT and PFP legislators raised questions about the
incident, which they believe played a role in the bitterly contested
election and changed the outcome in Chen's favor.
</P>
<P>
The legislators said that the "pan-blue alliance" has offered a
reward of NT$10 million and asked if the Ministry of the Interior
(MOI) will raise the reward from NT$3 million to NT$100 million.
</P>
<P>
Yu said that he would "consider the request but will have to
study it with the National Police Administration and other related
agencies."
</P>
<P>
Ho claimed that "this was a standard shooting incident and there
is absolutely no possibility of its having being faked."
</P>
<P>
Responding to the slow progress of the investigation so far, he
said the bureau has been unable to determine the exact location of
the attacker, because there are different ways to shoot and from
different positions.
</P>
<P>
He added that except for the jeep in which Chen was shot while
canvassing in his hometown of Tainan in southern Taiwan -- which has
been impounded by the Tainan Prosecutor's Office -- all related
evidence is still in the possession of the CIB.
</P>
<P>
Legislators also said that Tsai Chao-ming, head of the National
Security Bureau, and Chen Tsai-fu, head guard of the Presidential
Office, should take responsibility for the shooting,
</P>
<P>
The duo should be suspended from their duties and removed from
their posts pending the investigation, they said.
</P>
<P>
Legislator Liao Feng-teh, KMT party whip at the legislature,
noted that Tsai is a retired general, while Chen is on active service
in the military. According to the related regulations of military and
criminal law, they should not be safe from prosecution if they are
proved to have been negligent in their duty. Chen Tsai-fu was with
Chen and Vice President Annette Hu in the same open jeep when the
incident took place in the afternoon of March 19.
</P>
<P>
Huang Lei, deputy head of the National Security Bureau, said that
Tsai tendered his resignation one day after the shooting incident to
take political responsibility.
</P>
<P>
An appropriate punishment for other related personnel will have
to wait for the collection of more information before being decided,
Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, PFP legislators expressed concern about how many
military and police officers were unable to vote due to the
activation of a national security mechanism in the wake of the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Ministry of National Defense (MND) said that
only 37,855 servicemen were unable to return to their registered
domiciles to vote, but the legislators claimed that the figure was
far higher.
</P>
<P>
Hsieh Chang-chieh, PFP legislative whip, claimed that 200,000
military servicemen were unable to vote and asked the MND and the
National Police Administration to provide the correct figure.
</P>
</TEXT>
