<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040329.0024" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
LIEN, SOONG SHOULD PAY FOR LOSSES CAUSED BY WEEK-LONG PROTESTS: TSU
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 29 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The opposition Taiwan Solidarity Union
(TSU) said Monday that the defeated "pan-blue alliance" presidential
candidates should pay for losses caused by the alliance's week-long
post-election protests at the square in front of the Presidential
Office.
</P>
<P>
Legislator Chen Chien-ming, who concurrently serves as the TSU
legislative whip, said the 170-hour sit-in protests on Ketagalan
Boulevard in front of the Presidential Office have had a strong
adverse impact on national image, social order, economic development
and student rights.
</P>
<P>
"The defeated challenger, Kuomintang (KMT) Chairman Lien Chan,
and his running mate, People First Party (PFP) Chairman James Soong,
should compensate for the losses because they organized the grueling
marathon demonstration to protest against alleged unfairness in the
March 20 presidential election," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Lien lost the election to incumbent President Chen Shui-bian by a
razor-thin margin of 29,518 votes out of about 13 million ballots
cast. Lien and Soong then incited their supporters to demonstrate
non-stop at the Presidential Office square for eight days.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday afternoon, about half a million Lien-Soong
supporters thronged the streets surrounding the Presidential Office,
demanding a vote recount and an independent inquiry into a failed
election-eve assassination attempt against Chen, which the opposition
camp claimed gave Chen unfair sympathy votes that swayed the election
in his favor.
</P>
<P>
According to Legislator Chen, the Lien-Soong camp's massive
protests caused an estimated decrease of NT$1.6 trillion in the local
stock market capitalization and average losses of NT$200,000 for each
stock investor.
</P>
<P>
Worse still, he claimed, real estate deals have shrunk by 80
percent over the past week as compared with the pre-election records.
Real estate-related advertising also declined 60 percent, more than
10,000 police officers worked overtime and the demonstrators left
more than 20 tons of garbage in the vicinity of the Presidential
Office.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, demonstrators spoiled historic relics in the area,
including the Taipei Guest House and the Chingfu Gate. Last Friday, a
group of Lien-Soong supporters also stormed the Central Election
Commission in an attempt to prevent the commission from formally
announcing President Chen's re-election. Repairs of these buildings
will require a large sum of money," the legislator said.
</P>
<P>
The TSU, which supported President Chen in the bitterly fought
presidential race, has set up a special telephone line allowing those
who sustained losses during the Lien-Soong camp's post-election
demonstrations to file complaints.
</P>
<P>
"Would-be applicants are also welcome to file complaints by
e-mail to the TSU Internet Web site at lytsu@ly.gov.tw, " said Chen
Chien-ming. "The TSU will compile all applications and then seek
compensation from the "pan-blue alliance."
</P>
<P>
The "pan-blue alliance" rally in front of the Presidential Office
officially ended at 6 p.m. Saturday, but some demonstrators refused
to leave and had to be dispersed by riot police early Sunday. Some of
them then began a sit-in at the nearby Chiang Kai-shek (CKS) Memorial
Hall complex. They can legally stay there until April 3.
</P>
<P>
TSU Legislator Huang Chung-yuan urged the "pan-blue alliance"
leaders to lead their supporters away from the CKS Memorial Hall
complex and end all protest activities as soon as possible so that
calm can be restored to society and economic activities can proceed
normally.
</P>
</TEXT>
