<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040329.0025" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TRAFFIC CONTROLS AROUND PRESIDENTIAL OFFICE LIFTED
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 29 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Taipei City Government lifted traffic
controls around the Presidential Office in downtown Taipei Sunday at
midnight, with traffic returning to normal Monday.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of supporters of the "pan-blue alliance" had occupied
the square in front of the Presidential Office since March 20 to
protest against what they perceived as an "unfair" presidential
election, which saw President Chen Shui-bian win re-election by a
slim margin of 29,518 votes out of 13 million ballots cast against
Lien Chan, Kuomintang party chairman.
</P>
<P>
A mass protest rally was held Saturday to highlight their demands
for a recount of the votes and an independent investigation of the
shooting of President Chen and Vice President Annette Lu on election
eve, in which both were lightly injured, which the protestors believe
changed the outcome of the election in Chen's favor.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of the protestors remained in the square after the
permit for the demonstration expired at 6 p.m. A large police force,
mainly comprised of female police officers, persuaded some to move to
the nearby Chiang Kai-shek Memorial Hall early Sunday morning, and
carried others away who were less cooperative.
</P>
<P>
Police were told beforehand that they should refrain from using
sticks and water cannons and use only their hands.
</P>
<P>
Judging that the protestors would not return to the square in
front of the Presidential Office, the Taipei City Government
announced it was lifting traffic controls around the Presidential
Office starting from Sunday midnight.
</P>
<P>
But to protect the safety of President Chen, traffic controls
around his official residence, which lies about 100 meters away from
the Presidential Office, are still in effect.
</P>
</TEXT>
