<HEADLINE>
KMT URGED TO APOLOGIZE FOR VIOLENCE AT CKS MEMORIAL HALL COMPLEX
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  29 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The legislative caucus of the ruling
Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) asked the opposition Kuomintang
(KMT) Monday to make a public apology for violent incidents at the
Chiang Kai-shek (CKS) Memorial Hall complex in downtown Taipei.
</P>
<P>
The DPP caucus made the demand after a Soochow University student
and a woman were beaten Sunday at a so-called "Democracy Square" at
the CKS Memorial Hall complex where scores of supporters of the
"pan-blue alliance" of the KMT and the People First Party (PFP) were
staging a sit-in protest against alleged unfairness in the March 20
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
In a brief English speech delivered at the "Democracy Square, "
the Soochow University student asked the demonstrators not to make
too much noise to spoil the quiet in the nearby region. Soochow
University's downtown campus is located near the CKS Memorial Hall
complex. The woman delivered a brief speech in support of President
Chen Shui-bian's administration.
</P>
<P>
"It's ironic that the two victims were beaten simply because they
expressed different views at the 'Democracy Square, '" said DPP
legislative whip Tsai Huang-lang.
</P>
<P>
Since the KMT has "borrowed" the site for the sit-in, Tsai said,
the party should assume the responsibility for maintaining order and
should apologize to society for the incidents. "We hope no more
violence cases will happen at the site," he added.
</P>
<P>
President Chen narrowly defeated KMT Chairman Lien Chan in the
bitterly contested presidential election. Lien and his running mate,
PFP Chairman James Soong mobilized their supporters to demonstrate
non-stop at the Presidential Office square for eight days.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday afternoon, about half a million of Lien-Soong
supporters thronged the streets surrounding the Presidential Office,
demanding a vote recount and an independent inquiry into a failed
election-eve assassination attempt against Chen that the opposition
camp claimed had unfairly swayed sympathy votes Chen's way.
</P>
<P>
The "pan-blue alliance" rally in front of the Presidential Office
ended at 6 p.m. Saturday, but some demonstrators refused to leave the
site. They were dispersed by riot police early Sunday and some of
them then began a sit-in at the CKS Memorial Hall complex nearby.
</P>
</TEXT>
