<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040329.0034" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIPEI Z00 ORANGUTAN TRANSPORTED TO JAPAN FOR BREEDING PROGRAM
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 29 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A four-year-old female orangutan who was
born in Taipei City Zoo was ferried to Japan on Monday as part of a
breeding program underway at the Himeji City Zoo, according to Taipei
City Zoo officials.
</P>
<P>
This marked the first time that Japan has imported a primate
since the country banned all primate animal imports in 1999 in an
effort to prevent animal epidemic diseases.
</P>
<P>
"Hsiao-chen," born at Taipei City Zoo more than four years ago to
Indonesia-originating parents, is expected to join the Himeji City
Zoo in late April after undergoing a one-month quarantine at Japanese
customs, the zoo officials said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Himeji orangutan breeding program, "Hsiao-chen" is
expected to mate with a seven-year-old male orangutan named "Keli" --
who was brought to the zoo from Taipei City Zoo in exchange for a
young red panda in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Although "Hsiao-chen" and "Keli" are both originally from Taipei
City Zoo, it will be all right for them to have offspring together
because the pair are not related by blood, the zoo officials said.
</P>
<P>
According to Himeji City Zoo officials, the Japanese government
gave the green light to import of "Hsiao-chen" based on reproduction
considerations after the one and only female orangutan at the zoo
died of unknown causes in recent months.
</P>
<P>
In order to acquire "Hsiao-chen, " the Himeji City Zoo had
promised to give four black-foot penguins, six ring-tailed lemurs and
six ruffed lemurs to Taipei City Zoo. The four penguins arrived in
Taipei last July, while the six lemurs are expected to be delivered
this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
