<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040329.0042" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 29 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Monday, March 29, or the ninth
day of the leap second month of the Year of the Monkey according to
the lunar calendar. The following is a list of important events that
have occurred on this date in the past:

1788: Charles Wesley, British religious leader, dies at the age
of 81. He wrote thousands of hymns, including "Hark, the Herald
Angels Sing." His brother, John, founded Methodism in 1738.

1790: John Tyler, the 10th president of the United States, is
born. He succeeded to the presidency while serving as vice president
upon the death of incumbent William Henry Harrison.

1827: More than 10,000 mourners attend German composer Ludwig van
Beethoven's funeral in Vienna. Beethoven died on March 26 at the age
of 57.

1867: The British North America Act establishes the Dominion of
Canada, made up of the provinces of Quebec, Ontario, Nova Scotia and
New Brunswick.

1911: Revolutionists raid the Ching dynasty's Canton government
office. After fierce fighting, the rebels' attempt to overturn the
Ching dynasty fails. Seventy-two of them die and are later buried at
Huanghuakang, a knoll outside Canton. They later become known as "the
72 Revolutionary Martyrs of Huanghuakang."

1940: Wang Ching-wei establishes a puppet regime in Nanking,
eastern mainland China, which is recognized by Japan on Nov. 19.

1948: The Republic of China's first National Assembly under the
ROC Constitution opens with 1,631 delegates attending.

1959: Barthelemy Boganda, president of the Central African
Republic, is killed in a plane crash.

1965: The Republic of China's Foreign Ministry closes its
Commissioner's Office in Macao.

1969: The Republic of China's ruling Nationalist Party
(Kuomintang) holds its tenth national congress.

1973: U.S. troops pull out of South Vietnam.

1974: The U.S. spacecraft Mariner 10 takes the first close-up
pictures of Mercury.

1976: Dr. Robben W. Fleming, president of the University of
Michigan, arrives in Taipei for a six-day visit.

1976: Christian services are conducted in Taipei for Dr. Lin
Yu-tang, with President Yen Chia-kan and Premier Chiang Ching-kuo
attending.

1979: Uganda's dictator Idi Amin Dada is driven from Kampala, the
capital of the African country, and later hides in the interior. His
army is soon defeated by Tanzanian forces sent by President Julius
Nyerere to aid the Ugandan rebels.

1989: Soviet citizens give the thumbs down to the ruling
Communist Party in the first real political choice they have had
since the 1917 Revolution.

1989: French president Francois Mitterrand inaugurates the vast
glass pyramid, a work by Chinese-born American architect I.M. Pei, at
the entrance to the Louvre in Paris.

1993: Direct air service begins between the Republic of China and
the United Kingdom.

1993: Edouard Balladur, France's new conservative premier, takes
over for outgoing socialist Pierre Beregovoy.

1993: Murray McCully, New Zealand's Minister of Customs and
Associate Minister of Tourism, leads a nine-member delegation to
Taipei. He is the first New Zealand minister to visit Taipei since
1972.

1998: The U.S. Food and Drug Administration approves the
marketing of the anti-impotence drug Viagra.

1999: Joe Williams, legendary American jazz and blues singer,
dies at the age of 80.

2000: The Republic of China's first lady Tseng Wen-hui lodges a
lawsuit against Legislators Hsieh Chi-ta and Elmer Feng of the New
Party, and Tai Chi, a member of the Cabinet-level Overseas Chinese
Affairs Commission.

2000: Republic of China President Chen Shui-bian of the
Democratic Progressive Party names incumbent Defense Minister Tang
Fei of the Kuomintang as premier.

2001: Legislative caucus members of the opposition People First
Party lodge a lawsuit with the Taipei District Prosecutors Office
against Lo Fu-chu, an independent legislator, for assaulting PFP
lawmaker Diane Lee.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "If a man has put his personal
conduct in order, what difficulty should he find in governing a
country? But if a man has not put his personal conduct in order, how
can he put in order the people of a country?"
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040330.0001" type="multi" >
