<HEADLINE>
DPP RESERVED ON IDEA OF INVESTIGATION COMMITTEE AT LEGISLATURE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  30  (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A "pan-blue alliance" idea for the
formation of an investigation committee under the Legislative Yuan to
look into the March 19 shooting of President Chen Shui-bian could be
unconstitutional in two ways, ruling Democratic Progressive Party
(DPP) Secretary-General Chang Chun-hsiung said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting of the ruling party's Central Standing
Committee, Chang said authorizing the Legislative Yuan to investigate
criminal cases through special legislation, as demanded by the
Kuomintang (KMT) and People First Party (PFP), could encroach on the
power of the Control Yuan, which is the government's supreme
watchdog, and on the authority of the Ministry of Justice, which is
tasked with crime investigation.
</P>
<P>
Chang said he understands the depression of the KMT and PFP after
losing the presidential election by only a wafer-thin margin, but he
expressed reservations about their demand for a special investigation
committee in the Legislative Yuan on the grounds it could destroy the
delicate system of checks and balances between the different branches
of government.
</P>
<P>
The "pan-blue alliance" conveyed its demand to President Chen
Shui-bian a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
Chang said the president has yet to express an opinion on the
demand but added that an answer of "no" might be inevitable, since a
"yes" answer would ruin the country's hard-earned democracy.
</P>
<P>
Noting that KMT Chairman Lien Chan is clamoring for a entirely
new presidential election, Chang said he was surprised, since the
court has not yet ruled on Lien's demand for an annulment of the
election.
</P>
<P>
Lien and his running mate, PFP Chairman James Soong, also suggest
that the shooting of President Chen Shui-bian one day before polling
day was a political scheme designed to boost Chen 's popularity, and
have demanded -- via their party lawmakers -- an investigation into
the incident by the Legislative Yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
