<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040330.0011" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS ENCOURAGE MANUFACTURERS TO EXPLORE EUROPEAN MARKET
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  30  (CNA)
(By Luis Huang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ministry of Economic Affairs (MOEA)
officials suggested Tuesday that domestic manufacturers consider
investing in 10 Central and East European countries soon to be
admitted to the European Union (EU) , in order to make inroads into
the vast European market.
</P>
<P>
From May 1, the Czech Republic, Hungary, Poland, Slovakia,
Slovenia, Latvia, Lithuania, Estonia, Cyprus and Malta will be
formally integrated into the EU, the officials noted.
</P>
<P>
This will not only bring the EU's member states from the current
15 to 25 but will increase its total population to 370 million, its
gross domestic product (GDP) to US$10.4 trillion and its total trade
volume to US$4.8 trillion, thereby making it the world's largest
economic community, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the official noted, their entry is expected to bring
direct economic benefits worth 10 billion euros for current EU member
states.
</P>
<P>
As some of the newcomers, such as the Czech Republic, Hungary and
Poland, boast excellent industrial foundations, qualified labor
forces and lower wages, many manufacturers from advanced countries in
Western Europe have set up production lines in Central and East
Europe, the officials pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The officials further said that several multinational enterprises
seeking to globalize their operations, such as IBM and Motorola, have
also relocated their production lines from Western Europe to East
Europe, while several Taiwan-based companies, such as Hon Hai
Precision Industry Co., ASUSTek Computer Inc. and Acer Sertek
Incorporated have also carried out investment projects in the Czech
Republic, Hungary and Poland.
</P>
<P>
To facilitate their entry into the EU, the 10 countries are
working to improve their administrative efficiency and revise trade
laws, as well as to improve environmental protection, social order
and human rights, the officials explained, adding that now is a good
opportunity for domestic manufacturers to invest there.
</P>
<P>
According to the officials, customs duties for the 10 nations
will be lowered from the current 9 percent to 4 percent after their
accession into the EU.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
