<HEADLINE>
20 PERCENT OF TAIWAN FAMILIES TO OWN DIGITAL CAMERAS IN 2004
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 30 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
About 20 percent of Taiwan families are
expected to own a digital camera this year, up from 17 percent
recorded late last year, a domestic camera company sales manager said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a new product promotion, the Koda Taiwan sales
manager said that the penetration rate of digital cameras among
Taiwan families will increase to 20 percent in 2004, thanks to
product simplification that makes the devices easier to use.
</P>
<P>
According to the results of a survey conducted by GfK -- a United
States-based marketing research and customer satisfaction service --
the global market scale of digital cameras hit around 660,000 units
in 2003, with the figure likely to rise to 1.3 million for 2004, the
Koda executive said, adding that between 70 percent and 75 percent of
worldwide users are first-time users.
</P>
<P>
At present, 70 percent of the users are men, with the number of
female users growing fast, he noted, adding that 3 mega pixel and 4
mega pixel models are the most popular.
</P>
<P>
The digital camera ownership rate in the United States was around
30 percent as of the end of last year, with units priced at between
US$100 and US$700 being the best sellers. The top priority for 45
percent of U.S. consumers when buying a digital camera was
resolution, while 41 percent pointed to price as their primary choice
motivator.
</P>
</TEXT>
