<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040330.0028" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
ROC SEVERS DIPLOMATIC TIES WITH COMMONWEALTH OF DOMINICA
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 30 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Republic of China broke off diplomatic
relations with the tiny Caribbean island nation of the Commonwealth
of Dominica Tuesday, Minister of Foreign Affairs Eugene Chien
announced at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
"All of the ROC's financial aid programs for Dominica have also
been canceled," Chien said.
</P>
<P>
Chien's announcement came after Dominica forged formal ties with
mainland China.
</P>
<P>
Chien said he feels deep regret that mainland China has offered
huge financial aid to entice Dominica into switching diplomatic
recognition from Taipei to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
According to Chien, Dominica Prime Minister Roosevelt Skerrit had
requested US$58 million in various aid programs shortly after he
assumed office in January following Pierre Charles' abrupt death.
</P>
<P>
"Those demands far exceeded the existing cooperative programs
between our two countries and most of the programs had nothing to do
with Dominica's national development and people's livelihood, " Chien
said.
</P>
<P>
In the negotiation process, Chien said Skerrit had on many
occasions threatened to switch diplomatic allegiance to Beijing if
Taiwan failed to satisfy his demand. Ignoring the ROC's dissuasion,
Skerrit signed a joint communique with Beijing on the establishment
of diplomatic ties on March 23, Chien said.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that the ROC has no intention of competing with Beijing
in the "dollar diplomacy" game, Chien said mainland China's
diplomatic offensive against Taiwan will not help cross-Taiwan Strait
relations and will not gain the approval of Taiwan's 23 million
people. "This will only make cross-strait relations worse," he added.
</P>
<P>
With an ultimate aim to annihilate the ROC's existence, Chien
said, mainland China's diplomatic strategy has focused on luring away
all of the ROC's diplomatic allies and blocking the ROC's
participation in international organizations.
</P>
<P>
"Beijing should stop its diplomatic stranglehold against the ROC
because such moves only hurt the feelings of the people of Taiwan, "
Chien said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the government has adopted a pragmatic attitude
toward boosting external relations on the basis of reciprocity, Chien
said he hopes local people will support the government's decision to
cut ties with Dominica.
</P>
<P>
The ROC established diplomatic ties with Dominica in 1983. Over
the past 21 years, the ROC government has assisted Dominica in various
national development projects, including stationing a five-member
technical mission since 1985 to help the Caribbean country of 70,000
people develop agriculture and aquaculture.
</P>
<P>
Javier Ho, director of the Central and South American Affairs
Department under the Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MOFA), said the ROC
government will seek repayment of more than US$1 million in
outstanding loans to Dominica through legal procedures. "And we'll
evacuate our embassy in Dominica after completing all necessary
procedures," he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, MOFA spokesman Richard Shih said mainland
China used the period of Taiwan's presidential election to engage in
"dollar diplomacy" and suppressed the ROC's survival in the
international arena by luring away Dominica.
</P>
<P>
"We express our serious objections and condemnation," Shih said.
</P>
<P>
According to foreign wire service reports, mainland China
promised to offer more than US$100 million in aid to Dominica over
the next six years, beginning with US$11 million up front.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040330.0029" type="story" >
