<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN-MADE NOTEBOOK PCS TO HOLD 70 PERCENT OF WORLD OUTPUT IN 2004
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  30 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan's output of notebook personal
computers is expected to top 32 million units this year, grabbing a
dominating 70 percent of the entire world market of such increasingly
popular products, the non-profit Institute for Information Industry
(III) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Continuing to be the leading manufacturing country of notebook
PCs, Taiwan churned out more than 18 million units in 2002 and
substantially increased to 25 million units in 2003, said Chiang
Fang-yun, a chief product analyst of the III.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's notebook PC makers are expected to produce a record high
32 million units this year, with the output in the first quarter
exceeding seven million, Chiang forecast.
</P>
<P>
Chiang attributed the brisk growth of Taiwan's notebook PC
manufacturing industry to the increasing PC retirement and
replacement rate among businesses around the world; the rising trend
of replacing desktop PCs with notebooks among general users; and
additional orders placed by international big-name computer-makers
with Taiwan manufacturers on an OEM basis.
</P>
<P>
Despite increasingly severe competition from counterparts in
Japan and South Korea, Taiwan's notebook PC-makers have been
continuing to flourish because they have been able to win orders that
otherwise would go to Japan and South Korea by offering competitive
prices, Chiang noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
