<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040330.0034" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
DROUGHT IN SOUTHERN TAIWAN COULD MEAN MORE WATER RESTRICTIONS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 30 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Farmers in southern Taiwan are praying for
rain as dry days continue and the drought shows little sign of
subsiding, meaning that more water restrictions could be imposed in
the future, sources from the Water Resources Agency (WRA) said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
With water levels at major reservoirs in southern Taiwan falling
to record lows due to sparse rainfall, the WRA does not exclude the
possibility of imposing a new round of fallow plans for farmland and
rice paddies in the weeks to come, said WRA chief secretary Wu
Yueh-hsi.
</P>
<P>
Water conservation in the Tsengwen-Wushantou Reservoir, the
largest in Taiwan and the main source of water in the southern part
of the country, has dropped to some 72 million tons as of Monday
after months of dry weather, according reservoir officials.
</P>
<P>
The water level of the reservoir dropped to 172.66 meters
Tuesday, the third-lowest level recorded on the same day in the past
30 years, reservoir officials said.
</P>
<P>
Wu said the WRA imposed the first round of fallow plans for
farmland and rice paddies in southern Taiwan for this spring to save
water and allow households and industrial water users to enjoy normal
supplies. These condition are expected to hold until the end of May.
</P>
<P>
If the upcoming monsoon season does not bring enough rainfall to
southern Taiwan, Wu said, the WRA will soon start planning for a
second-phase fallow plan to be imposed in the second quarter of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Wu made the remarks during a national anti-drought task force
meeting sponsored by the Ministry of Economic Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, northern Taiwan as a whole has fared comparatively
better, with water in major reservoirs maintaining comfortable levels
as a result of continued wet weather, according to Wu.
</P>
<P>
The Feitsui Reservoir, the main water source in the greater
Taipei area, and the Shihmen Reservoir in neighboring Taoyuan County,
will have no problems meeting normal water-use needs of northern
Taiwan residents and users until the end of May, Wu noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040330.0035" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRICES UP ON TAIPEI STOCK MARKET
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 30 (CNA)
(By Eric Liu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Share prices ended the day higher on the
Taiwan Stock Exchange (TAIEX) Tuesday, with the weighted index, the
market's key barometer, moving up 20.60 points, to close at 6,494.71.
</P>
<P>
The bourse opened at 6,492.93 and fluctuated between 6,535.02 and
6,441.43 during trading.
</P>
<P>
A total of 6.17 billion shares changed hands on a market turnover
of NT$144.01 billion (US$4.3 billion), an increase from the previous
day's trading session which saw 4.79 billion stocks traded on a
market turnover of NT$112.43 billion (US$3.36 billion).
</P>
<P>
Seven of the eight major stock categories posted gains with
construction stocks moving up the most at 5.6 percent, followed by
foodstuff stocks at 3.1 percent, pulp and paper issues at 2.3
percent, textile issues at 1.6 percent, cement stocks at 1.1 percent,
bank and insurance shares at 0.8 percent, and plastics and chemical
shares at 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Only electrical shares moved down 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Gainers outnumbered losers 487 to 372, with 118 stocks remaining
unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
