<HEADLINE>
FEITSUI RESERVOIR BUREAU OPPOSES DRUG ADDICT FACILITY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 30 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Taipei City Government said Tuesday it
does not approve of the Ministry of Justice's (MOJ's) establishment
earlier this year of a detention center for drug addicts in the
vicinity of Feitsui Reservoir because of concerns about pollution.
</P>
<P>
Kang Shih-fang, director of the Feitsui Reservoir Administration
Bureau, said the number of drug inmates and staff at the drug
treatment center in Taipei County's mountainous Pinglin township is
expected to reach 1,200 in two years, or about one-fifth of Pinglin's
current population of 6,000. He added that by then, the center will
turn out more than 300 tons of waste water per day.
</P>
<P>
As the center is only one kilometer away from the Peishih Creek
in the upper stretch of Feitsui Reservoir, Kang said he is worried
that waste water from the drug treatment center might flow into the
Peishih Creek and eventually pollute water in Feitsui Reservoir.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Feitsui Reservoir is the main source of drinking
water for 4 million residents in the greater Taipei area, Kang said
the establishment of the Pinglin drug addict detention center
threatens the region's water supply safety.
</P>
<P>
"We think it's inappropriate to set up a drug center in the
reservoir's vicinity," Kang said, adding that the bureau will send a
letter to the central government expressing its opposition to the
facility.
</P>
<P>
Taipei City Government spokesman Wu Yu-sheng said the Pinglin
drug treatment center was originally a vocational training facility
under the now defunct Garrison Command. The facility had laid idle
for many years before it was turned into a drug treatment center
early this year. According to the current regulations, Wu said, an
environmental impact evaluation is needed for establishing such a
facility in the vicinity of Feitsui Reservoir.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
