<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040330.0040" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 30 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Tuesday, March 30, or the 10th
day of the leap second month of the Year of the Monkey according
to the lunar calendar. The following is a list of important events
that have occurred on this date in the past:

1746: Francesco Goya, Spanish court painter, is born. Over the
course of his career, his works grew increasingly gloomy, especially
those inspired by the French invasion of Spain.

1814: Britain and its allies march into Paris in triumph against
Napoleon Bonaparte.

1842: Ether is used as an anesthetic for the first time, by
American Surgeon Dr. Crawford Long.

1853: Vincent van Gogh, Dutch Post-Impressionist painter driven
by insanity to suicide, is born. He sold only one of his paintings
during his lifetime. "Sunflowers," one of his works, fetched a record
price of 24.75 million pounds (US$39.7 million) at auction in London
on March 30, 1987.

1855: The Taiping rebellion ends in China.

1856: The Crimean War, a bloody three-year conflict between
Europe and Russia, ends with today's signing of the Treaty of Paris.

1867: The United States acquires Alaska from Russia for US$7.2
million.

1870: The U.S. Congress adopts the 15th amendment to the
Constitution, stipulating that basic human rights cannot be denied on
the basis of race or color.

1936: The construction of Taipei's Sungshan Airport is completed.

1940: The Republic of China's Ministry of Foreign Affairs
declares the Nanking puppet regime, led by Wang Ching-wei, illegal.

1942: U.S. President Roosevelt announces establishment of the
Pacific War Council in Washington. The council comprises China, the
United States, the United Kingdom, New Zealand, Canada and the
Netherlands.

1955: In order to prevent mainland China from attacking Taiwan by
force, U.S. President Dwight D. Einsenhower announces that the United
States will assist in defending Kinmen and Matsu, two military
outposts of the Nationalist government located opposite mainland
China's Fujian province.

1972: Nicaraguan Foreign Minister Dr. Lorenzo Guerrero arrives in
Taipei for a five-day visit.

1973: The last U.S. prisoner of war is released and the last U.S.
soldier withdraws, ending the U.S. military's role in Vietnam.

1974: A mainland jetliner arrives in New York in what is
described as the first civilian flight from the Chinese mainland to
the United States.

1976: A 25-member mission of the Belgium-ROC Friendship Society
headed by the society's vice president, William Ugeux, arrives in
Taipei for an eight-day visit.

1976: Twenty-two Taiwan technicians leave for Saudi Arabia to
build a sewage system in Jiddah.

1976: The ROC Legislative Yuan passes the "Rehabilitation and
Protection Act" to help released convicts re-enter society.

1978: Taiwan's first nuclear power plant begins operation with a
capacity of 636,000 kilowatts.

1981: U.S. President Ronald Reagan is wounded in an assassination
attempt as he walks out of a Washington hotel. He is rushed to George
Washington Hospital, where a bullet, which passed inches from his
heart, is removed from his lung.

1990: Estonia's Parliament declares the Soviet Union an occupying
power and pledges to seek full independence.

1992: The United Nations starts its efforts to return nearly 3.37
million refugees to Cambodia.

1998: Russian leader Boris Yeltsin says he will not run in the
presidential election in 2000.

2000: Tse-chen Hsu, a 13-year-old genius pianist from Taiwan who
was born blind, receives the Rosemary Kennedy International Young
Soloists Award for 2000 at John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing
Arts in Washington D.C.

2000: U.S. President Bill Clinton reiterates his support for the
"one China policy" and stresses that differences between mainland
China and Taiwan must be resolved peacefully.

2001: The Association of World Citizens (AWC), a non-governmental
organization, formally inaugurates Friday its 11th World Citizen
Congress at Taipei's Grand Hotel, with representatives from domestic
and foreign civic groups attending the event.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "If I cannot find equitable and
reasonable men to have to do with, upon necessity I would choose men
of enthusiastic or even fanatical character. Enthusiastic men are
zealous and there are always limits which fanatical men would not
pass."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040331.0001" type="multi" >
