<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040331.0007" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT CHEN REAFFIRMS COMMITMENT TO CONSTITUTIONAL REFORM
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
London, March 30 (CNA)
(By N. K. Han and Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROC President Chen Shui-bian has
reaffirmed his commitment to constitutional reform during his
second four-year term.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with British Broadcasting Corp. (BBC), Chen also
reiterated that Taiwan is an independent sovereign state while
pledging to stabilize ties with mainland China.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to make continuous efforts to stabilizing
cross-Strait relations, eventually reaching peace across the
Taiwan Strait and stability and security in the Asia-Pacific
region," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
"Hopefully eventually we will become a peacemaker instead
of a troublemaker," said Chen.
</P>
<P>
He also told BBC that his plan to adopt a new constitution by
2008 is a timetable for Taiwan's democratic and constitutional
reforms.
</P>
<P>
"It is never a timetable for independence. If anyone who
regards this as a timetable for independence then it is a
serious misunderstanding and a serious distortion," the
president said.
</P>
<P>
Chen further said whether Taiwan will adopt a new constitution
will be decided by the people of Taiwan through a referendum. The
implementation of a new constitution has nothing to do with the
"independence or unification" issue and will not change Taiwan's
present status quo, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Chen held Taiwan's first-ever referendum alongside
the March 20 presidential election. Although the referendum on
beefing up missile defence failed because fewer than 50 percent of
voters participated, Chen said voters proved they wanted
an independent Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
"As we can see from the election this time, even the
opposition parties cannot oppose the mainstream value, the will
of the people, [who] oppose unification of the two sides and
insist on Taiwan being an independent sovereign country," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The majority of Taiwan people cannot accept Taiwan
becoming a second Hong Kong, nor can we accept Taiwan becoming
a local government of the People's Republic of China or a
Special Administrative Region of China," Chen added.
</P>
<P>
Chen won re-election with a narrow margin of 29,518 votes
out of some 13 million ballots cast. His sole contender, Kuomintang
Chairman Lien Chan has filed a tawsuit to the high court contesting
Chen's victory, saying an election-eve assassination attempt that
slightly wounded Chen had led to a swelling of sympathy votes.
Chen has given his consent to the high court for a complete vote
recount.
</P>
<P>
Chen told BBC he believed that the crisis stemming from the
election dispute would soon be over.
</P>
</TEXT>
