DPP TO DISCUSS AMENDING LEGISLATIVE NOMINATION RULES
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 31 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ruling Democratic Progressive Party
(DPP) said Wednesday it will hold an extraordinary party congress
April 10 to discuss partial amendments to its legislative election
nomination regulations.
</P>
<P>
"The proposed amendments are part of our preparations for the
year-end legislative election," said DPP Deputy Secretary-General Lee
Chin-yung.
</P>
<P>
The proposed amendments include authorizing the DPP chairman to
recommend several candidates for the overseas and aboriginal
representative seats for the approval by the party's Central
Executive Committee, Lee said, adding that the revisions are aimed at
enhancing representativeness of its nominees.
</P>
<P>
During a lunch meeting with party officials Tuesday, President
Chen Shui-bian, who concurrently serves as DPP chairman, said the DPP
should strive to win a majority in the new legislature to be elected
late this year to facilitate implementation of the party's ambitious
reform agenda.
</P>
<P>
During his first four-year term, Chen was unable to undertake his
major reform programs as the opposition-controlled Legislative Yuan
often stonewalled passage of relevant bills.
</P>
<P>
"Now that I have been re-elected, our next goal is to control a
majority of the seats in the legislature to facilitate implementation
of our reform agenda," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
According to the DPP's work schedule, it will decide on the
number of candidates to be nominated for each legislative
constituency. The party's nomination list will be unveiled in
mid-June in terms of the results of direct voting by party members as
well and the outcome of a series of public opinion surveys.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the DPP said it will organize a "thanksgiving party"
at Yuanshan No. 1 Park near the Grand Hotel in Taipei in the evening
of April 10 to mark the re-election of President Chen and Vice
President Annette Lu.
</P>
<P>
"The gala party is mainly aimed at expressing our heartfelt
gratitude for the electorate's support in the fiercely fought
presidential election, " said Cheng Wen-tsan, deputy director of the
DPP's publicity department.
</P>
<P>
"We'll arrange more musical programs to replace political
speeches in the party as we hope the event can help defuse the
confrontational atmosphere resulting from the fiery, bruising
election campaign," Cheng said.
</P>
<P>
President Chen narrowly defeated his sole challenger, Kuomintang
Chairman Lien Chan, by a razor-thin margin of 29,518 ballots out of
some 13 million cast in the March 20 presidential election. Lien
contested the outcome and filed a lawsuit earlier this week for an
annulment of the election on the grounds that the election-eve
shooting of Chen unfairly swayed sympathy votes for him. Both Chen
and Lu were slightly injured in the March 19 assassination attempt on
them while campaigning in the southern city of Tainan.
</P>
</TEXT>
