<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040331.0013" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAICHUNG MAYOR PROMISES TO PUSH FOR DIRECT FLIGHTS WITH HK, OKINAWA
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taichung,  March  31  (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taichung Mayor Jason Hu promised
Wednesday to promote direct flights between Taichung and Hong Kong
and Okinawa as well as direct charter flights with Xiamen and Shantou
in mainland China.
</P>
<P>
Hu made the promise in response to a call made by a group of
local business leaders, including Lai Cheng-i, chairman of the
Taichung Chamber of Commerce, during a meeting at the Taichung City
government headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Pledging that he will relay the idea to the Cabinet-level Council
for Economic Planning and Development (CEPD) , Hu said that direct
flights will not only make the homecoming of the more than 50,000
mainland-based businessmen from central Taiwan easier, but it will
also give a boost to Taichung's tourism and make the city more
cosmopolitan.
</P>
<P>
Hu said that he will propose the CEPD allow direct flights
between Taichung's Chingchuankang Airport and Hong Kong and Okinawa
from July and charter flights linking destinations in mainland China,
such as Xiamen in Fujian province and Shantou in Guangdong province,
during the next Chinese new year holiday season.
</P>
<P>
According to Lai, China Airlines -- the Taiwan's largest carrier
-- has contacted him to assess the feasibility of opening direct
flights on the Taichung-Hong Kong and the Taichung-Okinawa routes as
more than half of the passengers on board CAL flights from Taiwan to
Hong Kong are businessmen from central areas.
</P>
<P>
Lai also suggested Hu invite the chiefs from neighboring cities
and counties to work jointly toward the aim.
</P>
</TEXT>
