<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040331.0014" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN BUSINESSMEN URGED NOT TO TRAVEL TO IVORY COAST
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  31 (CNA)
(By Eric Liu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Board of Foreign Trade under the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs is urging Taiwan businessmen not to
travel to Ivory Coast Wednesday, citing the volatile political
condition there.
</P>
<P>
Ever since a coup attempt in September 2002, Ivory Coast has
continued to be socially unstable, an official with the Board of
Foreign Trade said, adding that the bloody clashes between government
soldiers and the opponents of government in the capital, Abidjan, has
prompted the opposition party to launch a series of peace parades
which has caused concerns from countries such as the U.S., Canada,
England, France, Switzerland. They have called on their nationals to
refrain from traveling to Ivory Coast.
</P>
<P>
Ivory Coast used to be one of Taiwan's most important trading
partners, the official said, but bilateral trade has been sharply
impacted by the unstable situation, with trade falling from US$44.68
million in 2002 to US$19.10 million in 2003, out of which the imports
from Ivory Coast has dropped from US$26.08 million to US$8.48
million.
</P>
<P>
According to the representative office there, the official
continued, the turmoil in Ivory Coast won't be settled in the near
future, adding that to prevent their lives from being threatened, he
urged businessmen not to travel to Ivory Coast for now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
