<HEADLINE>
CHIEF OF NATIONAL SECURITY BUREAU RESIGNS OVER SHOOTING OF PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 31 (CNA)
(By Maubo Chang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tsai Chao-ming, director of the National
Security Bureau, resigned Wednesday to take responsibility for the
March 19 shooting of President Chen Shui-bian, according to a
statement issued by the Office of the President.
</P>
<P>
He will be replaced by General Hsueh Shih-ming, who is the
commander-in-chief of the Reserve Command under the Ministry of
National Defense, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Tsai, whose job including the security of the head of the state,
had hinted at a news conference the same day after Chen suffered
injury to his abdomen in a failed assassination attempt in Tainan,
southern Taiwan, that he would bear the full responsibility for
failing to protect the president.
</P>
</TEXT>
