<HEADLINE>
MARITIME AFFAIRS COMMISSION SET UP
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 31 (CNA)
(By Eric Liu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Premier Yu Shyi-kun presided Wednesday
over the first meeting of a commission for maritime affairs that will
be an integrated platform for the government, industry and academia
to lay down the country's maritime policy and will set out a program
within the next six months for the short-, medium- and long-term
development of the country's maritime affairs.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan is a typical island country and short of abundant minerals
and resources, making maritime affairs key to national survival, Yu
said, adding that maritime policies are needed to maintain harmony
with other countries and to protect the national interest.
</P>
<P>
The maritime commission will continue its work until such time as
a ministry of maritime affairs is established, Yu added.
</P>
</TEXT>
