<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040331.0017" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN REPRESENTATIVE HOPES FOR STRONGER TIES WITH U.S.
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Washington,  March 30 (CNA)
(By Lin Wen-chi and Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan's representative to the United
States expressed hope Monday that bilateral relations between Taiwan
and the United States will grow even stronger.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a party held at the U.S. Congress to celebrate the
25th anniversary of the promulgation of the Taiwan Relations Act
(TRA), Chen Chien-jen said that the decision of former President
Jimmy Carter a quarter of century ago to sever diplomatic ties with
the Republic of China was a "shocking one."
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, Congress then formulated the TRA, Chen noted, which
he said has not only maintained U.S. interests and bilateral
relations but also stability in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
It has also helped produce a good environment for the development
of Taiwan's economy and society, which has helped it move forward on
the path of freedom and democracy.
</P>
<P>
Chen conveyed his heartfelt appreciation for the United States
and said he hopes bilateral relations will be further upgraded based
on the existing solid basis.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the United States has helped in Taiwan's bids to
join international organizations such as the Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) forum and the World Trade Organization (WTO), and
he expressed hope that Taiwan can soon join the World Health
Organization as an observer, again with the assistance of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The United States severed diplomatic ties with the Republic of
China in January 1979 and Congress passed the TRA March 29 of the
same year. It was signed into law April 10 by Carter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040331.0018" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
DR. HENRY LEE TO ARRIVE APRIL 13 TO HELP IN PROBE OF SHOOTING
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,   March  31  (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dr. Henry Lee, a world-renowned
Chinese-American forensic scientist, will arrive in Taipei April 13
to assist in the investigation into an assassination attempt on
President Chen Shui-bian March 19, the nation's top prosecutor said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting of the Legislative Yuan's Judicial Affairs
Committee, State Public Prosecutor-General Lu Ren-fa said he has
invited Lee to examine evidence in the election-eve shooting of
President Chen and Vice President Annette Lu.
</P>
<P>
"I had hoped that Dr. Lee could come to Taiwan as soon as
possible. Because of his busy schedule, however, Lee cannot arrive
until the evening of April 13. He is scheduled to leave Taipei April
15," Lu Ren-fa told lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Lee would be able to produce a definitive report on
the shooting before his departure, Lu Ren-fa said he must respect
Lee's opinion. "I cannot give him a timetable."
</P>
<P>
The president and vice president were both slightly wounded by
two bullets from what is believed to have been a homemade gun as they
campaigned in the southern city of Tainan March 19. After they won
re-election by a razor-thin margin of 29,518 votes out of the more
than 13 million ballots cast in the following day's election, the
defeated contending ticket of Kuomintang (KMT) Chairman Lien Chan
and People First Party Chairman James Soong contested the outcome
and filed a lawsuit for an annulment of the election on the grounds
that the shooting unfairly swayed sympathy votes for the Chen-Lu
team.
</P>
<P>
Lu Ren-fa said if necessary, Lee has agreed to testify to the
case in the Taiwan High Court, which is screening Lien's election
annulment suit.
</P>
<P>
Responding to independent Legislator Su Ying-kuei's suggestion
that an independent prosecutor be appointed to investigate the
shooting, Lu Ren-fa said such a move would deal a severe blow to
Taiwan's prosecutorial system.
</P>
<P>
"The United States scrapped its special prosecutor system last
year after it found flaws in the system. For years, I have been
opposed to the introduction of a special prosecutor system for
Taiwan," Lu Ren-fa said.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed opposition to the KMT proposal that a special
investigative committee be created under the Legislative Yuan through
special legislation to look into the election-eve shooting.
</P>
<P>
"If the proposal were adopted, it would seriously hurt our
prosecutorial system," Lu Ren-fa stressed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Judicial Yuan said Wednesday that if the high
court decide to recount all ballots cast in the March 20 presidential
poll, it will offer all necessary administrative support.
</P>
<P>
The Lien-Soong ticket has demanded a complete vote recount and
President Chen and Vice President Lu have presented a letter of
consent to the high court. With their consent, the plaintiffs need
not present any evidence of irregularities to justify their demand
for a judicial recount.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday evening, the high court announced it will hold the
first hearing on the unprecedented presidential election lawsuit this
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Whether or not to recount, how to recount, and the extent
of a recount is something that the tribunal needs to consult
with the two sides about," Taiwan High Court spokesman Wen Yao-yuan
said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
"What we will do on April 2 is to understand the situation
on both sides," Wen said.
</P>
<P>
There was no word on when the judges could reach a decision
and when a recount might begin, if one was ordered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040331.0019" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC PROCESSING ZONES WELCOME INVESTORS: EPZA
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,   March   31   (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Economic Processing Zone
Administration (EPZA) under the Ministry of Economic Affairs has
extended a welcome to both traditional and hi-tech businesses to
invest in the country's economic processing zones (EPZs).
</P>
<P>
According to an investigation made by the administration, there
are about 130 hectares of vacant land scattered around the country's
EPZs, such as the Kaohsiung Economic Processing Zone and the Nantze
Economic Processing Zone, an EPZA spokesman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Companies from various sectors are welcome to open up shop at the
EPZs, which are focusing on a shift from traditional labor-intensive
and manufacturing facilities to value-added and diversified compounds
and are keen on luring investors from the foreign trade,
telecommunications, warehousing and service-oriented industries, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Compared with launching investments in Taiwan's hi-tech
industrial parks -- which require a higher investment threshold -- it
is easier to set up strongholds in EPZs, the spokesman said. In
addition, companies investing in EPZs are subject to different
standards as part of the administration's efforts to pursue
diversification and create more job opportunities for local
residents, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Nine EPZ investment projects, mainly from the hi-tech and
value-added industries, were approved in the first two months of this
year, with their combined value amounting to NT$ 1.45 billion. There
were six additional capital increment plans worth a total of NT$4.2
billion (about US$126 million) during the two-month period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
