<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN DIRECT INVESTMENT IN TAIWAN UNAFFECTED: MOEA OFFICIAL
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 31 (CNA)
(By Flor Wang)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Foreign direct investment in Taiwan has
not been affected by the current dispute over the March 20
presidential election, a government official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chu Ta-wen, director-general of the Industrial Development and
Investment Center under the Ministry of Economic Affairs,
acknowledged that the mass protest staged last Saturday by the
opposition camp has stirred up grave concern among foreign investors
with operations in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
But Chu claimed that foreign direct investment willingness has
not been noticeably undermined now that the demonstrations, which
prompted about 500,000 people to take to the streets in Taipei, have
ended smoothly. Short-term political instability is not expected to
have a major impact on foreign investment projects at home, which are
usually launched only after long-term assessment, he noted.
</P>
<P>
For instance, he went on, construction of a plant by Japan's Hoya
Corporation in the fourth compound of the Hsinchu Science-based
Industrial Park will kick off April 2 as scheduled, while mass
production is slated to begin by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Hoya, Chu said, another 13 multinational enterprises
have invested in Taiwan this year, including heavy hitters such as
Alcatel and DuPont. Meanwhile, there are an additional 26 promised
investment plans by other foreign investors, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
