<HEADLINE>
U.S. HOUSE MAJORITY LEADER WELCOMES VISIT BY ROC PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Washington, March 30 (CNA)
(By Jay Chen and Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
U.S. House Majority Leader Tom DeLay
(R-TX) said Tuesday that he would welcome President Chen Shui-bian
should he make another visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
DeLay made the remarks while attending a party to mark the 25th
anniversary of the Taiwan Relations Act, the U.S. legislation that
has governed relations between the United States and Taiwan since the
two countries severed diplomatic ties in 1979.
</P>
<P>
DeLay said that he expects bilateral relations will be further
strengthened during Chen's second term.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he would support a visit by Chen to Washington,
D.C. during his second term, DeLay said: "Absolutely. I hosted
President Chen in Houston and we had a very good time and created a
personal relationship during that visit. So anytime the president
wants to come, I'm very supportive, even to Washington."
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he has talked to the White House about this in
light of the fact that the Bush administration seems to have a
different view on the issue, DeLay said that he has always talked to
the White House about Taiwan and about Taiwan-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
Turning to his views on Chen's plan to introduce a new
constitution, DeLay said that is a decision for the Taiwan people.
"That's not something that the U.S. should dictate or even
comment on. That's part of freedom. If they want to have a different
constitution, that's their right to do so."
</P>
<P>
On the March 20 presidential election, he said that the message
sent to the whole world is that democracy and freedom is flourishing
in Taiwan and that the whole world should be very happy about that.
</P>
<P>
"Whenever we can find freedom and have it blossom, it's very good
for everyone in all parts of the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to DeLay, nearly 20 U.S. senators and congressmen
also attended the party, during which they said they attach great
importance to the TRA.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist (R-TN) said that the
TRA helps maintain close relations between the American and
Taiwanese people and provides a solid basis for bilateral exchanges
in business and other relations.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the election, he noted that the Central Election
Commission has announced that Chen won re-election. Although the
dispute over the election is not yet over, the high turnout rate of
80.2 percent at the polls proves the Taiwan people's genuine love for
democracy.
</P>
<P>
He said that the United States has weathered many crises during
its democratic process and that he believes it will be the same for
Taiwan, although the future is bright for both countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040331.0026" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
BEIJING HOLDS THE KEY TO RECONCILIATION: MAC OFFICIALS
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March 31 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing holds the key to whether the two
sides of the Taiwan Strait can appoint representatives from each side
in efforts to seek peace and stability across the strait, a Mainland
Affairs Council (MAC) official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In view of President Chen Shui-bian's recent calls for both sides
to seriously consider engaging in negotiations through formally
authorized representatives as soon as possible, Jan Jyh-horng,
director of the MAC's Department of Research and Planning, said that
although Taiwan is willing to do so immediately, it will still
require willingness from both sides before any cross-strait consensus
on the matter can be reached.
</P>
<P>
Jan quoted MAC Chairwoman Tsai Ing-wen as having said recently
that for benign interaction across the strait, there must be a
marriage of "a subjective intention and an objective climate."
"Formal cross-strait interaction in a spirit of goodwill will be
impossible if either of these two conditions are absent, " Tsai was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Jan stressed the importance of delegating representatives from
both sides, saying that only through such officially authorized
representatives can the two sides communicate sufficiently and avoid
misunderstandings.
</P>
<P>
He said the mainland Chinese authorities have become increasingly
confident in China's economic reforms and growth and he expressed
hope that the Beijing leadership will also become confident in
China's internal reforms and cross-strait relations so as to benefit
the creation of an easier environment for better cross-strait
interaction.
</P>
<P>
In his first news conference with members of the media from home
and abroad this year held Feb. 3 to promote the March 20 referendum,
Chen called for a cross-strait agreement to serve as the basis for
future cooperation and the maintenance of peace and stability in the
Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
"With the concrete, common goal of seeking peace and stability,
we must seriously consider engaging in negotiations through formally
authorized representatives from both sides as early as possible, "
Chen said.
</P>
<P>
"After March 20, " the president went on, "we will invite
mainland China to appoint a special envoy to meet and work with our
special envoy towards the initiation of cross-strait negotiation, in
light of 'one principle and four major issue areas.'"
</P>
<P>
The "one principle" is the establishment of the principle of
peace, Chen said, adding that in order to establish joint
responsibility for maintaining peace and the consensus for
cooperation, both sides must recognize that maintaining peace in the
Taiwan Strait is the joint responsibility of both parties and should,
therefore, necessitate working together.
</P>
<P>
The "four issue areas, " meanwhile, are: the establishment of a
negotiation mechanism; exchanges based on equality and reciprocity;
the establishment of a political relationship; and the prevention of
military conflicts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040331.0027" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT RAISES REWARD TO NT$50 MILLION FOR SHOOTING INFORMATION
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 31 (CNA)
(By Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Premier Yu Shyi-kun said Wednesday that he
has agreed that the Ministry of the Interior should increase the
reward for information leading to the capture of the assailant or
assailants of President Chen Shui-bian and Vice President Annette Lu
to NT$50 million (US$0.66 million).
</P>
<P>
If the Ministry of the Interior does not have sufficient budget
to pay the reward -- which was increased from NT$12 million -- the
Executive Yuan will use the Second Reserve Fund to make up the
balance, Yu said.
</P>
<P>
The election-eve assassination attempt occurred in the southern
city of Tainan March 19 while Chen and Lu were riding in an
open-topped jeep on a street lined with supporters. Both Chen and Lu
were slightly injured when a gunman or gunmen is believed to have
taken advantage of the roar of firecrackers and the excitement of the
crowds to fire two shots at the president.
</P>
<P>
According to Kuo Chen-ni, a Tainan city prosecutor presiding over
the investigation into the assassination attempt, her office has
collected a total of 96 items of information and possible evidence
over the past week. Of the total, 89 have been ruled out as evidence,
while the remaining seven will continue to be studied by the Tainan
District Prosecutors' Office, she added.
</P>
<P>
Chen's opponent in the election, Kuomintang Chairman Lien Chan,
lost to Chen by a razor-thin margin of 29,518 votes, or 0.228 percent
of the more-than 13 million ballots cast nationwide. In the days
following the election, Lien said many questions still surround the
shooting and demanded an independent investigation into the incident.
</P>
<P>
In the afternoon of March 27, about 500,000 of Lien's supporters
thronged the streets surrounding the Presidential Office, demanding a
vote recount and an independent inquiry into the shooting, which the
opposition camp claims unfairly swayed sympathy votes in Chen's
favor.
</P>
<P>
Three U.S. crime experts, traveling on behalf of world-renowned
forensic expert Dr. Henry Lee, arrived in Taiwan Monday to help
investigate the shooting.
</P>
<P>
In related news, Central Election Commission Chairman Huang
Shih-cheng said Wednesday that if a judicial vote recount is
conducted, the recount should be first filed in a lawsuit at the
Taiwan High Court and the costs of the recount and related affairs
should be footed by the side that loses the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the President and Vice President Election and
Recall Law, costs should be decided by the court that receives the
lawsuit, Huang added.
</P>
</TEXT>
