<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040331.0030" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
PREMIER DISMISSES REPORTS OF IMMEDIATE CABINET RESHUFFLE
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei,  March  31 (CNA)
(By Lilian Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Premier Yu Shyi-kun denied Wednesday
reports that there has been a decision made to reshuffle the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The premier was responding to reports by the mass-circulation
China Times that after the Cabinet resigns en masse in April,
President Chen Shui-bian is sure to retain Yu and only undertake a
partial reshuffle of the Cabinet. The paper had claimed that the
interior, education and economic affairs ministers are about to be
replaced and that the number of Cabinet spokesmen will be increased
to two.
</P>
<P>
"The reports are a far cry from the truth," the premier said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Cabinet will resign en masse according to
established constitutional practice before a new president is sworn
in May 20, but said he is "not in a position to talk about Cabinet
changes at the moment."
</P>
<P>
Yu said that he was surprised by the reports, adding that during
the week-long period of protests and disputes over the result of the
March 20 election -- which Chen won by a razor-thin margin of 29,518
votes -- he did not have a chance to discuss with the president the
issue of the make-up of the new Cabinet or even to report to him on
the matter.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that people outside the loop will not
speculate and said he called the interior, education and economic
affairs Wednesday to ask them not to "lose confidence" when
questioned by the media and not to give misleading information.
</P>
<P>
As to whether he will retain the post of premier, Yu said he must
respect the president's authority on the matter, pointing out that
the president has his own considerations and plans for the next four
years.
</P>
<P>
Lin Chia-lung, spokesman of the Executive Yuan, said that Yu's
Cabinet will resign en masse in due time and that all Cabinet members
will stay in their posts until then.
</P>
<P>
It would be premature to speculate on any new Cabinet lineup, he
added.
</P>
<P>
On whether the number of Cabinet spokesman will be increased, Lin
said that this must be a "creation of the media, " adding that in
theory, the fewer spokesman the better, in order to keep
communication problems to a minimum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
