<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040331.0032" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
CONTROL YUAN TO PROBE MALFEASANCE IN ELECTION-EVE SHOOTING
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 31 (CNA)
(By Sofia Wu)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Control Yuan President Fredrick Chien said
Wednesday that the nation's supreme watchdog body has formed a panel
to probe whether there has been any administrative malfeasance in the
March 19 shooting of President Chen Shui-bian.
</P>
<P>
The three-member panel will investigate any possible misconduct
or negligence on the part of national security units in protecting
the safety of the head of state, Chien said.
</P>
<P>
The panel will also look into whether there was any wrongdoing in
activating the national security mechanism after Chen and Vice
President Annette Lu were shot on the campaign trail on the eve of
the bitterly fought March 20 presidential election, Chien added.
</P>
<P>
As to a proposal initiated by the opposition camp that
legislation be enacted to allow for the formation of an investigative
committee under the Legislative Yuan to probe the assassination
attempt, as well as the incident's impact on the presidential
election outcome, Chien said the Control Yuan is the most appropriate
body to organize a panel to carry out such work.
</P>
<P>
According to the Constitution, the Control Yuan is the supreme
supervisory organization, exercising the powers of impeachment,
censure and audit.
</P>
<P>
Chien said the Control Yuan panel will investigate the
administrative branch's handling of the shooting in a rational and
impartial manner.
</P>
<P>
As for the case's criminal investigation, Chien said, law
enforcement authorities will be in charge. "The Control Yuan is not
in a position to handle criminal investigations," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Control Yuan investigative panel is composed of three members
-- Huang Wu-tsu, Chao Jung-yao and Chen Chin-li. Chao said the panel
will investigate possible malfeasance of the National Security
Bureau's special service center, which is responsible for the head of
state's safety.
</P>
<P>
A Control Yuan member who spoke on condition of anonymity said
the controversy surrounding the activation of the national security
mechanism will also be probed.
</P>
<P>
The proposal for legislation to legalize the formation of a
Legislative Yuan investigative committee to probe the shooting was
brought up by the opposition "pan-blue alliance" of the Kuomintang
(KMT) and the People First Party (PFP) during a meeting with
Presidential Office Secretary-General Chiou I-jen a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
KMT Secretary-General Lin Feng-cheng and PFP Secretary-General
Tsai Chung-hsiung came up with the proposal during their meeting with
Chiou to hammer out an agenda for a planned meeting of President
Chen, KMT Chairman Lien Chan and PFP Chairman James Soong.
</P>
<P>
Chen and Lu were both slightly wounded by two bullets from what
is believed to have been a homemade gun as they campaigned in the
southern city of Tainan March 19. After they won re-election by a
razor-thin margin of 29,518 votes out of the 13 million ballots cast
in the following day's election, the defeated Lien-Soong ticket
contested the outcome and filed a lawsuit for an annulment of the
election on the grounds that the shooting unfairly swayed sympathy
votes for Chen.
</P>
<P>
Chen has yet to express his opinion about the "pan-blue alliance"
proposal and KMT Secretary-General Lin said Wednesday that the
"pan-blue alliance" is waiting for his response. In his view, Lin
said, if Chen rejects the proposal, then the proposed Chen-Lien-Soong
meeting would be meaningless.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP)
Secretary-General Chang Chun-hsiung said that authorizing the
Legislative Yuan to investigate a criminal case like the March 19
shooting through special legislation could be unconstitutional in two
ways -- encroaching on the power of the Control Yuan and on the
authority of the Ministry of Justice, which is tasked with crime
investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
