<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040331.0038" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TRANS ASIA, XIAMEN AIRLINES TIE KNOT ON CROSS-STRAIT PACKAGES
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Xiamen,  March  31 (CNA)
(By K.Y. Ni and Deborah Kuo)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taiwan-based Trans Asia Airways and
mainland China's Xiamen Airlines tied a cooperative knot Wednesday to
jointly offer convenient cross-strait travel packages mainly
targeting mainland-based Taiwan businesspeople.
</P>
<P>
The cross-strait travel packages, based on the extended "mini
three links" framework, feature two-way airline services among
Taipei, Kaohsiung, Kinmen, Xiamen and Macau and from those cities to
50 other destinations around the world.
</P>
<P>
Trans Asia President Sun Hung-hsiang and Xiamen Airlines
President Wu Rongnan signed the cooperation agreement on behalf of
their respective companies at a ceremony held at the Xiamen Airlines
Jinyan Hotel in downtown Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
The convenient cross-strait travel packages plan is aimed at
upgrading the southern Chinese coastal city of Xiamen to the third
major transit center behind Hong Kong and Macau for mainland-based
Taiwanese businesspeople, believed to number at least 800,000, Wu
said.
</P>
<P>
The Republic of China's Cabinet-level Mainland Affairs Council
(MAC) took the initiative to open the "mini three links" on Jan. 2,
2001, to allow direct trade, postal and shipping links between the
ROC outlying islands of Kinmen and Matsu and the mainland Chinese
port cities of Xiamen and Fuzhou in Fujian Province to help
facilitate bilateral exchanges between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The MAC extended and expanded the "mini three links" program
March 1 of this year to allow Taiwanese businesspeople from other
mainland Chinese cities beyond Fujian Province to travel between
Taiwan and mainland China via the "mini three links" channel.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen Airlines is rated as one of the best airlines in mainland
China, winning the prestigious "Golden Goose Cup" over the past three
consecutive years, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
According to Sun, an average of 12,000 people traveled across the
Taiwan Strait via the "mini three links" channel each month last
year. Of the total, about 80 percent were Taiwanese businesspeople.
</P>
<P>
The total number of trips by Taiwanese businesspeople, their
dependents and elderly mainland-originating ROC military veterans to
and from mainland China via the "mini three links" channel will
definitely grow by leaps and bounds following the expansion of the
"mini three links" program, Sun said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he noted, after the mainland authorities give the
green light to Fujian residents to travel to Kinmen for tourism --
expectedly by the beginning of next month -- more people from the
mainland will also likely take advantage of the Trans Asia-Xiamen
Airlines cross-strait travel packages for tours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
