<DOC id="CNA_ENG_20040331.0041" type="multi" >
<HEADLINE>
TODAY IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
Taipei, March 31 (CNA)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Today is Wednesday, March 31, or the 11th
day of the leap second month of the Year of the Monkey according to
the lunar calendar. Following is a list of important events that have
occurred on this date in the past:

1596: Rene Descartes, French philosopher, mathematician, and
inventor of the technique of methodical doubt, is born.

1854: The U.S. Navy and Japan's shogunate sign the first
U.S.-Japanese treaty. Under the treaty, Japan agrees to open two
ports to U.S. traders, marking the end of more than 200 years of
isolation from the outside world.

1858: China's Ching court capitulates to British and French
demands for trade concessions.

1889: The Eiffel Tower is opened in Paris by France's premier.

1901: Gottlieb Daimler, German inventor, names his latest 53 mph,
four-cylinder creation after his daughter, Mercedes.

1917: The United States acquires the Virgin Islands from Denmark.

1918: Daylight savings time goes into effect throughout the
United States for the first time.

1927: Ching dynasty political reformer Kang Yu-wei dies at the
age of 70.

1941: Germany launches a counter-offensive against the Allies in
North Africa.

1947: The Nationalist government of the Republic of China
promulgates laws governing the organization of the National Assembly;
the organization of the five branches of the central government; the
election and recall of deputies of the National Assembly; the
election and recall of the president and vice president of the
republic; the election and recall of legislators; and the election
and recall of members of the Control Yuan.

1948: The U.S. Congress adopts the Marshall Aid Pact for Europe's
post-war recovery.

1959: The Dalai Lama, the ruler and spiritual leader of Tibet,
flees to safety in India after Chinese communist military occupation
of Tibet makes his position in the Tibetan capital of Lhasa
impossible.

1968: President Lyndon Johnson of the United States announces he
will not stand for re-election.

1971: Chow Shu-kai, ROC ambassador to the United States, is named
foreign minister, succeeding Dr. Wei Tao-ming.

1971: Dr. Lo Yun-pin, president of the National Cheng Kung
University, is named minister of education, succeeding Dr. Choong
Kow-kwong.

1974: Dr. Ku Cheng-kang, honorary chairman of the World
Anti-Communist League, leaves Taipei for Tokyo to attend an executive
council meeting of the Asian Peoples' Anti-Communist League.

1983: Earthquake rocks the city of Popayan in Colombia, killing
more than 500 people.

1988: Sir William McMahon, prime minister of Australia from 1971
to 1972, dies.

1991: The Warsaw Pact formally ceases to exist as a military
force after Soviet commanders surrender their powers.

1992: The United Nations Security Council imposes an air and arms
embargo on Libya.

1994: Twenty-four tourists from Taiwan are killed during a
robbery at a tourist resort in mainland China's Zhejiang Province.

1998: The United Nations Security Council imposes an arms embargo
on Yugoslavia.

2000: Former Taiwan Governor James Soong and his supporters
formally establish Taiwan's 90th officially recognized political
party, the People First Party. Soong is unanimously selected as PFP
chairman.

2000: President-elect Chen Shui-bian promises that the working
week will be shortened to 44 hours from the present 48 hours by
year's end.

2001: A new page in the "three mini links" between the two sides
of the Taiwan Strait is turned when a mainland China-registered
freighter enters a harbor on the Taiwan-ruled offshore island of
Kinmen for the first time.

2001: The Dalai Lama, the exiled spiritual leader of Tibet,
arrives in Taiwan on his second visit to the Republic of China.

Confucius' lesson of the day: "A wise man is sociable, but not
familiar. A fool is familiar but not sociable."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
